WEBVTT

00:00:10.820 --> 00:00:15.300
The Adventures of Tom Sawyer by Mark Twain.

00:00:15.900 --> 00:00:19.160
To my wife, this book is affectionately dedicated.

00:00:19.980 --> 00:00:20.540
Preface.

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:26.160
Most of the adventures recorded in this book really occurred. One or two

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:30.880
were experiences of my own, the rest those of boys who were schoolmates

00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:36.860
of mine. Huck Finn is drawn from life, Tom Sawyer also, but not from an

00:00:36.860 --> 00:00:41.040
individual. He is a combination of the characteristics of three boys

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:45.740
whom I knew, and therefore belongs to the composite order of architecture.

00:00:46.460 --> 00:00:50.760
The odds superstitions touched upon were all prevalent among children

00:00:50.760 --> 00:00:55.120
and slaves in the West at the period of this story, that is to say thirty

00:00:55.120 --> 00:00:59.940
or forty years ago. Although my book is intended mainly for the

00:00:59.940 --> 00:01:04.280
entertainment of boys and girls, I hope it will not be shunned by men

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:08.540
and women on that account, for part of my plan has been to try to

00:01:08.540 --> 00:01:13.720
pleasantly remind adults of what they once were themselves, and of how

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:18.460
they felt and thought and talked, and what queer enterprises they

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:20.220
sometimes engaged in.

00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:24.860
The Author. Hartford. 1876.

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:27.360
CHAPTER I.

00:01:28.740 --> 00:01:29.520
No answer.

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:30.740
Tom?

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:32.440
No answer.

00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:36.280
What's gone with that boy, I wonder? You, Tom?

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:41.780
No answer. The old lady pulled her spectacles down and looked over them

00:01:41.780 --> 00:01:50.200
about the room, then she put them up and looked out under them. She

00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:55.200
They were her state-pair, the pride of her heart, and were built for

00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:59.540
style, not service. She could have seen through a pair of stove-lids

00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:04.320
just as well. She looked perplexed for a moment, and then said, not

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:07.380
fiercely, but still loud enough for the furniture to hear,

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:12.420
"'Well, I lay, if I get hold of you, I'll--" She did not finish, for by

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:16.520
this time she was bending down and punching under the bed with a broom,

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:21.300
and so she needed breath to punctuate the punches with. She resurrected

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:26.600
nothing but the cat. I never see the beat of that boy! She went to the

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:30.400
open door and stood in it, and looked out among the tomato-vines and

00:02:30.400 --> 00:02:36.140
jimson-weeds that constituted the garden. No, Tom. So she lifted up her

00:02:36.140 --> 00:02:39.300
voice at an angle calculated for distance, and shouted,

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:46.320
"'You, Tom!' There was a slight noise behind her, and she turned just

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:50.560
in time to seize a small boy by the slack of his roundabout, and arrest

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:55.000
his flight. There! I might a thought of that closet. What you been

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:00.380
doing in there? Nothing? Nothing? Look at your hands, and look at your

00:03:00.380 --> 00:03:07.080
mouth. What is that truck? I don't know, Aunt. Well, I know. It's jam,

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:11.420
that's what it is. Forty times I've said, if you didn't let that jam

00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:14.360
alone, I'll skin you. Hand me that switch."

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:17.640
The switch hovered in the air. The peril was desperate.

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:20.460
"'My! Look behind you, Aunt!'

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:24.200
The old lady whirled round and snatched her skirts out of danger. The

00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:27.600
lad fled on the instant, scrambled up the high board-fence and

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:31.960
disappeared over it. His Aunt Polly stood surprised a moment, and then

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:33.460
broke into a gentle laugh.

00:03:33.940 --> 00:03:38.440
"'Hang that boy! Can't I never learn anything? Ain't he played me tricks

00:03:38.440 --> 00:03:42.680
enough like that for me to be looking out for him by this time? But old

00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:46.860
fools is the biggest fools there is. Can't learn an old dog new tricks,

00:03:46.940 --> 00:03:51.120
as the saying is. But, my goodness, he never plays them alike two days,

00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:55.540
and how is a body to know what's coming? He peers to know just how long

00:03:55.540 --> 00:03:59.440
he can torment me before I get my dander up, and he knows if he can

00:03:59.440 --> 00:04:03.220
make out to put me off for a minute or make me laugh, it's all down

00:04:03.220 --> 00:04:07.120
again and I can't hit him a lick. I ain't doing my duty by that, boy,

00:04:07.120 --> 00:04:10.940
and that's the Lord's truth, goodness knows. Spare the rod and smile

00:04:10.940 --> 00:04:14.880
at the child, as the Good Book says. I'm a-laying up sin and sufferin'

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:20.100
for us both, I know. He's full of the old scratch but laws of me. He's

00:04:20.100 --> 00:04:24.220
my own dead sister's boy, poor thing, and I ain't got the heart to lash

00:04:24.220 --> 00:04:28.760
him somehow. Every time I let him off my conscience does hurt me so,

00:04:29.080 --> 00:04:33.980
and every time I hit him my old heart most breaks. Well, well, a man

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:40.920
that is born of a woman is a few days and full of trouble, as the

00:04:41.620 --> 00:04:46.340
evening. That's south-western for afternoon. And I'll just be

00:04:46.340 --> 00:04:51.020
obliged to make him work tomorrow to punish him. It's mighty hard to

00:04:51.020 --> 00:04:54.300
make him work Saturdays when all the boys is having holiday, but he

00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:58.040
hates work more than he hates anything else, and I've got to do some of

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:01.420
my duty by him, or I'll be the ruination of the child.

00:05:02.500 --> 00:05:07.520
Tom did play hooky, and he had a very good time. He got back, home

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:12.360
barely in season to help Jim, the small-colored boy, saw next day's

00:05:12.360 --> 00:05:15.900
wood, and split the kindling before supper. At least he was there in

00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:19.500
time to tell his adventures to Jim, while Jim did three-fourths of the

00:05:19.500 --> 00:05:24.560
work. Tom's younger brother, or rather half-brother, Sid, was already

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:28.140
through with his part of the work, picking up chips, for he was a

00:05:28.140 --> 00:05:32.440
quiet boy and had no adventurous, troublesome ways. While Tom was

00:05:32.440 --> 00:05:36.140
eating his supper and stealing sugar as opportunity offered, Aunt

00:05:36.140 --> 00:05:40.240
Polly asked him questions that were full of guile and very deep, for

00:05:40.240 --> 00:05:44.420
she wanted to trap him into damaging revealments. Like many other

00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:49.120
simple-hearted souls, it was her pet vanity to believe she was endowed

00:05:49.120 --> 00:05:53.340
with a talent for dark and mysterious diplomacy, and she loved to

00:05:53.340 --> 00:05:57.380
contemplate her most transparent devices as marvels of low cunning.

00:05:58.020 --> 00:05:58.680
Said she,

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:04.760
Tom, it was middling warm in school, wasn't it? Yesen. Powerful warm,

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:10.880
wasn't it? Yesen. Didn't you want to go in a swimmin', Tom? A bit of a

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:14.900
scare shot through Tom, a touch of uncomfortable suspicion. He searched

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:17.960
Aunt Polly's face, but it told him nothing, so he said,

00:06:18.280 --> 00:06:20.660
No, well, not very much.

00:06:21.060 --> 00:06:24.780
The old lady reached out her hand and felt Tom's shirt, and said,

00:06:24.780 --> 00:06:29.200
But you ain't too warm now, though! And it flattered her to reflect that

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:32.800
she had discovered that the shirt was dry without anybody knowing that

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:37.240
that was what she had in her mind. But in spite of her, Tom knew where

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:40.760
the wind lay now, so he forestalled what might be the next move.

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:44.880
Some of us pumped on our heads, minds damp yet, see?

00:06:45.860 --> 00:06:48.980
Aunt Polly was vexed to think she had overlooked that bit of

00:06:48.980 --> 00:06:52.380
circumstantial evidence and missed a trick. Then she had a new

00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:57.400
Tom, you didn't have to undo your shirt collar where I sewed it, to

00:06:57.400 --> 00:07:00.160
pump on your head, did you? Unbutton your jacket.

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:04.920
The trouble vanished out of Tom's face. He opened his jacket. His

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:07.060
shirt collar was securely sewed.

00:07:07.580 --> 00:07:12.180
Bother! Well, go along with you. I'd made sure you'd played hooky and

00:07:12.180 --> 00:07:15.800
been a swimmin', but I forgive you, Tom. I reckon you're a kind of

00:07:15.800 --> 00:07:19.760
singed cat, as the saying is. Better in your look. This time.

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:24.520
She was half sorry her sagacity had miscarried, and half glad that Tom

00:07:24.520 --> 00:07:28.260
had stumbled into obedient conduct for once. But Sidney said,

00:07:28.820 --> 00:07:32.680
Well, now if I didn't think you sewed his collar with white thread,

00:07:32.800 --> 00:07:33.660
but it's black.

00:07:34.360 --> 00:07:37.160
Why, I did sew it with white. Tom!

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:41.300
But Tom did not wait for the rest. As he went out the door, he said,

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:43.800
City, I'll lick you for that.

00:07:44.360 --> 00:07:48.680
In a safe place, Tom examined two large needles, which were thrust

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:52.700
into the lapels of his jacket, and had thread bound about them. One

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:55.760
needle carried white thread, and the other black. He said,

00:07:56.320 --> 00:08:00.320
She'd never noticed if it hadn't been for Sid. Con found it. Sometimes

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:04.400
she sews it with white, and sometimes she sews it with black. I wish to

00:08:04.400 --> 00:08:08.340
Jiminy she'd stick to one or t'other. I can't keep the run of them. But

00:08:08.340 --> 00:08:11.020
I bet I'll learn Sid for that. I'll learn him.

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:15.940
He was not the model boy of the village. He knew the model boy very

00:08:15.940 --> 00:08:17.860
well, though, and loathed him.

00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:21.520
Within two minutes, or even less, he had forgotten all his troubles.

00:08:22.140 --> 00:08:25.620
Not because his troubles were one whit less heavy and bitter to him

00:08:25.620 --> 00:08:29.260
than a man's are to a man, but because a new and powerful interest

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:33.600
bore them down, and drove them out of his mind for the time. Just as

00:08:33.600 --> 00:08:36.960
men's misfortunes are forgotten in the excitement of new enterprises.

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:41.540
This new interest was a valued novelty in whistling, which he had just

00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:45.680
acquired from a negro, and he was suffering to practice it undisturbed.

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:50.320
It consisted in a peculiar bird-like turn, a sort of liquid warble,

00:08:50.680 --> 00:08:53.840
produced by touching the tongue to the roof of the mouth at short

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:57.960
intervals in the midst of the music. The reader probably remembers how

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:00.180
to do it, if he has ever been a boy.

00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:05.340
Diligence and attention soon gave him the knack of it, and he strode

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:08.540
down the street with his mouth full of harmony and his soul full of

00:09:08.540 --> 00:09:12.580
gratitude. He felt much as an astronomer feels who has discovered a

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:16.940
new planet. No doubt, as far as strong, deep, unalloyed pleasure is

00:09:16.940 --> 00:09:20.620
concerned, the advantage was with a boy, not the astronomer.

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:26.180
The summer evenings were long. It was not dark yet. Presently Tom

00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:30.720
checked his whistle. A stranger was before him, a boy a shade larger

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:35.140
than himself. A newcomer of any age or either sex was an impressive

00:09:35.140 --> 00:09:42.560
curiosity in the poor little shabby village of St. Petersburg. This

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:48.280
was simply astounding. His cap was a dainty thing, his close-buttoned

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:52.760
blue cloth round about was new and natty, and so were his pantaloons.

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:58.120
He had shoes on, and it was only Friday. He even wore a necktie, a

00:09:58.120 --> 00:10:02.660
bright bit of ribbon. He had acidified air about him that ate into Tom's

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:06.900
vitals. The more Tom stared at the splendid marvel, the higher he

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:11.440
turned up his nose at his finery, and the shabbier and shabbier his own

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:16.220
outfit seemed to him to grow. Neither boy spoke. If one moved, the

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:21.260
other moved, but only sidewise, in a circle. They kept face to face and

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:24.560
eye to eye all the time. Finally Tom said,

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:26.300
I can lick you.

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:28.520
I'd like to see you try it.

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:30.320
Well, I can do it.

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:31.620
No, you can't either.

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:32.960
Yes, I can.

00:10:33.260 --> 00:10:34.140
No, you can't.

00:10:34.140 --> 00:10:34.760
I can.

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:35.420
You can't.

00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:35.960
Can't.

00:10:36.100 --> 00:10:36.300
Can't.

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:39.200
An uncomfortable pause. Then Tom said,

00:10:39.700 --> 00:10:40.540
What's your name?

00:10:40.540 --> 00:10:42.720
It isn't any of your business, maybe.

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:45.820
Well, I'll make it my business.

00:10:46.300 --> 00:10:47.700
Well, why don't you?

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:49.740
If you say much, I will.

00:10:50.900 --> 00:10:53.480
Much, much, much. There, now.

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:57.380
Oh, you think you're mighty smart, don't you? I could lick you with one

00:10:57.380 --> 00:10:59.040
hand tied behind me if I wanted to.

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:02.620
Well, why don't you do it? You say you can do it.

00:11:02.700 --> 00:11:04.640
Well, I will, if you fool with me.

00:11:05.020 --> 00:11:08.200
Oh, yes, I've seen whole families in the same fix.

00:11:08.740 --> 00:11:12.580
Smarty, you think you're some, now, don't you? Oh, what a hat!

00:11:13.100 --> 00:11:16.680
You can lump that hat if you don't like it. I dare you to knock it

00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:19.460
off. And anybody that'll take a dare will suck eggs.

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:20.800
You're a liar.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:22.100
You're another.

00:11:22.560 --> 00:11:24.720
You're a fighting liar and doesn't take it up.

00:11:25.120 --> 00:11:26.300
Ah, take a walk.

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:30.700
Say, if you give me much more of your sass, I'll take and bounce a

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:31.660
rock off in your head.

00:11:32.140 --> 00:11:33.540
Oh, of course you will.

00:11:33.780 --> 00:11:34.600
Well, I will.

00:11:35.060 --> 00:11:36.920
Well, why don't you do it, then?

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:41.420
Why do you keep saying you will for? Why don't you do it? It's

00:11:41.420 --> 00:11:42.360
because you're afraid.

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:43.840
I ain't afraid.

00:11:44.120 --> 00:11:44.740
You are.

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:45.740
I ain't.

00:11:45.860 --> 00:11:46.460
You are.

00:11:46.900 --> 00:11:50.580
Another pause, and more eyeing and sidling around each other.

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:53.480
Presently they were shoulder to shoulder, Tom said.

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:57.120
Get away from me. Go away yourself. I won't.

00:11:57.480 --> 00:11:58.400
Well, I won't, either.

00:11:58.700 --> 00:12:02.760
So they stood, each with a foot placed at an angle as a brace, and

00:12:02.760 --> 00:12:06.240
both shoving with might and mane and glowering at each other with

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:10.540
hate. But neither could get an advantage. After struggling till both

00:12:10.540 --> 00:12:14.580
were hot and flushed, each relaxed his strain with watchful caution,

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:15.640
and Tom said,

00:12:16.120 --> 00:12:20.180
You're a coward and a pup. I'll tell my big brother on you, and he can

00:12:20.180 --> 00:12:23.120
thrash you with his little finger, and I'll make him do it, too.

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:27.140
Who do I care for your big brother? I've got a brother that's bigger

00:12:27.140 --> 00:12:30.680
than he is, and what's more, he can throw him over that fence, too.

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:32.960
Both brothers were imaginary.

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:36.660
That's a lie! Your saying so doesn't make it so.

00:12:37.100 --> 00:12:39.920
Tom drew a line in the dust with his big toe, and said,

00:12:39.980 --> 00:12:44.000
I dare you to step over that, and I'll lick you till you can't stand

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.980
up. Anybody that'll take a dare will steal sheep.

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:50.240
The new boy stepped over promptly, and said,

00:12:50.600 --> 00:12:54.680
Now you said you'd do it. Now let's see you do it. Don't you crowd me

00:12:54.680 --> 00:12:56.100
now. You'd better look out.

00:12:56.700 --> 00:13:00.480
Well, you said you'd do it. Why don't you do it? Buy jingo for two

00:13:00.480 --> 00:13:01.680
pence, I will do it.

00:13:01.860 --> 00:13:06.140
The new boy took two broad coppers out of his pocket, and held them out

00:13:06.140 --> 00:13:11.420
with derision. Tom struck them to the ground. In an instant both boys

00:13:11.420 --> 00:13:15.160
were rolling and tumbling in the dirt, gripped together like cats, and

00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:18.260
for the space of a minute they tugged and tore at each other's hair

00:13:18.260 --> 00:13:22.080
and clothes, punched and scratched each other's noses, and covered

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:26.300
themselves with dust and glory. Presently the confusion took form,

00:13:26.440 --> 00:13:30.180
and through the fog of battle Tom appeared seated astride the new boy,

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:31.940
and pounding him with his fists.

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:36.320
Holler nuff! said he. The boy only struggled to free himself. He was

00:13:36.320 --> 00:13:37.900
crying, mainly from rage.

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:42.700
Holler nuff! and the pounding went on. At last the stranger got out of

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:47.140
smothered. Nuff! and Tom let him up, and said, Now that'll learn you.

00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:49.420
Better look out who you're fooling with next time.

00:13:49.980 --> 00:13:53.400
The new boy went off brushing the dust from his clothes, sobbing,

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:56.340
snuffling, and occasionally looking back and shaking his head and

00:13:56.340 --> 00:13:59.240
threatening what he would do to Tom the next time he caught him out,

00:13:59.240 --> 00:14:03.040
to which Tom responded with jeers and started off in a high feather,

00:14:03.400 --> 00:14:06.720
and as soon as his back was turned the new boy snatched up a stone,

00:14:07.160 --> 00:14:10.600
threw it, and hit him between the shoulders, and then turned tail and

00:14:10.600 --> 00:14:14.680
ran like an antelope. Tom chased the traitor home, and thus found out

00:14:14.680 --> 00:14:18.440
where he lived. He then held a position at the gate for some time,

00:14:18.820 --> 00:14:22.760
daring the enemy to come outside, but the enemy only made faces at him

00:14:22.760 --> 00:14:26.420
through the window and declined. At last the enemy's mother appeared,

00:14:26.420 --> 00:14:31.560
called Tom a bad, vicious, vulgar child, and ordered him away. So he

00:14:31.560 --> 00:14:36.320
went away, but he said he allowed to lay for that boy. He got home

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:39.720
pretty late that night, and when he climbed cautiously in at the

00:14:39.720 --> 00:14:44.420
window he uncovered an ambuscade in the person of his aunt, and when

00:14:44.420 --> 00:14:47.940
she saw the state his clothes were in, her resolution to turn his

00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:52.920
Saturday holiday into captivity at hard labor became adamantine in its

00:14:52.920 --> 00:14:53.580
firmness.

00:14:55.060 --> 00:14:58.180
CHAPTER II THE GLORIOUS WHITE-WASHER

00:14:59.220 --> 00:15:04.160
Saturday morning was come, and all the summer world was bright and

00:15:04.160 --> 00:15:08.540
fresh and brimming with life. There was a song in every heart, and if

00:15:08.540 --> 00:15:13.120
the heart was young the music issued at the lips. There was cheer in

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:18.020
every face, and a spring in every step. The locust trees were in bloom,

00:15:18.160 --> 00:15:22.460
and the fragrance of the blossoms filled the air. Cardiff Hill,

00:15:22.460 --> 00:15:26.760
beyond the village and above it, was green with vegetation, and it

00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:32.000
lay just far enough away to seem a delectable land, dreamy, reposeful

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.700
and inviting. Tom appeared on the sidewalk with a bucket of whitewash

00:15:36.700 --> 00:15:41.980
and a long-handled brush. He surveyed the fence, and all gladness left

00:15:41.980 --> 00:15:47.220
him, and a deep melancholy settled down upon his spirit. Thirty yards

00:15:47.220 --> 00:15:52.980
of bored fence nine feet high, life to him seemed hollow, an existence

00:15:52.980 --> 00:15:58.080
but a burden. Sighing, he dipped his brush and passed it along the

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:02.760
topmost plank, repeated the operation, did it again, compared the

00:16:02.760 --> 00:16:06.560
insignificant whitewash streak with a far-reaching continent of

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:12.180
un-whitewashed fence, and sat down on a tree-box discouraged. Jim came

00:16:12.180 --> 00:16:17.220
out at the gate with a tin pail and singing Buffalo Gals. Bringing

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:21.140
water from the town pump had always been hateful work in Tom's eyes

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:25.700
before, but now it did not strike him so. He remembered that there was

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:30.560
company at the pump. White, mulatto, and negro boys and girls were

00:16:30.560 --> 00:16:34.380
always there waiting their turns, resting, trading, playthings,

00:16:34.500 --> 00:16:38.990
quarreling, fighting, skylarking, and he remembered that although the

00:16:38.990 --> 00:16:43.130
pump was only a hundred and fifty yards off, Jim never got back with a

00:16:43.130 --> 00:16:47.090
bucket of water under an hour, and even then somebody generally had to

00:16:47.090 --> 00:16:49.290
go after him. Tom said,

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:53.610
"'Say, Jim, I'll fetch the water if you'll whitewash some.'

00:16:53.610 --> 00:16:55.370
Jim shook his head and said,

00:16:55.970 --> 00:17:00.410
"'Can't, Mars Tom. Old Mrs. she told me I got to go and get this water

00:17:00.410 --> 00:17:04.510
and stop fooling around with anybody. She say she spec'd Mars Tom

00:17:04.510 --> 00:17:08.290
going to ask me to whitewash, and so she told me to go long and tend to

00:17:08.290 --> 00:17:13.470
my own business. She loud she'd tend to whitewashing. Oh, never mind

00:17:13.470 --> 00:17:16.790
what she said, Jim. That's the way she always talks. Give me the

00:17:16.790 --> 00:17:21.090
bucket. I won't be gone only a minute. She won't ever know. Oh, I

00:17:21.090 --> 00:17:26.050
dazzle Mars Tom. Old Mrs. she takin' tar to head off in me. Deed she

00:17:26.670 --> 00:17:27.170
would.'

00:17:27.170 --> 00:17:31.550
"'She never licks anybody, whacks him over the head with her thimble,

00:17:31.610 --> 00:17:35.470
and who cares for that, I'd like to know. She talks awful, but talk

00:17:35.470 --> 00:17:40.690
hurt. Anyways, it don't if she don't cry. Jim, I'll give you a marvel.

00:17:41.150 --> 00:17:43.830
I'll give you a white alley.'

00:17:43.830 --> 00:17:45.650
Jim began to wave her.

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:49.810
"'White alley, Jim. And it's a bully-tall.'

00:17:49.810 --> 00:17:54.770
"'Mah, that's a mighty gay marvel, I tell you. But Mars Tom, I's

00:17:54.770 --> 00:17:58.870
powerful, afraid old Mrs. and besides, if you will, I'll show you my

00:17:58.870 --> 00:18:03.750
sore toe.' Jim was only human. This attraction was too much for him. He

00:18:03.750 --> 00:18:08.210
put down his pail, took the white alley, and bent over the toe with

00:18:08.210 --> 00:18:11.750
absorbing interest while the bandage was being unwound. In another

00:18:11.750 --> 00:18:15.330
moment he was flying down the street with his pail and a tingling rear.

00:18:15.770 --> 00:18:19.890
Tom was whitewashing with vigour, and Aunt Polly was retiring from the

00:18:19.890 --> 00:18:24.910
field with a slipper in her hand and triumph in her eye. But Tom's

00:18:24.910 --> 00:18:29.070
energy did not last. He began to think of the fun he had planned for

00:18:29.070 --> 00:18:34.110
his day, and his sorrows multiplied. Soon the free boys would come

00:18:34.110 --> 00:18:37.910
tripping along on all sorts of delicious expeditions, and they would

00:18:37.910 --> 00:18:41.270
make a world of fun of him for having to work. The very thought of it

00:18:41.270 --> 00:18:46.130
burnt him like fire. He got out his worldly wealth and examined it—bits

00:18:46.130 --> 00:18:51.870
of toys, marbles, and trash—enough to buy an exchange of work, maybe,

00:18:52.150 --> 00:18:56.750
but not half enough to buy so much as half an hour of pure freedom. So

00:18:56.750 --> 00:19:00.750
he returned his straightened means to his pocket and gave up the idea of

00:19:00.750 --> 00:19:05.130
trying to buy the boys. At this dark and hopeless moment an inspiration

00:19:05.130 --> 00:19:10.090
burst upon him—nothing less than a great magnificent inspiration. He

00:19:10.090 --> 00:19:14.770
took up his brush and went tranquilly to work. Ben Rogers hove in sight

00:19:14.770 --> 00:19:18.970
presently—the very boy of all boys, whose ridicule he had been

00:19:18.970 --> 00:19:23.910
dreading. Ben's gait was the hop, skip, and jump, proof enough that his

00:19:23.910 --> 00:19:28.630
heart was light and his anticipations high. He was eating an apple, and

00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:33.310
giving a long, melodious whoop at intervals, followed by a deep-toned

00:19:33.310 --> 00:19:39.870
ding-dong-dong, ding-dong-dong, for he was personating a steamboat. As he

00:19:39.870 --> 00:19:43.930
drew near he slackened speed, took the middle of the road, leaned far

00:19:43.930 --> 00:19:48.490
over to starboard, and rounded to, ponderously and with laborious pomp

00:19:48.490 --> 00:19:52.890
and circumstance, for he was personating the Big Missouri, and considered

00:19:52.890 --> 00:19:57.690
himself to be drawing nine feet of water. He was boat and captain and

00:19:57.690 --> 00:20:01.750
engine-bells combined, so he had to imagine himself standing on his own

00:20:01.750 --> 00:20:04.190
hurricane deck giving the orders and executing them.

00:20:04.530 --> 00:20:09.210
Stop her, sir! Ding-a-ling-a-ling! The headway ran almost out, and he

00:20:09.210 --> 00:20:13.670
drew up slowly towards the sidewalk. Ship up to back! Ding-a-ling-a-ling!

00:20:14.070 --> 00:20:18.270
His arms straightened and stiffened down his sides. Set her back on the

00:20:18.270 --> 00:20:23.330
starboard! Ding-a-ling-a-ling! Chow! Chow! Chow! Chow! Chow! His right

00:20:23.330 --> 00:20:27.370
hand, meantime, described stately circles, for it was representing a 40

00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:32.150
foot wheel. Let her go back on the starboard! Ding-a-ling-a-ling! Chow!

00:20:32.290 --> 00:20:37.110
Chow! Chow! The left hand began to describe circles. Stop the starboard!

00:20:37.290 --> 00:20:41.730
Ding-a-ling-a-ling! Stop the starboard! Come ahead on the starboard!

00:20:42.070 --> 00:20:47.650
Stop her! Let her outside! Turn her over slow! Ding-a-ling! Chow! Chow!

00:20:47.650 --> 00:20:52.270
Get out that headline! Lively, now! Come! Come out of there with your

00:20:52.270 --> 00:20:55.870
spring line! What are you about there? Take up a turn in that stump

00:20:55.870 --> 00:21:00.550
with the bright of it! Stand by that stage! Now let her go! Done with

00:21:00.550 --> 00:21:05.530
the engine, sir! Ding-a-ling-a-ling! Chit! Chit! Chit! Chit!

00:21:05.690 --> 00:21:10.390
Trying the gauge-cocks, Tom went on whitewashing, paid no attention to

00:21:10.390 --> 00:21:13.130
the steamboat. Ben stared a moment and then said,

00:21:13.130 --> 00:21:16.450
Hi-ee! You're up a stump, ain't you?

00:21:16.830 --> 00:21:21.450
No answer. Tom surveyed his last touch with the eye of an artist, then

00:21:21.450 --> 00:21:24.710
he gave his brush another gentle sweep and surveyed the result as

00:21:24.710 --> 00:21:29.750
before. Ben ranged up alongside of him. Tom's mouth watered for the

00:21:29.750 --> 00:21:32.310
apple, but he stuck to his work. Ben said,

00:21:32.750 --> 00:21:35.090
Hello, old chap! You got to work, eh?

00:21:35.810 --> 00:21:37.630
Tom wheeled suddenly and said,

00:21:37.630 --> 00:21:42.990
Why, it's you, Ben. I weren't noticing. Say, I'm going in a swimming.

00:21:43.210 --> 00:21:47.090
I am. Don't you wish you could? But of course you'd rather work,

00:21:47.190 --> 00:21:50.610
wouldn't you? Of course you would. Tom contemplated the boy a bit and

00:21:50.610 --> 00:21:50.970
said,

00:21:51.530 --> 00:21:53.190
What do you call work?

00:21:53.730 --> 00:21:57.470
Why, ain't that work? Tom resumed his whitewashing and answered

00:21:57.470 --> 00:21:58.010
carelessly,

00:21:58.710 --> 00:22:04.010
Well, maybe it is and maybe it ain't. All I know is it suits Tom Sawyer.

00:22:04.570 --> 00:22:08.790
Oh, come, now, you don't mean to let on that you like that.

00:22:09.330 --> 00:22:10.830
The brush continued to move.

00:22:11.130 --> 00:22:15.630
Like it? Well, I don't see why I oughtn't to like it. Does a boy get a

00:22:15.630 --> 00:22:17.310
chance to whitewash a fence every day?

00:22:17.970 --> 00:22:21.850
That put the thing in a new light. Ben stopped nibbling his apple.

00:22:22.370 --> 00:22:26.990
Tom swept his brush daintily, back and forth, stepped back to note the

00:22:26.990 --> 00:22:31.810
effect, added a touch here and there, criticized the effect again. Ben,

00:22:31.810 --> 00:22:34.950
watching every move and getting more and more interested, more and

00:22:34.950 --> 00:22:36.890
more absorbed. Presently he said,

00:22:37.410 --> 00:22:40.510
Say, Tom, let me whitewash a little.

00:22:41.090 --> 00:22:44.870
Tom considered, was about to consent, but he altered his mind.

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:49.830
No, no, I reckon it wouldn't hardly do, Ben. You see Aunt Polly's awful

00:22:49.830 --> 00:22:53.430
particular about this fence, right here on the street, you know. But if

00:22:53.430 --> 00:22:56.950
it was the back fence I wouldn't mind and she wouldn't. Yes, she's

00:22:56.950 --> 00:23:01.490
awful particular about this fence. It's got to be done very careful. I

00:23:01.490 --> 00:23:05.210
reckon there ain't one boy in a thousand—maybe two thousand—that

00:23:05.210 --> 00:23:07.030
can do it the way it's got to be done.

00:23:07.610 --> 00:23:13.290
No, is that so? Oh, come now, let me just try. Only just a little. I'd

00:23:13.290 --> 00:23:14.830
let you if you was me, Tom.

00:23:15.530 --> 00:23:18.690
Ben, I'd like to. Honest, Injun. But Aunt Polly—

00:23:19.290 --> 00:23:24.250
Well, Jim wanted to do it, but she wouldn't let him. Sid wanted to do

00:23:24.250 --> 00:23:28.990
it, and she wouldn't let Sid. Now, don't you see how I'm fixed? If you

00:23:28.990 --> 00:23:32.370
was to tackle this fence and anything was to happen to it—aw, shucks,

00:23:32.370 --> 00:23:37.570
I'll be just as careful. Now let me try. Say, I'll give you the core of

00:23:37.570 --> 00:23:37.990
my apple.

00:23:38.850 --> 00:23:44.710
Well, here. No, no, Ben, now don't. I'm afeard. I'll give you all of

00:23:44.710 --> 00:23:44.850
it.

00:23:45.150 --> 00:23:49.430
Tom gave up the brush with reluctance in his face, but alacrity in his

00:23:49.430 --> 00:23:53.550
heart, and while the late steamer Big Missouri worked and sweated in

00:23:53.550 --> 00:23:57.630
the sun, the retired artist sat on a barrel in the shade close by,

00:23:57.630 --> 00:24:02.130
dangled his legs, munched his apple, and planned the slaughter of more

00:24:02.130 --> 00:24:06.650
innocence. There was no lack of material. Boys happened along every

00:24:06.650 --> 00:24:11.530
little while. They came to jeer, but remained to whitewash. By the time

00:24:11.530 --> 00:24:15.530
Ben was fagged out, Tom had traded the next chance to Billy Fisher for

00:24:15.530 --> 00:24:20.170
a kite in good repair. And when he played out, Johnny Miller bought in

00:24:20.170 --> 00:24:24.910
for a dead rat on a string to swing it with, and so on and so on hour

00:24:24.910 --> 00:24:29.170
after hour. And when the middle of the afternoon came, from being a

00:24:29.170 --> 00:24:33.190
poor poverty-stricken boy in the morning, Tom was literally rolling in

00:24:33.190 --> 00:24:37.970
wealth. He had beside the things before mentioned twelve marbles, part

00:24:37.970 --> 00:24:42.530
of a Jew's harp, a piece of blue bottle-glass to look through, a spool

00:24:42.530 --> 00:24:47.390
cannon, a key that wouldn't unlock anything, a fragment of chalk, a

00:24:47.390 --> 00:24:53.130
glass stopper of a decanter, a tin soldier, a couple of tadpoles, six

00:24:53.130 --> 00:24:58.830
firecrackers, a kitten with only one eye, a brass doorknob, a dog collar

00:24:58.830 --> 00:25:03.890
but no dog, the handle of a knife, four pieces of orange peel, and a

00:25:03.890 --> 00:25:09.750
dilapidated old window-sash. He had had a nice, good, idle time all the

00:25:09.750 --> 00:25:13.410
while, plenty of company, and the fence had had three coats of

00:25:13.410 --> 00:25:17.250
whitewash on it. If he hadn't run out of whitewash, he would have

00:25:17.250 --> 00:25:18.850
bankrupted every boy in the village.

00:25:19.530 --> 00:25:24.130
Tom said to himself that it was not such a hollow world after all. He

00:25:24.130 --> 00:25:28.250
had discovered a great law of human action without knowing it, namely,

00:25:28.290 --> 00:25:32.730
that in order to make a man or boy covet a thing, it is only necessary

00:25:32.730 --> 00:25:37.350
to make the thing difficult to attain. If he had been a great and wise

00:25:37.350 --> 00:25:40.790
philosopher, like the writer of this book, he would now have

00:25:40.790 --> 00:25:45.710
comprehended that work consists of whatever a body is obliged to do,

00:25:45.710 --> 00:25:51.250
and that play consists of whatever a body is not obliged to do. And

00:25:51.250 --> 00:25:55.030
this would help him to understand why constructing artificial flowers

00:25:55.030 --> 00:26:00.450
or performing on a treadmill is work, while rolling tenpins or climbing

00:26:00.450 --> 00:26:05.290
Mont Blanc is only amusement. There are wealthy gentlemen in England

00:26:05.290 --> 00:26:09.810
who drive four-horse passenger coaches twenty or thirty miles on a

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:13.650
daily line in the summer because the privilege costs them considerable

00:26:13.650 --> 00:26:18.190
money. But if they were offered wages for the service, that would turn

00:26:18.190 --> 00:26:23.290
it into work, and then they would resign. The boy mused a while over

00:26:23.290 --> 00:26:26.250
the substantial change which had taken place in his worldly

00:26:26.250 --> 00:26:30.730
circumstances, and then wended toward headquarters to report.

00:26:46.570 --> 00:26:47.310
III.

00:26:48.330 --> 00:26:50.810
Busy at War and Love.

00:26:52.090 --> 00:26:55.930
Tom presented himself before Aunt Polly, who was sitting by an open

00:26:55.930 --> 00:27:00.250
window in a pleasant rearward apartment which was bedroom, breakfast

00:27:00.250 --> 00:27:05.970
dining-room, and library combined. The balmy summer air, the restful

00:27:05.970 --> 00:27:10.310
quiet, the odour of the flowers, and the drowsing murmur of the bees

00:27:10.310 --> 00:27:14.450
had had their effect, and she was nodding over her knitting, for she

00:27:14.450 --> 00:27:17.950
had no company but the cat, and it was asleep in her lap.

00:27:18.530 --> 00:27:22.990
Her spectacles were propped up on her grey head for safety. She had

00:27:22.990 --> 00:27:26.990
thought that of course Tom had deserted long ago, and she wondered at

00:27:26.990 --> 00:27:32.250
him place himself in her power again, in this intrepid way. He said,--"Meant

00:27:33.130 --> 00:27:35.230
I go and play now, Aunt?"--"What,

00:27:35.810 --> 00:27:38.230
already? How much have you done?"--"It's

00:27:38.850 --> 00:27:40.230
all done, Aunt."--"Tom,

00:27:40.950 --> 00:27:44.410
don't lie to me. I can't bear it."--"I ain't,

00:27:44.490 --> 00:27:48.590
Aunt. It is all done." Aunt Polly placed small

00:27:48.590 --> 00:27:52.930
trust in such evidence. She went out to see for herself, and she would

00:27:52.930 --> 00:27:55.390
have been content to find twenty per cent of

00:27:55.390 --> 00:28:00.030
Tom's statement true. When she found the entire fence whitewashed, and

00:28:00.030 --> 00:28:03.930
not only whitewashed, but elaborately coated and recoated, and even a

00:28:03.930 --> 00:28:08.750
streak added to the ground, her astonishment was almost unspeakable. She

00:28:08.750 --> 00:28:13.510
said,--"Well, I never. There's no getting round it. You can work when

00:28:13.510 --> 00:28:18.010
you're a-mind to, Tom." And then she diluted the compliment by adding,--"But

00:28:18.010 --> 00:28:22.370
it's powerful seldom you're a-mind to, I'm bound to say. Well, go

00:28:22.370 --> 00:28:26.610
along and play. But mind you get back some time in the week, or I'll

00:28:26.610 --> 00:28:27.650
tan you."

00:28:27.650 --> 00:28:31.370
She was so overcome by the splendour of his achievement that she took

00:28:31.370 --> 00:28:35.770
him into the closet and selected a choice apple and delivered it to him,

00:28:36.050 --> 00:28:40.050
along with an improving lecture upon the added value and flavour a treat

00:28:40.050 --> 00:28:45.010
took to itself when it came without sin through virtuous effort. And

00:28:45.010 --> 00:28:49.870
while she closed with a happy scriptural flourish, he hooked a doughnut.

00:28:50.270 --> 00:28:54.050
Then he skipped out and saw Sid just starting up the outside stairway

00:28:54.050 --> 00:28:58.190
that led to the back rooms on the second floor. Clods were handy, and

00:28:58.190 --> 00:29:02.290
the air was full of them in a twinkling. They raged around Sid like a

00:29:02.290 --> 00:29:06.590
hailstorm, and before Aunt Polly could collect her surprised faculties

00:29:06.590 --> 00:29:10.770
and Sally to the rescue, six or seven clods had taken personal effect,

00:29:11.190 --> 00:29:15.670
and Tom was over the fence and gone. There was a gate, but as a general

00:29:15.670 --> 00:29:19.830
thing he was too crowded for time to make use of it. His soul was at

00:29:19.830 --> 00:29:23.370
peace, now that he had settled with Sid for calling attention to his

00:29:23.370 --> 00:29:27.890
black thread and getting him into trouble. Tom skirted the block and came

00:29:27.890 --> 00:29:32.350
round into a muddy alley that led by the back of his aunt's cow-stable.

00:29:32.810 --> 00:29:36.810
He presently got safely beyond the reach of capture and punishment and

00:29:36.810 --> 00:29:40.510
hastened towards the public square of the village, where two military

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:44.770
companies of boys had met for conflict according to previous appointment.

00:29:45.210 --> 00:29:49.730
Tom was general of one of these armies, Joe Harper, a bosom friend,

00:29:50.030 --> 00:29:54.210
general of the other. These two great commanders did not condescend to

00:29:54.210 --> 00:29:58.510
fight in person, that being better suited to the still smaller fry, but

00:29:58.510 --> 00:30:02.430
sat together on an eminence and conducted the field operations by

00:30:02.430 --> 00:30:07.030
orders delivered through aide-de-camp. Tom's army won a great victory

00:30:07.030 --> 00:30:10.950
after a long and hard-fought battle. Then the dead were counted,

00:30:10.950 --> 00:30:15.430
prisoners exchanged, the terms of the next disagreement agreed upon, and

00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:19.190
the day for the necessary battle appointed. After which the armies fell

00:30:19.190 --> 00:30:22.870
into line and marched away, and Tom turned homeward alone.

00:30:23.510 --> 00:30:27.550
As he was passing by the house where Jeff Thatcher lived, he saw a new

00:30:27.550 --> 00:30:31.630
girl in the garden, a lovely little blue-eyed creature with yellow hair

00:30:31.630 --> 00:30:35.710
plaited into two long tails, white summer frock, and embroidered

00:30:35.710 --> 00:30:40.930
pantilettes. The fresh-crowned hero fell without firing a shot. A

00:30:40.930 --> 00:30:45.530
certain Amy Lawrence vanished out of his heart and left not even a

00:30:45.530 --> 00:30:49.730
memory of herself behind. He had thought he loved her to distraction.

00:30:50.350 --> 00:30:55.010
He had regarded his passion as adoration, and, behold, it was only a

00:30:55.010 --> 00:31:00.090
poor little evanescent partiality. He had been months winning her, she

00:31:00.090 --> 00:31:03.950
had confessed hardly a week ago. He had been the happiest and the

00:31:03.950 --> 00:31:07.870
loudest boy in the world only seven short days, and here in one

00:31:07.870 --> 00:31:11.630
instant of time she had gone out of his heart like a casual stranger

00:31:11.630 --> 00:31:16.530
whose visit is done. He worshipped this new angel with furtive eye, till

00:31:16.530 --> 00:31:20.330
he saw that she had discovered him. Then he pretended he did not know

00:31:20.330 --> 00:31:24.270
she was present, and began to show off in all sorts of absurd boyish

00:31:24.270 --> 00:31:28.350
ways in order to win her admiration. He kept up this grotesque

00:31:28.350 --> 00:31:32.250
foolishness for some time, but by and by, while he was in the midst of

00:31:32.250 --> 00:31:36.350
some dangerous gymnastic performances, he glanced aside and saw that

00:31:36.350 --> 00:31:40.370
the little girl was wending her way toward the house. Tom came up to

00:31:40.370 --> 00:31:44.410
the fence and leaned on it, grieving and hoping she would tarry yet a

00:31:44.410 --> 00:31:48.110
while longer. She halted a moment on the steps and then moved toward

00:31:48.110 --> 00:31:52.770
the door. Tom heaved a great sigh as she put her foot on the threshold.

00:31:53.410 --> 00:31:57.090
But his face lit up right away, for she tossed a pansy over the fence a

00:31:57.090 --> 00:31:58.410
moment before she disappeared.

00:31:59.190 --> 00:32:03.410
The boy ran around and stopped within a foot or two of the flower, and

00:32:03.410 --> 00:32:07.750
then shaded his eyes with his hand and began to look down street as if

00:32:07.750 --> 00:32:10.630
he had discovered something of interest going on in that direction.

00:32:11.370 --> 00:32:15.190
Presently he picked up a straw and began trying to balance it on his

00:32:15.190 --> 00:32:19.870
nose, with his head tilted far back, and as he moved from side to side

00:32:19.870 --> 00:32:24.230
in his efforts he edged nearer and nearer toward the pansy. Finally his

00:32:24.230 --> 00:32:28.790
bare foot rested upon it, his pliant toes closed upon it, and he hopped

00:32:28.790 --> 00:32:32.790
away with a treasure and disappeared round the corner. But only for a

00:32:32.790 --> 00:32:36.350
minute, only while he could button the flower inside his jacket next

00:32:36.350 --> 00:32:40.230
to his heart—or next to his stomach, possibly, for he was not much

00:32:40.230 --> 00:32:43.430
posted in anatomy, and not hypercritical, anyway.

00:32:44.210 --> 00:32:48.150
He returned now and hung about the fence till nightfall, showing off,

00:32:48.290 --> 00:32:52.690
as before, but the girl never exhibited herself again, though Tom

00:32:52.690 --> 00:32:56.530
comforted himself a little with the hope that she had been near some

00:32:56.530 --> 00:33:00.930
window meantime and been aware of his attentions. Finally he rode home

00:33:00.930 --> 00:33:03.270
reluctantly with his poor head full of visions.

00:33:04.050 --> 00:33:08.390
All through supper his spirits were so high that his aunt wondered what

00:33:08.390 --> 00:33:13.170
had got into the child. He took a good scolding about clotting Sid, and

00:33:13.170 --> 00:33:17.130
did not seem to mind it in the least. He tried to steal sugar under his

00:33:17.130 --> 00:33:20.090
aunt's very nose and got his knuckles wrapped for it. He said,

00:33:20.090 --> 00:33:25.330
"'Aunt, you don't whack Sid when he takes it.' Well, Sid, don't torment

00:33:25.330 --> 00:33:29.390
a body the way you do. You'd be always into that sugar if I weren't

00:33:29.390 --> 00:33:33.410
watching you.' Presently she stepped into the kitchen, and Sid, happy in

00:33:33.410 --> 00:33:37.490
his immunity, reached for the sugar bowl, a sort of glorying over Tom,

00:33:37.530 --> 00:33:41.630
which was well nigh unbearable. But Sid's fingers slipped, and the bowl

00:33:41.630 --> 00:33:47.590
dropped and broke. Tom was in ecstasies—in such ecstasies that he even

00:33:47.590 --> 00:33:51.250
controlled his tongue and was silent. He said to himself that he would

00:33:51.250 --> 00:33:55.510
not speak a word, even when his aunt came in, but would sit perfectly

00:33:55.510 --> 00:34:00.010
still till she asked who did the mischief, and then he would tell, and

00:34:00.010 --> 00:34:03.210
there would be nothing so good in the world as to see that pet model

00:34:03.210 --> 00:34:07.670
catch it. He was so brimful of exultation that he could hardly hold

00:34:07.670 --> 00:34:11.630
himself when the old lady came back and stood above the wreck discharging

00:34:11.630 --> 00:34:16.130
lightnings of wrath from over her spectacles. He said to himself, "'Now

00:34:16.130 --> 00:34:20.270
it's coming,' and the next instant he was sprawling on the floor. The

00:34:20.270 --> 00:34:24.950
potent palm was uplifted to strike again when Tom cried out, "'Hold on

00:34:24.950 --> 00:34:29.590
now! What are you belting me for? Sid broke it!' Aunt Polly paused,

00:34:29.830 --> 00:34:34.290
perplexed, and Tom looked for healing pity. But when she got her tongue

00:34:34.290 --> 00:34:38.690
again she only said, "'Oomph!' Well, you didn't get a lick amiss, I

00:34:38.690 --> 00:34:42.230
reckon. You've been into some other odashes, mischief, when I wasn't

00:34:42.230 --> 00:34:46.270
round like enough.' Then her conscience reproached her, and she yearned

00:34:46.270 --> 00:34:49.910
to say something kind and loving, but she judged that this would be

00:34:49.910 --> 00:34:53.590
construed into a confession that she had been in the wrong, and

00:34:53.590 --> 00:34:57.670
disciplined for bad that. So she kept silence, and went about her

00:34:57.670 --> 00:35:02.290
affairs with a troubled heart. Tom sulked in a corner and exalted his

00:35:02.290 --> 00:35:07.010
woes. He knew that in her heart his aunt was on her knees to him, and

00:35:07.010 --> 00:35:11.370
he was morosely gratified by the consciousness of it. He would hang out

00:35:11.370 --> 00:35:16.150
with no signals. He would take notice of none. He knew that a yearning

00:35:16.150 --> 00:35:19.910
glance fell upon him now and then through a film of tears, but he

00:35:19.910 --> 00:35:24.010
refused recognition of it. He pictured himself lying sick unto death,

00:35:24.010 --> 00:35:27.550
and his aunt bending over him, beseeching one little forgiving word,

00:35:27.930 --> 00:35:32.030
but he would turn his face to the wall and die with that word unsaid.

00:35:32.510 --> 00:35:36.830
Ah, how would she feel then? And he pictured himself brought home from

00:35:36.830 --> 00:35:41.670
the river, dead, with his curls all wet and his sore heart at rest. How

00:35:41.670 --> 00:35:45.550
she would throw herself upon him, and how her tears would fall like

00:35:45.550 --> 00:35:50.350
rain, and her lips pray God to give her back her boy, and she would

00:35:50.350 --> 00:35:54.850
never, never abuse him any more. But he would lie there, cold and white

00:35:54.850 --> 00:35:59.250
and make no sign, a poor little sufferer whose griefs were at an end.

00:35:59.690 --> 00:36:03.810
He so worked upon his feelings with the pathos of these dreams that he

00:36:03.810 --> 00:36:08.310
had to keep swallowing. He was so like to choke. And his eyes swam in a

00:36:08.310 --> 00:36:12.330
blur of water which overflowed when he winked, and ran down and trickled

00:36:12.330 --> 00:36:16.730
from the end of his nose. And such a luxury to him was this petting of

00:36:16.730 --> 00:36:20.650
his sorrows that he could not bear to have any worldly cheeriness or

00:36:20.650 --> 00:36:24.790
any grating delight intrude upon it. It was too sacred for such contact.

00:36:25.110 --> 00:36:29.690
And so, presently, when his cousin Mary danced in, all alive with the

00:36:29.690 --> 00:36:33.790
joy of seeing home again after an age-long visit of one week to the

00:36:33.790 --> 00:36:38.490
country, he got up and moved in clouds and darkness out at one door as

00:36:38.490 --> 00:36:41.350
she brought song and sunshine in at the other.

00:36:41.790 --> 00:36:46.250
He wandered far from the accustomed haunts of boys, and sought desolate

00:36:46.250 --> 00:36:50.750
places that were in harmony with his spirit. A log raft in the river

00:36:50.750 --> 00:36:55.470
invited him, and he seated himself on its outer edge, and contemplated

00:36:55.470 --> 00:36:59.970
the dreary vastness of the stream, wishing the while that he could only

00:36:59.970 --> 00:37:04.730
at once and unconsciously, without undergoing the uncomfortable routine

00:37:04.730 --> 00:37:10.190
devised by nature. Then he thought of his flower. He got it out, rumpled

00:37:10.190 --> 00:37:14.750
and wilted, and it mightily increased his dismal felicity. He wondered

00:37:14.750 --> 00:37:19.510
if she would pity him if she knew. Would she cry, and wish that she had

00:37:19.510 --> 00:37:24.270
a right to put her arms round his neck and comfort him? Or would she

00:37:24.270 --> 00:37:28.730
turn coldly away like all the hollow world? This picture brought such

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:32.270
an agony of pleasurable suffering that he worked it over and over again

00:37:32.270 --> 00:37:36.610
in his mind, and set it up in new and varied lights till he wore it

00:37:36.610 --> 00:37:41.390
threadbare. At last he rose up, sighing, and departed in the darkness.

00:37:41.990 --> 00:37:45.570
About half-past nine or ten o'clock he came along the deserted street

00:37:45.570 --> 00:37:51.190
to where the adored unknown lived. He paused a moment. No sound fell

00:37:51.190 --> 00:37:55.370
upon his listening ear. A candle was casting a dull glow upon the

00:37:55.370 --> 00:37:59.950
curtain of a second-story window. Was the sacred presence there? He

00:37:59.950 --> 00:38:03.470
climbed the fence, threaded his stealthy way through the plants till

00:38:03.470 --> 00:38:07.350
he stood under that window. He looked up at it long and with emotion.

00:38:07.830 --> 00:38:11.610
Then he laid him down on the ground under it, disposing himself upon

00:38:11.610 --> 00:38:15.890
his back, with his hands clasped upon his breast and holding his poor

00:38:15.890 --> 00:38:20.810
wilted flower. And thus he would die, out in the cold world, with no

00:38:20.810 --> 00:38:24.790
shelter over his homeless head, no friendly hand to wipe the death

00:38:24.790 --> 00:38:29.710
lamps from his brow, no loving face to bend pittingly over him when the

00:38:29.710 --> 00:38:33.910
great agony came. And thus she would see him when she looked out upon

00:38:33.910 --> 00:38:38.570
the glad morning, and, oh, would she drop one little tear upon his poor

00:38:38.570 --> 00:38:43.230
lifeless form, would she heave one little sigh to see a bright young

00:38:43.230 --> 00:38:48.570
life so rudely blighted, so untimely cut down. The window went up, a

00:38:48.570 --> 00:38:52.410
maid-servant's discordant voice profaned the holy calm, and a deluge of

00:38:52.410 --> 00:38:56.730
water drenched the prone martyr's remains. The strangling hero sprang up

00:38:56.730 --> 00:39:00.310
with a relieving snort. There was a whiz as of a missile in the air,

00:39:00.590 --> 00:39:04.750
mingled with a murmur of a curse, a sound as of shivering glass followed,

00:39:05.050 --> 00:39:08.550
and a small vague form went over the fence and shot away in the gloom.

00:39:09.250 --> 00:39:14.030
Not long after, as Tom, all undressed for bed, was surveying his

00:39:14.030 --> 00:39:18.410
drenched garments by the light of a tallow-dip, Sid woke up. But if he

00:39:18.410 --> 00:39:22.610
had any dim idea of making any references to illusions, he thought

00:39:22.610 --> 00:39:27.550
better of it and held his peace, for there was danger in Tom's eye. Tom

00:39:27.550 --> 00:39:31.990
turned in without the added vexation of prayers, and Sid made mental

00:39:31.990 --> 00:39:33.250
note of the admission.

00:39:37.290 --> 00:39:38.570
CHAPTER IV.

00:39:39.030 --> 00:39:40.610
SHOWING OFF IN SUNDAY SCHOOL.

00:39:42.090 --> 00:39:46.130
The sun rose upon a tranquil world and beamed down upon the peaceful

00:39:46.130 --> 00:39:50.990
village like a benediction. Breakfast over, Aunt Polly had family

00:39:50.990 --> 00:39:55.290
worship. It began with a prayer built from the ground up of solid

00:39:55.290 --> 00:39:59.530
courses of scriptural quotations, welded together with a thin mortar of

00:39:59.530 --> 00:40:03.490
originality. And from the summit of this she delivered a grim chapter

00:40:03.490 --> 00:40:08.910
of the Mosaic Law, as from Sinai. Then Tom girded up his loins, so to

00:40:08.910 --> 00:40:13.170
speak, and went to work to get his verses. Sid had learned his lesson

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:17.570
days before. Tom bent all his energies to the memorizing of five

00:40:17.570 --> 00:40:21.150
verses, and he chose part of the Sermon on the Mount, because he could

00:40:21.150 --> 00:40:25.530
find no verses that were shorter. At the end of half an hour Tom had a

00:40:25.530 --> 00:40:29.710
vague general idea of his lesson, but no more, for his mind was

00:40:29.710 --> 00:40:33.210
traversing the whole field of human thought, and his hands were busy

00:40:33.210 --> 00:40:37.730
with distracting recreations. Mary took his book to hear him recite,

00:40:37.850 --> 00:40:40.410
and he tried to find his way through the fog.

00:40:41.290 --> 00:40:52.990
Blessed are the poor in spirit. Blessed are the poor in spirit, for

00:40:52.990 --> 00:41:00.510
they theirs. Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom

00:41:00.510 --> 00:41:12.230
of heaven. Blessed are they that mourn, for they, oh, I don't know

00:41:12.230 --> 00:41:22.670
what it is, shall, oh, shall, for they shall mourn. Blessed are they

00:41:23.270 --> 00:41:30.930
that mourn, for they shall, uh, shall what? Why don't you tell me,

00:41:31.030 --> 00:41:35.810
Mary? What do you want to be so mean for? Oh, Tom, you poor thick-headed

00:41:35.810 --> 00:41:39.050
thing, I'm not teasing you, I wouldn't do that. You must go and learn

00:41:39.050 --> 00:41:43.150
it again. Don't you be discouraged, Tom, you'll manage it, and if you do

00:41:43.150 --> 00:41:46.870
I'll give you something ever so nice. There, now, that's a good boy.

00:41:47.610 --> 00:41:51.890
All right, what is it, Mary? Tell me what it is. Never you mind, Tom,

00:41:51.890 --> 00:41:56.470
you know if I say it's nice, it is nice. You bet you that's so, Mary,

00:41:56.650 --> 00:42:00.910
all right, I'll tackle it again. And he did tackle it again, and under

00:42:00.910 --> 00:42:05.010
the double pressure of curiosity and perspective gain, he did it with

00:42:05.010 --> 00:42:08.990
such spirit that he accomplished a shining success. Mary gave him a

00:42:08.990 --> 00:42:12.870
brand-new Barlow knife worth twelve and a half cents, and the

00:42:12.870 --> 00:42:15.910
convulsion of delight that swept his system shook him to his

00:42:15.910 --> 00:42:20.150
foundations. True, the knife would not cut anything, but it was a sure

00:42:20.150 --> 00:42:24.470
enough Barlow, and there was inconceivable grandeur in that, though

00:42:24.470 --> 00:42:27.450
where the Western boys ever got the idea that such a weapon could

00:42:27.450 --> 00:42:31.470
possibly be counterfeited to its injury is an imposing mystery and will

00:42:31.470 --> 00:42:35.750
always remain so, perhaps. Tom contrived to scarify the cupboard with

00:42:35.750 --> 00:42:39.870
it, and was arranging to begin on the bureau, when he was called off to

00:42:39.870 --> 00:42:41.010
dress for Sunday school.

00:42:41.750 --> 00:42:45.330
Mary gave him a tin basin of water and a piece of soap, and he went

00:42:45.330 --> 00:42:48.750
outside the door and set the basin on a little bench there. Then he

00:42:48.750 --> 00:42:52.090
dipped the soap in the water and laid it down, turned up his sleeves,

00:42:52.450 --> 00:42:56.210
poured out the water on the ground gently, and then entered the kitchen

00:42:56.210 --> 00:43:00.910
and began to wipe his face diligently on the towel behind the door. But

00:43:00.910 --> 00:43:02.410
Mary removed the towel and said,

00:43:02.750 --> 00:43:07.850
"'Now ain't you ashamed, Tom? You mustn't be so bad. Water won't hurt

00:43:07.850 --> 00:43:12.970
you.' Tom was a trifle disconcerted. The basin was refilled, and this

00:43:12.970 --> 00:43:16.610
time he stood over it a little while, gathering resolution, took in a

00:43:16.610 --> 00:43:20.290
big breath, and began. When he entered the kitchen presently, with both

00:43:20.290 --> 00:43:23.690
eyes shut and groping for the towel with his hands, an honourable

00:43:23.690 --> 00:43:27.610
testimony of suds and water was dripping from his face. But when he

00:43:27.610 --> 00:43:31.370
emerged from the towel he was not yet satisfactory, for the clean

00:43:31.370 --> 00:43:36.490
territory stopped short at his chin and his jaws like a mask. Below

00:43:36.490 --> 00:43:41.230
and beyond this line there was a dark expanse of unirrigated soil that

00:43:41.230 --> 00:43:45.370
spread downward in front and backward around his neck. Mary took him in

00:43:45.370 --> 00:43:49.970
hand, and when she was done with him he was a man and a brother without

00:43:49.970 --> 00:43:54.190
distinction of colour, and his saturated hair was neatly brushed and its

00:43:54.190 --> 00:43:58.770
short curls wrought into a dainty and symmetrical general effect. He

00:43:58.770 --> 00:44:01.950
privately smoothed out the curls with labour and difficulty and

00:44:01.950 --> 00:44:05.810
plastered his hair close down to his head, for he held curls to be

00:44:05.810 --> 00:44:10.930
effeminate, and his own filled his life with bitterness. Then Mary got

00:44:10.930 --> 00:44:14.910
out a suit of his clothing that had been used only on Sundays during two

00:44:14.910 --> 00:44:20.570
years. They were simply called his other clothes, and so by that we know

00:44:20.570 --> 00:44:25.110
the size of his wardrobe. The girl put him to rights after he had dressed

00:44:25.110 --> 00:44:29.870
himself, she buttoned his neat roundabout up to his chin, turned his

00:44:29.870 --> 00:44:34.090
vast shirt collar down over his shoulders, brushed him off and crowned

00:44:34.090 --> 00:44:38.390
him with his speckled straw hat. He now looked exceedingly improved and

00:44:38.390 --> 00:44:42.930
uncomfortable. He was fully as uncomfortable as he looked, for there was

00:44:42.930 --> 00:44:47.270
a restraint about whole clothes and cleanliness that galled him. He

00:44:47.270 --> 00:44:51.530
hoped that Mary would forget his shoes, but the hope was blighted. She

00:44:51.530 --> 00:44:55.670
coated them thoroughly with tallow, as was the custom, and brought them

00:44:55.670 --> 00:44:59.550
out. He lost his temper and said he was always being made to do

00:44:59.550 --> 00:45:02.830
everything he didn't want to do, but Mary said persuasively,

00:45:02.890 --> 00:45:07.430
"'Please, Tom, that's a good boy.' So he got into the shoes, snarling.

00:45:07.950 --> 00:45:11.410
Mary was soon ready, and the three children set out for Sunday school,

00:45:11.410 --> 00:45:15.750
a place that Tom hated with his whole heart, but Sid and Mary were fond

00:45:15.750 --> 00:45:21.170
of. Sabbath school hours were from nine to half-past ten, and then

00:45:21.170 --> 00:45:24.790
church service. Two of the children always remained for the sermon

00:45:24.790 --> 00:45:28.510
voluntarily, and the other always remained too, for stronger reasons.

00:45:29.190 --> 00:45:32.930
The church's high-backed, uncushioned pews would seat about three

00:45:32.930 --> 00:45:37.190
hundred persons. The edifice was but a small plain affair, with a sort

00:45:37.190 --> 00:45:42.190
pine-bored tree-box on top of it, for a steeple. At the door, Tom

00:45:42.190 --> 00:45:45.390
dropped back a step and accosted a Sunday-dressed comrade.

00:45:45.730 --> 00:45:48.130
"'Say, Billy, got a yaller ticket?'

00:45:48.750 --> 00:45:49.270
"'Yes.'

00:45:49.270 --> 00:45:50.730
"'Well, you take for her.'

00:45:50.730 --> 00:45:51.450
"'Well, you give.'

00:45:51.970 --> 00:45:54.850
"'Piece of licorice and a fish-hook. Let's see them.'

00:45:55.390 --> 00:45:59.430
Tom exhibited. They were satisfactory, and the property changed hands.

00:45:59.930 --> 00:46:04.030
Then Tom traded a couple of white alleys for three red tickets, and

00:46:04.030 --> 00:46:06.630
some small trifle or other for a couple of blue ones.

00:46:06.630 --> 00:46:10.470
He waylaid other boys as they came, and went on buying tickets of

00:46:10.470 --> 00:46:14.750
various colors ten or fifteen minutes longer. He entered the church,

00:46:14.910 --> 00:46:18.790
now with a swarm of clean and noisy boys and girls, proceeded to his

00:46:18.790 --> 00:46:22.650
seat, and started a quarrel with the first boy that came handy. The

00:46:22.650 --> 00:46:26.450
teacher, a grave elderly man, interfered, then turned his back a

00:46:26.450 --> 00:46:30.010
moment, and Tom pulled a boy's hair in the next bench, and was

00:46:30.010 --> 00:46:34.050
absorbed in his book when the boy turned round. Stuck a pin in another

00:46:34.050 --> 00:46:37.750
boy presently in order to hear him say, Ouch!, and got a new reprimand

00:46:37.750 --> 00:46:42.610
from his teacher. Tom's whole class were of a pattern, restless, noisy,

00:46:42.770 --> 00:46:46.730
and troublesome. When they came to recite their lessons, not one of

00:46:46.730 --> 00:46:50.070
them knew his verses perfectly, but had to be prompted all along.

00:46:50.690 --> 00:46:55.050
However, they worried through, and each got his reward in small blue

00:46:55.050 --> 00:46:59.030
tickets, each with a passage of scripture on it. Each blue ticket was

00:46:59.510 --> 00:47:04.350
two verses of the recitation. Ten blue tickets equaled a red one, and

00:47:04.350 --> 00:47:08.570
could be exchanged for it. Ten red tickets equaled a yellow one. For

00:47:08.570 --> 00:47:12.610
ten yellow tickets the superintendent gave a very plainly bound Bible

00:47:12.610 --> 00:47:17.950
worth forty cents in those easy days to the pupil. How many of my

00:47:17.950 --> 00:47:21.510
readers would have the industry and application to memorize two thousand

00:47:21.510 --> 00:47:26.290
verses even for a Doray Bible, and yet Mary had acquired two Bibles in

00:47:26.290 --> 00:47:30.730
this way? It was the patient work of two years, and a boy of German

00:47:30.730 --> 00:47:35.750
parentage had won four or five. He once recited three thousand verses

00:47:35.750 --> 00:47:40.230
without stopping. But the strain upon his mental faculties was too

00:47:40.230 --> 00:47:44.870
great, and he was little better than an idiot from that day forth. A

00:47:44.870 --> 00:47:48.410
grievous misfortune for the school, for on great occasions before

00:47:48.410 --> 00:47:52.750
company the superintendent, as Tom expressed it, had always made this

00:47:52.750 --> 00:47:57.430
boy come out and spread himself. Only the older pupils managed to keep

00:47:57.430 --> 00:48:00.570
their tickets and stick to their tedious work long enough to get a

00:48:00.570 --> 00:48:04.630
Bible, and so the delivery of one of these prizes was a rare and

00:48:04.630 --> 00:48:08.530
noteworthy circumstance. The successful pupil was so great and

00:48:08.530 --> 00:48:12.690
conspicuous for that day that on the spot every scholar's heart was

00:48:12.690 --> 00:48:17.430
fired with a fresh ambition that often lasted a couple of weeks. It is

00:48:17.430 --> 00:48:21.070
possible that Tom's mental stomach had never really hungered for one

00:48:21.070 --> 00:48:25.910
of those prizes. But unquestionably his entire being had for many a

00:48:25.910 --> 00:48:31.530
day longed for the glory and the eclat that came with it. In due course

00:48:31.530 --> 00:48:35.410
the superintendent stood up in front of the pulpit with a closed hymn

00:48:35.410 --> 00:48:39.350
book in his hand, and his forefinger inserted between its leaves, and

00:48:39.350 --> 00:48:42.930
commanded attention. When a Sunday school superintendent makes his

00:48:42.930 --> 00:48:46.890
customary little speech, a hymn book in the hand is as necessary as is

00:48:46.890 --> 00:48:50.410
the inevitable sheet of music in the hand of a singer who stands

00:48:50.410 --> 00:48:55.770
forward on the platform and sings a solo at a concert. Though why is a

00:48:55.770 --> 00:48:59.470
mystery, for neither the hymn book nor the sheet of music is ever

00:48:59.470 --> 00:49:04.050
referred to by the sufferer. This superintendent was a slim creature of

00:49:04.050 --> 00:49:09.170
thirty-five, with a sandy goatee and short sandy hair. He wore a stiff

00:49:09.170 --> 00:49:13.390
standing collar whose upper edge almost reached his ears, and whose

00:49:13.390 --> 00:49:17.310
sharp points curved forward abreast the corners of his mouth, a fence

00:49:17.310 --> 00:49:21.210
that compelled a straight look out ahead and a turning of the whole body

00:49:21.210 --> 00:49:24.770
when a side view was required. His chin was propped on a spreading

00:49:24.770 --> 00:49:29.470
cravat which was as broad and as long as a bank-note, and had fringed

00:49:29.470 --> 00:49:33.790
ends. His boot-toes were turned sharply up, in the fashion of the day,

00:49:34.130 --> 00:49:37.950
like sleigh-runners, an effect patiently and laboriously produced by

00:49:37.950 --> 00:49:41.230
the young men by sitting with their toes pressed against a wall for

00:49:41.230 --> 00:49:46.890
hours together. Mr. Walters was very earnest of mien, and very sincere

00:49:46.890 --> 00:49:50.930
and honest at heart. And he held sacred things and places in such

00:49:50.930 --> 00:49:55.310
reverence, and so separated them from worldly matters, that unconsciously

00:49:55.310 --> 00:49:59.250
to himself his Sunday-school voice had acquired a peculiar intonation,

00:49:59.670 --> 00:50:04.130
which was wholly absent on week-days. He began after this fashion,

00:50:04.810 --> 00:50:09.970
"'Now, children, I want you all to sit up just as straight and pretty as

00:50:09.970 --> 00:50:14.510
you can, and give me all your attention for a minute or two. There,

00:50:14.510 --> 00:50:19.550
that is it. That is the way good little boys and girls should do. I see

00:50:19.550 --> 00:50:23.450
one little girl who is looking out of the window. I am afraid she thinks

00:50:23.450 --> 00:50:27.870
I am out there somewhere, perhaps up in one of the trees making a speech

00:50:27.870 --> 00:50:30.870
to the little birds.' A plosive titter.

00:50:31.730 --> 00:50:36.050
"'I want to tell you how good it makes me feel to see so many bright

00:50:36.050 --> 00:50:40.050
clean little faces assembled in a place like this, learning to do right

00:50:40.050 --> 00:50:44.830
and be good,' and so forth and so on. It is not necessary to set down

00:50:44.830 --> 00:50:48.990
the rest of the oration. It was of a pattern which does not vary, and so

00:50:48.990 --> 00:50:53.530
it is familiar to us all. The latter third of the speech was marred by

00:50:53.530 --> 00:50:57.170
the resumption of fights and other recreations among certain of the bad

00:50:57.170 --> 00:51:01.430
boys, and by fidgetings and whisperings that extended far and wide,

00:51:01.930 --> 00:51:06.130
washing even to the bases of isolated and incorruptible rocks like Sid

00:51:06.130 --> 00:51:11.170
and Mary. But now every sound ceased suddenly, with the subsidence of

00:51:11.170 --> 00:51:15.310
Mr. Walter's voice and the conclusion of the speech was received with a

00:51:15.310 --> 00:51:19.410
burst of silent gratitude. A good part of the whispering had been

00:51:19.410 --> 00:51:23.050
occasioned by an event which was more or less rare—the entrance of

00:51:23.050 --> 00:51:28.250
visitors, lawyer Thatcher, accompanied by a very feeble and aged man, a

00:51:28.250 --> 00:51:32.990
fine, portly middle-aged gentleman with iron-grey hair, and a dignified

00:51:32.990 --> 00:51:37.030
lady who was doubtless the latter's wife. The lady was leading a child.

00:51:37.270 --> 00:51:41.490
Tom had been restless and full of chaffings and repinings, conscience

00:51:41.490 --> 00:51:45.950
smitten too—he could not meet Amy Lawrence's eye—he could not brook

00:51:45.950 --> 00:51:50.570
her loving gaze. But when he saw this small newcomer his soul was all

00:51:50.570 --> 00:51:54.230
ablaze with bliss in a moment. The next moment he was showing off with

00:51:54.230 --> 00:51:58.250
all his might, cuffing boys, pulling hair, making faces—in a word,

00:51:58.430 --> 00:52:02.290
using every art that seemed likely to fascinate a girl and win her

00:52:02.290 --> 00:52:07.430
applause. His exultations had but one alloy—the memory of his

00:52:07.430 --> 00:52:12.070
humiliation in this angel's garden—and that record in sand was fast

00:52:12.070 --> 00:52:15.430
washing out under the waves of happiness that were sweeping over it

00:52:15.430 --> 00:52:20.190
now. The visitors were given the highest seat of honour, and as soon as

00:52:20.190 --> 00:52:23.830
Mr. Walter's speech was finished he introduced them to the school. The

00:52:23.830 --> 00:52:28.390
middle-aged man turned out to be a prodigious personage, no less a one

00:52:28.390 --> 00:52:32.870
than the county judge, altogether the most august creation these

00:52:32.870 --> 00:52:36.570
children had ever looked upon, and they wondered what kind of material

00:52:36.570 --> 00:52:40.730
he was made of, and they half wanted to hear him roar, and were half

00:52:40.730 --> 00:52:45.670
afraid he might too. He was from Constantinople, twelve miles away, so

00:52:45.670 --> 00:52:50.050
he had travelled, and seen the world. These very eyes had looked upon

00:52:50.050 --> 00:52:55.190
the county courthouse, which was said to have a tin roof. The awe which

00:52:55.190 --> 00:52:59.630
these reflections inspired was attested by the impressive silences and

00:52:59.630 --> 00:53:04.630
the ranks of staring eyes. This was the great Judge Thatcher, brother of

00:53:04.630 --> 00:53:08.870
their own lawyer. Jeff Thatcher immediately went forward to be familiar

00:53:08.870 --> 00:53:12.450
with the great man, and be envied by the school. It would have been

00:53:12.450 --> 00:53:14.630
music to his soul to hear the whisperings,

00:53:14.910 --> 00:53:18.770
"'Look at him, Jim, he's a-goin' up there. Say, look, he's a-goin' to

00:53:18.770 --> 00:53:22.290
shake hands with him. He is shakin' hands with him. By jinx, don't you

00:53:22.290 --> 00:53:26.930
wish you was Jeff?' Mr. Walters fell to showing off, with all sorts of

00:53:26.930 --> 00:53:30.950
official bustlings and activities, giving orders and delivering judgments,

00:53:31.550 --> 00:53:35.750
discharging directions here, there, everywhere, that he could find a

00:53:35.750 --> 00:53:39.690
target. The librarian showed off, running hither and thither with his

00:53:39.690 --> 00:53:43.930
arms full of books, and making a deal of the splutter and fuss that

00:53:43.930 --> 00:53:48.750
insect authority delights in. The young lady-teacher showed off, bending

00:53:48.750 --> 00:53:53.290
sweetly over pupils that were lately being boxed, lifting pretty warning

00:53:53.290 --> 00:53:57.550
fingers at bad little boys, and patting good ones lovingly. The young

00:53:57.550 --> 00:54:01.610
gentleman-teachers showed off with small scoldings and other little

00:54:01.610 --> 00:54:05.970
displays of authority and fine attention to discipline, and most of the

00:54:05.970 --> 00:54:10.130
teachers of both sexes found business up at the library by the pulpit.

00:54:10.490 --> 00:54:14.530
And it was business that frequently had to be done over again two or

00:54:14.530 --> 00:54:19.570
three times, with much seeming vexation. The little girls showed off in

00:54:19.570 --> 00:54:23.430
various ways, and the little boys showed off with such diligence that

00:54:23.430 --> 00:54:27.930
the air was thick with paper wads and the murmur of scuffling. And above

00:54:27.930 --> 00:54:32.530
it all the great man sat and beamed a majestic judicial smile upon all

00:54:32.530 --> 00:54:37.730
the house, and warmed himself in the sun of his own grandeur, for he was

00:54:37.730 --> 00:54:38.990
showing off, too.

00:54:39.990 --> 00:54:43.630
There was only one thing wanting to make Mr. Walters' ecstasy complete,

00:54:43.630 --> 00:54:48.010
and that was a chance to deliver a Bible prize and exhibit a prodigy.

00:54:48.350 --> 00:54:52.890
Several pupils had a few yellow tickets, but none had enough, and he had

00:54:52.890 --> 00:54:57.410
been around among the star pupils inquiring. He would have given worlds

00:54:57.410 --> 00:55:02.230
now to have that German lad back again with a sound mind. And now at this

00:55:02.230 --> 00:55:06.490
moment, when hope was dead, Tom Sawyer came forward with nine yellow

00:55:06.490 --> 00:55:12.750
tickets, nine red tickets, and ten blue ones, and demanded a Bible. This

00:55:12.750 --> 00:55:17.490
was a thunderbolt out of a clear sky. Walters was not expecting an

00:55:17.490 --> 00:55:21.370
application from this source for the next ten years, but there was no

00:55:21.370 --> 00:55:24.890
getting around it. Here were the certified checks, and they were good

00:55:24.890 --> 00:55:29.170
for their face. Tom was therefore elevated to a place with a judge and

00:55:29.170 --> 00:55:33.130
the other elect, and the great news was announced from headquarters. It

00:55:33.130 --> 00:55:36.750
was the most stunning surprise of the decade, and so profound was the

00:55:36.750 --> 00:55:40.450
sensation that it lifted the new hero up to the judicial one's altitude,

00:55:40.450 --> 00:55:45.410
and the school had two marvels to gaze upon in place of one. The boys

00:55:45.410 --> 00:55:49.270
were all eaten up with envy, and those that suffered the bitterest pangs

00:55:49.270 --> 00:55:52.650
were those who perceived too late that they themselves had contributed to

00:55:52.650 --> 00:55:56.410
this hated splendour by trading tickets to Tom for the wealth he had

00:55:56.410 --> 00:56:01.330
amassed in selling whitewashing privileges. These despised themselves as

00:56:01.330 --> 00:56:06.250
being the dupes of a wily fraud, a guileful snake in the grass. The

00:56:06.250 --> 00:56:09.790
prize was delivered to Tom with as much effusion as the superintendent

00:56:09.790 --> 00:56:13.790
could pump up under the circumstances, but it lacked somewhat of the

00:56:13.790 --> 00:56:17.930
true gush, for the poor fellow's instinct taught him that there was a

00:56:17.930 --> 00:56:22.570
mystery here that could not well bear the light, perhaps. It was simply

00:56:22.570 --> 00:56:27.190
preposterous that this boy had warehoused two thousand sheaves of

00:56:27.190 --> 00:56:31.510
scriptural wisdom on his premises. A dozen would strain his capacity

00:56:31.510 --> 00:56:35.850
without a doubt. Amy Lawrence was proud and glad, and she tried to make

00:56:35.850 --> 00:56:40.770
Tom see it in her face, but he wouldn't look. She wondered. Then she was

00:56:40.770 --> 00:56:45.670
just a grain troubled. Next a dim suspicion came and went, came again.

00:56:46.110 --> 00:56:50.610
She watched, a furtive glance told her worlds, and then her heart broke,

00:56:50.710 --> 00:56:54.150
and she was jealous, and angry, and the tears came, and she hated

00:56:54.150 --> 00:56:58.290
everybody. Tom, most of all, she thought. Tom was introduced to the

00:56:58.290 --> 00:57:02.730
judge, but his tongue was tied, his breath would hardly come, his heart

00:57:02.730 --> 00:57:06.310
quaked, partly because of the awful greatness of the man, but mainly

00:57:06.310 --> 00:57:10.990
because he was her parent. He would have liked to fall down and worship

00:57:10.990 --> 00:57:14.550
him if it were in the dark. The judge put his hand on Tom's head and

00:57:14.550 --> 00:57:18.650
called him a fine little man, and asked him what his name was. The boy

00:57:18.650 --> 00:57:20.990
stammered, gasped, and got it out.

00:57:21.310 --> 00:57:21.790
Tom.

00:57:22.490 --> 00:57:25.610
Oh, no, not Tom. It is—

00:57:25.610 --> 00:57:26.390
Thomas.

00:57:27.190 --> 00:57:31.470
Ah, that's it. I thought there was more to it, maybe. That's very well.

00:57:31.470 --> 00:57:35.350
But you've another one, I dare say. And you'll tell it to me, won't you?

00:57:35.610 --> 00:57:39.930
Tell the gentleman your other name, Thomas, said Walters, and say Sir—you

00:57:39.930 --> 00:57:44.390
mustn't forget your manners—Thomas Sawyer, Sir. That's it. That's a

00:57:44.390 --> 00:57:49.210
good boy. Fine, boy, fine manly little fellow. Two thousand verses is a

00:57:49.210 --> 00:57:53.210
great many, very, very great many, and you never can be sorry for the

00:57:53.210 --> 00:57:56.550
trouble you took to learn them. For knowledge is worth more than

00:57:56.550 --> 00:58:00.290
anything there is in the world. It's what makes great men and good men.

00:58:00.290 --> 00:58:04.970
You'll be a great man and a good man yourself some day, Thomas, and then

00:58:04.970 --> 00:58:08.750
you'll look back and say, it's all owing to the precious Sunday school

00:58:08.750 --> 00:58:12.870
privileges of my boyhood. It's all owing to my dear teachers that taught

00:58:12.870 --> 00:58:17.410
me to learn. It's all owing to the good superintendent who encouraged me

00:58:17.410 --> 00:58:22.070
and watched over me and gave me a beautiful Bible—a splendid, elegant

00:58:22.070 --> 00:58:27.310
Bible to keep and have it all for my own, always. It's all owing to right

00:58:27.310 --> 00:58:32.090
That is what you will say, Thomas, and you wouldn't take any money for

00:58:32.090 --> 00:58:36.110
those two thousand verses, no, indeed you wouldn't. And now you wouldn't

00:58:36.110 --> 00:58:39.990
mind telling me and this lady some of the things you've learned. No, I

00:58:39.990 --> 00:58:44.290
know you wouldn't, for we are proud of little boys that learn. Now, no

00:58:44.290 --> 00:58:47.950
doubt you know the names of all the twelve disciples. Won't you tell us

00:58:47.950 --> 00:58:50.090
the names of the first two that were appointed?

00:58:50.790 --> 00:58:54.970
Tom was tugging at a button-hole and looking sheepish. He blushed now,

00:58:54.970 --> 00:58:59.950
and his eyes fell. Mr. Walter's heart sank within him. He said to

00:58:59.950 --> 00:59:03.530
himself, it is not possible that the boy can answer the simplest

00:59:03.530 --> 00:59:08.950
question. Why did the judge ask him? Yet he felt obliged to speak up

00:59:08.950 --> 00:59:09.530
and say,

00:59:09.910 --> 00:59:14.610
"'Answer the gentleman, Thomas. Don't be afraid.' Tom still hung fire.

00:59:15.190 --> 00:59:20.290
Now I know you'll tell me,' said the lady. The names of the first two

00:59:20.290 --> 00:59:23.590
disciples were David and Goliath.

00:59:24.290 --> 00:59:29.250
Let us draw the curtain of charity over the rest of the scene. End of

00:59:29.250 --> 00:59:30.430
Chapter 4

00:59:45.710 --> 00:59:50.770
V. The Pinch-Bug and His Prey.

00:59:51.430 --> 00:59:57.270
About half-past ten the cracked bell of the small church began to ring, and presently

00:59:57.270 --> 01:00:02.290
the people began to gather for the morning sermon. The Sunday-school children distributed

01:00:02.290 --> 01:00:07.970
themselves about the house, and occupied pews with their parents, so as to be under supervision.

01:00:08.670 --> 01:00:14.570
Aunt Polly came, and Tom and Sid and Mary sat with her, Tom being placed next to the

01:00:14.570 --> 01:00:20.470
aisle, in order that he might be as far away from the open window and the seductive outside

01:00:20.470 --> 01:00:26.470
summer scenes as possible. The crowd filed up the aisles, the aged and needy postmaster,

01:00:26.470 --> 01:00:32.650
who had seen better days, the mayor and his wife, for they had a mayor there, among other

01:00:32.650 --> 01:00:39.450
unnecessary, the justice of the peace, the widow Douglas, fair, smart and forty, a generous

01:00:39.450 --> 01:00:44.750
good-hearted soul and well-to-do, her hill mansion the only palace in the town, and the

01:00:44.750 --> 01:00:50.210
most hospitable and much the most lavish in the matter of festivities that St. Petersburg

01:00:50.210 --> 01:00:57.010
could boast, the bent and venerable major and Mrs. Ward, lawyer Riverson, they knew

01:00:57.010 --> 01:01:02.490
notable from a distance, next the bell of the village, followed by a troop of lawn-clad

01:01:02.490 --> 01:01:08.390
and ribbon-decked young heartbreakers, then all the young clerks in town in a body, for

01:01:08.390 --> 01:01:13.970
they had stood in the vestibule sucking their cane-heads, a circling wall of oiled and simpering

01:01:13.970 --> 01:01:17.270
admirers till the last girl had run their gauntlet.

01:01:17.670 --> 01:01:23.890
And last of all came the model-boy, Willie Mufferson, taking as heedful care of his mother

01:01:23.890 --> 01:01:29.510
as if she were cut glass. He always brought his mother to church, and was the pride of

01:01:29.510 --> 01:01:35.730
all the matrons. The boys all hated him, he was no good. And besides, he had been thrown

01:01:35.730 --> 01:01:41.910
up to them so much. His white handkerchief was hanging out of his pocket behind, as usual

01:01:41.910 --> 01:01:48.850
on Sundays, accidentally. Tom had no handkerchief, and he looked upon boys who had as snobs.

01:01:49.490 --> 01:01:55.390
The congregation, being fully assembled now, the bell rang once more, to warn laggards

01:01:55.390 --> 01:02:00.290
and stragglers, and then a solemn hush fell upon the church, which was only broken by

01:02:00.290 --> 01:02:04.770
the tittering and whispering of the choir in the gallery. The choir always tittered

01:02:04.770 --> 01:02:10.030
and whispered all through service. There was once a church choir that was not ill-bred,

01:02:10.030 --> 01:02:15.870
but I have forgotten where it was now. It was a great many years ago, and I can scarcely

01:02:15.870 --> 01:02:20.530
remember anything about it, but I think it was in some foreign country.

01:02:21.250 --> 01:02:26.370
The minister gave out the hymn, and read it through with a relish in a peculiar style,

01:02:26.450 --> 01:02:31.770
which was much admired in that part of the country. His voice began on a medium key,

01:02:31.890 --> 01:02:37.210
and climbed steadily up till it reached a certain point where it bore with strong emphasis

01:02:37.210 --> 01:02:42.070
the topmost word, and then plunged down as if from a spring-board.

01:02:43.050 --> 01:02:51.270
Shall I be carried to the skies On flowery beds of ease,

01:02:51.890 --> 01:02:58.450
Whilst others fight to win the prize And sail through bloody seas?

01:02:58.810 --> 01:03:04.610
He was regarded as a wonderful reader. At church, sociables, he was always called upon

01:03:04.610 --> 01:03:09.910
to read poetry, and when he was through, the ladies would lift up their hands and let

01:03:09.910 --> 01:03:16.610
them fall helplessly in their laps, and wall their eyes and shake their heads as much as

01:03:16.610 --> 01:03:23.550
to say, Words cannot express it, it is too beautiful, too beautiful for this mortal earth.

01:03:23.890 --> 01:03:29.210
After the hymn had been sung, the reverend Mr. Sprague turned himself into a bulletin-board,

01:03:29.210 --> 01:03:35.350
and read off notices of meetings and societies and things, till it seemed that the list would

01:03:35.350 --> 01:03:39.950
stretch out to the crack of doom, a queer custom which is still kept up in America even

01:03:39.950 --> 01:03:45.970
in cities away here in this age of abundant newspapers. Often the less there is to justify

01:03:45.970 --> 01:03:49.350
a traditional custom, the harder it is to get rid of it.

01:03:49.910 --> 01:03:57.330
And now the minister prayed. A good, generous prayer it was, and went into details. It pleaded

01:03:57.330 --> 01:04:01.730
for the church and the little children of the church, for the other churches of the

01:04:01.730 --> 01:04:08.330
village, for the village itself, for the county, for the state, for the state officers, for

01:04:08.330 --> 01:04:13.630
the United States, for the churches of the United States, for Congress, for the president,

01:04:14.170 --> 01:04:20.490
for the officers of the government, for poor sailors tossed by stormy seas, for the oppressed

01:04:20.490 --> 01:04:27.030
millions groaning under the heel of European monarchies and Oriental despotisms, for such

01:04:27.030 --> 01:04:32.610
as have the light and the good tidings, and yet have not eyes to see nor ears to hear

01:04:32.610 --> 01:04:37.610
withal, for the heathen in the far islands of the sea, and closed with a supplication

01:04:37.610 --> 01:04:43.250
that the words he was about to speak might find grace and favour, and be as seeds sown

01:04:43.250 --> 01:04:49.230
in fertile ground, yielding in time a grateful harvest of good. Amen.

01:04:50.050 --> 01:04:55.390
There was a rustling of dresses, and the standing congregation sat down. The boy whose history

01:04:55.390 --> 01:05:01.410
this book relates did not enjoy the prayer. He only endured it, if he even did that much.

01:05:01.790 --> 01:05:06.870
He was restive all through it. He kept tally of the details of the prayer unconsciously,

01:05:06.890 --> 01:05:11.270
for he was not listening, but he knew the ground of old and the clergyman's regular

01:05:11.270 --> 01:05:16.650
route over it, and when a little trifle of new matter was interlarded, his ear detected

01:05:16.650 --> 01:05:22.050
it, and his whole nature resented it. He considered additions unfair and scoundrelly.

01:05:22.590 --> 01:05:27.310
In the midst of the prayer a fly had lit on the back of the pew in front of him, and

01:05:27.310 --> 01:05:31.970
tortured his spirit by calmly rubbing its hands together, embracing its head with its

01:05:31.970 --> 01:05:36.210
arms, and polishing it so vigorously that it seemed to almost part company with the

01:05:36.210 --> 01:05:41.890
body, and the slender thread of a neck was exposed to view, scraping its wings with its

01:05:41.890 --> 01:05:46.970
hind legs and smoothing them to its body as if they had been coattails, going through

01:05:46.970 --> 01:05:52.310
its whole toilet as tranquilly as if it knew it was perfectly safe, as indeed it was,

01:05:52.650 --> 01:05:58.530
for as sorely as Tom's hands itched to grab for it, they did not dare. He believed his

01:05:58.530 --> 01:06:02.150
soul would be instantly destroyed if he did such a thing while the prayer was going on,

01:06:02.490 --> 01:06:07.950
but with the closing sentence his hand began to curve and steel forward, and the instant

01:06:07.950 --> 01:06:14.470
the Amen was out the fly was a prisoner of war. His aunt detected the act and made him

01:06:14.470 --> 01:06:15.090
let it go.

01:06:15.830 --> 01:06:20.030
The minister gave out his text and droned along monotonously through an argument that

01:06:20.030 --> 01:06:26.510
was so prosy that many ahead by and by began to nod, and yet it was an argument that dealt

01:06:26.510 --> 01:06:32.510
in limitless fire and brimstone and thinned the predestined elect down to a company so

01:06:32.510 --> 01:06:38.830
small as to be hardly worth the saving. Tom counted the pages of the sermon. After church

01:06:38.830 --> 01:06:43.430
he always knew how many pages there had been, but he seldom knew anything else about the

01:06:43.430 --> 01:06:48.450
discourse. However, this time he was really interested for a little while. The minister

01:06:48.450 --> 01:06:54.010
made a grand and moving picture of the assembling together of the world's hosts at the millennium,

01:06:54.330 --> 01:06:58.110
when the lion and the lamb should lie down together and a little child should lead them.

01:06:58.450 --> 01:07:03.830
But the pathos, the lesson, the moral of the great spectacle were lost upon the boy. He

01:07:03.830 --> 01:07:08.230
only thought of the conspicuousness of the principal character before the onlooking nations.

01:07:08.670 --> 01:07:13.270
His face lit with the thought, and he said to himself that he wished he could be that

01:07:13.270 --> 01:07:15.530
child if it was a tame lion.

01:07:16.450 --> 01:07:21.770
Now he lapsed into suffering again, as the dry argument was resumed. Presently he bethought

01:07:21.770 --> 01:07:28.370
him of a treasure he had and got it out. It was a large black beetle with formidable jaws—a

01:07:28.370 --> 01:07:33.610
pinch bug, he called it. It was in a percussion cap box. The first thing the beetle did was

01:07:33.610 --> 01:07:38.830
take him by the finger. A natural Philip followed. The beetle went floundering into the aisle

01:07:38.830 --> 01:07:44.530
and lit on its back, and the hurt finger went into the boy's mouth. The beetle lay there

01:07:44.530 --> 01:07:50.270
working its helpless legs, unable to turn over. Tom eyed it and longed for it, but it

01:07:50.270 --> 01:07:51.530
was safe out of his reach.

01:07:52.270 --> 01:07:56.770
Other people uninterested in the sermon found relief in the beetle, and they eyed it too.

01:07:57.290 --> 01:08:02.290
Presently a vagrant poodle dog came idling along, sad at heart, lazy with the summer

01:08:02.290 --> 01:08:08.670
and the quiet, weary of captivity, sighing for change. He spied the beetle. The drooping

01:08:08.670 --> 01:08:14.470
tail lifted and wagged. He surveyed the prize, walked around it, smelt at it from a safe

01:08:14.470 --> 01:08:21.130
distance, walked around it again, grew bolder, and took a closer smell. Then lifted his lip

01:08:21.130 --> 01:08:27.070
and made a gingerly snatch at it, just missing it, made another and another, began to enjoy

01:08:27.070 --> 01:08:32.070
the diversion, subsided to his stomach with the beetle between his paws, and continued

01:08:32.070 --> 01:08:37.010
his experiments. Grew weary at last, and then indifferent and absent-minded.

01:08:37.610 --> 01:08:42.070
His head nodded, and little by little his chin descended and touched the enemy who seized

01:08:42.070 --> 01:08:47.150
it. There was a sharp yelp, a flirt of the poodle's head, and the beetle fell a couple

01:08:47.150 --> 01:08:52.390
of yards away and lit on its back once more. The neighboring spectators shook with a gentle

01:08:52.390 --> 01:08:57.990
inward joy, several faces went behind fans and handkerchiefs, and Tom was entirely happy.

01:08:58.330 --> 01:09:02.850
The dog looked foolish and probably felt so, but there was resentment in his heart, too,

01:09:02.950 --> 01:09:08.490
and a craving for revenge. So he went to the beetle and began a wary attack on it again,

01:09:08.990 --> 01:09:13.270
jumping at it from every point of a circle, lighting with his forepaws within an inch

01:09:13.270 --> 01:09:18.210
of the creature, making even closer snatches at it with his teeth, and jerking his head

01:09:18.210 --> 01:09:24.070
till his ears flapped again. But he grew tired once more, after a while, tried to amuse himself

01:09:24.070 --> 01:09:29.170
with a fly, but found no relief, followed an ant around with his nose close to the floor,

01:09:29.490 --> 01:09:35.410
and quickly wearied of that, yawned, sighed, forgot the beetle entirely, and sat down on

01:09:35.410 --> 01:09:35.630
it.

01:09:36.210 --> 01:09:40.670
Then there was a wild yelp of agony, and the poodle went sailing up the aisle. The yelps

01:09:40.670 --> 01:09:45.490
continued, and so did the dog. He crossed the house in front of the altar. He flew down

01:09:45.490 --> 01:09:51.070
the other aisle. He crossed before the doors. He clamored up the homestretch. His anguish

01:09:51.070 --> 01:09:55.530
grew with his progress, till presently he was but a woolly comet moving in its orbit

01:09:55.530 --> 01:10:00.650
with a gleam and the speed of light. At last the frantic sufferer sheered from its course

01:10:00.650 --> 01:10:05.930
and sprang into its master's lap. He flung it out of the window, and the voice of distress

01:10:05.930 --> 01:10:10.850
quickly thinned away and died in the distance. By this time the whole church was red-faced

01:10:10.850 --> 01:10:15.650
and suffocating with suppressed laughter, and the sermon had come to a dead standstill.

01:10:15.650 --> 01:10:22.090
The discourse was resumed presently, but it went lame and halting, all possibility of

01:10:22.090 --> 01:10:26.930
impressiveness being at an end. For even the gravest sentiments were constantly being received

01:10:26.930 --> 01:10:32.430
with a smothered burst of unholy mirth, under cover of some remote pew-back, as if the poor

01:10:32.430 --> 01:10:37.990
parson had said a rarely facetious thing. It was a genuine relief to the whole congregation

01:10:37.990 --> 01:10:43.250
when the ordeal was over and the benediction pronounced. Tom Sawyer went home quite cheerful,

01:10:43.630 --> 01:10:48.990
thinking to himself that there was some satisfaction about divine service when there was a bit

01:10:48.990 --> 01:10:54.810
of variety in it. He had but one marring thought. He was willing that the dog should play with

01:10:54.810 --> 01:10:59.290
his pinch-bug, but he did not think it was upright in him to carry it off.

01:11:01.310 --> 01:11:02.430
CHAPTER VI.

01:11:03.050 --> 01:11:05.490
TOM MEETS BECKY

01:11:05.990 --> 01:11:11.530
Monday morning found Tom Sawyer miserable. Monday morning always found him so, because

01:11:11.530 --> 01:11:17.290
it began another week's slow suffering in school. He generally began that day with wishing

01:11:17.290 --> 01:11:22.530
he had had no intervening holiday. It made the going into captivity in fetters again

01:11:22.530 --> 01:11:29.570
so much more odious. Tom lay thinking. Presently it occurred to him that he wished he was sick,

01:11:30.010 --> 01:11:35.530
then he could stay home from school. Here was a vague possibility. He canvassed his

01:11:35.530 --> 01:11:42.210
system. No ailment was found, and he investigated again. This time he thought he could detect

01:11:42.210 --> 01:11:48.230
colicky symptoms, and he began to encourage them with considerable hope. But they soon

01:11:48.230 --> 01:11:54.170
grew feeble and presently died wholly away. He reflected further. Suddenly he discovered

01:11:54.170 --> 01:12:00.470
something. One of his upper front teeth was loose. This was lucky. He was about to begin

01:12:00.470 --> 01:12:05.570
to groan as a starter, as he called it, when it occurred to him that if he came into court

01:12:05.570 --> 01:12:10.430
with that argument, his aunt would pull it out, and that would hurt. So he thought he

01:12:10.430 --> 01:12:15.550
would hold a tooth in reserve for the present, and seek further. Nothing offered for some

01:12:15.550 --> 01:12:19.670
little time, and then he remembered hearing the doctor tell about a certain thing that

01:12:19.670 --> 01:12:23.550
laid up a patient for two or three weeks, and threatened to make him lose a finger.

01:12:24.190 --> 01:12:29.010
So the boy eagerly drew his sore toe from under the sheet, and held it up for inspection.

01:12:29.430 --> 01:12:35.030
But now he did not know the necessary symptoms. However, it seemed well worth while to chance

01:12:35.030 --> 01:12:41.470
it, so he fell to groaning with considerable spirit. But Sid slept on unconscious. Tom

01:12:41.470 --> 01:12:46.710
groaned louder, and fancied that he began to feel pain in the toe. No result from Sid.

01:12:47.530 --> 01:12:52.150
Tom was panting with his exertions by this time. He took a rest, and then swelled himself

01:12:52.150 --> 01:12:56.950
up and fetched a succession of admirable groans. Sid snored on.

01:12:57.710 --> 01:12:59.450
Tom was aggravated. He said,

01:12:59.550 --> 01:13:06.710
"'Sid! Sid!' and shook him. This course worked well, and Tom began to groan again. Sid yawned,

01:13:06.990 --> 01:13:10.830
stretched, then brought himself up on his elbow with a snort, and began to stare at

01:13:10.830 --> 01:13:13.790
Tom. Tom went on groaning, and Sid said,

01:13:14.310 --> 01:13:17.150
"'Tom! Say, Tom!' No response.

01:13:17.750 --> 01:13:23.750
"'Here, Tom. Tom! What is the matter, Tom?' And he shook him and looked in his face anxiously.

01:13:24.310 --> 01:13:25.470
Tom moaned out,

01:13:25.530 --> 01:13:29.450
"'Oh! Don't, Sid! Don't joggle me!'

01:13:29.450 --> 01:13:32.290
"'Why, what's the matter, Tom? I must call Auntie.'

01:13:32.290 --> 01:13:38.430
"'No, never mind. It'll be over by and by, maybe. Don't call anybody.'

01:13:38.430 --> 01:13:39.630
"'But I must.'

01:13:39.630 --> 01:13:43.410
"'Don't groan so, Tom. It's awful. How long you been this way?'

01:13:44.230 --> 01:13:44.850
"'Hours.'

01:13:44.850 --> 01:13:49.810
"'Ouch! Oh, don't stir so, Sid. You'll kill me.'

01:13:49.810 --> 01:13:51.670
"'Tom, why didn't you wake me sooner?'

01:13:51.670 --> 01:13:56.900
"'Oh, Tom, don't. It makes my flesh crawl to hear you. Tom, what is the matter?'

01:13:57.590 --> 01:14:05.170
"'I forgive you everything, Sid. Oh, everything you ever done to me. When I'm gone.'

01:14:05.170 --> 01:14:07.730
"'Tom, you ain't dying, are you?'

01:14:07.730 --> 01:14:10.750
"'Don't, Tom. Oh, don't. Maybe.'

01:14:10.750 --> 01:14:18.530
"'Oh, I forgive everything, Sid. Oh, tell him so, Sid. And, Sid, you give my window

01:14:18.530 --> 01:14:23.390
sash, and my cat with one eye to that new girl that's come to town, and tell her—'

01:14:23.570 --> 01:14:28.430
But Sid had snatched his clothes and gone. Tom was suffering in reality now, so handsomely

01:14:28.430 --> 01:14:34.290
was his imagination working, and so his groans had gathered quite a genuine tone. Sid flew

01:14:34.290 --> 01:14:35.250
downstairs and said,

01:14:35.270 --> 01:14:38.530
"'Oh, Aunt Polly, come! Tom's dying!'

01:14:39.210 --> 01:14:39.730
"'Dying?'

01:14:39.730 --> 01:14:43.850
"'Yes, and don't wait. Come, quick! Rubbish! I don't believe it!'

01:14:43.850 --> 01:14:48.910
But she fled upstairs, nevertheless, with Sid and Mary at her heels, and her face grew

01:14:48.910 --> 01:14:53.630
white too, and her lip trembled. When she reached the bedside, she gasped out,

01:14:53.850 --> 01:14:56.950
"'You, Tom! Tom, what's the matter with you?'

01:14:56.950 --> 01:15:02.030
"'Oh, Auntie, I'm—what's the matter with you? What is the matter with you, child?'

01:15:02.030 --> 01:15:06.190
"'Oh, Auntie, my sore toe's mortified!'

01:15:06.190 --> 01:15:10.430
The old lady sank down into the chair and laughed a little, then cried a little, then

01:15:10.430 --> 01:15:13.610
did both together. This restored her, and she said,

01:15:13.810 --> 01:15:19.470
"'Tom, what a turn you did give me! Now you shut up that nonsense and climb out of this!'

01:15:19.470 --> 01:15:23.930
The groans ceased, and the pain vanished from the toe. The boy felt a little foolish, and

01:15:23.930 --> 01:15:24.310
he said,

01:15:24.870 --> 01:15:29.670
"'Aunt Polly, it seemed mortified, and it hurt so I never minded my tooth at all.'

01:15:30.210 --> 01:15:32.950
"'Your tooth, indeed. What's the matter with your tooth?'

01:15:32.950 --> 01:15:36.450
"'One of them's loose, and it aches perfectly awful.'

01:15:36.450 --> 01:15:41.870
"'There, there, now, don't begin that groaning again. Open your mouth. Well, your tooth

01:15:41.870 --> 01:15:46.970
is loose, but you're not going to die about that. Mary, get me a silk thread, and a chunk

01:15:46.970 --> 01:15:48.650
of fire out of the kitchen.'

01:15:48.650 --> 01:15:49.410
Tom said,

01:15:49.490 --> 01:15:54.250
"'Oh, please, Auntie, don't pull it out. It don't hurt any more. I wish I may never stir

01:15:54.250 --> 01:15:58.430
if it does. Please don't, Auntie. I don't want to stay home from school.'

01:15:58.950 --> 01:16:04.250
"'Oh, you don't, don't you? So all this raw was because you thought you'd get to stay

01:16:04.250 --> 01:16:10.070
home from school and go fishing. Tom, Tom, I love you so, and you seem to try every

01:16:10.070 --> 01:16:13.470
way you can to break my old heart with your outrageousness.'

01:16:13.470 --> 01:16:18.490
By this time the dental instruments were ready. The old lady made one end of the silk thread

01:16:18.490 --> 01:16:23.910
fast to Tom's tooth with a loop, and tied the other to the bed-post. Then she seized

01:16:23.910 --> 01:16:28.730
the chunk of fire, and suddenly thrust it almost into the boy's face, the tooth hung

01:16:28.730 --> 01:16:30.550
dangling by the bed-post now.

01:16:31.210 --> 01:16:37.350
But all trials bring their compensations. As Tom wended to school after breakfast, he

01:16:37.350 --> 01:16:41.910
was the envy of every boy he met because the gap in his upper row of teeth enabled him

01:16:41.910 --> 01:16:47.630
to expectorate in a new and admirable way. He gathered quite a following of lads interested

01:16:47.630 --> 01:16:52.330
in the exhibition, and one that had cut his finger and had been a centre of fascination

01:16:52.330 --> 01:16:57.630
and homage up to this time, now found himself suddenly without an adherent and shorn of

01:16:57.630 --> 01:17:02.650
his glory. His heart was heavy, and he said with a disdain which he did not feel that

01:17:02.650 --> 01:17:08.610
it wasn't anything to spit like Tom Sawyer, but another boy said, Sour Grapes, and he

01:17:08.610 --> 01:17:10.610
wandered away a dismantled hero.

01:17:11.330 --> 01:17:16.290
Shortly Tom came upon the juvenile pariah of the village, Huckleberry Finn, son of the

01:17:16.290 --> 01:17:21.750
town drunkard. Huckleberry was cordially hated and dreaded by all the mothers of the town,

01:17:22.110 --> 01:17:28.010
because he was idle, and lawless, and vulgar, and bad, and because all their children admired

01:17:28.010 --> 01:17:34.390
him so, and delighted in his forbidden society, and wished they dared to be like him. Tom

01:17:34.390 --> 01:17:39.710
was like the rest of the respectable boys in that he envied Huckleberry his gaudy outcast

01:17:39.710 --> 01:17:44.370
condition, and was under strict orders not to play with him, so he played with him every

01:17:44.370 --> 01:17:49.410
time he got a chance. Huckleberry was always dressed in the cast-off clothes of full-grown

01:17:49.410 --> 01:17:55.570
men, and they were in perennial bloom and fluttering with rags. His hat was a vast ruin

01:17:55.570 --> 01:18:01.670
with a wide crescent lopped out of its brim. His coat, when he wore one, hung nearly to

01:18:01.670 --> 01:18:06.990
his heels, and had the rearward buttons far down the back, but one suspender supported

01:18:06.990 --> 01:18:12.590
his trousers. The seat of the trousers bagged low and contained nothing, the fringed legs

01:18:12.590 --> 01:18:14.950
dragged in the dirt when not rolled up.

01:18:15.590 --> 01:18:20.670
Huckleberry came and went at his own free will. He slept on doorsteps in fine weather

01:18:20.670 --> 01:18:25.910
and in empty hogsheads and wet. He did not have to go to school or to church, or call

01:18:25.910 --> 01:18:31.770
any being master or obey anybody. He could go fishing or swimming when and where he chose,

01:18:32.130 --> 01:18:37.270
and stay as long as it suited him. Nobody forbade him to fight. He could sit up as late

01:18:37.270 --> 01:18:41.770
as he pleased. He was always the first boy that went barefoot in the spring, and the

01:18:41.770 --> 01:18:47.730
to resume leather in the fall. He never had to wash nor put on clean clothes. He could

01:18:47.730 --> 01:18:54.070
swear wonderfully. In a word, everything that goes to make life precious, that boy had.

01:18:54.430 --> 01:19:00.410
So thought every harassed, hampered, respectable boy in St. Petersburg. Tom hailed the romantic

01:19:00.410 --> 01:19:00.930
outcast.

01:19:01.210 --> 01:19:06.190
"'Hullo, Huckleberry! Hello yourself, and see how you like it. What's that you got?

01:19:06.670 --> 01:19:11.670
Dead cat. Let me see him, Huck. My, he's pretty stiff. Where'd you get him?'

01:19:11.670 --> 01:19:13.030
"'Bought him off in a boy.'

01:19:13.550 --> 01:19:14.410
"'What'd you give?'

01:19:14.410 --> 01:19:18.250
"'I give a blue ticket and a bladder that I got at the slaughterhouse.'

01:19:18.250 --> 01:19:20.090
"'Where'd you get the blue ticket?'

01:19:20.090 --> 01:19:23.670
"'Bought it off in Ben Rogers two weeks ago for a hoop-stick.'

01:19:23.670 --> 01:19:27.930
"'Say, what is dead cats good for, Huck?'

01:19:27.930 --> 01:19:30.910
"'Good for? Pure warts with.'

01:19:30.910 --> 01:19:34.550
"'No, is that so? I know something that's better.'

01:19:34.550 --> 01:19:38.230
"'I bet you don't. What is it? Why, spunk-water.'

01:19:38.970 --> 01:19:44.870
"'Spunk-water? I wouldn't give a durn for spunk-water. You wouldn't, wouldn't you? Do you ever try

01:19:44.870 --> 01:19:45.430
it?'

01:19:45.430 --> 01:19:48.550
"'No, I ain't. But Bob Tanner did.'

01:19:48.550 --> 01:19:54.230
"'Who told you so? Why, he told Jeff Thatcher, and Jeff told Johnny Baker, and Johnny told

01:19:54.230 --> 01:19:59.490
Jim Hollis, and Jim told Ben Rogers, and Ben told a nigger, and the nigger told me there

01:19:59.490 --> 01:20:00.310
now.'

01:20:00.310 --> 01:20:06.250
"'Well, whatever. They'll all lie. Least wise, all but the nigger. I don't know him. But

01:20:06.250 --> 01:20:12.590
I never see a nigger that wouldn't lie. Shucks. Now you tell me how Bob Tanner done it, Huck.'

01:20:12.590 --> 01:20:17.850
"'Why, he took and dipped his hand in a rotten stump where the rain-water was. In the day-time?

01:20:18.330 --> 01:20:23.970
Certainly. With his face to the stump? Yes. Least I reckon so.'

01:20:23.970 --> 01:20:29.750
"'Did he say anything? I don't reckon he did. I don't know. Ah ha! Talk about trying

01:20:29.750 --> 01:20:34.710
to cure warts with spunk-water such a blameful way as that. Why, that ain't it going to do

01:20:34.710 --> 01:20:39.110
any good. You gotta go all by yourself to the middle of the woods where you know there's

01:20:39.110 --> 01:20:44.910
a spunk-water stump, and just as it's midnight, you back up against the stump and jam your

01:20:44.910 --> 01:20:50.270
hand in and say, "'Barley-corn, barley-corn, Injun-meal shorts, spunk-water, spunk-water,

01:20:50.450 --> 01:20:55.450
swallow these warts,' and then walk away quick, eleven steps, with your eyes shut, and then

01:20:55.450 --> 01:21:00.230
turn around three times and walk home without speaking to anybody. Because if you speak,

01:21:00.270 --> 01:21:01.270
the charm's busted.'

01:21:01.970 --> 01:21:05.710
"'Well, that sounds like a good way, but that ain't the way Bob Tanner done.'

01:21:06.350 --> 01:21:10.930
"'No, sir, you can bet he didn't, because he's the wardiest boy in this town, and he

01:21:10.930 --> 01:21:14.330
wouldn't have a wart on him if he'd known how to work spunk-water.'

01:21:15.150 --> 01:21:19.890
"'I've took thousands of warts off my hands that way, Huck. I play with frogs so much

01:21:19.890 --> 01:21:24.250
I've always got considerable many warts. Sometimes I take them off with a bean.'

01:21:25.610 --> 01:21:29.990
"'Yes, bean's good. I've done that. Have you? What's your way?'

01:21:30.450 --> 01:21:35.350
"'You take and split the bean and cut the wart so as to get some blood, and then you

01:21:35.350 --> 01:21:40.530
put the blood on one piece of the bean and take and dig a hole and bury it about midnight

01:21:40.530 --> 01:21:44.470
at the crossroads in the dark of the moon, and then you burn up the rest of the bean.

01:21:44.950 --> 01:21:49.470
You see, that piece that's got the blood on it will keep drawing and drawing, trying to

01:21:49.470 --> 01:21:54.370
fetch the other piece to it, and so that helps the blood to draw the wart. And pretty soon

01:21:54.370 --> 01:21:55.270
off she comes.'

01:21:55.830 --> 01:22:01.550
"'Yes, that's it, Huck, that's it. Though when you're burying it, if you say, Down bean,

01:22:02.270 --> 01:22:08.270
off wart, come no more to bother me, it's better. That's the way Joe Harper does, and

01:22:08.270 --> 01:22:14.210
he's been nearly to Coonville and most everywhere's. But say, how do you cure him with dead cats?'

01:22:14.870 --> 01:22:19.450
"'Why, you take your cat and go and get in the graveyard long about midnight when somebody

01:22:19.450 --> 01:22:24.370
that was wicked has been buried. And when it's midnight a devil will come, or maybe

01:22:24.370 --> 01:22:29.250
two or three, but you can't see him. You can only hear something like the wind, or maybe

01:22:29.250 --> 01:22:33.910
hear him talk. And when they're taking that feller away, you heave your cat after him

01:22:33.910 --> 01:22:40.070
and say, Devil follow corpse, cat follow devil, warts follow cat, I'm done with you. And that'll

01:22:40.070 --> 01:22:41.650
fetch any wart.'

01:22:41.650 --> 01:22:44.450
"'Sounds right. Do you ever try it, Huck?'

01:22:44.450 --> 01:22:47.290
"'No, but old Mother Hopkins told me.'

01:22:47.290 --> 01:22:51.050
"'Well, I reckon it's so, then, because they say she's a witch.'

01:22:51.750 --> 01:22:52.230
"'Say?'

01:22:52.230 --> 01:22:59.270
"'Why, Tom, I know she is. She witched Pap. Pap says so his own self. He come along one

01:22:59.270 --> 01:23:04.230
day, and he sees she was a witch in him, so he took up a rock, and if she hadn't dodged

01:23:04.230 --> 01:23:09.190
he'd a got her. Well, that very night he rolled off in the shed where he was a-laying drunk

01:23:09.190 --> 01:23:10.570
and broke his arm.'

01:23:10.570 --> 01:23:13.970
"'Why, that's awful. How did he know she was a witch in him?'

01:23:13.970 --> 01:23:20.970
"'Lord, Pap can tell easy. Pap says when they keep looking at you right stidy, they're

01:23:20.970 --> 01:23:26.070
witching you, especially if they mumble, because when they mumble they're saying the Lord's

01:23:26.070 --> 01:23:30.950
Prayer backwards. Say, Huckie, when you going to try the cat?'

01:23:30.950 --> 01:23:35.390
"'To-night. I reckon they'll come after old Hoss Williams to-night.'

01:23:36.150 --> 01:23:40.370
"'But they buried him Saturday. Didn't they get him Saturday night?'

01:23:40.370 --> 01:23:45.490
"'Why, how you talk. How could their charms work till midnight, and then it's Sunday?

01:23:46.070 --> 01:23:51.010
Devils don't slosh round much of a Sunday, I don't reckon. I never thought of that.

01:23:51.270 --> 01:23:53.370
That's so. Let me go with you.'

01:23:53.370 --> 01:23:54.890
"'Of course, if he ain't afeard.'

01:23:55.850 --> 01:23:58.970
"'Afeard? Taint likely. Will you meow?'

01:23:58.970 --> 01:24:03.990
"'Yes, and you meow back, if you get a chance. Last time you kept me a-meowing around till

01:24:03.990 --> 01:24:08.850
old Hayes went to throwing rocks at me and says, "'Darn that cat!' and so I hove a

01:24:08.850 --> 01:24:11.370
brick through his window. But don't you tell?'

01:24:11.370 --> 01:24:16.470
"'I won't. I couldn't meow that night because Auntie was watching me. But I'll meow this

01:24:16.470 --> 01:24:18.510
time. Say, what's that?'

01:24:18.510 --> 01:24:22.090
"'Nothin' but a tick. Where'd you get him? Out in the woods.'

01:24:22.090 --> 01:24:23.630
"'What'll you take for him?'

01:24:23.630 --> 01:24:28.990
"'I don't know. I don't want to sell him. All right. It's a mighty small tick, anyway.

01:24:29.250 --> 01:24:34.650
Oh, anybody can run a tick down that don't belong to them. I'm satisfied with it. It's

01:24:34.650 --> 01:24:40.590
a good enough tick for me. Show! There's ticks aplenty. I could have a thousand of them if

01:24:40.590 --> 01:24:41.530
I wanted to.'

01:24:41.530 --> 01:24:47.010
"'Well, why don't you? Because you know mighty well you can't. This is a pretty early tick,

01:24:47.030 --> 01:24:52.270
I reckon. It's the first one I've seen this year. Say, Huck, I'll give you my tooth for

01:24:52.270 --> 01:24:54.170
him. Let's see it.'

01:24:54.170 --> 01:25:00.030
Tom got on a bit of paper and carefully unrolled it. Huckleberry viewed it wistfully. The temptation

01:25:00.030 --> 01:25:06.490
was very strong. At last he said, "'Is it genuine?' Tom lifted his lip and showed the

01:25:06.490 --> 01:25:06.970
vacancy.

01:25:07.570 --> 01:25:13.310
"'Well, all right,' said Huckleberry. "'It's a trade.' Tom enclosed the tick in the percussion

01:25:13.310 --> 01:25:18.070
cat-box that had lately been the Pinchbugs' prison, and the boys separated, each feeling

01:25:18.070 --> 01:25:23.070
wealthier than before. When Tom reached the little isolated frame schoolhouse he strode

01:25:23.070 --> 01:25:27.890
in briskly, with the manner of one who had come with all honest speed. He hung his hat

01:25:27.890 --> 01:25:32.690
on a peg and flung himself into a seat with businesslike alacrity. The master, thrown

01:25:32.690 --> 01:25:38.570
on high in his great splint-bottom arm-chair, was dozing, lulled by the drowsy hum of study.

01:25:38.990 --> 01:25:40.510
The interruption roused him.

01:25:41.030 --> 01:25:46.290
"'TOMMAS SOYER?' Tom knew that when his name was pronounced in full it meant trouble.

01:25:46.510 --> 01:25:52.230
"'Sir, come up here. Now, sir, why are you late again, as usual?'

01:25:52.630 --> 01:25:58.050
Tom was about to take refuge in a lie when he saw two long tails of yellow hair hanging

01:25:58.050 --> 01:26:04.070
down a back that he recognized by the electric sympathy of love, and by that form was the

01:26:04.070 --> 01:26:09.270
only vacant place on the girls' side of the schoolhouse. He instantly said,

01:26:09.470 --> 01:26:12.190
"'I stopped to talk with Huckleberry Finn!'

01:26:12.190 --> 01:26:17.810
The master's pulse stood still, and he stared helplessly. The buzz of study ceased. The

01:26:17.810 --> 01:26:21.730
pupils wondered if this foolhardy boy had lost his mind. The master said,

01:26:22.350 --> 01:26:22.950
"'You—'

01:26:23.230 --> 01:26:24.250
"'You did what?'

01:26:25.050 --> 01:26:27.190
"'Stopped to talk with Huckleberry Finn.'

01:26:27.190 --> 01:26:29.110
There was no mistaking the words.

01:26:29.290 --> 01:26:35.270
"'TOMMAS SOYER, this is the most astounding confession I have ever listened to. No mere

01:26:35.270 --> 01:26:39.390
feral will answer for this offence. Take off your jacket.'

01:26:39.390 --> 01:26:43.190
The master's arm performed until it was tired, and the stock of switches

01:26:43.190 --> 01:26:45.630
notably diminished. Then the order followed,

01:26:45.950 --> 01:26:51.930
"'Now, sir, go and sit with the girls, and let this be a warning to you.'

01:26:51.930 --> 01:26:56.050
The titter that rippled around the room appeared to bash the boy, but in

01:26:56.050 --> 01:27:00.310
reality that result was caused rather more by his worshipful awe of his

01:27:00.310 --> 01:27:05.990
unknown idol, and a dread pleasure that lay in his high good fortune. He

01:27:05.990 --> 01:27:09.430
sat down upon the end of the pine bench, and the girl hitched herself

01:27:09.430 --> 01:27:13.510
away from him with a toss of her head. Nudges and winks and whispers

01:27:13.510 --> 01:27:18.130
traversed the room, but Tom sat still with his arms upon the long, low

01:27:18.130 --> 01:27:23.250
desk before him, and seemed to study his book. By-and-by attention ceased

01:27:23.250 --> 01:27:27.110
from him, and the accustomed school murmur rose upon the dull air once

01:27:27.110 --> 01:27:31.390
more. Presently the boy began to steal furtive glances at the girl. She

01:27:31.390 --> 01:27:35.450
observed it, made a mouth at him, and gave him the back of her head for

01:27:35.450 --> 01:27:39.530
the space of a minute. When she cautiously faced around again, a peach

01:27:39.530 --> 01:27:45.190
lay before her. She thrusted away. Tom gently put it back. She thrusted

01:27:45.190 --> 01:27:49.930
away again, but with less animosity. Tom patiently returned it to its

01:27:49.930 --> 01:27:53.790
place. Then she let it remain. Tom scrawled on his slate.

01:27:54.090 --> 01:27:58.750
"'Please take it. I got more.' The girl glanced at the words, but made

01:27:58.750 --> 01:28:03.070
no sign. Now the boy began to draw something on the slate, hiding his

01:28:03.070 --> 01:28:07.210
work with his left hand. For a time the girl refused to notice, but her

01:28:07.210 --> 01:28:11.290
human curiosity presently began to manifest itself by hardly perceptible

01:28:11.290 --> 01:28:11.810
signs.

01:28:12.350 --> 01:28:19.910
The boy worked on, apparently unconscious. The girl made a sort of

01:28:19.910 --> 01:28:20.530
noise.

01:28:20.650 --> 01:28:24.210
At last she gave in, and hesitatingly whispered,

01:28:24.510 --> 01:28:29.630
"'Let me see it.' Tom uncovered a dismal caricature of a house with two

01:28:29.630 --> 01:28:34.350
gable ends to it, and a corkscrew of smoke issuing from the chimney. Then

01:28:34.350 --> 01:28:37.690
the girl's interest began to fasten itself upon the work as she forgot

01:28:37.690 --> 01:28:41.390
everything else. When it was finished she gazed a moment, then whispered,

01:28:41.550 --> 01:28:46.910
"'It's nice. Make a man.' The artist erected a man in the front yard

01:28:46.910 --> 01:28:50.510
that resembled a derrick. He could have stepped over the house. But the

01:28:50.510 --> 01:28:53.970
girl was not hypercritical. She was satisfied with the monster, and

01:28:53.970 --> 01:28:54.370
whispered,

01:28:54.710 --> 01:29:00.210
"'It's a beautiful man. Now make me coming along.' Tom drew an hourglass

01:29:00.210 --> 01:29:04.550
with a full moon and straw limbs to it, and armed the spreading fingers

01:29:04.550 --> 01:29:09.310
with a portentous fan. The girl said, "'It's ever so nice. I wish I could

01:29:09.310 --> 01:29:10.070
draw.'

01:29:10.070 --> 01:29:12.450
"'It's easy,' whispered Tom. I'll learn you.

01:29:12.650 --> 01:29:15.190
"'Oh, will you? When?'

01:29:15.190 --> 01:29:17.650
"'At noon. Do you go home to dinner?'

01:29:17.650 --> 01:29:19.250
"'I'll stay, if you will.'

01:29:19.250 --> 01:29:21.590
"'Good. That's a whack. What's your name?'

01:29:22.250 --> 01:29:23.210
"'Becky Thatcher.'

01:29:23.210 --> 01:29:24.310
"'What's yours?'

01:29:24.310 --> 01:29:26.190
"'Oh, I know. It's Thomas Sawyer.'

01:29:26.910 --> 01:29:31.350
"'That's the name they lick me by. I'm Tom when I'm good. You can call

01:29:31.350 --> 01:29:33.070
me Tom, will you?'

01:29:33.890 --> 01:29:34.410
"'Yes.'

01:29:34.410 --> 01:29:37.850
Now Tom began to scrawl something on the slate, hiding the words from

01:29:37.850 --> 01:29:41.330
the girl. But she was not backward this time. She begged to see. Tom

01:29:41.330 --> 01:29:41.630
said,

01:29:42.010 --> 01:29:43.310
"'Oh, it ain't anything.'

01:29:43.310 --> 01:29:44.450
"'Yes, it is.'

01:29:44.450 --> 01:29:46.510
"'No, it ain't. You don't want to see it.'

01:29:46.510 --> 01:29:50.530
"'Yes, I do. Indeed, I do. Please let me. You'll tell.'

01:29:50.530 --> 01:29:53.970
"'No, I won't. Deed and deed and double deed, I won't.'

01:29:53.970 --> 01:29:57.330
"'You won't tell anybody at all? Ever as long as you live?'

01:29:57.330 --> 01:30:00.270
"'No, I won't ever tell anybody. Now let me.'

01:30:00.270 --> 01:30:05.250
"'Oh, you don't want to see. Now that you treat me so, I will see.' And

01:30:05.250 --> 01:30:09.030
she put her small hand upon his, and the little scuffle ensued. Tom

01:30:09.030 --> 01:30:12.530
pretending to resist in earnest, but letting his hand slip by degrees

01:30:12.530 --> 01:30:14.490
till these words were revealed.

01:30:14.970 --> 01:30:16.370
"'I love you.'

01:30:16.370 --> 01:30:21.190
"'Oh, you bad thing!' And she hit his hand a smart wrap, but reddened

01:30:21.190 --> 01:30:25.550
and looked pleased nevertheless. Just at this juncture the boy felt a

01:30:25.550 --> 01:30:30.990
slow, fateful grip closing on his ear, and a steady lifting impulse. In

01:30:30.990 --> 01:30:35.170
that vice he was borne across the house, and deposited in his own seat

01:30:35.170 --> 01:30:39.790
under a peppering fire of giggles from the whole school. Then the master

01:30:39.790 --> 01:30:44.270
stood over him during a few awful moments, and finally moved away to his

01:30:44.270 --> 01:30:48.570
throne without saying a word. But although Tom's ear tingled, his heart

01:30:48.570 --> 01:30:53.470
was jubilant. As the school quieted down, Tom made an honest effort to

01:30:53.470 --> 01:30:57.810
study, but the turmoil within him was too great. In turn he took his

01:30:57.810 --> 01:31:01.830
place in the reading class and made a botch of it, then in the geography

01:31:01.830 --> 01:31:06.110
class and turned lakes into mountains, mountains into rivers, and rivers

01:31:06.110 --> 01:31:10.190
into continents, till chaos was come again, then in the spelling class

01:31:10.190 --> 01:31:14.910
and got turned down by a succession of mere baby words, till he brought

01:31:14.910 --> 01:31:19.070
up at the foot and yielded up the pewter metal which he had worn with

01:31:19.070 --> 01:31:20.630
ostentation for months.

01:31:43.070 --> 01:31:49.450
The harder Tom tried to fasten his mind on his book, the more his ideas wandered. So,

01:31:49.450 --> 01:31:54.930
at last, with a sigh and a yawn, he gave it up. It seemed to him that the noon recess

01:31:54.930 --> 01:32:01.470
would never come. The air was utterly dead. There was not a breath stirring. It was the

01:32:01.470 --> 01:32:08.130
sleepiest of sleepy days. The drowsing murmur of the five-and-twenty studying scholars soothed

01:32:08.130 --> 01:32:14.310
the soul like the spell that is in the murmur of bees. Away off in the flaming sunshine,

01:32:14.310 --> 01:32:20.210
Cart of Hill lifted its soft green sides through a shimmering veil of heat tinted with a purple

01:32:20.210 --> 01:32:26.970
of distance. A few birds floated on lazy wing high in the air. No other living thing was

01:32:26.970 --> 01:32:34.710
visible, but some cows, and they were asleep. Tom's heart ached to be free, or else to have

01:32:34.710 --> 01:32:40.370
something of interest to do to pass the dreary time. His hand wandered into his pocket, and

01:32:40.370 --> 01:32:44.930
his face lit up with a glow of gratitude that was prayer, though he did not know it.

01:32:45.490 --> 01:32:50.770
Then furtively the percussion-cap box came out. He released the tick, and put him on

01:32:50.770 --> 01:32:55.970
the long flat desk. The creature probably glowed with a gratitude that amounted to prayer,

01:32:56.350 --> 01:33:01.530
too, at this moment, but it was premature, for when he started thankfully to travel off,

01:33:02.150 --> 01:33:07.930
Tom turned him aside with a pin, and made him take a new direction. Tom's bosom friend

01:33:07.930 --> 01:33:13.090
sat next to him, suffering just as Tom had been, and now he was deeply and gratefully

01:33:13.090 --> 01:33:18.230
interested in this entertainment in an instant. This bosom friend was Joe Harper. The two

01:33:18.230 --> 01:33:23.990
boys were sworn friends all the week, and embattled enemies on Saturdays. Joe took a

01:33:23.990 --> 01:33:28.790
pin out of his lapel, and began to assist in exercising the prisoner. The sport grew

01:33:28.790 --> 01:33:34.010
in interest momently. Soon Tom said that they were interfering with each other, and neither

01:33:34.010 --> 01:33:38.490
getting the fullest benefit of the tick. So he put Joe's slate on the desk, and drew

01:33:38.490 --> 01:33:40.690
a line down the middle of it from top to bottom.

01:33:41.110 --> 01:33:46.010
"'Now,' said he, "'as long as he is on your side, you can stir him up, and I'll let him

01:33:46.010 --> 01:33:51.050
alone. But if you let him get away and get on my side, you're to leave him alone as long

01:33:51.050 --> 01:33:56.130
as I can keep him from crossing over. All right, go ahead, start him up.'

01:33:56.130 --> 01:34:00.950
The tick escaped from Tom, presently, and crossed the equator. Joe harassed him a while,

01:34:00.950 --> 01:34:06.270
and then he got away, and crossed back again. This change of base occurred often. While

01:34:06.270 --> 01:34:10.530
one boy was worrying the tick with absorbing interest, the other would look on with interest

01:34:10.530 --> 01:34:15.970
as strong. The two heads bowed together over the slate, and the two souls dead to all things

01:34:15.970 --> 01:34:22.050
else. At last luck seemed to settle and abide with Joe. The tick tried this, that, and the

01:34:22.050 --> 01:34:26.830
other course, and got as excited and as anxious as the boys themselves, but time and again,

01:34:26.830 --> 01:34:31.370
just as he would have victory in his very grasp, so to speak, and Tom's fingers would

01:34:31.370 --> 01:34:37.230
be twitching to begin, Joe's pin would deftly head him off and keep possession. At last

01:34:37.230 --> 01:34:42.310
Tom could stand it no longer. The temptation was too strong, so he reached out and lent

01:34:42.310 --> 01:34:47.490
a hand with his pin. Joe was angry in a moment. Said he, "'Tom, you let him alone.'

01:34:47.490 --> 01:34:50.050
"'I only just want to stir him up a little, Joe.'

01:34:50.050 --> 01:34:52.810
"'No, sir, it ain't fair. You just let him alone.'

01:34:53.510 --> 01:34:57.970
"'Blame it, I ain't going to stir him much. Let him alone, I tell you.'

01:34:57.970 --> 01:35:02.870
"'Well, I won't. You shall. He's on my side of the line. Look here, Joe Harper, whose

01:35:02.870 --> 01:35:07.550
is that tick? I don't care whose tick he is. He's on my side of the line, and you shan't

01:35:07.550 --> 01:35:08.930
touch him.'

01:35:08.930 --> 01:35:12.890
"'Well, I'll just bet I will, though. He's my tick, and I'll do what I blame please with

01:35:12.890 --> 01:35:14.070
him, or die.'

01:35:14.070 --> 01:35:19.410
A tremendous whack came down on Tom's shoulders, and its duplicate on Joe's, and for the space

01:35:19.410 --> 01:35:23.610
of two minutes the dust continued to fly from the two jackets and the whole school to enjoy

01:35:23.610 --> 01:35:28.650
it. The boys had been too absorbed to notice the hush that had stolen upon the school a

01:35:28.650 --> 01:35:33.990
while before, when the master came tip-toeing down the room and stood over them. He had

01:35:33.990 --> 01:35:38.170
contemplated a good part of the performance before he contributed his bit of variety to

01:35:38.170 --> 01:35:44.050
it. When school broke up at noon, Tom flew to Becky Thatcher, and whispered in her ear,

01:35:44.370 --> 01:35:48.730
"'Put on your bonnet and let on your going home, and when you get to the corner, give

01:35:48.730 --> 01:35:53.110
the rest of them the slip, and turn down through the lane and come back. I'll go the

01:35:53.110 --> 01:35:56.270
other way, and come it over them the same way.'

01:35:56.270 --> 01:36:01.450
So the one went off with one group of scholars, and the other with another. In a little while

01:36:01.450 --> 01:36:05.370
the two met at the bottom of the lane, and when they reached the school they had it all

01:36:05.370 --> 01:36:10.630
to themselves. Then they sat together with a slate before them, and Tom gave Becky the

01:36:10.630 --> 01:36:16.170
pencil and held her hand in his, guiding it, and so created another surprising house.

01:36:16.590 --> 01:36:21.550
When the interest in art began to wane, the two fell to talking. Tom was swimming in bliss.

01:36:21.670 --> 01:36:22.110
He said,

01:36:22.470 --> 01:36:24.030
"'Do you love rats?'

01:36:24.030 --> 01:36:25.770
"'No, I hate them.'

01:36:26.290 --> 01:36:31.190
"'Well, I do, too. Live ones. But I mean dead ones, to swing round your head with a

01:36:31.190 --> 01:36:31.990
string.'

01:36:31.990 --> 01:36:36.850
"'No, I don't care for rats much, anyway. What I like is chewing-gum.'

01:36:36.850 --> 01:36:40.070
"'Oh, I should say so. I wish I had some now.'

01:36:40.070 --> 01:36:45.610
"'Do you? I've got some. I'll let you chew it a while. But you must give it back to me.

01:36:45.610 --> 01:36:50.490
"'That was agreeable.' So they chewed it, turned about, and dangled their legs against

01:36:50.490 --> 01:36:52.370
the bench in excess of contentment.

01:36:52.790 --> 01:36:55.010
"'Was you ever at a circus?' said Tom.

01:36:55.450 --> 01:37:00.810
"'Yes, and my pa's going to take me again some time, if I'm good. I've been to the

01:37:00.810 --> 01:37:05.790
circus three or four times, lots of times. Church ain't shucks to a circus. There's

01:37:05.790 --> 01:37:10.090
things going on at a circus all the time. I'm going to be a clown in a circus when I

01:37:10.090 --> 01:37:10.790
grow up.'

01:37:10.790 --> 01:37:15.790
"'Oh, are you? That will be nice. They're so lovely, all spotted up.'

01:37:16.290 --> 01:37:21.450
"'Yes, that's so. And they get slathers of money, most a dollar a day,' Ben Rogers

01:37:21.450 --> 01:37:24.930
says. Say, Becky, was you ever engaged?'

01:37:24.930 --> 01:37:26.270
"'What's that?'

01:37:26.270 --> 01:37:28.070
"'Why, engaged to be married.'

01:37:29.370 --> 01:37:29.930
"'No.'

01:37:29.930 --> 01:37:31.390
"'Would you like to?'

01:37:31.390 --> 01:37:34.390
"'I reckon so. I don't know. What is it like?'

01:37:35.350 --> 01:37:40.190
"'Like? Why, it ain't like anything. You only just tell a boy you won't ever have anybody

01:37:40.190 --> 01:37:45.070
but him, ever, ever, ever, and then you kiss and that's all. Anybody can do it.'

01:37:45.070 --> 01:37:47.830
"'Kiss? What do you kiss for?'

01:37:47.830 --> 01:37:50.630
"'Why, that, you know, is to—'

01:37:50.690 --> 01:37:52.470
"'Well, they always do that.'

01:37:53.190 --> 01:37:53.750
"'Everybody?'

01:37:53.750 --> 01:37:57.750
"'Why, yes, everybody that's in love with each other. Do you remember what I wrote

01:37:57.750 --> 01:37:58.890
on the slate?'

01:38:00.310 --> 01:38:00.870
"'Yes.'

01:38:00.870 --> 01:38:02.110
"'What was it?'

01:38:02.110 --> 01:38:04.130
"'I shan't tell you.'

01:38:04.130 --> 01:38:05.830
"'Shall I tell you?'

01:38:05.830 --> 01:38:08.830
"'Yes, but some other time.'

01:38:08.830 --> 01:38:16.910
"'No, now. No, not now. To-morrow. Oh, no, now. Please, Becky, I'll whisper it. I'll

01:38:16.910 --> 01:38:18.630
whisper it ever so easy.'

01:38:18.630 --> 01:38:24.550
Becky hesitating, Tom took silence for consent, and passed his arm about her waist and whispered

01:38:24.550 --> 01:38:29.090
the tale ever so softly, with his mouth close to her ear, and then he added,

01:38:29.650 --> 01:38:32.850
"'Now you whisper it to me. Just the same.'

01:38:32.850 --> 01:38:34.910
She resisted for a while, and then said,

01:38:34.910 --> 01:38:40.470
"'You turn your face away so you can't see, and then I will. But you mustn't ever tell

01:38:40.470 --> 01:38:43.590
anybody, will you, Tom? Now you won't, will you?'

01:38:43.590 --> 01:38:46.250
"'No, indeed, indeed, I won't. Now, Becky.'

01:38:46.250 --> 01:38:51.930
He turned his face away, and she bent timidly around till her breath stirred his curls and

01:38:51.930 --> 01:38:52.470
whispered,

01:38:53.670 --> 01:38:55.830
"'I love you.'

01:38:56.370 --> 01:39:00.650
Then she sprang away and ran around and around the desks and benches, with Tom after her,

01:39:00.650 --> 01:39:05.730
and took refuge in a corner at last, with her little white apron to her face. Tom clasped

01:39:05.730 --> 01:39:07.170
her about her neck and pleaded,

01:39:07.430 --> 01:39:12.230
"'Now, Becky, it's all done, all over, but the kiss. Don't you be afraid of that. It

01:39:12.230 --> 01:39:14.670
ain't anything at all. Please, Becky.'

01:39:14.670 --> 01:39:19.930
And he tugged at her apron and the hands. By and by she gave up and let her hands drop.

01:39:20.330 --> 01:39:25.370
Her face, all glowing with a struggle, came up and submitted. Tom kissed the red lips

01:39:25.370 --> 01:39:25.850
and said,

01:39:26.490 --> 01:39:31.530
"'Now, it's all done, Becky. And always after this, you know, you ain't ever to love anybody

01:39:31.530 --> 01:39:36.990
but me, and you ain't ever to marry anybody but me. Never, never and for ever, will you?'

01:39:36.990 --> 01:39:42.610
"'No, I'll never love anybody but you, Tom, and I'll never marry anybody but you. And

01:39:42.610 --> 01:39:45.390
you ain't to ever marry anybody but me either.'

01:39:46.290 --> 01:39:51.250
"'Certainly, of course. That's part of it. And always coming to school, or when we're

01:39:51.250 --> 01:39:56.470
home, you're to walk with me—when there ain't anybody looking—and you choose me

01:39:56.470 --> 01:40:02.070
and I choose you at parties, because that's the way you do when you're engaged. It's so

01:40:02.070 --> 01:40:07.770
nice I never heard of it before. Oh, it's ever so gay. Why, me and Amy Lawrence!'

01:40:07.770 --> 01:40:11.210
The big eyes told Tom his blunder and he stopped confused.

01:40:11.570 --> 01:40:15.670
"'Oh, Tom, then I ain't the first you've ever been engaged to.'

01:40:15.670 --> 01:40:18.290
The child began to cry and Tom said,

01:40:18.290 --> 01:40:22.110
"'Oh, don't cry, Becky. I don't care for her any more.'

01:40:22.110 --> 01:40:24.710
"'Yes, you do, Tom, you know you do.'

01:40:24.710 --> 01:40:28.650
Tom tried to put his arm about her neck, but she pushed him away and turned her face to

01:40:28.650 --> 01:40:33.150
the wall and went on crying. Tom tried again, with soothing words in his mouth, and was

01:40:33.150 --> 01:40:38.450
repulsed again. Then his pride was up, and he strode away and went outside. He stood

01:40:38.450 --> 01:40:43.390
about restless and uneasy for a while, glancing at the door every now and then, hoping she

01:40:43.390 --> 01:40:48.830
would repent and come to find him, but she did not. Then he began to feel badly and fear

01:40:48.830 --> 01:40:54.270
that he was in the wrong. It was a hard struggle with him to make new advances now, but he

01:40:54.270 --> 01:40:59.370
nerved himself to it and entered. She was still standing back there in the corner sobbing

01:40:59.370 --> 01:41:05.110
with her face to the wall. Tom's heart smote him. He went to her and stood a moment, not

01:41:05.110 --> 01:41:08.770
knowing exactly how to proceed. Then he said hesitatingly,

01:41:09.410 --> 01:41:14.370
"'Becky, I—I don't care for anybody but you.'

01:41:14.370 --> 01:41:16.290
No reply. But sobs.

01:41:17.410 --> 01:41:18.530
"'Becky,' pleadingly,

01:41:18.690 --> 01:41:21.350
"'Becky, won't you say something?'

01:41:21.350 --> 01:41:28.250
More sobs. Tom got out his chiefest jewel, a brass knob from the top of an andiron, and

01:41:28.250 --> 01:41:30.830
passed it around her so that she could see it, and said,

01:41:31.270 --> 01:41:33.250
"'Please, Becky, won't you take it?'

01:41:33.250 --> 01:41:38.410
She struck it to the floor. Then Tom marched out of the house and over the hills and far

01:41:38.410 --> 01:41:44.130
away, to return to school no more that day. Presently Becky began to suspect. She ran

01:41:44.130 --> 01:41:49.250
to the door. He was not in sight. She flew around to the play yard. He was not there.

01:41:49.510 --> 01:41:50.390
Then she called,

01:41:50.650 --> 01:41:53.450
"'Tom! Come back, Tom!'

01:41:53.830 --> 01:41:59.250
She listened intently, but there was no answer. She had no companions but silence and loneliness.

01:41:59.690 --> 01:42:04.830
So she sat down to cry again and upbraid herself, and by this time the scholars began to gather

01:42:04.830 --> 01:42:09.710
again, and she had to hide her griefs and still her broken heart, and take up the cross

01:42:09.710 --> 01:42:15.150
of a long, dreary, aching afternoon, with none among the strangers about her to exchange

01:42:15.150 --> 01:42:16.090
sorrows with.

01:42:19.930 --> 01:42:21.210
CHAPTER 8

01:42:21.210 --> 01:42:24.070
A PIRATE BOLD TO BE

01:42:24.470 --> 01:42:28.810
Tom dodged hither and thither through lanes until he was well out of the track of returning

01:42:28.810 --> 01:42:34.810
scholars, and then fell into a moody jog. He crossed a small branch, two or three times,

01:42:35.210 --> 01:42:40.970
because of a prevailing juvenile superstition that to cross water baffles pursuit. Half

01:42:40.970 --> 01:42:44.830
an hour later he was disappearing behind the Douglas Mansion on the summit of Cardiff

01:42:44.830 --> 01:42:50.730
Hill, and the schoolhouse was hardly distinguishable away off in the valley behind him. He entered

01:42:50.730 --> 01:42:56.330
a dense wood, picked his pathless way to the centre of it, and sat down on a mossy spot

01:42:56.330 --> 01:43:02.470
under a spreading oak. There was not even a zephyr stirring. The dead noonday heat had

01:43:02.470 --> 01:43:07.870
even stilled the songs of the birds. Nature lay in a trance that was broken by no sound

01:43:07.870 --> 01:43:12.410
but the occasional far-off hammering of a woodpecker, and this seemed to render the

01:43:12.410 --> 01:43:18.230
prevailing silence and sense of loneliness the more profound. The boy's soul was steeped

01:43:18.230 --> 01:43:24.070
in melancholy. His feelings were in happy accord with his surroundings. He sat long

01:43:24.070 --> 01:43:29.510
with his elbows on his knees and his chin in his hands, meditating. It seemed to him

01:43:29.510 --> 01:43:35.650
that life was but a trouble at best, and he more than half envied Jimmy Hodges so lately

01:43:35.650 --> 01:43:40.970
released. It must be very peaceful, he thought, to lie and slumber and dream for ever and

01:43:40.970 --> 01:43:45.610
ever, with the wind whispering through the trees and caressing the grass and the flowers

01:43:45.610 --> 01:43:51.290
over the grave, and nothing to bother and grieve about ever any more. If he only had

01:43:51.290 --> 01:43:56.770
a clean Sunday-school record he could be willing to go—and be done with it all. Now

01:43:56.770 --> 01:44:03.450
as to this girl, what had he done? Nothing. He had meant the best in the world and been

01:44:03.450 --> 01:44:09.330
treated like a dog, like a very dog. She would be sorry some day—maybe when it was too

01:44:09.930 --> 01:44:12.470
late—if he could only die temporarily.

01:44:13.270 --> 01:44:18.730
But the elastic heart of youth cannot be compressed into one constrained shape long at any time.

01:44:19.230 --> 01:44:24.830
Tom presently began to drift insensibly back into the concerns of this life again. What

01:44:24.830 --> 01:44:31.150
if he turned his back now and disappeared mysteriously? What if he went away, ever so

01:44:31.150 --> 01:44:37.330
far away, into unknown countries beyond the seas, and never came back any more? How would

01:44:37.330 --> 01:44:43.730
she feel then? The idea of being a clown recurred to him now, only to fill him with disgust.

01:44:44.090 --> 01:44:49.090
For frivolity and jokes and spotted tights were an offence when they intruded themselves

01:44:49.090 --> 01:44:55.710
upon a spirit that was exalted into the vague, august realm of the romantic. No, he would

01:44:55.710 --> 01:45:02.870
be a soldier, and return after long years all war-worn and illustrious. No, better still,

01:45:03.110 --> 01:45:07.630
he would join the Indians, and hunt buffaloes and go on the war-path in the mountain ranges

01:45:07.630 --> 01:45:12.870
and the trackless great plains of the far west, and away in the future come back a great

01:45:12.870 --> 01:45:18.810
chief, bristling with feathers, hideous with paint, and prance into Sunday school some

01:45:18.810 --> 01:45:24.250
drowsy summer morning, with a blood-curling war-whoop, and sear the eyeballs of all his

01:45:24.250 --> 01:45:31.250
companions with unappeasable envy. But no, there was something gaudier even than this.

01:45:31.610 --> 01:45:39.930
He would be a pirate. That was it. Now his future lay plain before him, and glowing with

01:45:39.930 --> 01:45:45.590
unimaginable splendour. How his name would fill the world, and make people shudder!

01:45:45.830 --> 01:45:51.790
How gloriously he would go ploughing the dancing seas in his long, low, black-hulled racer,

01:45:52.030 --> 01:45:57.770
the Spirit of the Storm, with his grizzly flag flying at the fore! And at the zenith

01:45:57.770 --> 01:46:02.090
of his fame, how he would suddenly appear at the old village and stalk into church,

01:46:02.290 --> 01:46:07.690
brown and weather-beaten, in his black velvet doublet and trunks, his great jack-boots,

01:46:07.690 --> 01:46:13.950
his crimson sash, his belt bristling with horse pistols, his crime-rusted cutlass at

01:46:13.950 --> 01:46:20.230
his side, his slouch-hat with waving plumes, his black flag unfurled, with a skull and

01:46:20.230 --> 01:46:24.650
crossbones on it, and here, with swelling ecstasy, the whisperings,

01:46:24.930 --> 01:46:29.770
"'It's Tom Sawyer, the pirate, the black avenger of the Spanish main!'

01:46:29.770 --> 01:46:35.530
Yes, it was settled. His career was determined. He would run away from home and enter upon

01:46:35.530 --> 01:46:40.330
it. He would start the very next morning. Therefore he must now begin to get ready.

01:46:40.670 --> 01:46:45.650
He would collect his resources together. He went to a rotten log near at hand, and began

01:46:45.650 --> 01:46:51.590
to dig under one end of it with his barlow-knife. He soon struck wood that sounded hollow. He

01:46:51.590 --> 01:46:54.970
put his hand there, and uttered this incantation impressively,

01:46:55.390 --> 01:47:01.510
"'What hasn't come here, come! What's here, stay here!'

01:47:01.910 --> 01:47:07.450
Then he scraped away the dirt, and exposed a pine-shingle. He took it up and disclosed

01:47:07.450 --> 01:47:13.090
a shapely little treasure-house whose bottom and sides were of shingles. In it lay a marble.

01:47:13.830 --> 01:47:19.210
Tom's astonishment was boundless. He scratched his head with perplexed air, and said,

01:47:19.550 --> 01:47:22.230
"'Well, that beats anything!'

01:47:22.730 --> 01:47:30.990
Then he tossed the marble away, pettishly, and stood cogitating. The truth was that a

01:47:31.370 --> 01:47:37.250
had always looked upon as infallible. If you buried a marble with certain necessary incantations

01:47:37.250 --> 01:47:41.610
and left it alone a fortnight, and then opened the place with the incantation he had just

01:47:41.610 --> 01:47:45.910
used, you would find that all the marbles you had ever lost had gathered themselves

01:47:45.910 --> 01:47:52.190
together there, meantime, no matter how widely they had been separated. But now this thing

01:47:52.190 --> 01:47:54.550
had actually and unquestionably failed.

01:47:55.210 --> 01:48:00.230
Tom's whole structure of faith was shaken to its foundations. He had many a time heard

01:48:00.230 --> 01:48:05.190
of this thing succeeding, but never of its failing before. It did not occur to him that

01:48:05.190 --> 01:48:10.430
he had tried it several times before, himself, but could never find the hiding-places afterward.

01:48:10.910 --> 01:48:15.570
He puzzled over the matter some time, and finally decided that some witch had interfered

01:48:15.570 --> 01:48:20.190
and broken the charm. He thought he would satisfy himself on that point, so he searched

01:48:20.190 --> 01:48:30.210
around till he found a small sandy spot with a little funnel-shaped depression in it. He

01:48:30.210 --> 01:48:35.730
tell me what I want to know. Doodle-bug, doodle-bug, tell me what I want to know.

01:48:36.130 --> 01:48:41.430
The sand began to work, and presently a small black bug appeared for a second, and then

01:48:41.430 --> 01:48:47.950
darted under again in a fright. He doesn't tell, so it was a witch that done it. I just

01:48:47.950 --> 01:48:48.230
noted.

01:48:49.210 --> 01:48:53.510
He well knew the futility of trying to contend against witches, so he gave up discouraged.

01:48:53.830 --> 01:48:58.570
But it occurred to him that he might as well have the marble he had just thrown away, and

01:48:58.570 --> 01:49:03.930
therefore he went and made a patient search for it. But he could not find it. Now he went

01:49:03.930 --> 01:49:08.070
back to his treasure-house, and carefully placed himself just as he had been standing

01:49:08.070 --> 01:49:12.590
when he tossed the marble away. Then he took another marble from his pocket, and tossed

01:49:12.590 --> 01:49:13.710
it in the same way, saying,

01:49:13.990 --> 01:49:18.690
"'Brother, go find your brother!' He watched where it stopped, and went there and looked.

01:49:19.150 --> 01:49:24.510
But it must have fallen short or gone too far, so he tried twice more. The last repetition

01:49:24.510 --> 01:49:27.830
was successful. The two marbles lay within a foot of each other.

01:49:28.450 --> 01:49:33.430
Just here the blast of a toy tin trumpet came faintly down the green aisles of the forest.

01:49:33.890 --> 01:49:39.630
Tom flung off his jacket and trousers, turned a suspender into a belt, raked away some brush

01:49:39.630 --> 01:49:45.450
behind the rotten log, disclosing a rude bow and arrow, a lath sword, and a tin trumpet,

01:49:45.770 --> 01:49:49.910
and in a moment had seized these things and bounded away bare-legged with fluttering shirt.

01:49:50.230 --> 01:49:55.870
He presently halted under a great elm, blew an answering blast, and then began to tip-toe

01:49:55.870 --> 01:50:01.090
and look warily out, this way and that. He said cautiously to an imaginary company,

01:50:01.510 --> 01:50:08.150
"'Hold, my merry men! Keep hid till I blow!' Now appeared Joe Harper, as airily clad and

01:50:08.150 --> 01:50:10.850
elaborately armed as Tom. Tom called,

01:50:11.050 --> 01:50:17.170
"'Hold! Who comes into Sherwood Forest without my pass? Guy of Gisborne wants no man's pass!

01:50:17.170 --> 01:50:22.670
Who art thou that—that dares to hold such language?' said Tom, prompting, for they talked

01:50:22.670 --> 01:50:27.450
by the book from memory. "'Who art thou that dares to hold such language?'

01:50:27.450 --> 01:50:32.530
"'I, indeed. I am Robin Hood, as thy Cate of Carcass soon shall know.'

01:50:33.090 --> 01:50:37.930
"'Then art thou indeed that famous outlaw? Right gladly will I dispute with thee the

01:50:37.930 --> 01:50:43.270
passes of the Merry Wood. Have at thee!' They took their lath swords, dumped their other

01:50:43.270 --> 01:50:47.850
traps on the ground, and struck a fencing attitude, foot to foot, and began a grave

01:50:47.850 --> 01:50:51.550
careful combat, two up and two down. Presently Tom said,

01:50:51.830 --> 01:50:57.750
"'Now if you've got the hang, go it lively!' So they went it lively, panting and perspiring

01:50:57.750 --> 01:50:59.770
with the work. By and by Tom shouted,

01:51:00.090 --> 01:51:02.670
"'Fall! Fall! Why don't you fall?'

01:51:02.670 --> 01:51:07.490
"'I shan't. Why don't you fall yourself? You're getting the worst of it.'

01:51:07.490 --> 01:51:12.670
"'Why, that ain't anything. I can't fall. That ain't the way it is in the book. The

01:51:12.670 --> 01:51:18.690
book says, then, with one black-handed stroke, he slew poor Guy of Gisborne. You're to turn

01:51:18.690 --> 01:51:22.970
round and let me hit you on the back.' There was no getting around the authorities, so

01:51:22.970 --> 01:51:25.110
Joe turned, received the whack, and fell.

01:51:25.710 --> 01:51:29.610
"'Now,' said Joe, getting up, "'you got to let me kill you. That's fair.'

01:51:30.190 --> 01:51:32.570
"'Why, I can't do that. It ain't in the book.'

01:51:32.570 --> 01:51:34.810
"'Well, it's blamed mean, that's all.'

01:51:34.810 --> 01:51:41.110
"'Well, say, Joe, you can be Friar Tuck, or Much, the miller's son, and land me with

01:51:41.110 --> 01:51:45.650
the quarter-staff, or I'll be the Sheriff of Nottingham, and you be Robin Hood a little

01:51:45.650 --> 01:51:47.270
while and kill me.'

01:51:47.270 --> 01:51:52.770
This was satisfactory, and so these adventures were carried out. Then Tom became Robin Hood

01:51:52.770 --> 01:51:56.990
again, and was allowed by the treacherous nun to bleed his strength away through his

01:51:56.990 --> 01:52:02.270
neglected wound. And at last Joe, representing a whole tribe of weeping outlaws, dragged

01:52:02.270 --> 01:52:07.050
him sadly forth, gave his bow into his feeble hands, and Tom said,

01:52:07.550 --> 01:52:14.250
"'Where this arrow falls, there bury poor Robin Hood under the Greenwood tree.' Then

01:52:14.250 --> 01:52:19.010
he shot the arrow and fell back, and would have died, but he lit on a nuttle, and sprang

01:52:19.010 --> 01:52:25.030
up too gaily for a corpse. The boys dressed themselves, hid their accouterments, and went

01:52:25.030 --> 01:52:30.290
off grieving that there were no outlaws any more, and wondering what modern civilization

01:52:30.290 --> 01:52:35.030
could claim to have done to compensate for their loss. They said they would rather be

01:52:35.030 --> 01:52:39.510
outlaws a year in Sherwood Forest than President of the United States forever.

01:52:57.870 --> 01:53:00.530
IX. TRAGEDY IN THE GRAVE-YARD.

01:53:01.490 --> 01:53:07.210
At half-past nine that night Tom and Sid were sent to bed as usual. They said their prayers,

01:53:07.210 --> 01:53:13.410
and Sid was soon asleep. Tom lay awake and waited in restless impatience. When it seemed

01:53:13.410 --> 01:53:19.490
to him that it must be nearly daylight he heard the clock strike ten. This was despair.

01:53:20.010 --> 01:53:24.210
He would have tossed and fidgeted as his nerves demanded, but he was afraid he might wake

01:53:24.210 --> 01:53:31.970
Sid, so he lay still and stared up into the dark. Everything was dismally still. By and

01:53:32.310 --> 01:53:39.070
of the stillness little scarcely perceptible noises began to emphasize themselves. The ticking

01:53:39.070 --> 01:53:45.730
of the clock began to bring itself into notice. Old beams began to crack mysteriously. The

01:53:45.730 --> 01:53:51.910
stairs creaked faintly. Evidently spirits were abroad. A measured, muffled snore issued

01:53:51.910 --> 01:53:57.530
from Aunt Polly's chamber. And now the tiresome chirping of a cricket that no human ingenuity

01:53:57.530 --> 01:54:04.350
could locate began. Next the ghastly ticking of a death watch in the wall at the bed's

01:54:04.350 --> 01:54:11.670
head made Tom shudder. It meant that somebody's days were numbered. Then the howl of a far-off

01:54:11.670 --> 01:54:16.550
dog rose on the night air and was answered by a fainter howl from a remoter distance.

01:54:17.250 --> 01:54:26.870
Tom was in an agony. At last he was satisfied the time had ceased and eternity begun. He

01:54:26.870 --> 01:54:33.030
clock chimed eleven, but he did not hear it. And then there came, mingling with his half-formed

01:54:33.030 --> 01:54:39.030
dreams, a most melancholy catterwalling. The raising of a neighbouring window disturbed

01:54:39.030 --> 01:54:43.830
him. A cry of, "'Scat, you devil!' and the crash of an empty bottle against the back

01:54:43.830 --> 01:54:49.370
of his aunt's woodshed brought him wide awake, and a single minute later he was dressed and

01:54:49.370 --> 01:54:54.890
out of the window and creeping along the roof of the L on all fours. He meowed with caution

01:54:54.890 --> 01:54:59.590
once or twice as he went, then jumped to the roof of the woodshed and thence to the ground.

01:55:00.210 --> 01:55:05.050
Huckleberry Finn was there, with his dead cat. The boys moved off and disappeared in

01:55:05.050 --> 01:55:09.610
the gloom. At the end of half an hour they were wading through the tall grass of the

01:55:09.610 --> 01:55:15.310
graveyard. It was a graveyard of the old-fashioned Western kind. It was on a hill, about a mile

01:55:15.310 --> 01:55:20.230
and a half from the village. It had a crazy bored fence around it, which leaned inward

01:55:20.230 --> 01:55:26.490
in places, and outward the rest of the time, but stood upright nowhere. Grass and weeds

01:55:26.490 --> 01:55:31.670
grew rank over the whole cemetery. All the old graves were sunken in, there was not a

01:55:31.670 --> 01:55:37.370
tombstone on the place. Round-topped, worm-eaten boards staggered over the graves, leaning

01:55:37.370 --> 01:55:43.370
for support, and finding none. Sacred to the memory of, so-and-so had been painted

01:55:43.370 --> 01:55:47.970
on them once, but it could no longer have been read on the most of them now, even if

01:55:47.970 --> 01:55:53.010
there had been light. A faint wind moaned through the trees, and Tom feared it might

01:55:53.010 --> 01:55:57.850
be the spirits of the dead complaining of being disturbed. The boys talked little, and

01:55:57.850 --> 01:56:02.270
only under their breath, for the time and the place and the pervading solemnity and

01:56:02.270 --> 01:56:07.610
silence oppressed their spirits. They found the sharp new heap they were seeking, and

01:56:07.610 --> 01:56:12.430
ensconced themselves within the protection of three great elms that grew in a bunch within

01:56:12.430 --> 01:56:17.850
a few feet of the grave. Then they waited in silence for what seemed a long time. The

01:56:17.850 --> 01:56:22.830
mooting of a distant owl was all the sound that troubled the dead's stillness. Tom's

01:56:22.830 --> 01:56:27.830
reflections grew oppressive. He must force some talk, so he said in a whisper,

01:56:28.190 --> 01:56:34.090
"'Huckie, do you believe the dead people like it for us to be here?' Huckleberry whispered,

01:56:34.550 --> 01:56:38.790
"'I wished I'd knowed. It's awful solemn-like, ain't it?'

01:56:38.790 --> 01:56:41.130
"'I bet it is.'

01:56:41.130 --> 01:56:45.830
There was a considerable pause while the boys canvassed this matter inwardly. Then Tom whispered,

01:56:45.830 --> 01:56:49.950
"'Say, Huckie, do you reckon Hoss Williams hears us talkin'?'

01:56:49.950 --> 01:56:53.770
"'Oh, course he does—least his spirit does.'

01:56:53.770 --> 01:56:59.930
Tom after a pause, "'I wish I'd said Mr. Williams, but I never meant any harm. Everybody called

01:56:59.930 --> 01:57:00.990
him Hoss.'

01:57:00.990 --> 01:57:05.530
"'A body can't be too particular how they talk about these here dead people, Tom.'

01:57:05.530 --> 01:57:11.210
This was a damper, and conversation died again. Presently Tom seized his comrade's arm and

01:57:11.830 --> 01:57:15.810
"'Shh! What is it, Tom?' And the two clung together with beating hearts.

01:57:15.890 --> 01:57:21.810
"'Shh! There it is again. Didn't you hear it? Ay, there, now you hear it. Lord, Tom, they're

01:57:21.810 --> 01:57:24.290
comin'—they're comin' sure. What do we do?'

01:57:24.830 --> 01:57:27.750
"'I don't know. Think they'll see us?'

01:57:27.750 --> 01:57:32.310
"'Oh, Tom, they can see in the dark—same as cats. I wished I hadn't come.'

01:57:32.310 --> 01:57:38.650
"'Oh, don't be feared. I don't believe they'll bother us. We ain't doin' any harm. If we

01:57:38.650 --> 01:57:41.830
keep perfectly still, maybe they won't notice us at all.'

01:57:41.830 --> 01:57:46.390
"'I'll try to, Tom, but, Lord, I'm all a shiver. Listen!'

01:57:46.830 --> 01:57:51.850
The boys bent their heads together and scarcely breathed. A muffled sound of voices floated

01:57:51.850 --> 01:57:53.170
up from the far end of the graveyard.

01:57:53.810 --> 01:57:56.050
"'Look! See! There!' whispered Tom.

01:57:56.250 --> 01:57:57.390
"'What is it?'

01:57:57.390 --> 01:58:00.790
"'It's devil fire! Oh, Tom, this is awful!'

01:58:01.270 --> 01:58:05.410
Some vague figures approached through the gloom, swinging an old-fashioned tin lantern

01:58:05.410 --> 01:58:09.710
that freckled the ground with innumerable little spangles of light. Presently Huckleberry

01:58:09.710 --> 01:58:10.790
whispered with a shudder.

01:58:11.270 --> 01:58:16.350
"'It's the devils, sure enough—three of them. Lordy, Tom, we're goners. Can you pray?'

01:58:16.350 --> 01:58:21.270
"'I'll try, but don't you be feared. They ain't going to hurt us. Now I lay me down

01:58:21.270 --> 01:58:21.830
to sleep—I—'

01:58:21.890 --> 01:58:23.630
"'Shh! What is it, Huck?'

01:58:23.630 --> 01:58:29.490
"'They're humans. One of them is, anyway. One of them's old muff Potter's voice.'

01:58:29.490 --> 01:58:35.390
"'No, taint so, is it? I bet I know it. Don't you stir nor budge. He ain't got

01:58:35.390 --> 01:58:39.790
taint sharp enough to notice us. Drunk the same as usual, likely. Blamed old rip.'

01:58:40.510 --> 01:58:45.090
"'All right, I'll keep still. Now they're stuck. Can't find it. Here they come again.

01:58:45.450 --> 01:58:51.010
Now they're hot. Cold again. Hot again. Red hot. They're pointed right this time. Say,

01:58:51.170 --> 01:58:54.750
Huck, I know another of them voices. It's Injun Joe.'

01:58:54.750 --> 01:59:00.150
"'That's so, that murdering half-breed. I'd rather they was devils a-durn sight. What

01:59:00.150 --> 01:59:01.550
can they be up to?'

01:59:01.550 --> 01:59:06.250
The whisper died wholly out now, for the three men had reached the grave and stood within

01:59:06.250 --> 01:59:07.770
a few feet of the boy's hiding-place.

01:59:08.870 --> 01:59:13.650
"'Here it is,' said the third voice, and the owner of it held up the lantern and revealed

01:59:13.650 --> 01:59:19.270
the face of young Dr. Robinson. Potter and Injun Joe were carrying a hand-barrow with

01:59:19.270 --> 01:59:23.470
a rope and a couple of shovels on it. They cast down their load and began to open the

01:59:23.470 --> 01:59:28.430
grave. The doctor put the lantern at the head of the grave, and came and sat with his back

01:59:28.430 --> 01:59:32.530
against one of the elm-trees. He was so close the boys could have touched him.

01:59:33.190 --> 01:59:37.670
"'Hurry, men,' he said in a low voice, "'the moon might come out at any moment.'

01:59:38.300 --> 01:59:43.270
They growled a response and went on digging. For some time there was no noise but the grating

01:59:43.270 --> 01:59:48.810
sound of the spades discharging their freight of mold and gravel. It was very monotonous.

01:59:49.350 --> 01:59:54.510
Finally a spade struck upon the coffin with a dull woody accent, and within another minute

01:59:54.510 --> 01:59:58.510
or two the men had hoisted it out of the ground. They pried off the lid with their

01:59:58.510 --> 02:00:03.530
shovels, got out the body, and dumped it rudely on the ground. The moon drifted from behind

02:00:03.530 --> 02:00:08.430
the clouds and exposed the pallid face. The barrow was got ready, and the corpse placed

02:00:08.430 --> 02:00:13.790
on it, covered with a blanket, and bound to its place with a rope. Potter took out a large

02:00:13.790 --> 02:00:17.270
spring-knife and cut off the dangling end of the rope, and then said,

02:00:17.390 --> 02:00:21.730
"'Now the cussed thing's ready, Sawbones, and you'll just out with another five, or

02:00:21.730 --> 02:00:23.170
here she stays.'

02:00:23.170 --> 02:00:25.170
"'That's the talk,' said Injun Joe.

02:00:25.570 --> 02:00:27.550
"'Look here, what does this mean?' said the doctor.

02:00:27.650 --> 02:00:30.530
"'You required your pay in advance, and I've paid you.'

02:00:30.530 --> 02:00:34.650
"'Yes, and you've done more than that,' said Injun Joe, approaching the doctor who

02:00:34.650 --> 02:00:39.570
was now standing. "'Five years ago you drove me away from your father's kitchen one night,

02:00:39.790 --> 02:00:44.330
when I come to ask for something to eat, and you said I weren't there for any good, and

02:00:44.330 --> 02:00:49.130
when I swore I'd get even with you, if it took a hundred years, your father had me jailed

02:00:49.130 --> 02:00:51.570
for a vagrant. Did you think I'd forget?'

02:00:51.570 --> 02:00:57.050
"'The Injun blood ain't in me for nothing. And now I've got you, and you got to settle,

02:00:57.090 --> 02:00:57.590
you know.'

02:00:57.590 --> 02:01:02.390
He was threatening the doctor, with his fist in his face by this time. The doctor struck

02:01:02.390 --> 02:01:06.730
out suddenly and stretched the ruffian on the ground. Potter dropped his knife and exclaimed,

02:01:06.990 --> 02:01:11.550
"'Here, now, don't you hit my pard!' and the next moment he was grappled with the doctor,

02:01:11.910 --> 02:01:15.890
and the two were struggling with might and main, trampling the grass and tearing the

02:01:15.890 --> 02:01:20.030
ground with their heels. Injun Joe sprang to his feet, his eyes flaming with passion,

02:01:20.030 --> 02:01:24.690
snatched up Potter's knife, and went creeping, cat-like and snooping, round and round about

02:01:24.690 --> 02:01:29.410
the combatants, seeking an opportunity. All at once the doctor flung himself free, seized

02:01:29.410 --> 02:01:33.450
the heavy headboard of William's grave, and felled Potter to the earth with it, and in

02:01:33.450 --> 02:01:37.690
the same instance the half-breed saw his chance and drove the knife to the hilt in the young

02:01:37.690 --> 02:01:44.130
man's breast. He reeled and fell partly upon Potter, flooding him with his blood, and in

02:01:44.130 --> 02:01:48.170
the same moment the clouds blotted out the dreadful spectacle, and the two frightened

02:01:48.170 --> 02:01:53.690
boys went speeding away in the dark. Presently, when the moon emerged again, Injun Joe was

02:01:53.690 --> 02:01:58.390
standing over the two forms, contemplating them. The doctor murmured inarticulately,

02:01:58.750 --> 02:02:03.070
gave a long gasp or two, and was still. The half-breed muttered,

02:02:03.490 --> 02:02:08.790
"'That score is settled, damn you!' Then he robbed the body, after which he put the

02:02:08.790 --> 02:02:14.390
fatal knife in Potter's open right hand, and sat down on the dismantled coffin. Three,

02:02:14.390 --> 02:02:20.190
four, five minutes passed, and then Potter began to stir and moan. His hand closed upon

02:02:20.190 --> 02:02:25.550
the knife. He raised it, glanced at it, and let it fall with a shudder. Then he sat up

02:02:25.550 --> 02:02:30.770
pushing the body from him, and gazed at it, and then around him, confusedly, his eyes

02:02:30.770 --> 02:02:31.770
met Joe's.

02:02:32.010 --> 02:02:34.550
"'Lord, how is this, Joe?' he said.

02:02:34.890 --> 02:02:37.550
"'It's a dirty business,' said Joe, without moving.

02:02:37.890 --> 02:02:39.770
"'What did you do it for?'

02:02:40.750 --> 02:02:45.610
"'I—I never done it. Look here, that kind of talk won't wash.'

02:02:45.610 --> 02:02:47.150
Potter trembled and grew white.

02:02:47.250 --> 02:02:52.450
"'I thought I'd got sober. I've no business to drink to-night. But it's in my head yet,

02:02:52.770 --> 02:02:57.570
worse than when we started here. I'm all in a muddle, can't recollect anything of it hardly.

02:02:57.990 --> 02:03:03.490
Tell me, Joe—honest now, old feller—did I do it? Joe, I never meant to, upon my soul

02:03:03.490 --> 02:03:08.690
and honour, I never meant to, Joe. Tell me how it was, Joe. Oh, it's awful! And him so

02:03:08.690 --> 02:03:14.290
young and promising. Why, you two were scuffling, and he fetched you one with a headboard, and

02:03:14.290 --> 02:03:19.630
you fell flat, and then up you come, all reeling and staggering-like, and snatched the knife

02:03:19.630 --> 02:03:24.290
and jammed it into him, just as he fetched you another awful clip, and here you've laid,

02:03:24.570 --> 02:03:30.950
as dead as a wedge till now. Oh, I didn't know what I was doing. I wish I may die this

02:03:30.950 --> 02:03:35.430
minute if I did. It was all on account of the whisky—and the excitement, I reckon.

02:03:35.430 --> 02:03:40.510
I never used a weepin' in my life before, Joe. I've fought, but never with weepins.

02:03:40.750 --> 02:03:45.750
They'll all say that. Joe, don't tell. Say you won't tell, Joe. That's a good feller.

02:03:45.910 --> 02:03:50.250
I always liked you, Joe, and stood up for you, too. Don't you remember? You won't tell,

02:03:50.350 --> 02:03:55.230
will you, Joe?" And the poor creature dropped on his knees before the stolid murderer and

02:03:55.230 --> 02:03:56.750
clasped his appealing hands.

02:03:57.810 --> 02:04:02.670
No. You've always been fair and square with me, Muff Potter, and I won't go back on you.

02:04:02.670 --> 02:04:05.110
There, now, that's as fair as a man can say.

02:04:05.790 --> 02:04:10.490
Oh, Joe, you're an angel. I'll bless you for this, the longest day I live—and Potter

02:04:10.490 --> 02:04:11.250
began to cry.

02:04:11.870 --> 02:04:16.970
Come, now, that's enough of that. This ain't any time for blubbering. You be off yonderway,

02:04:16.970 --> 02:04:20.730
and I'll go this. Move now, and don't leave any tracks behind you.

02:04:21.290 --> 02:04:26.290
Potter started on a trot that quickly increased to a run. The half-breed stood looking after

02:04:26.290 --> 02:04:27.150
him, and he muttered—

02:04:27.630 --> 02:04:32.650
If he's as much stunned with the lick and fuddled with the rum as he had the look of

02:04:32.650 --> 02:04:37.450
being, he won't think of the knife, till he's gone so far he'll be afraid to come back after

02:04:37.450 --> 02:04:42.470
it to such a place by himself, chicken-heart. Two or three minutes later the murdered man,

02:04:42.730 --> 02:04:47.810
the blanketed corpse, the lidless coffin, and the open grave rendered no inspection

02:04:47.810 --> 02:04:51.610
but the moon's. The stillness was complete again, too.

02:04:55.610 --> 02:04:56.650
CHAPTER X.

02:04:57.070 --> 02:04:59.870
DIRE PROPHECY OF THE HOWLING DOG

02:05:00.470 --> 02:05:05.710
The two boys flew on and on toward the village, speechless with horror. They glanced backwards

02:05:05.710 --> 02:05:10.110
over their shoulders from time to time, apprehensively, as if they feared they might be followed.

02:05:10.590 --> 02:05:15.350
Every stump that started up in their path seemed a man and an enemy, and made them catch

02:05:15.350 --> 02:05:20.670
their breath. And as they sped by some outlying cottages that lay near the village, the barking

02:05:20.670 --> 02:05:24.030
of the aroused watch-dogs seemed to give wings to their feet.

02:05:24.330 --> 02:05:29.130
"'If we can only get to the old tannery before we break down,' whispered Tom in short catches

02:05:29.130 --> 02:05:33.950
between breaths, "'I can't stand it much longer.' Huckleberry's hard pantings were his only

02:05:33.950 --> 02:05:38.070
reply, and the boys fixed their eyes on the goal of their hopes and bent to their work

02:05:38.070 --> 02:05:42.970
to win it. They gained steadily on it, and at last, breast to breast, they burst through

02:05:42.970 --> 02:05:47.950
the open door and fell grateful and exhausted in the sheltering shadows beyond. By and by

02:05:47.950 --> 02:05:52.350
their pulses slowed down, and Tom whispered, "'Huckleberry, what do you reckon'll come

02:05:52.350 --> 02:05:53.150
of this?'

02:05:53.150 --> 02:05:57.390
"'If Dr. Robinson dies, I reckon hangin''ll come of it.'

02:05:57.390 --> 02:05:58.910
"'Do you, though?'

02:05:58.910 --> 02:06:01.510
"'Why, I know it, Tom.'

02:06:01.510 --> 02:06:07.330
Tom thought awhile, and he said, "'Who'll tell? We? What are you talkin' about? Suppose

02:06:07.330 --> 02:06:11.890
something happened and Injun Joe didn't hang. Why, he'd kill us some time or other, just

02:06:11.890 --> 02:06:17.850
as dead sure as we're layin' here. That's just what I was thinkin' to myself, Huck.'

02:06:17.850 --> 02:06:22.830
"'If anybody tells, let Muff Potter do it. If he's fool enough, he's generally drunk

02:06:22.830 --> 02:06:23.650
enough.'

02:06:23.650 --> 02:06:27.230
Tom said nothing, went on thinking. Presently he whispered,

02:06:27.230 --> 02:06:31.730
"'Huck, Muff Potter don't know it. How can he tell?'

02:06:31.730 --> 02:06:33.710
"'What's the reason he don't know it?'

02:06:33.710 --> 02:06:38.510
"'Because he'd just got that whack when Injun Joe done it. Do you reckon he could see anything?

02:06:39.030 --> 02:06:41.370
Do you reckon he knowed anything?'

02:06:41.370 --> 02:06:47.630
"'By hokey, that's so, Tom. And besides, look here, maybe that whack done for him.

02:06:47.630 --> 02:06:52.670
"'No, taint likely, Tom. He had liquor in him. I could see that. And besides, he always

02:06:52.670 --> 02:06:58.010
has. Well, when paps full, he might take and belt him over the head with a church and you

02:06:58.010 --> 02:07:03.110
couldn't faze him. He says so his own self. So it's the same with Muff Potter, of course.

02:07:03.530 --> 02:07:08.470
But if a man was dead sober, I reckon maybe that whack might fetch him. I don't know.'

02:07:08.470 --> 02:07:10.670
After another reflective silence Tom said,

02:07:10.970 --> 02:07:13.350
"'Hucky, you sure you can keep Mum?'

02:07:13.810 --> 02:07:18.910
"'Tom, we got to keep Mum. You know that. That Injun devil wouldn't make any more of drowning

02:07:18.910 --> 02:07:24.330
us than a couple of cats, if we was to squeak about this and they didn't hang him. Now look

02:07:24.330 --> 02:07:29.090
here, Tom, let's take and swear to one another. That's what we got to do—swear to keep Mum.'

02:07:29.590 --> 02:07:33.550
"'I'm agreed. It's the best thing. Would you just hold hands and swear that we—'

02:07:33.630 --> 02:07:38.070
"'Oh, no, that wouldn't do for this. That's good enough for little rubbishy common things,

02:07:38.070 --> 02:07:42.930
especially with gals, because they go back on you anyway, and blab if they get in a huff.

02:07:43.190 --> 02:07:48.190
But there ought to be writing about a big thing like this—and blood.'

02:07:48.190 --> 02:07:53.690
Tom's whole being applauded this idea. It was deep and dark and awful. The hour, the

02:07:53.690 --> 02:07:58.630
circumstances, the surroundings were in keeping with it. He picked up a clean pine shingle

02:07:58.630 --> 02:08:03.190
that lay in the moonlight, took a little fragment of red keel out of his pocket, got the moon

02:08:03.190 --> 02:08:08.950
on his work, and painfully scrawled these lines, emphasizing each slow downstroke by

02:08:08.950 --> 02:08:12.950
clamping his tongue between his teeth and letting up the pressure on the upstrokes.

02:08:13.310 --> 02:08:14.630
See next page.

02:08:15.230 --> 02:08:19.370
Huckleberry was filled with admiration of Tom's facility in writing and the sublimity

02:08:19.370 --> 02:08:23.270
of his language. He at once took a pin from his lapel and was going to prick his flesh,

02:08:23.290 --> 02:08:23.890
but Tom said,

02:08:24.090 --> 02:08:29.150
"'Hold on! Don't do that! A pin's brass. It might have vertigrease on it.'

02:08:29.590 --> 02:08:34.490
What's vertigrease? It's pison. That's what it is. You just swallow some of it once—you'll

02:08:34.490 --> 02:08:35.270
see."

02:08:35.270 --> 02:08:40.670
So Tom unwound a thread from one of his needles, and each boy pricked the ball of his thumb

02:08:40.670 --> 02:08:42.550
and squeezed out a drop of blood.

02:08:43.950 --> 02:08:50.470
Huck Finn and Tom Sawyer swears they will keep mum about this, and they wish they may

02:08:50.470 --> 02:08:54.930
drop down dead in their tracks if they ever tell and rot.

02:08:55.550 --> 02:09:00.370
In time, after many squeezes, Tom managed to sign his initials using the ball of his

02:09:00.370 --> 02:09:06.130
little finger for a pen. Then he showed Huckleberry how to make an H and an F, and the oath was

02:09:06.130 --> 02:09:11.030
complete. They buried the shingle close to the wall, with some dismal ceremonies and

02:09:11.030 --> 02:09:15.590
incantations, and the fetters that bound their tongues were considered to be locked, and

02:09:15.590 --> 02:09:20.430
the key thrown away. A figure crept stealthily through a break in the other end of the ruined

02:09:20.430 --> 02:09:22.470
building now, but they did not notice it.

02:09:23.210 --> 02:09:24.570
Tom whispered to Huckleberry,

02:09:25.170 --> 02:09:27.950
"'Does this keep us from ever telling—always?'

02:09:28.610 --> 02:09:33.990
"'Of course it does. It don't make any difference. What happens? We gotta keep mum. We drop down

02:09:33.990 --> 02:09:35.910
dead. Don't you know that?'

02:09:35.910 --> 02:09:38.110
"'Yes, I reckon that's so."

02:09:38.110 --> 02:09:42.550
They continued to whisper for some little time. Presently a dog set up a long, lugubrious

02:09:42.550 --> 02:09:46.990
howl just outside, within ten feet of them. The boys clasped each other suddenly in an

02:09:46.990 --> 02:09:47.590
agony of fright.

02:09:47.830 --> 02:09:50.110
"'Which of us does he mean?' gasped Huckleberry.

02:09:50.110 --> 02:09:52.470
"'I don't know. Peep through the crack, quick.'

02:09:52.470 --> 02:09:53.730
"'No, you, Tom.'

02:09:53.730 --> 02:09:55.690
"'I can't. I can't do it, Huck.'

02:09:55.690 --> 02:09:57.970
"'Please, Tom. There it is again.'

02:09:57.970 --> 02:10:03.610
"'Oh, Lordy, I'm thankful,' whispered Tom. I know his voice. It's Bull Harbison."

02:10:03.610 --> 02:10:10.330
Note. If Mr. Harbison had owned a slave named Bull, Tom would have spoken of him as Harbison's

02:10:10.330 --> 02:10:14.850
Bull. But a son, or a dog, of that name was Bull Harbison.

02:10:14.850 --> 02:10:19.970
"'Oh, that's good. I tell you, Tom, I was scared to death, and I'd have bet anything

02:10:19.970 --> 02:10:24.630
it was a stray dog.' The dog howled again. The boys' hearts sank once more.

02:10:25.210 --> 02:10:28.210
"'Oh, my! That ain't no Bull Harbison!' whispered Huckleberry.

02:10:28.470 --> 02:10:29.590
"'Do, Tom!'

02:10:29.590 --> 02:10:33.930
Tom, quicking with fear, yielded and put his eye to the crack. His whisper was hardly

02:10:33.930 --> 02:10:34.770
audible when he said,

02:10:35.410 --> 02:10:37.890
"'Oh, Huck, it's a stray dog.'

02:10:38.490 --> 02:10:41.110
"'Quick, Tom, quick. Who does he mean?'

02:10:41.110 --> 02:10:44.350
"'Huck, he must mean us both. We're right together.'

02:10:44.350 --> 02:10:48.590
"'Oh, Tom, I reckon we're goners. I reckon there ain't no mistake about where I'll go

02:10:48.590 --> 02:10:50.010
to. I've been so wicked.'

02:10:50.710 --> 02:10:54.850
"'Dag-fetch it! This comes of playing hooky and doing everything a feller's told not to

02:10:54.850 --> 02:10:59.470
do. I might have been good like Sid if I'd a tried, but no, I wouldn't, of course. But

02:10:59.470 --> 02:11:04.850
if ever I get off of this time, I lay I'll just waller in Sunday schools.' And Tom began

02:11:04.850 --> 02:11:06.050
to snuffle a little.

02:11:07.130 --> 02:11:08.090
"'You bad?'

02:11:08.090 --> 02:11:10.210
And Huckleberry began to snuffle, too.

02:11:10.330 --> 02:11:17.010
"'Con sound it, Tom Sawyer. You're just old pie, long side of what I am. Oh, lordy, lordy,

02:11:17.010 --> 02:11:19.950
lordy! I wished I'd only had half your chance.'

02:11:19.950 --> 02:11:21.490
Tom choked off and whispered,

02:11:21.650 --> 02:11:24.690
"'Look, Hucky, look! He's got his back to us.'

02:11:24.690 --> 02:11:26.510
Hucky looked with joy in his heart.

02:11:26.930 --> 02:11:30.050
"'Well, he has, by jingos. Did he before?'

02:11:30.050 --> 02:11:35.590
"'Yes, he did. But I—like a fool, I never thought. Oh, this is bully, you know. Now,

02:11:35.810 --> 02:11:37.090
who can he mean?'

02:11:37.090 --> 02:11:39.210
The howling stopped, and Tom pricked up his ears.

02:11:39.350 --> 02:11:41.330
"'Shh! What's that?' he whispered.

02:11:41.370 --> 02:11:46.570
"'Sounds like—like hogs grunting. No, it's somebody snoring, Tom.'

02:11:46.570 --> 02:11:52.430
"'That is it. Whereabouts is it, Huck? I believe it's down at Tother End. Sounds so, anyway.

02:11:52.870 --> 02:11:58.270
Pap used to sleep there sometimes, long with the hogs. But laws bless you, he just lifts

02:11:58.270 --> 02:12:03.150
things when he snores. Besides, I reckon he ain't ever coming back to this town any more.'

02:12:03.150 --> 02:12:06.550
The spirit of adventure rose in the boy's soul once more.

02:12:06.550 --> 02:12:12.430
"'Hucky, do you dare to go if I lead? I don't like too much. Tom's supposed it's Injun Joe.'

02:12:12.430 --> 02:12:17.370
Tom quailed. But presently the temptation rose up strong again, and the boys agreed to try,

02:12:17.390 --> 02:12:22.070
with the understanding that they would take to their heels if the snoring stopped. So

02:12:22.070 --> 02:12:26.770
they went tip-toeing, stealthily down, the one behind the other. When they had got to

02:12:26.770 --> 02:12:31.710
within five steps of the snore, Tom stepped on a stick, and it broke with a sharp snap.

02:12:32.070 --> 02:12:37.830
The man moaned, writhed little, and his face came into the moonlight. It was Muff Potter.

02:12:38.450 --> 02:12:42.490
The boys' hearts had stood still in their hopes, too, when the man moved, but their

02:12:42.490 --> 02:12:47.550
fears passed away now. They tip-toed out, through the broken weather-boarding, and stopped

02:12:47.550 --> 02:12:52.930
a little distance to exchange a parting word. That long, lugubrious howl rose on the nightmare

02:12:52.930 --> 02:12:57.370
again. They turned and saw the strange dog standing within a few feet of where Potter

02:12:57.370 --> 02:13:01.310
was lying, and facing Potter, with his nose pointing heavenward.

02:13:02.090 --> 02:13:05.290
"'Oh, Jiminy, it's him!' exclaimed both boys, in a breath.

02:13:06.090 --> 02:13:10.750
"'Say, Tom, they say a stray dog come howling round Johnny Miller's house about midnight

02:13:10.750 --> 02:13:16.090
as much as two weeks ago, and a whipper-wheel come in and lit on a banister and sung the

02:13:16.090 --> 02:13:19.290
very same evening, and there ain't anybody dead there yet.'

02:13:19.290 --> 02:13:24.470
"'Well, I know that, and suppose there ain't. Didn't Gracie Miller fall in the kitchen

02:13:24.470 --> 02:13:26.870
and burn herself terrible the very next Saturday?'

02:13:27.570 --> 02:13:31.870
"'Yes, but she ain't dead. And what's more, she's getting better, too.'

02:13:31.870 --> 02:13:36.270
"'All right, well, you wait and see. She's a goner just as dead sure as Muff Potter's

02:13:36.270 --> 02:13:40.630
a goner. That's what the niggers say, and they know all about these kind of things,

02:13:40.950 --> 02:13:41.270
Huck.'

02:13:41.270 --> 02:13:43.030
Then they separated, cogitating.

02:13:43.550 --> 02:13:48.490
When Tom crept in at his bedroom window, the night was almost spent. He undressed with

02:13:48.490 --> 02:13:53.530
excessive caution, and fell asleep congratulating himself that nobody knew of his escapade.

02:13:53.530 --> 02:13:59.770
He was not aware that the gently snoring Sid was awake, and had been so for an hour. When

02:13:59.770 --> 02:14:04.570
Tom awoke, Sid was dressed and gone. There was a late look in the light, a late sense

02:14:04.570 --> 02:14:10.290
in the atmosphere. He was startled. Why had he not been called? Persecuted till he was

02:14:10.290 --> 02:14:15.830
up as usual. The thought filled him with boatings. Within five minutes he was dressed and downstairs,

02:14:16.090 --> 02:14:20.210
feeling sore and drowsy. The family were still at table, but they had finished breakfast.

02:14:20.210 --> 02:14:26.130
There was no voice of rebuke, but there were averted eyes. There was a silence and an air

02:14:26.130 --> 02:14:31.030
of solemnity that struck a chill to the culprit's heart. He sat down and tried to seem gay,

02:14:31.230 --> 02:14:37.270
but it was uphill work. It roused no smile, no response, and he lapsed into silence and

02:14:37.270 --> 02:14:38.890
let his heart sink down to the depths.

02:14:39.530 --> 02:14:43.790
After breakfast his aunt took him aside, and Tom was almost brightened in the hope that

02:14:43.790 --> 02:14:48.850
he was going to be flogged, but it was not so. His aunt wept over him and asked him how

02:14:48.850 --> 02:14:54.170
he could go and break her old heart so, and finally told him to go on and ruin himself

02:14:54.170 --> 02:14:59.210
and bring her grey hairs with sorrow to the grave, for it was no use for her to try any

02:14:59.210 --> 02:15:04.470
more. This was worse than a thousand whippings, and Tom's heart was soarer now than his body.

02:15:04.890 --> 02:15:10.790
He cried, he pleaded for forgiveness, promised to reform over and over again, and then received

02:15:10.790 --> 02:15:15.990
his dismissal, feeling that he had won but an imperfect forgiveness and established but

02:15:15.990 --> 02:15:22.310
confidence. He left the presence too miserable to even feel revengeful towards Sid, and so

02:15:22.310 --> 02:15:27.290
the latter's prompt retreat through the back gateway was unnecessary. He moped to school

02:15:27.290 --> 02:15:32.210
gloomy and sad, and took his flogging, along with Joe Harper, for playing hooky the day

02:15:32.210 --> 02:15:37.750
before, with the air of one whose heart was busy with heavier woes and wholly dead to

02:15:37.750 --> 02:15:42.730
trifles. Then he betook himself to his seat, rested his elbows on his desk and his jaws

02:15:42.730 --> 02:15:47.110
in his hands, and stared at the wall with a stony stare of suffering that has reached

02:15:47.110 --> 02:15:52.150
the limit and can no further go. His elbow was pressing against some hard substance.

02:15:52.510 --> 02:15:57.290
After a long time he slowly and sadly changed his position and took up this object with

02:15:57.290 --> 02:16:03.710
a sigh. It was in a paper. He unrolled it. A long, lingering, colossal sigh followed

02:16:03.710 --> 02:16:11.670
and his heart broke. It was his brass and iron knob. This final feather broke the camel's

02:16:11.670 --> 02:16:12.250
back.

02:16:28.610 --> 02:16:29.330
XI.

02:16:29.730 --> 02:16:32.210
CONSCIENCE RACKS TOM.

02:16:33.550 --> 02:16:38.490
Close upon the hour of noon the whole village was suddenly electrified with the ghastly

02:16:38.490 --> 02:16:45.790
news. No need of the as yet undreamed of telegraph. The tale flew from man to man, from group

02:16:45.790 --> 02:16:51.230
to group, from house to house, with little less than telegraphic speed. Of course, the

02:16:51.230 --> 02:16:55.770
schoolmaster gave holiday for that afternoon. The town would have thought strangely of him

02:16:55.770 --> 02:17:01.710
if he had not. A gory knife had been found close to the murdered man, and it had been

02:17:01.710 --> 02:17:06.970
recognized by somebody as belonging to Muff Potter. So the story ran. And it was said

02:17:06.970 --> 02:17:12.330
that a belated citizen had come upon Potter washing himself in the branch, about one or

02:17:12.330 --> 02:17:18.070
two o'clock in the morning, and that Potter had at once sneaked off. Suspicious circumstances,

02:17:18.310 --> 02:17:23.310
especially the washing, which was not a habit with Potter. It was also said that the town

02:17:23.310 --> 02:17:28.250
had been ransacked for this murderer—the public are not slow in the matter of sifting

02:17:28.250 --> 02:17:33.390
evidence and arriving at a verdict—but that he could not be found. Horsemen had departed

02:17:33.390 --> 02:17:38.490
all the roads in every direction, and the sheriff was confident that he would be captured

02:17:38.490 --> 02:17:43.970
before night. All the town was drifting toward the graveyard. Tom's heartbreak vanished,

02:17:44.110 --> 02:17:49.010
and he joined the procession, not because he would not a thousand times rather go anywhere

02:17:49.010 --> 02:17:55.990
else, but because an awful unaccountable fascination drew him on. Arrived at the dreadful place,

02:17:56.170 --> 02:18:01.130
he wormed his small body through the crowd and saw the dismal spectacle. It seemed to

02:18:01.130 --> 02:18:06.730
him an age since he was there before. Somebody pinched his arm. He turned, and his eyes met

02:18:06.730 --> 02:18:11.470
huckleberries. Then both looked elsewhere at once, and wondered if anybody had noticed

02:18:11.470 --> 02:18:16.650
anything in their mutual glance. But everybody was talking, and intent upon the grisly spectacle

02:18:16.650 --> 02:18:17.410
before them.

02:18:17.810 --> 02:18:24.150
"'Poor fellow! Poor young fellow! This ought to be a lesson to grave robbers. Muff Potter

02:18:24.150 --> 02:18:28.530
will hang for this if they catch him.' This was the drift of remark, and the minister

02:18:28.530 --> 02:18:33.330
said, "'It was a judgment. His hand is here.'"

02:18:33.330 --> 02:18:38.630
Now Tom shivered from head to heel, for his eye fell upon the stolid face of Injun Joe.

02:18:38.970 --> 02:18:42.490
At this moment the crowd began to sway and struggle, and voices shouted,

02:18:42.650 --> 02:18:47.770
"'It's him! It's him! He's coming himself! Who? Who?" from twenty voices.

02:18:48.130 --> 02:18:49.530
"'Muff Potter!'

02:18:49.530 --> 02:18:54.830
"'Hullo! He's stopped. Look out! He's turning. Don't let him get away!' People in the branches

02:18:54.830 --> 02:18:59.030
of the trees over Tom's head said he wasn't trying to get away. He only looked doubtful

02:18:59.030 --> 02:18:59.770
and perplexed.

02:19:00.610 --> 02:19:05.150
"'Infernal impudence!' said a bystander. Wanted to come and take a quiet look at his

02:19:05.150 --> 02:19:10.890
work. I reckon. Didn't expect any company.' The crowd fell apart now, and the sheriff

02:19:10.890 --> 02:19:16.490
came through, ostentatiously leading Potter by the arm. The poor fellow's face was haggard,

02:19:16.630 --> 02:19:20.950
and his eyes showed the fear that was upon him. When he stood before the murdered man

02:19:20.950 --> 02:19:25.610
he shook as with a palsy, and he put his face in his hands and burst into tears.

02:19:26.010 --> 02:19:32.990
"'I didn't do it, friends!' he sobbed. "'Pon my word! An honour! I never done it!'

02:19:32.990 --> 02:19:38.710
"'Whose accused you?' shouted a voice. This shot seemed to carry home. Potter lifted his

02:19:38.710 --> 02:19:43.410
face and looked around him with a pathetic hopelessness in his eyes. He saw Injun Joe

02:19:43.410 --> 02:19:44.070
and exclaimed,

02:19:44.430 --> 02:19:47.610
"'Oh, Injun Joe, you promised me you'd never—'

02:19:47.610 --> 02:19:52.970
"'Is that your knife?' And it was thrust before him by the sheriff. Potter would have

02:19:52.970 --> 02:19:57.630
fallen if they had caught him, and eased him to the ground. Then he said,

02:19:58.590 --> 02:20:03.830
"'Something's told me to—if I didn't come back and get—' he shuddered, and then

02:20:03.830 --> 02:20:06.830
waved his nerveless hand with a vanquished gesture, and said,

02:20:07.150 --> 02:20:10.670
"'Tell him, Joe, tell him! It ain't any use any more!'

02:20:10.670 --> 02:20:16.470
Then Huckleberry and Tom stood dumb and staring, and heard the stony-hearted liar reel off

02:20:16.470 --> 02:20:22.990
his serene statement, they expecting every moment that the clear sky would deliver God's

02:20:22.990 --> 02:20:28.790
lightnings upon his head, and wondering to see how long the stroke was delayed. And when

02:20:28.790 --> 02:20:33.370
he had finished, and still stood alive and whole, their wavering impulse to break their

02:20:33.370 --> 02:20:38.790
oath and save the poor betrayed prisoner's life faded and vanished away, for plainly

02:20:38.790 --> 02:20:43.390
this miscreant had sold himself to Satan, and it would be fatal to meddle with the property

02:20:43.390 --> 02:20:44.670
of such a power as that.

02:20:45.230 --> 02:20:49.550
"'Why didn't you leave? What did you want to come here for?' somebody said.

02:20:49.810 --> 02:20:52.870
"'I couldn't help it, I couldn't help it!' Potter moaned.

02:20:53.230 --> 02:20:57.910
"'I wanted to run away, but I couldn't seem to come anywhere but here.' And he fell to

02:20:57.910 --> 02:20:58.690
sobbing again.

02:20:59.310 --> 02:21:04.670
Injun Joe repeated his statement just as calmly a few minutes afterwards on the inquest, under

02:21:04.670 --> 02:21:10.150
oath, and the boys, seeing that the lightnings were still withheld, were confirmed in their

02:21:10.150 --> 02:21:16.610
belief that Joe had sold himself to the devil. He was now become to them the most balefully

02:21:16.610 --> 02:21:21.250
interesting object they had ever looked upon, and they could not take their fascinated eyes

02:21:21.250 --> 02:21:26.970
from his face. They inwardly resolved to watch him, nights, when opportunity should offer,

02:21:27.230 --> 02:21:32.710
in the hope of getting a glimpse of his dread master. Injun Joe helped to raise the body

02:21:32.710 --> 02:21:36.850
of the murdered man and put it in a wagon for removal, and it was whispered through

02:21:36.850 --> 02:21:41.670
the shuddering crowd that the wound bled a little. The boys thought that this happy

02:21:41.670 --> 02:21:46.310
circumstance would turn suspicion in the right direction, but they were disappointed, for

02:21:46.310 --> 02:21:47.890
more than one villager remarked,

02:21:47.950 --> 02:21:51.670
"'It was within three feet of Muff Potter when he'd done it!'

02:21:51.670 --> 02:21:57.050
Tom's fearful secret and gnawing conscience disturbed his sleep for as much as a week

02:21:57.050 --> 02:22:00.230
after this, and at breakfast one morning Sid said,

02:22:00.890 --> 02:22:06.630
"'Tom, you pitch around and talk in your sleep so much that you keep me awake half the time!'

02:22:06.630 --> 02:22:08.790
Tom blanched and dropped his eyes.

02:22:09.410 --> 02:22:14.850
"'It's a bad sign,' said Aunt Polly gravely. "'What you got on your mind, Tom?'

02:22:15.490 --> 02:22:18.570
"'Nothing. Nothing to know of.'

02:22:18.570 --> 02:22:21.770
But the boy's hand shook so that he spilled his coffee.

02:22:21.850 --> 02:22:27.810
"'And you do talk such stuff,' said Sid. "'Last night you said, It's blood, It's blood,

02:22:27.810 --> 02:22:33.090
that's what it is. You said that over and over, and you said, Don't torment me so. I'll

02:22:33.090 --> 02:22:33.850
tell.'

02:22:33.850 --> 02:22:36.310
"'Tell what? What is it you'll tell?'

02:22:36.970 --> 02:22:41.250
Everything was swimming before, Tom. There's no telling what might have happened now, but

02:22:41.250 --> 02:22:46.390
luckily the concern passed out of Aunt Polly's face, and she came to Tom's relief without

02:22:46.390 --> 02:22:47.710
knowing it. She said,

02:22:47.890 --> 02:22:53.270
"'Sure. It's that dreadful murder. I dream about it most every night myself. Sometimes

02:22:53.270 --> 02:22:55.310
I dream it's me that done it.'

02:22:55.310 --> 02:23:01.090
Mary said she had been affected much the same way. Sid seemed satisfied. Tom got out of

02:23:01.090 --> 02:23:05.250
the presence as quick as he plausibly could, and after that he complained of a toothache

02:23:05.250 --> 02:23:10.850
for a week, and tied up his jaws every night. He never knew that Sid lay nightly watching,

02:23:11.210 --> 02:23:16.410
and frequently slipped the bandage free, and then leaned on his elbow, listening a good

02:23:16.410 --> 02:23:22.290
while at a time, and afterwards slipped the bandage back to its place again. Tom's distress

02:23:22.290 --> 02:23:29.050
of mind wore off gradually, and the toothache grew irksome and was discarded. If Sid really

02:23:29.050 --> 02:23:34.830
managed to make anything out of Tom's disjointed mutterings, he kept it to himself. It seemed

02:23:34.830 --> 02:23:40.810
to Tom that his schoolmates never would get done holding inquests on dead cats, and thus

02:23:40.810 --> 02:23:46.230
keeping his trouble present to his mind. Sid noticed that Tom never was coroner at one

02:23:46.230 --> 02:23:51.210
of these inquiries, though it had been his habit to take the lead in all new enterprises.

02:23:51.910 --> 02:23:57.190
He noticed, too, that Tom never acted as a witness, and that was strange, and Sid did

02:23:57.190 --> 02:24:02.370
not overlook the fact that Tom even showed a marked aversion to these inquests, and always

02:24:02.370 --> 02:24:03.430
avoided them when he could.

02:24:04.190 --> 02:24:11.030
Sid marveled, but said nothing. However, even inquests went out of vogue at last, and ceased

02:24:11.030 --> 02:24:17.270
to torture Tom's conscience. Every day or two, during this time of sorrow, Tom watched

02:24:17.270 --> 02:24:23.130
his opportunity, and went to the little grated jail window, and smuggled such small comforts

02:24:23.130 --> 02:24:28.890
through to the murderer, as he could get hold of. The jail was a trifling little brick den

02:24:28.890 --> 02:24:34.210
that stood in a marsh at the edge of the village, and no guards were afforded for it, indeed

02:24:34.210 --> 02:24:40.350
it was seldom occupied. These offerings greatly helped to ease Tom's conscience. The villagers

02:24:40.350 --> 02:24:45.150
had a strong desire to tar and feather Injun Joe and ride him on a rail for body-snatching,

02:24:45.630 --> 02:24:50.710
but so formidable was his character that nobody could be found who was willing to take the

02:24:50.710 --> 02:24:56.130
lead in the matter, so it was dropped. He had been careful to begin both of his inquest

02:24:56.130 --> 02:25:02.710
the fight, without confessing the grave robbery that preceded it. Therefore it was deemed

02:25:02.710 --> 02:25:05.970
wisest not to try the case in the courts at present.

02:25:10.250 --> 02:25:14.230
CHAPTER XII. THE CAT AND THE PAIN-KILLER.

02:25:14.990 --> 02:25:19.890
One of the reasons why Tom's mind had drifted away from its secret troubles was that it

02:25:19.890 --> 02:25:25.770
had found a new and weighty matter to interest itself about. Becky Thatcher had stopped coming

02:25:25.770 --> 02:25:31.130
to school. Tom had struggled with his pride a few days, and tried to whistle her down

02:25:31.130 --> 02:25:36.410
the wind, but failed. He began to find himself hanging around her father's house nights,

02:25:36.810 --> 02:25:38.130
and feeling very miserable.

02:25:38.790 --> 02:25:45.330
She was ill. What if she should die? There was distraction in the thought. He no longer

02:25:45.330 --> 02:25:51.370
took an interest in war, nor even in piracy. The charm of life was gone. There was nothing

02:25:51.370 --> 02:25:57.050
but dreariness left. He put his hoop away, and his bat. There was no joy in them anymore.

02:25:57.510 --> 02:26:03.110
His aunt was concerned. She began to try all manner of remedies on him. She was one of

02:26:03.110 --> 02:26:08.610
those people who are infatuated with patent medicines, and all newfangled methods of producing

02:26:08.610 --> 02:26:14.290
health or mending it. She was an inveterate experimenter in these things. When something

02:26:14.290 --> 02:26:20.450
fresh in this line came out, she was in a fever, right away, to try it. Not on herself,

02:26:20.450 --> 02:26:26.630
for she was never ailing, but on anybody else that came handy. She was a subscriber for

02:26:26.630 --> 02:26:32.930
all the health periodicals and phenomenological frauds, and the solemn ignorance they were

02:26:32.930 --> 02:26:39.710
inflated with was breath to her nostrils. All the rot they contained about ventilation

02:26:39.710 --> 02:26:46.070
and how to go to bed, and how to get up, and what to eat, and what to drink, and how much

02:26:46.070 --> 02:26:52.470
to take, and what frame of mind to keep oneself in, and what sort of clothing to wear, was

02:26:52.470 --> 02:26:57.750
all gospel to her, and she never observed that her health journals of the current month

02:26:57.750 --> 02:27:04.330
customarily upset everything they had recommended the month before. She was as simple-hearted

02:27:04.330 --> 02:27:10.170
and honest as the day was long, and so she was an easy victim. She gathered together

02:27:10.170 --> 02:27:15.990
her quack periodicals and her quack medicines, and thus armed with death went about on her

02:27:15.990 --> 02:27:22.630
pale horse, metaphorically speaking, with the hell following after. But she never suspected

02:27:22.630 --> 02:27:27.330
that she was not an angel of healing and the balm of Gilead in disguise to the suffering

02:27:27.330 --> 02:27:34.250
neighbors. The water treatment was new, now, and Tom's low condition was a windfall to

02:27:34.250 --> 02:27:39.610
her. She had him out at daylight every morning, stood him up in the woodshed, and drowned

02:27:39.610 --> 02:27:44.670
him with a deluge of cold water. Then she scrubbed him down with a towel like a file,

02:27:44.670 --> 02:27:50.410
and so brought him to. Then she rolled him up in a wet sheet and put him away under blankets

02:27:50.410 --> 02:27:56.110
till she sweated his soul clean, and the yellow stains of it came through his pores, as Tom

02:27:56.110 --> 02:27:56.450
said.

02:27:57.210 --> 02:28:01.990
Yet notwithstanding all this, the boy grew more and more melancholy and pale and dejected.

02:28:02.410 --> 02:28:14.650
She added hot baths, sitz baths, shower baths, and plunges. The boy remained as dismal as

02:28:14.650 --> 02:28:20.750
She calculated his capacity as she would a jugs, and filled him up every day with quack

02:28:20.750 --> 02:28:27.110
cure-alls. Tom had become indifferent to persecution by this time. This phase filled the old lady's

02:28:27.110 --> 02:28:33.590
heart with consternation. This indifference must be broken up at any cost. Now she heard

02:28:33.590 --> 02:28:39.190
of painkiller for the first time. She ordered a lot at once. She tasted it and was filled

02:28:39.190 --> 02:28:44.810
with gratitude. It was simply fire in a liquid form. She dropped the water treatment and

02:28:44.810 --> 02:28:51.570
everything else, and pinned her faith to painkiller. She gave Tom a teaspoonful and watched with

02:28:51.570 --> 02:28:56.810
the deepest anxiety for the result. Her troubles were instantly at rest, her soul at peace

02:28:56.810 --> 02:29:03.410
again. For the indifference was broken up. The boy could not have shown a wilder, heartier

02:29:03.410 --> 02:29:10.550
if she had built a fire under him. Tom felt that it was time to wake up. This sort of

02:29:10.550 --> 02:29:15.670
life might be romantic enough in his blighted condition, but it was getting to have too

02:29:15.670 --> 02:29:21.150
little sentiment and too much distracting variety about it. So he thought over various

02:29:21.150 --> 02:29:27.750
plans for relief, and finally hit upon that of professing to be fond of painkiller. He

02:29:27.750 --> 02:29:32.290
asked for it so often that he became a nuisance, and his aunt ended by telling him to help

02:29:32.290 --> 02:29:37.070
himself and quit bothering her. If it had been Sid, she would have had no misgivings

02:29:37.070 --> 02:29:42.770
to alloy her delight, but since it was Tom she watched the bottle clandestinely. She

02:29:42.770 --> 02:29:47.630
found that the medicine did really diminish, but it did not occur to her that the boy was

02:29:47.630 --> 02:29:51.030
mending the health of a crack in the sitting-room floor with it.

02:29:51.930 --> 02:29:58.410
One day Tom was in the act of dosing the crack when his aunt's yellow cat came along purring,

02:29:58.410 --> 02:30:03.510
eyeing the teaspoon avariciously, and begging for a taste. Tom said,

02:30:03.930 --> 02:30:09.390
"'Don't ask for it unless you want it, Peter.' But Peter signified that he did want it.

02:30:09.670 --> 02:30:14.830
"'You'd better make sure.' Peter was sure. "'Now you've asked for it, and I'll give

02:30:14.830 --> 02:30:19.770
it to you, because there ain't anything mean about me. But if you find you don't like it,

02:30:19.910 --> 02:30:22.650
you mustn't blame anybody but your own self.'

02:30:22.650 --> 02:30:29.210
Peter was agreeable, so Tom pried his mouth open and poured down the painkiller. Peter

02:30:29.210 --> 02:30:33.150
sprang a couple of yards in the air and then delivered a war-whoop and set off round and

02:30:33.150 --> 02:30:37.350
round the room, banging against furniture, upsetting flower-pots, and making general

02:30:37.350 --> 02:30:43.230
havoc. Next he rose on his hind feet and pranced around in a frenzy of enjoyment, with his

02:30:43.230 --> 02:30:48.790
head over his shoulder and his voice proclaiming his unappeasable happiness. Then he went tearing

02:30:48.790 --> 02:30:53.530
around the house again, spreading chaos and destruction in his path. Aunt Polly entered

02:30:53.530 --> 02:30:59.250
in time to see him throw a few double summer sets, deliver a final mighty hurrah, and sail

02:30:59.250 --> 02:31:04.390
through the open window, carrying the rest of the flower-pots with him. The old lady

02:31:04.390 --> 02:31:10.750
stood petrified with astonishment, peering over her glasses. Tom lay on the floor, expiring

02:31:10.750 --> 02:31:11.430
with laughter.

02:31:12.190 --> 02:31:14.870
"'Tom, what on earth ails that cat?'

02:31:15.690 --> 02:31:17.970
"'I don't know, aunt,' gasped the boy.

02:31:18.430 --> 02:31:22.670
"'Why, I never see anything like it. What did make him act so?'

02:31:22.670 --> 02:31:27.390
"'Deed I don't know, Aunt Polly. Cats always act so when they're having a good time.'

02:31:27.970 --> 02:31:32.670
"'They do, do they?' There was something in the tone that made Tom apprehensive.

02:31:33.550 --> 02:31:36.430
"'Yesem! That is, I believe they do.'

02:31:36.430 --> 02:31:39.190
"'You do? Yesem!'

02:31:39.190 --> 02:31:45.330
The old lady was bending down, Tom watching, with interest emphasized by anxiety. Too late

02:31:45.330 --> 02:31:51.330
he divined her drift. The handle of the tell-tale teaspoon was visible under the bed valance.

02:31:51.790 --> 02:31:57.950
Aunt Polly took it, held it up. Tom winced, and dropped his eyes. Aunt Polly raised him

02:31:57.950 --> 02:32:02.670
by the usual handle—his ear—and cracked his head soundly with her thimble.

02:32:02.950 --> 02:32:07.710
"'Now, sir, what did you want to treat that poor dumb beast so for?'

02:32:07.710 --> 02:32:11.590
"'I done it out of pity for him, because he hadn't any aunt.'

02:32:11.590 --> 02:32:15.730
"'Hadn't any aunt, you numbskull! What has that got to do with it?'

02:32:15.730 --> 02:32:22.150
"'Heaps! Because if he'd a had one, she'd a burnt him out herself. She'd a roasted

02:32:22.150 --> 02:32:26.550
his bowels out of him, without any more feeling than if he was a human.'

02:32:26.550 --> 02:32:31.770
Aunt Polly felt a sudden pang of remorse. This was putting the thing in a new light.

02:32:31.770 --> 02:32:38.450
What was cruelty to a cat might be cruelty to a boy, too.' She began to soften. She felt

02:32:38.450 --> 02:32:43.190
sorry. Her eyes watered a little, and she put her hand on Tom's head and said gently,

02:32:44.070 --> 02:32:51.190
"'I was meaning for the best, Tom, and Tom, it did do you good.' Tom looked up in her

02:32:51.190 --> 02:32:54.390
face with just a perceptible twinkle peeping through his gravity.

02:32:54.950 --> 02:33:00.450
"'I know you was meaning for the best, auntie, and so was I with Peter. It done him good,

02:33:00.450 --> 02:33:06.110
too. I never seen him get around so since. Oh, go along with you, Tom, before you aggravate

02:33:06.110 --> 02:33:11.070
me again, and you try and see if you can't be a good boy for once, and you needn't take

02:33:11.070 --> 02:33:12.570
any more medicine.'

02:33:12.570 --> 02:33:17.250
Tom reached school ahead of time. It was noticed that this strange thing had been occurring

02:33:17.250 --> 02:33:23.050
every day laterly. And now, as usual of late, he hung about the gate of the schoolyard instead

02:33:23.050 --> 02:33:28.290
of playing with his comrades. He was sick, he said, and he looked it. He tried to seem

02:33:28.290 --> 02:33:33.690
to be looking everywhere but whither he really was looking—down the road. Presently Jeff

02:33:33.690 --> 02:33:39.390
Thatcherhoff in sight, and Tom's face lighted. He gazed a moment and then turned sorrowfully

02:33:39.390 --> 02:33:45.730
away. When Jeff arrived Tom accosted him and led up, warily, to opportunities for remark

02:33:45.730 --> 02:33:51.650
about Becky, but the giddy lad never could see the bait. Tom watched and watched, hoping

02:33:51.650 --> 02:33:56.570
whenever a frisking frock came in sight, and hating the owner of it as soon as he saw she

02:33:56.570 --> 02:34:02.870
was not the right one. At last frocks ceased to appear, and he dropped hopelessly into

02:34:02.870 --> 02:34:06.950
their dumps. He entered the empty schoolhouse and sat down to suffer.

02:34:07.930 --> 02:34:13.510
Then one more frock passed in at the gate, and Tom's heart gave a great bound. The next

02:34:13.510 --> 02:34:18.590
instant he was out, and going on like an Indian, yelling and laughing and chasing boys, jumping

02:34:18.590 --> 02:34:23.570
over the fence at risk of life and limb, throwing hand-springs, standing on his head, doing

02:34:23.570 --> 02:34:28.210
the heroic things he could conceive of, and keeping a furtive eye out all the while to

02:34:28.210 --> 02:34:33.910
see if Becky Thatcher was noticing. But she seemed to be unconscious of it all. She never

02:34:33.910 --> 02:34:39.610
looked. Could it be possible that she was not aware that he was there? He carried his

02:34:39.610 --> 02:34:45.410
exploits to her immediate vicinity, came war-whooping around, snatched a body's cap, hurled it to

02:34:45.410 --> 02:34:49.430
the roof of the schoolhouse, broke through a group of boys, tumbling them in every direction,

02:34:49.430 --> 02:34:55.250
and fell sprawling, himself, under Becky's nose, almost upsetting her, and she turned,

02:34:55.570 --> 02:34:58.130
with her nose in the air, and he heard her say,

02:34:58.410 --> 02:35:03.490
"'Humph! Some people think their mighty smart-hall was showing off!'

02:35:03.490 --> 02:35:10.130
Tom's cheeks burned. He gathered himself up and sneaked off, crushed and crestfallen.

02:35:27.850 --> 02:35:28.490
XIII.

02:35:28.970 --> 02:35:30.930
The pirate crew set sail.

02:35:31.990 --> 02:35:36.330
Tom's mind was made up now. He was gloomy and desperate. He was a

02:35:36.330 --> 02:35:40.830
forsaken, friendless boy, he said. Nobody loved him. When they found

02:35:40.830 --> 02:35:44.530
out what they had driven him to, perhaps they would be sorry. He had

02:35:44.530 --> 02:35:48.250
tried to do right and get along, but they would not let him. Since

02:35:48.250 --> 02:35:52.510
nothing would do them but to get rid of him, let it be so. And let them

02:35:52.510 --> 02:35:56.550
blame him for the consequences. Why shouldn't they? What right had the

02:35:56.550 --> 02:36:01.050
friendless to complain? Yes, they had forced him to it at last. He would

02:36:01.050 --> 02:36:05.850
lead a life of crime. There was no choice. By this time he was far down

02:36:05.850 --> 02:36:10.310
Meadow Lane, and the bell for school to take up tingled faintly upon his

02:36:10.310 --> 02:36:15.290
ear. He sobbed, now, to think he should never, never hear that old

02:36:15.290 --> 02:36:19.890
familiar sound any more. It was very hard, but it was forced on him.

02:36:20.310 --> 02:36:25.090
Since he was driven out into the cold world, he must submit. But he

02:36:25.090 --> 02:36:25.770
forgave them.

02:36:26.270 --> 02:36:31.490
Then the sobs came thick and fast. Just at this point he met his soul's

02:36:31.490 --> 02:36:36.010
sworn comrade, Joe Harper, hard-eyed and with evidently a great and

02:36:36.010 --> 02:36:43.170
heart. Plainly, here were two souls with but a single thought. Tom, wiping

02:36:43.170 --> 02:36:46.410
his eyes with his sleeve, began to blubber out something about a

02:36:46.410 --> 02:36:50.530
resolution to escape from hard usage and lack of sympathy at home by

02:36:50.530 --> 02:36:54.970
roaming abroad into the great world never to return, and ended by hoping

02:36:54.970 --> 02:36:57.070
that Joe would not forget him.

02:36:57.490 --> 02:37:01.130
But it transpired that this was a request which Joe had just been going

02:37:01.130 --> 02:37:05.830
to make of Tom, and had come to hunt him up for that purpose. His mother

02:37:05.830 --> 02:37:09.550
had whipped him for drinking some cream which he had never tasted and

02:37:09.550 --> 02:37:13.050
knew nothing about. It was plain that she was tired of him and wished

02:37:13.050 --> 02:37:17.910
him to go. If she felt that way, there was nothing for him to do but

02:37:17.910 --> 02:37:22.230
succumb. He hoped she would be happy, and never regret having driven

02:37:22.230 --> 02:37:27.190
her poor boy out into the unfeeling world to suffer and die.

02:37:27.750 --> 02:37:32.090
As the two boys walked sorrowing along, they made a new compact to

02:37:32.090 --> 02:37:35.370
stand by each other and be brothers, and never separate till death

02:37:35.370 --> 02:37:39.070
relieved them of their troubles. Then they began to lay their plans.

02:37:39.510 --> 02:37:43.990
Joe was for being a hermit, and living on crusts in a remote cave, and

02:37:43.990 --> 02:37:48.270
dying, some time, of cold and want and grief. But after listening to

02:37:48.270 --> 02:37:52.490
Tom, he conceded that there were some conspicuous advantages about a

02:37:52.490 --> 02:37:58.010
life of crime, and so he consented to be a pirate. Three miles below St.

02:37:58.150 --> 02:38:01.870
Petersburg, at a point where the Mississippi River was a trifle over a

02:38:01.870 --> 02:38:07.270
There was a long, narrow, wooded island, with a shallow bar at the head

02:38:07.270 --> 02:38:11.730
of it, and this offered well as a rendezvous. It was not inhabited, it

02:38:11.730 --> 02:38:15.630
lay far over towards the further shore, abreast a dense and almost

02:38:15.630 --> 02:38:20.890
wholly unpeopled forest. So Jackson's island was chosen. Who were to be

02:38:20.890 --> 02:38:24.130
the subjects of their piracies was a matter that did not occur to them.

02:38:24.530 --> 02:38:28.090
Then they hunted up Huckleberry Finn, and he joined them promptly for

02:38:28.090 --> 02:38:32.830
careers were won to him. He was indifferent. They presently separated to

02:38:32.830 --> 02:38:36.350
meet at a lonely spot on the river bank, two miles above the village, at

02:38:36.350 --> 02:38:41.090
the favorite hour, which was midnight. There was a small log raft there

02:38:41.090 --> 02:38:45.450
which they meant to capture. Each would bring hooks and lines, and such

02:38:45.450 --> 02:38:49.210
provision as he could steal in the most dark and mysterious way, as

02:38:49.210 --> 02:38:53.410
became outlaws. And before the afternoon was done, they had all managed

02:38:53.410 --> 02:38:57.390
to enjoy the sweet glory of spreading the fact that pretty soon the town

02:38:57.390 --> 02:39:02.530
would hear something. All who got this vague hint were cautioned to be

02:39:02.530 --> 02:39:03.810
mum and wait.

02:39:04.570 --> 02:39:08.470
About midnight Tom arrived with a boiled ham and a few trifles, and

02:39:08.470 --> 02:39:11.870
stopped in a dense undergrowth, on a small bluff overlooking the meeting

02:39:11.870 --> 02:39:16.610
place. It was starlight and very still. The mighty river lay like an

02:39:16.610 --> 02:39:21.290
ocean at rest. Tom listened a moment, but no sound disturbed the quiet.

02:39:21.770 --> 02:39:27.370
Then he gave a low, distinct whistle. It was answered from under the

02:39:27.370 --> 02:39:31.510
twice more. These signals were answered in the same way. Then a guarded

02:39:31.510 --> 02:39:32.150
voice said,

02:39:32.410 --> 02:39:33.470
"'Who goes there?'

02:39:34.270 --> 02:39:38.990
"'Tom Sawyer, the black avenger of the Spanish main. Name your names!'

02:39:38.990 --> 02:39:44.050
"'Huck Finn, the red-handed, and Joe Harper, the terror of the seas!'

02:39:44.050 --> 02:39:48.270
Tom had furnished these titles from his favorite literature. "'Tis well.

02:39:48.630 --> 02:39:53.650
Give the countersign.' Two hoarse whispers delivered the same awful word

02:39:53.650 --> 02:39:55.730
simultaneously to the brooding night.

02:39:57.710 --> 02:39:58.230
"'Blood!'

02:39:58.230 --> 02:40:02.590
Then Tom tumbled his ham over the bluff and let himself down after it,

02:40:02.910 --> 02:40:06.590
tearing both skin and clothes to some extent in the effort. There was

02:40:06.590 --> 02:40:10.250
an easy, comfortable path along the shore under the bluff, but it lacked

02:40:10.250 --> 02:40:15.050
the advantages of difficulty in danger so valued by a pirate. The

02:40:15.050 --> 02:40:18.830
terror of the seas had brought a side of bacon, and had about worn

02:40:18.830 --> 02:40:23.090
himself out with getting it there. Finn, the red-handed, had stolen a

02:40:23.090 --> 02:40:26.870
skillet and a quantity of half-cured leaf tobacco, and had also brought

02:40:26.870 --> 02:40:31.050
a few corn cobs to make pipes with. But none of the pirates smoked or

02:40:31.050 --> 02:40:35.410
chewed but himself. The black avenger of the Spanish main said it would

02:40:35.410 --> 02:40:40.290
never do to start without some fire. That was a wise thought. Matches

02:40:40.290 --> 02:40:44.470
were hardly known there in that day. They saw a fire smoldering upon a

02:40:44.470 --> 02:40:48.250
great raft a hundred yards above, and they went stealthily thither and

02:40:48.250 --> 02:40:51.770
helped themselves to a chunk. They made an imposing adventure of it,

02:40:51.770 --> 02:40:55.390
saying, "'Hist!' every now and then, and suddenly halting with finger on

02:40:55.390 --> 02:40:59.370
lip, moving with hands on imaginary dagger-hilts, and giving orders in

02:40:59.370 --> 02:41:04.350
dismal whispers that, if the foe stirred, to, let him have it to the

02:41:04.350 --> 02:41:09.610
hilt, because dead men tell no tales. They knew well enough that the

02:41:09.610 --> 02:41:12.810
Rouse men were all down at the village laying in stores or having a

02:41:12.810 --> 02:41:16.410
spree, but still that was no excuse for their conducting this thing in

02:41:17.230 --> 02:41:18.170
unparadical way.

02:41:18.830 --> 02:41:23.530
They shoved off presently, Tom in command, Huck at the after oar, and

02:41:23.530 --> 02:41:28.230
Joe at the forward. Tom stood amidst ships gloomy-browed and with folded

02:41:28.230 --> 02:41:31.250
arms, and gave his orders in a low, stern whisper,

02:41:31.850 --> 02:41:34.150
"'Luff, and bring her to the wind!'

02:41:34.150 --> 02:41:35.470
"'Ay, ay, sir!'

02:41:35.470 --> 02:41:37.670
"'Steady, steady!'

02:41:37.670 --> 02:41:39.070
"'Steady it is, sir.'

02:41:39.070 --> 02:41:40.810
"'Let her go off a point.'

02:41:40.810 --> 02:41:42.490
"'Point it is, sir.'

02:41:42.490 --> 02:41:46.110
As the boys steadily and monotonously drove the raft toward mid-stream,

02:41:46.490 --> 02:41:50.010
it was no doubt understood that these orders were given only for style,

02:41:50.290 --> 02:41:52.550
and were not intended to mean anything in particular.

02:41:52.850 --> 02:41:54.590
"'What sails she carrying?'

02:41:55.170 --> 02:41:58.570
"'Courses, top sails, and flying jib, sir.'

02:41:58.570 --> 02:42:03.350
"'Send the riles up. Lay out a loft there. Half a dozen a year. For top

02:42:03.350 --> 02:42:05.470
manstel, sir. Lively now.'

02:42:05.470 --> 02:42:06.470
"'Ay, ay, sir.'

02:42:06.470 --> 02:42:11.110
"'Shake out that main to Galan, sir. Sheets and braces. Now, my hearties.'

02:42:11.110 --> 02:42:12.730
"'Ay, ay, sir.'

02:42:12.730 --> 02:42:16.450
"'Heel him a lee. Hire to port. Stand by to meet her when she comes.

02:42:16.670 --> 02:42:22.510
Port, port, now, men. With a will. Steady. Steady it is, sir.'

02:42:22.510 --> 02:42:26.270
The raft drew beyond the middle of the river. The boys pointed her head

02:42:26.270 --> 02:42:30.750
right, and then lay on their oars. The river was not high, so there was

02:42:30.750 --> 02:42:35.190
not more than a two- or three-mile current. Hardly a word was said during

02:42:35.190 --> 02:42:41.090
the next three-quarters of an hour. Now the raft was passing before the

02:42:41.090 --> 02:42:45.310
summering light showed where it lay, peacefully sleeping, beyond the vague

02:42:45.310 --> 02:42:50.010
vast sweep of a star-gemmed water, unconscious of the tremendous event

02:42:50.010 --> 02:42:54.070
that was happening. The Black Avenger stood still with folded arms,

02:42:54.370 --> 02:42:59.170
looking his last upon the scene of his former joys and his later

02:42:59.170 --> 02:43:04.030
sufferings, and wishing she could see him now, abroad on the wild sea,

02:43:04.430 --> 02:43:11.070
facing peril and death with dauntless heart, going to his doom with a

02:43:11.070 --> 02:43:15.210
small strain on his imagination to remove Jackson the Island beyond

02:43:15.210 --> 02:43:20.110
eye-shot of the village, and so he looked his last with a broken and

02:43:20.110 --> 02:43:24.230
satisfied heart. The other pirates were looking their last, too, and

02:43:24.230 --> 02:43:27.750
they all looked so long that they came near letting the current drift

02:43:27.750 --> 02:43:31.530
them out of the range of the island, but they discovered the danger in

02:43:31.530 --> 02:43:35.770
time and made shift to avert it. About two o'clock in the morning the

02:43:35.770 --> 02:43:38.850
raft grounded on the bar two hundred yards above the head of the

02:43:38.850 --> 02:43:42.370
island, and they waited back and forth until they had landed their

02:43:42.370 --> 02:43:46.370
freight. Part of the little raft's belongings consisted of an old sail,

02:43:46.770 --> 02:43:49.990
and this they spread over a nook in the bushes for a tent to shelter

02:43:49.990 --> 02:43:53.810
their provisions, but they themselves would sleep in the open air in

02:43:53.810 --> 02:43:58.870
good weather, as became outlaws. They built a fire against the side of

02:43:58.870 --> 02:44:02.430
a great log twenty or thirty steps within the somber depths of the

02:44:02.430 --> 02:44:06.450
forest, and then cooked some bacon in the frying-pan for supper, and

02:44:06.450 --> 02:44:10.750
used up half of the corn-pone stock they had brought. It seemed glorious

02:44:10.750 --> 02:44:14.490
sport to be feasting in that wild freeway in the virgin forest of an

02:44:14.490 --> 02:44:18.770
unexplored and uninhabited island, far from the haunts of men, and they

02:44:18.770 --> 02:44:22.930
said they never would return to civilization. The climbing fire lit up

02:44:22.930 --> 02:44:26.750
their faces and threw its ruddy glare upon the pillared tree-trunks of

02:44:26.750 --> 02:44:30.770
their forest temple, and upon the varnished foliage and festooning

02:44:30.770 --> 02:44:35.430
vines. When the last crisp slice of bacon was gone, and the last

02:44:35.430 --> 02:44:39.330
allowance of corn-pone devoured, the boys stretched themselves out in the

02:44:39.330 --> 02:44:43.430
grass, filled with contentment. They could have found a cooler place,

02:44:43.830 --> 02:44:46.930
but they would not deny themselves such a romantic feature as the

02:44:46.930 --> 02:44:48.030
roasting camp-fire.

02:44:48.770 --> 02:44:50.650
"'Ain't it gay?' said Joe.

02:44:51.150 --> 02:44:55.130
"'It's nuts,' said Tom. What would the boys say if they could see us?'

02:44:55.130 --> 02:44:58.830
"'Say? Well, they'd just die to be here. Hey, Hucky!'

02:44:59.230 --> 02:45:05.410
"'I reckon so,' said Huckleberry. Anyways, I'm suited. I don't want

02:45:05.410 --> 02:45:08.830
enough to eat, generally, and here they can't come and pick at a

02:45:08.830 --> 02:45:10.430
feller and bully-rag him so.'

02:45:10.930 --> 02:45:14.290
"'It's just the life for me,' said Tom. You don't have to get up,

02:45:14.350 --> 02:45:17.410
mornings, and you don't have to go to school and wash and all that

02:45:17.410 --> 02:45:21.170
blame-foolishness. You see, a pirate don't have to do anything, Joe,

02:45:21.430 --> 02:45:25.770
when he's ashore, but a hermit. He has to be a praying considerable,

02:45:25.910 --> 02:45:29.410
and then he don't have any fun, anyway, all by himself that way.'

02:45:30.030 --> 02:45:33.410
"'Oh, yes, that's so,' said Joe. But I hadn't thought much about it,

02:45:33.410 --> 02:45:36.910
I had a good deal rather be a pirate, now that I've tried it.'

02:45:37.390 --> 02:45:41.030
"'You see,' said Tom, people don't go much on hermits nowadays,

02:45:41.370 --> 02:45:45.230
like they used to in the old times. But a pirate's always respected,

02:45:45.510 --> 02:45:49.030
and a hermit's got to sleep on the hardest place he can find, and put

02:45:49.030 --> 02:45:53.090
sackcloth and ashes on his head, and stand out in the rain, and what

02:45:53.090 --> 02:45:56.370
does he put sackcloth and ashes on his head for?' inquired Huck.

02:45:56.770 --> 02:46:01.150
"'I don't know, but they's got to do it. Hermits always do. You'd have

02:46:01.150 --> 02:46:02.590
to do that if he was a hermit.'

02:46:03.110 --> 02:46:04.670
"'Durned if I would,' said Huck.

02:46:04.950 --> 02:46:06.450
"'Well, what would you do?'

02:46:06.830 --> 02:46:08.610
"'I don't know, but I wouldn't do that.'

02:46:09.270 --> 02:46:12.830
"'Why, Huck, you'd have to. How'd you get around it?'

02:46:13.310 --> 02:46:15.970
"'Why, I just wouldn't stand it. I'd run away.'

02:46:16.690 --> 02:46:21.230
"'Run away? Well, you would be a nice old slouch of a hermit. You'd be

02:46:21.230 --> 02:46:26.390
a disgrace.' The red-handed made no response, being better employed. He

02:46:26.390 --> 02:46:30.330
had finished gouging out a cob, and now he fitted a weed-stem to it,

02:46:30.330 --> 02:46:33.810
loaded it with tobacco, and was pressing a coal to the charge and

02:46:33.810 --> 02:46:38.010
blowing a cloud of fragrant smoke. He was in the full bloom of luxurious

02:46:38.010 --> 02:46:42.330
contentment. The other pirates envied him this majestic vice, and

02:46:42.330 --> 02:46:46.050
secretly resolved to acquire it shortly. Presently, Huck said,

02:46:46.290 --> 02:46:48.610
"'What does pirates have to do?'

02:46:48.610 --> 02:46:53.190
Tom said, "'Oh, they have just a bully time. Take ships and burn them,

02:46:53.470 --> 02:46:56.730
and get the money and bury it in awful places in their island, where

02:46:56.730 --> 02:47:00.190
there's ghosts and things to watch it, and kill everybody in the ships,

02:47:00.190 --> 02:47:02.030
and make them walk a plank.'

02:47:02.030 --> 02:47:04.710
"'And they carry the women to the island,' said Joe.

02:47:04.730 --> 02:47:06.190
"'They don't kill the women.'

02:47:06.190 --> 02:47:10.430
"'No,' assented Tom. They don't kill the women. They're too noble,

02:47:10.790 --> 02:47:12.530
and the women's always beautiful, too.'

02:47:13.030 --> 02:47:17.270
"'And don't they wear the bulliest clothes? Oh, no. All gold and silver

02:47:17.270 --> 02:47:19.170
and diamonds,' said Joe, with enthusiasm.

02:47:19.690 --> 02:47:20.910
"'Who?' said Chuck.

02:47:21.110 --> 02:47:22.190
"'Why, the pirates.'

02:47:22.990 --> 02:47:25.610
Huck scanned his own clothing forlornly.

02:47:25.710 --> 02:47:29.150
"'I reckon I ain't dressed fitting for a pirate,' said he, with a

02:47:29.150 --> 02:47:30.730
regretful pathos in his voice.

02:47:31.090 --> 02:47:32.830
"'But I ain't got none but these.'

02:47:33.490 --> 02:47:36.770
But the other boys told him the fine clothes would come fast enough

02:47:36.770 --> 02:47:39.770
after they should have begun their adventures. They made him

02:47:39.770 --> 02:47:43.370
understand that his poor rags would do to begin with, though it was

02:47:43.370 --> 02:47:46.590
customary for wealthy pirates to start with a proper wardrobe.

02:47:47.230 --> 02:47:50.990
Gradually their talk died out, and drowsiness began to steal upon the

02:47:50.990 --> 02:47:54.430
eyelids of the little waifs. The pipe dropped from the fingers of the

02:47:54.430 --> 02:47:59.130
red-handed, and he slept the sleep of the conscience-free and the

02:47:59.130 --> 02:48:03.110
black avenger of the Spanish main had more difficulty in getting to

02:48:03.110 --> 02:48:07.050
sleep. They said their prayers inwardly and lying down, since there

02:48:07.050 --> 02:48:10.110
was nobody there with authority to make them kneel and recite aloud.

02:48:10.550 --> 02:48:14.290
In truth they had a mind not to say them at all, but they were afraid

02:48:14.290 --> 02:48:18.710
to proceed to such lengths at that, lest they might call down a sudden

02:48:18.710 --> 02:48:23.150
and special thunderbolt from heaven. Then at once they reached and

02:48:23.150 --> 02:48:27.650
hovered upon the imminent verge of sleep. But an intruder came now that

02:48:27.650 --> 02:48:33.370
would not down. It was conscience. They began to feel a vague fear that

02:48:33.370 --> 02:48:37.110
they had been doing wrong to run away, and next they thought of the

02:48:37.110 --> 02:48:41.510
stolen meat, and then the real torture came. They tried to argue it

02:48:41.510 --> 02:48:45.330
away by reminding conscience that they had purloined sweetmeats and

02:48:45.330 --> 02:48:49.290
apple-scores at times, but conscience was not to be appeased by such

02:48:49.290 --> 02:48:53.150
thin plausibilities. It seemed to them in the end that there was no

02:48:53.150 --> 02:48:56.370
getting around the stubborn fact that taking sweetmeats was only

02:48:56.370 --> 02:49:01.090
cooking, while taking bacon and hams and such valuables was plain simple

02:49:02.030 --> 02:49:06.610
stealing—and there was a command against that in the Bible. So they

02:49:06.610 --> 02:49:10.070
inwardly resolved that so long as they remained in the business, their

02:49:10.070 --> 02:49:14.610
piracies should not again be sullied with the crime of stealing. Then

02:49:14.610 --> 02:49:19.190
conscience granted a truce, and these curiously inconsistent pirates

02:49:19.190 --> 02:49:21.030
fell peacefully to sleep.

02:49:24.570 --> 02:49:27.590
CHAPTER XIV HAPPY CAMP OF THE FREE BOOTERS

02:49:27.590 --> 02:49:32.050
When Tom awoke in the morning he wondered where he was. He sat up and

02:49:32.050 --> 02:49:35.870
rubbed his eyes and looked around. Then he comprehended. It was the

02:49:35.870 --> 02:49:39.810
cool, grey dawn, and there was a delicious sense of repose and peace in

02:49:39.810 --> 02:49:43.870
the deep, pervading calm and silence of the woods. Not a leaf stirred,

02:49:44.130 --> 02:49:49.350
not a sound obtruded upon great nature's meditation. Beaded dewdrops

02:49:49.350 --> 02:49:53.270
melted upon the leaves and grasses. A white layer of ashes covered the

02:49:53.270 --> 02:49:58.110
fire, and a thin blue breath of smoke rose straight into the air. Joe

02:49:58.110 --> 02:50:03.110
and Huck still slept. Now, far away in the woods, a bird called. Another

02:50:03.110 --> 02:50:07.310
answered. Presently the hammering of a Whitpecker was heard. Gradually

02:50:07.310 --> 02:50:11.530
the cool, dim grey of the morning whitened, and as gradually sounds

02:50:11.530 --> 02:50:16.610
multiplied and life manifested itself. The marvel of nature, shaking off

02:50:16.610 --> 02:50:20.690
sleep and going to work, unfolded itself to the musing boy. A little

02:50:20.690 --> 02:50:24.990
green worm came crawling over a dewy leaf, lifting two-thirds of his

02:50:24.990 --> 02:50:28.970
body into the air from time to time, and sniffing around, then proceeding

02:50:28.970 --> 02:50:33.350
again. For he was measuring, Tom said, and when the worm approached him

02:50:33.350 --> 02:50:38.350
of its own accord, he sat as still as a stone, with his hopes rising and

02:50:38.350 --> 02:50:42.350
falling by turns, as the creature still came toward him, or seemed

02:50:42.350 --> 02:50:43.850
inclined to go elsewhere.

02:50:43.850 --> 02:50:48.410
And when at last it considered a painful moment with its curved body in

02:50:48.410 --> 02:50:52.290
the air, and then came decisively down upon Tom's leg, and began

02:50:52.290 --> 02:50:56.690
journeying over him, his whole heart was glad, for that meant that he

02:50:56.690 --> 02:51:00.570
was going to have a new suit of clothes, without the shadow of a doubt

02:51:00.570 --> 02:51:05.770
a gaudy, piratical uniform. Now a procession of ants appeared, from

02:51:05.770 --> 02:51:09.350
nowhere in particular, and went about their labours. One struggled

02:51:09.350 --> 02:51:13.710
manfully by, with a dead spider five times as big as itself in its

02:51:13.710 --> 02:51:18.330
arms, and lugged it straight up a tree trunk. A brown-spotted ladybug

02:51:18.330 --> 02:51:22.950
climbed a dizzy height of a grass blade, and Tom bent down close to it

02:51:22.950 --> 02:51:23.270
and said,

02:51:24.210 --> 02:51:28.790
"'Ladybug, ladybug, fly away home! Your house is on fire, your children's

02:51:28.790 --> 02:51:32.710
alone!' And she took wing and went off to see about it. Which did not

02:51:32.710 --> 02:51:36.750
surprise the boy, for he knew of old that this insect was credulous

02:51:36.750 --> 02:51:40.970
about conflagrations, and he had practised upon its simplicity more

02:51:40.970 --> 02:51:45.910
than once. A tumble-bug came next, heaving sturdily at its ball, and

02:51:45.910 --> 02:51:49.630
Tom touched the creature to see it shut its legs against its body and

02:51:49.630 --> 02:51:54.130
pretend to be dead. The birds were fairly rioting by this time. A cat

02:51:54.130 --> 02:51:58.710
bird, the northern mocker, lit in a tree over Tom's head, and trilled

02:51:58.710 --> 02:52:03.550
out imitations of her neighbours in a rapture of enjoyment. Then a

02:52:03.550 --> 02:52:08.150
jay swept down, a flash of blue flame, and stopped on a twig almost

02:52:08.150 --> 02:52:11.710
within the boy's reach. Cocked his head to one side and eyed the

02:52:11.710 --> 02:52:15.870
strangers with a consuming curiosity. A grey squirrel and a big fellow

02:52:15.870 --> 02:52:20.110
of the fox-kind came scurrying along, sitting up at intervals to inspect

02:52:20.110 --> 02:52:24.030
and chatter at the boys, for the wild things had probably never seen a

02:52:24.030 --> 02:52:28.790
human being before, and scarcely knew whether to be afraid or not. All

02:52:28.790 --> 02:52:33.350
nature was wide awake and stirring now. Long lances of sunlight pierced

02:52:33.350 --> 02:52:37.750
down through the dense foliage far and near, and a few butterflies came

02:52:37.750 --> 02:52:41.990
fluttering upon the scene. Tom stirred up the other pirates, and they

02:52:41.990 --> 02:52:45.310
all clattered away with a shout, and in a minute or two were stripped

02:52:45.310 --> 02:52:49.050
and chasing after and tumbling over each other in the shallow, limpid

02:52:49.050 --> 02:52:53.210
water of the white sandbar. They felt no longing for the little village

02:52:53.210 --> 02:52:57.210
sleeping in the distance, beyond the majestic waste of water. A vagrant

02:52:57.210 --> 02:53:01.530
current, or a slight rise in the river, had carried off their raft, but

02:53:01.530 --> 02:53:05.450
this only gratified them since its going was something like burning the

02:53:05.450 --> 02:53:10.230
bridge between them and civilization. They came back to camp wonderfully

02:53:10.230 --> 02:53:15.370
refreshed, glad-hearted, and ravenous, and they soon had the campfire

02:53:15.370 --> 02:53:20.350
blazing up again. Huck found a spring of clear cold water close by, and

02:53:20.350 --> 02:53:24.970
the boys made cups of broad oak or hickory leaves, and felt that water,

02:53:25.130 --> 02:53:29.250
sweetened with such a wildwood charm as that, would be a good enough

02:53:29.250 --> 02:53:30.350
substitute for coffee.

02:53:31.070 --> 02:53:34.970
While Joe was slicing bacon for breakfast, Tom and Huck asked him to

02:53:34.970 --> 02:53:38.370
hold on a minute. They stepped to a promising nook in the river bank

02:53:38.370 --> 02:53:43.230
and threw in their lines. Almost immediately they had reward. Joe had

02:53:43.230 --> 02:53:46.370
not had time to get impatient before they were back again with some

02:53:46.370 --> 02:53:51.170
handsome bass, a couple of sun-perch, and a small catfish—provisions

02:53:51.170 --> 02:53:55.670
enough for quite a family. They fried the fish with the bacon, and were

02:53:55.670 --> 02:54:00.230
astonished, for no fish had ever seemed so delicious before. They did

02:54:00.230 --> 02:54:04.050
not know that the quicker a fresh-water fish is on the fire after it is

02:54:04.050 --> 02:54:08.710
caught the better he is, and they reflected little upon what a sauce

02:54:08.710 --> 02:54:13.030
open-air sleeping, open-air exercise, bathing, and a large ingredient of

02:54:13.030 --> 02:54:17.310
hunger makes, too. They lay around in the shade after breakfast while

02:54:17.310 --> 02:54:21.230
Huck had a smoke, and then went off through the woods on an exploring

02:54:21.230 --> 02:54:26.110
expedition. They trapped gaily along over decaying logs, through tangled

02:54:26.110 --> 02:54:30.870
underbrush, among solemn monarchs of the forest, hung from their crowns

02:54:30.870 --> 02:54:35.870
to the ground, with a drooping regalia of grape vines. Now and then they

02:54:35.870 --> 02:54:40.770
came upon snug nooks carpeted with grass and jeweled with flowers. They

02:54:40.770 --> 02:54:44.590
found plenty of things to be delighted with, but nothing to be astonished

02:54:44.590 --> 02:54:48.510
at. They discovered that the island was about three miles long and a

02:54:48.510 --> 02:54:52.610
quarter of a mile wide, and that the shore it lay it closest to was only

02:54:52.610 --> 02:54:56.890
separated from it by a narrow channel hardly two hundred yards wide. They

02:54:56.890 --> 02:55:00.350
took a swim about every hour, so it was close upon the middle of the

02:55:00.350 --> 02:55:04.150
afternoon when they got back to the camp. They were too hungry to stop to

02:55:04.150 --> 02:55:08.410
fish, but they fared sumptuously upon cold ham, and then threw themselves

02:55:08.410 --> 02:55:13.310
down in the shade to talk. But the talk soon began to drag, and then died.

02:55:13.830 --> 02:55:17.670
The stillness, the solemnity that brooded in the woods, and the sense of

02:55:17.670 --> 02:55:22.170
loneliness, began to tell upon the spirits of the boys. They fell to

02:55:22.170 --> 02:55:27.790
thinking. A sort of undefined longing crept upon them. This took dim

02:55:27.790 --> 02:55:33.210
shape presently. It was budding homesickness. Even Finn, the red-handed,

02:55:33.470 --> 02:55:37.770
was dreaming of his doorsteps and empty hogs' heads. But they were all

02:55:37.770 --> 02:55:41.230
ashamed of their weakness, and none was brave enough to speak his

02:55:41.230 --> 02:55:45.370
thought. For some time now the boys had been dully conscious of a

02:55:45.710 --> 02:55:49.630
particular sound in the distance, just as one sometimes is of the

02:55:49.630 --> 02:55:53.310
ticking of a clock which he takes no distinct note of. But now this

02:55:53.310 --> 02:55:57.470
mysterious sound became more pronounced, and forced a recognition. The

02:55:57.470 --> 02:56:01.550
boys started, glanced at each other, and then each assumed a listening

02:56:01.550 --> 02:56:06.410
attitude. There was a long silence, profound and unbroken, and then a

02:56:06.410 --> 02:56:10.250
deep sullen boom came floating down out of the distance.

02:56:10.250 --> 02:56:13.350
"'What is it?' exclaimed Joe, under his breath.

02:56:13.570 --> 02:56:15.410
"'I wonder,' said Tom, in a whisper.

02:56:15.970 --> 02:56:19.870
"'Taint thunder,' said Elkleberry, in an odd tone. "'Cause thunder—'

02:56:20.150 --> 02:56:21.970
Hark!' said Tom. Listen, don't talk."

02:56:23.070 --> 02:56:27.290
They waited a time that seemed an age, and then the same muffled boom

02:56:27.290 --> 02:56:28.690
troubled the solemn hush.

02:56:28.970 --> 02:56:32.550
"'Let's go and see.' They sprang to their feet and hurried to the shore

02:56:32.550 --> 02:56:36.510
toward the town. They parted the bushes on the bank and peered out over

02:56:36.510 --> 02:56:40.170
the water. The little steam ferry-boat was about a mile below the

02:56:40.170 --> 02:56:44.030
village, drifting with a current. Her broad deck seemed crowded with

02:56:44.030 --> 02:56:48.530
people. There was a great many skiffs rowing about or floating with a

02:56:48.530 --> 02:56:52.070
stream in the neighborhood of the ferry-boat, but the boys could not

02:56:52.070 --> 02:56:56.510
determine what the men in them were doing. Presently a great jet of

02:56:56.510 --> 02:57:00.530
white smoke burst from the ferry-boat's side, and as it expanded and

02:57:00.530 --> 02:57:05.290
rose in a lazy cloud, that same dull throb of sound was borne to the

02:57:05.290 --> 02:57:06.110
listeners again.

02:57:06.610 --> 02:57:10.330
"'I know now,' exclaimed Tom. "'Somebody's drowned.'

02:57:10.330 --> 02:57:14.350
"'That's it,' said Huck. They'd done that last summer when Bill Turner

02:57:14.350 --> 02:57:18.150
got drowned. They shoot a cannon over the water, and that makes him

02:57:18.150 --> 02:57:22.670
come up to the top. Yes, and they take loads of bread and put quick

02:57:22.670 --> 02:57:26.650
silver in them and set them afloat. And wherever there's anybody that's

02:57:26.650 --> 02:57:28.990
drowned, they'll float right there and stop.'

02:57:29.490 --> 02:57:32.870
"'Yes, I've heard about that,' said Joe. I wonder what makes the bread

02:57:32.870 --> 02:57:33.850
do that.'

02:57:33.850 --> 02:57:37.230
"'Oh, it ain't the bread so much,' said Tom. I reckon it's mostly what

02:57:37.230 --> 02:57:39.470
they say over it before they start it out.'

02:57:40.010 --> 02:57:43.050
"'But they don't say anything over it,' said Huck. I've seen them and

02:57:43.050 --> 02:57:43.470
they don't.'

02:57:43.950 --> 02:57:47.530
"'Well, that's funny,' said Tom. But maybe they say it to themselves.

02:57:47.790 --> 02:57:50.450
Of course they do. Anybody might know that.'

02:57:50.450 --> 02:57:53.790
The other boys agreed that there was reason in what Tom said, because

02:57:53.790 --> 02:57:57.930
an ignorant lump of bread uninstructed by an incantation could not be

02:57:57.930 --> 02:58:01.710
expected to act very intelligently when sent upon an errand of such

02:58:01.710 --> 02:58:02.250
gravity.

02:58:02.810 --> 02:58:05.530
"'By jings, I wish I was over there now,' said Joe.

02:58:05.550 --> 02:58:09.070
"'I do too,' said Huck. I'd give heaps to know who it is.'

02:58:09.510 --> 02:58:13.350
The boys still listened and watched. Presently a revealing thought

02:58:13.350 --> 02:58:15.270
flashed through Tom's mind, and he exclaimed,

02:58:16.010 --> 02:58:19.870
"'Boys! I know who's drowned! It's us!'

02:58:20.450 --> 02:58:25.630
They felt like heroes in an instant. Here was a gorgeous triumph. They

02:58:25.630 --> 02:58:29.950
were missed. They were mourned. Hearts were breaking on their account.

02:58:29.950 --> 02:58:34.690
Tears were being shed. Accusing memories of unkindness to these poor

02:58:34.690 --> 02:58:38.570
lost lads were rising up, and unavailing regrets and remorse were

02:58:38.570 --> 02:58:42.690
being indulged. And best of all, the departed were the talk of the whole

02:58:42.690 --> 02:58:46.990
town, and the envy of all the boys, as far as this dazzling notoriety

02:58:46.990 --> 02:58:51.890
was concerned. This was fine. It was worth while to be a pirate after

02:58:51.890 --> 02:58:52.150
all.'

02:58:52.750 --> 02:58:56.630
As twilight drew on, the ferry-boat went back to her accustomed business,

02:58:56.630 --> 02:59:01.230
and the skiffs disappeared. The pirates returned to camp. They were

02:59:01.230 --> 02:59:05.550
jubilant with vanity over their new grandeur and the illustrious trouble

02:59:05.550 --> 02:59:09.470
they were making. They caught fish, cooked supper and ate it, and then

02:59:09.470 --> 02:59:12.650
fell to guessing at what the village was thinking and saying about them.

02:59:12.950 --> 02:59:16.250
And the pictures they drew of the public distress on their account were

02:59:16.250 --> 02:59:20.070
gratifying to look upon, from their point of view. But when the shadows

02:59:20.070 --> 02:59:24.350
of night closed them in, they gradually ceased to talk, and sat gazing

02:59:24.350 --> 02:59:28.810
at the fire, with their minds evidently wandering elsewhere. The

02:59:28.810 --> 02:59:32.730
excitement was gone now, and Tom and Joe could not keep back thoughts

02:59:32.730 --> 02:59:36.710
of certain persons at home who were not enjoying this fine frolic as

02:59:36.710 --> 02:59:42.530
much as they were. Misgivings came. They grew troubled and unhappy. A

02:59:42.530 --> 02:59:47.110
sigh or two escaped unawares. By and by Joe timidly ventured upon a

02:59:47.110 --> 02:59:51.450
roundabout feeler as to how the others might look upon a return to

02:59:51.450 --> 02:59:53.610
civilization. Not right now, but—

02:59:54.430 --> 02:59:58.650
Tom withered him with derision. Huck, being uncommitted as yet, joined

02:59:58.650 --> 03:00:03.050
in with Tom, and the waverer quickly explained, and was glad to get out

03:00:03.050 --> 03:00:06.270
of the scrape with as little taint of chicken-hearted homesickness

03:00:06.270 --> 03:00:10.510
clinging to his garments as he could. Mutiny was effectually laid to rest

03:00:10.510 --> 03:00:14.970
for the moment. As the night deepened, Huck began to nod and presently to

03:00:14.970 --> 03:00:20.510
snore. Joe followed next. Tom lay upon his elbow motionless for some time

03:00:20.510 --> 03:00:24.510
watching the two intently. At last he got up cautiously on his knees

03:00:24.510 --> 03:00:27.870
and went searching among the grass and the flickering reflections flung

03:00:27.870 --> 03:00:32.530
by the campfire. He picked up and inspected several large semi-cylinders

03:00:32.530 --> 03:00:37.110
of the thin white bark of a sycamore, and finally chose two which seemed

03:00:37.110 --> 03:00:40.610
to suit him. Then he knelt by the fire and painfully wrote something

03:00:40.610 --> 03:00:45.490
upon each of these with his red keel. One he rolled up and put in his

03:00:45.490 --> 03:00:49.530
jacket pocket, and the other he put in Joe's hat and removed it to a

03:00:49.530 --> 03:00:53.110
little distance from the owner. And he also put into the hat certain

03:00:53.110 --> 03:00:57.690
school-boy treasures of almost inestimable value, among them a lump of

03:00:57.690 --> 03:01:02.190
chalk, an India rubber ball, three fish-hooks, and one of that kind of

03:01:02.190 --> 03:01:06.530
marbles known as the—sure enough—crystal. Then he tiptoed his way

03:01:06.530 --> 03:01:10.750
cautiously among the trees till he felt that he was out of hearing, and

03:01:10.750 --> 03:01:13.990
straightway broke into a keen run in the direction of the sand-bar.

03:01:17.990 --> 03:01:21.310
CHAPTER XV Tom's Stealthy Visit Home

03:01:21.890 --> 03:01:25.730
A few minutes later Tom was in the shoal-water of the bar, wading toward

03:01:25.730 --> 03:01:30.150
the Illinois shore. Before the depth reached his middle he was halfway

03:01:30.150 --> 03:01:34.650
over. The current would permit no more wading now, so he struck out

03:01:34.650 --> 03:01:38.530
confidently to swim the remaining hundred yards. He swam quartering

03:01:38.530 --> 03:01:42.370
upstream, but still was swept downward rather faster than he had

03:01:42.370 --> 03:01:46.090
expected. However, he reached the shore finally, and drifted along till

03:01:46.090 --> 03:01:49.870
he found a low place and drew himself out. He put his hand on his jacket

03:01:49.870 --> 03:01:53.550
pocket, found his piece of bark safe, and then struck through the woods

03:01:53.550 --> 03:01:57.910
following the shore with streaming garments. Shortly before ten o'clock

03:01:57.910 --> 03:02:01.430
he came out into an open place opposite the village, and saw the

03:02:01.430 --> 03:02:05.650
ferry-boat lying in the shadow of the trees and the high bank. Everything

03:02:05.650 --> 03:02:10.290
was quiet under the blinking stars. He crept down the bank, watching with

03:02:10.290 --> 03:02:14.450
all his eyes, slipped into the water, swam three or four strokes, and

03:02:14.450 --> 03:02:18.450
climbed into the skiff that did yawl-duty at the boat's stern. He laid

03:02:18.450 --> 03:02:22.490
himself down under the thwarps and waited, panting. Presently the

03:02:22.490 --> 03:02:26.910
cracked bell tapped, and a voice gave the order to cast off. A minute or

03:02:26.910 --> 03:02:31.210
two later the skiff's head was standing high up, against the boat's

03:02:31.210 --> 03:02:35.950
swell, and the voyage was begun. Tom felt happy in his success, for he

03:02:35.950 --> 03:02:39.490
knew it was the boat's last trip for the night. At the end of a long

03:02:39.490 --> 03:02:43.070
twelve or fifteen minutes the wheel stopped, and Tom slipped overboard

03:02:43.070 --> 03:02:47.410
and swam ashore in the dusk, landing fifty yards downstream, out of

03:02:47.410 --> 03:02:51.750
danger of possible stragglers. He flew along unfrequented alleys, and

03:02:51.750 --> 03:02:55.330
shortly found himself at his aunt's back fence. He climbed over,

03:02:55.630 --> 03:02:59.630
approached the El, and looked in at the sitting-room window, for a light

03:02:59.630 --> 03:03:04.630
was burning there. There sat Aunt Polly, Sid, Mary, and Joe Harper's

03:03:04.630 --> 03:03:09.030
mother grouped together, talking. They were by the bed, and the bed was

03:03:09.030 --> 03:03:12.850
between them and the door. Tom went to the door, and began to softly

03:03:12.850 --> 03:03:17.210
lift the latch. Then he pressed gently, and the door yielded a crack. He

03:03:17.210 --> 03:03:21.390
continued pushing, cautiously, and quaking every time it creaked, till

03:03:21.390 --> 03:03:25.090
he judged he might squeeze through on his knees. So he put his head

03:03:25.090 --> 03:03:26.810
through, and began whirly.

03:03:27.170 --> 03:03:32.210
"'What makes the candles blow so?' said Aunt Polly. Tom hurried up.

03:03:32.430 --> 03:03:39.010
"'Why, that door's open, I believe. Why, of course it is. No end of

03:03:39.010 --> 03:03:43.430
Tom disappeared under the bed just in time. He lay and breathed himself

03:03:43.430 --> 03:03:47.350
for a while, then crept to where he could almost touch his aunt's foot.

03:03:47.890 --> 03:03:52.190
"'But as I was saying,' said Aunt Polly, "'he warn't bad, so to say,

03:03:52.210 --> 03:03:57.850
only mischievous, only just giddy and harem-scarum, you know. You warn't

03:03:57.850 --> 03:04:01.930
any more responsible than a colt. He never meant any harm, and he was

03:04:01.930 --> 03:04:06.290
the best-hearted boy that ever was.' And she began to cry. It was just

03:04:06.290 --> 03:04:09.870
so with my Joe, always full of his devilment and up to every kind of

03:04:09.870 --> 03:04:13.570
mischief, but he was just as unselfish and kind as he could be. And

03:04:13.570 --> 03:04:17.430
laws bless me to think I went and whipped him for taking that cream,

03:04:17.850 --> 03:04:20.930
never once recollecting that I throwed it out myself because it was

03:04:20.930 --> 03:04:25.690
sour, and I never to see him again in this world, never, never, never,

03:04:25.810 --> 03:04:30.250
poor abused boy.' And Mrs. Harper sobbed as if her heart would break.

03:04:30.690 --> 03:04:35.170
"'I hope Tom's better off where he is,' said Sid. But if he'd been

03:04:35.170 --> 03:04:39.770
better in some ways—Sid!' Tom felt the glare of the old lady's eye,

03:04:39.990 --> 03:04:43.610
though he could not see it. Not a word against my Tom, now that he's

03:04:43.610 --> 03:04:49.450
gone. God'll take care of him. Never you trouble yourself, sir. Oh,

03:04:49.510 --> 03:04:53.530
Mrs. Harper, I don't know how to give him up. I don't know how to give

03:04:53.530 --> 03:04:57.710
him up. He was such a comfort to me, although he tormented my old heart

03:04:57.710 --> 03:05:02.850
out of me, most. The Lord giveth and the Lord hath taken away. Blessed

03:05:02.850 --> 03:05:08.450
be the name of the Lord. But it's so hard, oh, it's so hard. Only last

03:05:08.450 --> 03:05:12.210
Saturday my Joe busted a firecracker right under my nose, and I knocked

03:05:12.210 --> 03:05:17.070
him sprawling. Little did I know then how soon—oh, if it was to do

03:05:17.070 --> 03:05:19.690
over again, I'd hug him and bless him for it.'

03:05:20.730 --> 03:05:25.710
"'Yes, yes, yes, I know just how you feel, Mrs. Harper. I know just

03:05:25.710 --> 03:05:31.170
exactly how you feel. No longer ago than yesterday noon my Tom took and

03:05:31.170 --> 03:05:35.470
filled the cat full of painkiller. And I did think the creature would

03:05:35.470 --> 03:05:39.330
tear the house down. And, God forgive me, I cracked Tom's head with my

03:05:39.330 --> 03:05:43.950
thimble, poor boy, poor dead boy. But he's out of all his troubles now,

03:05:44.270 --> 03:05:48.750
and the last words I ever heard him say was to reproach. But this

03:05:48.750 --> 03:05:53.190
memory was too much for the old lady, and she broke entirely down. Tom

03:05:53.190 --> 03:05:57.230
was snuffling now himself, and more in pity of himself than anybody

03:05:57.230 --> 03:06:01.370
else. He could hear Mary crying and putting in a kindly word for him

03:06:01.370 --> 03:06:04.910
from time to time. He began to have a nobler opinion of himself than

03:06:04.910 --> 03:06:09.230
ever before. Still, he was sufficiently touched by his aunt's grief to

03:06:09.230 --> 03:06:13.270
long to rush out from under the bed and overwhelm her with joy, and the

03:06:13.270 --> 03:06:16.210
theatrical gorgeousness of the thing appealed strongly to his nature,

03:06:16.530 --> 03:06:21.210
too. But he resisted, and lay still. He went on listening, and gathered

03:06:21.210 --> 03:06:24.790
by odds and ends that it was conjectured at first that the boys had

03:06:24.790 --> 03:06:29.310
drowned while taking a swim. Then the small raft had been missed. Next

03:06:29.310 --> 03:06:32.710
certain boys said the missing lads had promised that the village should

03:06:32.710 --> 03:06:37.510
hear something soon. The wise heads had put this and that together, and

03:06:37.510 --> 03:06:41.310
decided that the lads had gone off on that raft, and would turn up at

03:06:41.310 --> 03:06:45.710
the next town below presently. But toward noon the raft had been found,

03:06:46.150 --> 03:06:49.450
lodged against the Missouri shore some five or six miles below the

03:06:49.450 --> 03:06:54.510
village, and then hope perished. They must be drowned, else hunger would

03:06:54.510 --> 03:06:58.450
have driven them home by nightfall if not sooner. It was believed that

03:06:58.450 --> 03:07:01.750
the search for the bodies had been a fruitless effort merely because

03:07:01.750 --> 03:07:05.690
the drowning must have occurred in mid-channel, since the boys, being

03:07:05.690 --> 03:07:09.950
good swimmers, would otherwise have escaped to shore. This was Wednesday

03:07:09.950 --> 03:07:14.490
night. If the bodies continued missing until Sunday, all hope would be

03:07:14.490 --> 03:07:18.550
given over, and the funerals would be preached on that morning. Tom

03:07:18.550 --> 03:07:23.650
shuddered. Mrs. Harper gave a sobbing good night and turned to go. Then,

03:07:23.650 --> 03:07:27.310
with a mutual impulse, the two bereaved women flung themselves into each

03:07:27.310 --> 03:07:32.450
other's arms, and had a good consoling cry, and then parted. Aunt Polly

03:07:32.450 --> 03:07:37.730
was tender far beyond her want. In her good night to Sid and Mary, Sid

03:07:37.730 --> 03:07:41.690
snuffled a bit, and Mary went off crying with all her heart. Aunt Polly

03:07:41.690 --> 03:07:45.750
knelt down and prayed for Tom so touchingly, so appealingly, and with

03:07:45.750 --> 03:07:50.050
such measureless love in her words and her old trembling voice, that he

03:07:50.050 --> 03:07:54.530
was weltering in tears again long before she was through. He had to keep

03:07:54.530 --> 03:07:58.210
still long after she went to bed, for she kept making broken-hearted

03:07:58.210 --> 03:08:02.910
ejaculations from time to time, tossing unrestfully and turning over, but

03:08:02.910 --> 03:08:05.770
alas, she was still only moaning a little in her sleep.

03:08:06.190 --> 03:08:10.290
Now the boy stole out, rose gradually from the bedside, shaded the candle

03:08:10.290 --> 03:08:14.110
light with his hand, and stood regarding her. His heart was full of

03:08:14.110 --> 03:08:18.110
pity for her. He took out his sycamore scroll and placed it by the

03:08:18.110 --> 03:08:22.110
candle, but something occurred to him, and he lingered considering. His

03:08:22.110 --> 03:08:25.670
face lighted with a happy solution of his thought. He put the bark

03:08:25.670 --> 03:08:30.390
hastily in his pocket. Then he bent over and kissed the faded lips, and

03:08:30.390 --> 03:08:34.890
straightway made his stealthy exit, latching the door behind him. He

03:08:34.890 --> 03:08:38.670
threaded his way back to the fairy landing, found nobody at large there,

03:08:38.790 --> 03:08:42.610
and walked boldly on board the boat, for he knew she was tenantless

03:08:42.610 --> 03:08:46.430
except that there was a watchman who always turned in and slept like a

03:08:46.430 --> 03:08:50.690
slave in image. He untied the skiff at the stern, slipped into it, and

03:08:50.690 --> 03:08:54.750
was soon rowing cautiously up-stream. When he had pulled a mile above

03:08:54.750 --> 03:08:58.990
the village, he started quartering across and bent himself stoutly to

03:08:58.990 --> 03:09:03.010
his work. He hit the landing on the other side neatly, for this was a

03:09:03.010 --> 03:09:07.290
familiar bit of work for him. He was moved to capture the skiff, arguing

03:09:07.290 --> 03:09:11.030
that it might be considered a ship and therefore a legitimate prey for a

03:09:11.030 --> 03:09:14.650
pirate, but he knew a thorough search would be made for it, and that

03:09:14.650 --> 03:09:19.330
might end in revelations. So he stepped ashore and entered the wood. He

03:09:19.330 --> 03:09:23.730
sat down and took a long rest, torturing himself meantime to keep awake,

03:09:24.070 --> 03:09:28.550
and then started warily down the home stretch. The night was far spent,

03:09:28.690 --> 03:09:31.630
it was broad daylight before he found himself fairly abreast the

03:09:31.630 --> 03:09:36.690
highland bar. He rested again until the sun was well up and gilding the

03:09:36.690 --> 03:09:40.830
great river with its splendor, and then he plunged into the stream. A

03:09:40.830 --> 03:09:43.810
little later he paused, dripping upon the threshold of the camp, and

03:09:43.810 --> 03:09:45.170
heard Joe say,--"No,

03:09:46.050 --> 03:09:50.850
Tom's true blue, Huck. He'll come back. He won't desert. He knows that would be

03:09:50.850 --> 03:09:53.950
a disgrace to a pirate, and Tom's too proud for that sort of thing.

03:09:54.250 --> 03:09:56.250
He's up to something or other."--"I wonder

03:09:56.950 --> 03:09:57.470
what?"--"Well,

03:09:57.750 --> 03:10:00.050
the things is ours, anyway, ain't they?"--"Pretty

03:10:00.550 --> 03:10:05.930
near, but not yet, Huck. The writing says they are if he ain't back here to breakfast."--"Which

03:10:05.930 --> 03:10:07.670
he is!" exclaimed

03:10:07.670 --> 03:10:10.810
Tom, with fine dramatic effect, stepping

03:10:10.810 --> 03:10:14.970
grandly into camp. A sumptuous breakfast of bacon and fish was

03:10:14.970 --> 03:10:19.190
shortly provided, and as the boys set to work upon it Tom recounted,

03:10:19.190 --> 03:10:23.730
and adorned, his adventures. They were a vain and boastful company of

03:10:23.730 --> 03:10:27.690
heroes when the tale was done. Then Tom hid himself away in a shady

03:10:27.690 --> 03:10:31.490
nook to sleep till noon, and the other pirates got ready to fish and

03:10:31.490 --> 03:10:31.970
explore.

03:10:49.730 --> 03:10:50.310
XVI.

03:10:50.550 --> 03:10:51.790
First Pipes.

03:10:52.110 --> 03:10:53.550
I've lost my knife.

03:10:54.370 --> 03:10:58.610
After dinner all the gang turned out to hunt for turtle-eggs on the bar.

03:10:58.950 --> 03:11:03.510
They went about poking sticks into the sand, and when they found a soft place they went

03:11:03.510 --> 03:11:05.530
down on their knees and dug with their hands.

03:11:06.390 --> 03:11:09.390
Sometimes they would take fifty or sixty eggs out of one hole.

03:11:09.810 --> 03:11:14.050
They were perfectly round white things, a trifle smaller than an English walnut.

03:11:14.450 --> 03:11:19.410
They had a famous fried-egg feast that night, and another on Friday morning.

03:11:20.070 --> 03:11:24.910
After breakfast they went whooping and prancing out on the bar, and chased each other round

03:11:24.910 --> 03:11:29.190
and round, shedding clothes as they went, until they were naked, and then continued

03:11:29.190 --> 03:11:35.330
far away, up the shoal-water of the bar, against the stiff current, which latter tripped their

03:11:35.330 --> 03:11:39.290
legs from under them from time to time, and greatly increased the fun.

03:11:39.730 --> 03:11:43.730
And now and then they stooped in a group and splashed water on each other's faces with

03:11:43.730 --> 03:11:48.590
their palms, gradually approaching each other with averted faces to avoid the strangling

03:11:48.590 --> 03:11:53.270
sprays, and finally gripping and struggling till the best man ducked his neighbour, and

03:11:53.270 --> 03:11:57.950
then they all went under in a tangle of white legs and arms, and came up blowing, sputtering,

03:11:57.950 --> 03:12:01.790
laughing and gasping for breath at one and the same time.

03:12:02.570 --> 03:12:08.050
When they were well exhausted, they would run out and sprawl on the dry, hot sand, and

03:12:08.050 --> 03:12:12.610
lie there and cover themselves up with it, and by and by break from the water again and

03:12:12.610 --> 03:12:14.650
go through the original performance once more.

03:12:15.390 --> 03:12:20.210
Finally it occurred to them that their naked skin represented flesh-coloured tights very

03:12:20.210 --> 03:12:25.550
fairly, so they drew a ring in the sand and had a circus, with three clowns in it, for

03:12:25.550 --> 03:12:30.310
none would yield this proudest post to his neighbour. Next they got their marbles and

03:12:30.310 --> 03:12:37.250
played nucks and ring-taw and keeps till that amusement grew stale. Then Joe and Huck had

03:12:37.250 --> 03:12:42.090
another swim, but Tom would not venture, because he found that in kicking off his trousers

03:12:42.090 --> 03:12:47.650
he had kicked his string of rattlesnake rattles off his ankle, and he wondered how he had

03:12:47.650 --> 03:12:52.650
escaped cramps so long without the protection of this mysterious charm. He did not venture

03:12:52.650 --> 03:12:56.810
again until he had found it, and by that time the other boys were tired and ready to rest.

03:12:57.210 --> 03:13:02.150
They gradually wandered apart and dropped into the dumps, and fell to gazing longingly

03:13:02.150 --> 03:13:07.670
across the wide river to where the village lay drowsing in the sun. Tom found himself

03:13:07.670 --> 03:13:12.910
writing BECKY in the sand with his big toe. He scratched it out and was angry with himself

03:13:12.910 --> 03:13:19.150
for his weakness. But he wrote it again, nevertheless. He could not help it. He erased it, once

03:13:19.150 --> 03:13:23.530
more, and then took himself out of temptation by driving the other boys together and joining

03:13:23.530 --> 03:13:23.990
them.

03:13:24.550 --> 03:13:30.330
But Joe's spirits had gone down almost beyond resurrection. He was so homesick that he could

03:13:30.330 --> 03:13:36.310
hardly endure the misery of it. The tears lay very near the surface. Huck was melancholy,

03:13:36.590 --> 03:13:42.510
too. Tom was downhearted, but tried hard not to show it. He had a secret, which he was

03:13:42.510 --> 03:13:47.690
not ready to tell yet, but if this mutinous depression was not broken up soon he would

03:13:47.690 --> 03:13:51.150
have to bring it out. He said, with a great show of cheerfulness,

03:13:51.590 --> 03:13:56.970
"'I bet there's been pirates on this island before, boys. We'll explore it again. They've

03:13:56.970 --> 03:14:02.290
hid treasures here somewhere.' How'd you feel to light on a rotten chest full of gold and

03:14:02.290 --> 03:14:03.490
silver, eh?'

03:14:03.930 --> 03:14:10.410
But it roused only a faint enthusiasm, which faded out with no reply. Tom tried one or

03:14:10.410 --> 03:14:16.610
two other seductions, but they failed, too. It was discouraging work. Joe sat poking up

03:14:16.610 --> 03:14:20.350
the sand with a stick, and looking very gloomy. Finally he said,

03:14:20.630 --> 03:14:25.450
"'Oh, boys, let's give it up. I want to go home. It's so lonesome.'

03:14:25.450 --> 03:14:29.850
"'Oh, no, Joe, you'll feel better by and by,' said Tom. Just think of the fishing that's

03:14:29.850 --> 03:14:30.530
here.'

03:14:30.530 --> 03:14:35.830
"'I don't care for fishing. I want to go home. But, Joe, there ain't such another swimming

03:14:35.830 --> 03:14:37.030
place anywhere.'

03:14:37.030 --> 03:14:41.570
"'Swimming's no good. I don't seem to care for it. Somehow, when there ain't anybody

03:14:41.570 --> 03:14:45.150
to say I shan't go in, I mean to go home.'

03:14:45.150 --> 03:14:49.530
"'Oh, shucks! Baby! You want to see your mother, I reckon?'

03:14:49.530 --> 03:14:54.590
"'Yes, I do want to see my mother. And you would, too, if you had one. I ain't any more

03:14:54.590 --> 03:14:56.830
baby than you are.' Joe snuffled a little.

03:14:57.470 --> 03:15:01.830
"'Well, we'll let the crybaby go home to his mother, won't we, Huck?'

03:15:01.830 --> 03:15:07.770
"'Poor thing! Does it want to see its mother? And so it shall. You like it here, don't you,

03:15:07.770 --> 03:15:10.110
Huck? We'll stay, won't we?'

03:15:10.110 --> 03:15:10.970
Huck said,

03:15:12.330 --> 03:15:16.730
"'Yes,' without any heart in it. I'll never speak to you again as long as I live,' said

03:15:16.730 --> 03:15:20.950
Joe, rising. There, now.' And he moved moodily away and began to dress himself.

03:15:21.350 --> 03:15:27.050
"'Who cares?' said Tom. Nobody wants you to. Go along home and get laughed at. Oh, you're

03:15:27.050 --> 03:15:32.130
a nice pirate. Huck and me ain't crybabies. We'll stay, won't we, Huck? Let him go if

03:15:32.130 --> 03:15:35.290
he wants to. I reckon we can get along without him, perhaps.'

03:15:35.290 --> 03:15:40.170
But Tom was uneasy, nevertheless, and was alarmed to see Joe go sullenly on with his

03:15:40.170 --> 03:15:44.950
dressing. And then it was discomforting to see Huck eyeing Joe's preparations so wistfully,

03:15:45.490 --> 03:15:50.810
and keeping up such an ominous silence. Presently, without a parting word, Joe began to wade

03:15:50.810 --> 03:15:57.470
off toward the Illinois shore. Tom's heart began to sink. He glanced at Huck. Huck could

03:15:57.470 --> 03:16:00.210
not bear the look, and dropped his eyes, and then he said,

03:16:00.930 --> 03:16:06.730
"'I want to go too, Tom. It was getting so lonesome anyway, and now it'll be worse. Let's

03:16:06.730 --> 03:16:07.490
us go too, Tom.'

03:16:08.410 --> 03:16:12.580
"'I won't. You can all go if you want to. I mean to stay.'

03:16:13.450 --> 03:16:14.780
"'Tom, I'd better go.'

03:16:15.590 --> 03:16:19.990
"'Well, go along. Who's hindering you?' Huck began to pick up his scattered clothes,

03:16:20.030 --> 03:16:20.550
and he said,

03:16:20.970 --> 03:16:25.710
"'Tom, I wish you'd come too. Now you think it over. We'll wait for you when we get to

03:16:25.710 --> 03:16:26.810
the shore.'

03:16:26.810 --> 03:16:30.210
"'Well, you'll wait a blame long time, that's all.'

03:16:30.210 --> 03:16:35.070
Huck started sorrowfully away, and Tom stood looking after him, with a strong desire tugging

03:16:35.070 --> 03:16:39.710
at his heart to yield his pride and go along too. He hoped the boys would stop, but they

03:16:39.710 --> 03:16:44.910
still waited slowly on. It suddenly dawned on Tom that it was become very lonely and

03:16:44.910 --> 03:16:49.910
still. He made one final struggle with his pride, and then darted after his comrades

03:16:49.910 --> 03:16:50.250
yelling,

03:16:50.510 --> 03:16:53.650
"'Wait! Wait! I want to tell you something!'

03:16:53.650 --> 03:16:58.510
They presently stopped and turned around. When he got to where they were, he began unfolding

03:16:58.510 --> 03:17:03.190
his secret, and they listened moodily till at last they saw the point he was driving

03:17:03.190 --> 03:17:08.970
at. And then they set up a war-whoop of applause, and said it was splendid, and said if he had

03:17:08.970 --> 03:17:13.770
told them at first they wouldn't have started away. He made a plausible excuse, but his

03:17:13.770 --> 03:17:18.950
real reason had been the fear that not even the secret would keep them with him any very

03:17:18.950 --> 03:17:25.190
length of time, and so he had meant to hold it in reserve as a last seduction. The lads

03:17:25.190 --> 03:17:30.050
came gaily back and went at their sports-gen with a will, chattering all the time about

03:17:30.050 --> 03:17:36.170
Tom's stupendous plan and admiring the genius of it. After a dainty egg and fish dinner,

03:17:36.590 --> 03:17:41.270
Tom said he wanted to learn to smoke now. Joe caught at the idea and said he would like

03:17:41.270 --> 03:17:47.310
to try too. So Huck made pipes and filled them. These novices had never smoked anything

03:17:47.310 --> 03:17:53.110
before but cigars made of grapevine, and they bit the tongue and were not considered

03:17:53.110 --> 03:17:53.990
manly anyway.

03:17:54.870 --> 03:17:59.910
Now they stretched themselves out on their elbows and began to puff charrily and with

03:17:59.910 --> 03:18:04.890
slender confidence. The smoke had an unpleasant taste, and they gagged a little, but Tom said,

03:18:04.910 --> 03:18:10.910
Why, it's just as easy. If I'd a knowed this was all, I'd a learned long ago. So would

03:18:10.910 --> 03:18:16.330
I, said Joe, it's just nothing. Why, many a time I've looked at people smoking and thought,

03:18:16.330 --> 03:18:19.810
Well, I wish I could do that. But I never thought I could, said Tom.

03:18:20.310 --> 03:18:24.710
That's just the way with me, ain't it, Huck? You've heard me talk just that way, haven't

03:18:24.710 --> 03:18:27.010
you, Huck? I'll leave it to Huck if I haven't.

03:18:27.670 --> 03:18:29.550
Yes, heaps of times, said Huck.

03:18:29.870 --> 03:18:34.750
Well, I have too, said Tom. Oh, hundreds of times. Once down by the slaughter-house, don't

03:18:34.750 --> 03:18:38.690
you remember, Huck? Bob Tanner was there, and Johnny Miller and Jeff Thatcher when I

03:18:38.690 --> 03:18:41.370
said it. Don't you remember, Huck, about me saying that?

03:18:41.370 --> 03:18:46.490
Yes, that's so, said Huck. That was the day after I lost a white alley. No, it was the

03:18:46.490 --> 03:18:47.110
day before.

03:18:47.490 --> 03:18:50.590
There, I told you so, said Tom. Huck recollects it.

03:18:51.010 --> 03:18:55.130
I believe I could smoke this pipe all day, said Joe. I don't feel sick.

03:18:55.750 --> 03:19:01.050
Neither do I, said Tom. I could smoke it all day. But I bet you Jeff Thatcher couldn't.

03:19:01.110 --> 03:19:07.530
Jeff Thatcher! Why, he'd keel over just—with two draws! Just let him try it once! He'd

03:19:07.530 --> 03:19:07.710
see.

03:19:07.710 --> 03:19:12.510
I bet he would. And Johnny Miller, I wish I could see Johnny Miller tackle it once.

03:19:12.890 --> 03:19:18.530
Oh, don't I, said Joe. Why, I bet now Johnny Miller couldn't any more do this than nothing.

03:19:19.150 --> 03:19:21.210
Just one little snifter would fetch him.

03:19:21.710 --> 03:19:24.830
Indeed it would, Joe. Say, I wish the boys could see us now.

03:19:25.290 --> 03:19:26.270
So do I.

03:19:26.910 --> 03:19:31.790
Say, boys, don't say anything about it, and some time when they're around I'll come up

03:19:31.790 --> 03:19:32.450
to you and say,

03:19:32.450 --> 03:19:38.250
Joe, got a pipe? I want to smoke. And you'll say, kind of careless like, as if it weren't

03:19:38.250 --> 03:19:39.150
anything, you'll say,

03:19:39.450 --> 03:19:44.950
Yes, I got my old pipe, and another one, but my tobacco ain't very good. And I'll say,

03:19:45.230 --> 03:19:49.390
Oh, that's all right, if it's strong enough. And then you'll out with the pipes, and we'll

03:19:49.390 --> 03:19:52.350
light up just as calm, and then just see them look.

03:19:52.770 --> 03:19:55.650
By, jing, that'll be gay, Tom, I wish it was now.

03:19:56.090 --> 03:20:00.710
So do I. And when we tell them we learned when we was off pirating, won't they wish

03:20:00.710 --> 03:20:01.470
they'd been along?

03:20:01.470 --> 03:20:05.150
Oh, I reckon not. I'll just bet they will."

03:20:05.150 --> 03:20:10.650
So the talk ran on, but presently it began to flag a trifle and grow disjointed. The

03:20:10.650 --> 03:20:16.490
silences widened, the expectoration marvelously increased. Every pore inside the boys' cheeks

03:20:16.490 --> 03:20:21.550
became a spouting fountain. They could scarcely bail out the cellars under their tongues fast

03:20:21.550 --> 03:20:26.670
enough to prevent an inundation. Little overflowing down their throats occurred in spite of all

03:20:26.670 --> 03:20:31.990
they could do, and sudden retchings followed every time. Both boys were looking very pale

03:20:31.990 --> 03:20:38.290
and miserable now. Joe's pipe dropped from his nerveless fingers. Tom swallowed. Both

03:20:38.290 --> 03:20:43.710
fountains were going furiously, and both pumps bailing with mite and maine. Joe said feebly,

03:20:44.210 --> 03:20:48.070
I've lost my knife. I reckon I'd better go and find it.

03:20:48.610 --> 03:20:51.110
Tom said with quivering lips and halting utterance,

03:20:51.510 --> 03:20:55.650
I'll help you. You go over that way, and I'll hunt around by the spring.

03:20:55.650 --> 03:20:58.590
No, you needn't come, Huck. We can find it.

03:20:58.850 --> 03:21:04.050
So Huck sat down again and waited an hour. Then he found it lonesome and went to find

03:21:04.050 --> 03:21:10.510
his comrades. They were wide apart in the woods, both very pale, both fast asleep. But

03:21:10.510 --> 03:21:16.010
something informed him that if they had had any trouble, they'd got rid of it. They were

03:21:16.010 --> 03:21:20.570
not talkative at supper that night. They had a humble look, and when Huck prepared his

03:21:20.570 --> 03:21:26.090
after the meal, and was going to prepare theirs, they said no, they were not feeling very well.

03:21:26.550 --> 03:21:28.910
Something they ate at dinner had disagreed with them.

03:21:29.390 --> 03:21:34.330
About midnight Joe awoke and called the boys. There was a brooding oppressiveness in the

03:21:34.330 --> 03:21:38.770
air that seemed to bode something. The boys huddled themselves together and sought the

03:21:38.770 --> 03:21:43.470
friendly companionship of the fire, though the dull, dead heat of the breathless atmosphere

03:21:43.470 --> 03:21:49.090
was stifling. They sat still, intent and waiting. The solemn hush continued.

03:21:49.090 --> 03:21:53.430
Beyond the light of the fire everything was swallowed up in the blackness of darkness.

03:21:54.150 --> 03:21:58.590
Presently there came a quivering glow that vaguely revealed the foliage for a moment,

03:21:58.910 --> 03:22:05.390
and then vanished. By and by another came, a little stronger. Then another. Then a faint

03:22:05.390 --> 03:22:10.530
moan came sighing through the branches of the forest, and the boys felt a fleeting breath

03:22:10.530 --> 03:22:14.530
upon their cheeks, and shuddered with the fancy that the spirit of the night had gone

03:22:14.530 --> 03:22:20.910
by. There was a pause. Now a weird flash turned night into day, and showed every little

03:22:20.910 --> 03:22:26.070
grass blade, separate and distinct, and grew about their feet. And it showed three white

03:22:26.070 --> 03:22:31.790
startled faces, too. A deep peal of thunder went rolling and tumbling down the heavens,

03:22:32.250 --> 03:22:37.410
and lost itself in sullen rumblings in the distance. A sweep of chilly air passed by,

03:22:37.690 --> 03:22:43.170
rustling all the leaves and snowing the flaky ashes broadcast about the fire. Another fierce

03:22:43.170 --> 03:22:47.890
glare lit up the forest, and an instant crash followed that seemed to rend the treetops

03:22:47.890 --> 03:22:52.910
right over the boys' heads. They clung together in terror in the thick gloom that followed.

03:22:53.470 --> 03:22:56.750
A few big raindrops fell pattering upon the leaves.

03:22:57.110 --> 03:23:02.170
Quick, boys, go for the tent! exclaimed Tom. They sprang away, stumbling over the roots

03:23:02.170 --> 03:23:07.890
and among vines in the dark, no two plunging in the same direction. A furious blast roared

03:23:07.890 --> 03:23:12.890
through the trees, making everything sing as it went. One blinding flash after another,

03:23:12.890 --> 03:23:18.030
and the peal on peal of deafening thunder. And now a drenching rain poured down, and

03:23:18.030 --> 03:23:23.010
the rising hurricane drove it in sheets along the ground. The boys cried out to each other,

03:23:23.330 --> 03:23:28.730
but the roaring wind and the booming thunder blast drowned their voices utterly. However,

03:23:28.850 --> 03:23:33.790
one by one they straggled in at last, and took shelter under the tent, cold, scared,

03:23:34.210 --> 03:23:38.510
and streaming with water. But to have company in misery seemed something to be grateful

03:23:38.510 --> 03:23:44.330
for. They could not talk, the old sail flat so furiously, even if the other noises would

03:23:44.330 --> 03:23:49.230
have allowed them. The tempest rose higher and higher, and presently the sail tore loose

03:23:49.230 --> 03:23:54.250
from its fastenings, and went winging away on the blast. The boys seized each other's

03:23:54.250 --> 03:23:59.130
hands and fled, with many tumblings and bruises, to the shelter of a great oak tree that stood

03:23:59.130 --> 03:24:04.610
upon the river bank. Now the battle was at its highest. Under the ceaseless conflagration

03:24:04.610 --> 03:24:09.950
of lightning that flamed in the skies, everything below stood out in clean cut and shadowless

03:24:09.950 --> 03:24:16.530
distinction. The bending trees, the billowy river, white with foam, the driving spray

03:24:16.530 --> 03:24:21.510
of spume flakes, the dim outlines of the high bluffs on the other side, glimpsed through

03:24:21.510 --> 03:24:27.090
the drifting cloud-rack and the slanting veil of rain. Every little while some giant tree

03:24:27.090 --> 03:24:32.230
yielded the fight and fell crashing through the younger growth, and the unflagging thunder-peals

03:24:32.230 --> 03:24:38.270
came now in ear-splitting explosive bursts, keen and sharp and unspeakably appalling.

03:24:38.990 --> 03:24:43.450
The storm culminated in one matchless effort that seemed likely to tear the island to pieces,

03:24:43.750 --> 03:24:48.470
burn it up, drown it to the treetops, and blow it away, and deafen every creature in

03:24:48.470 --> 03:24:53.530
it all at once at the same moment. It was a wild night for homeless young heads to be

03:24:53.530 --> 03:24:53.970
out in.

03:24:54.550 --> 03:24:59.610
But at last the battle was done, and the forces retired with weaker and weaker threatenings

03:24:59.610 --> 03:25:06.110
and grumblings, and peace resumed her sway. The boys went back to camp, a good deal awed,

03:25:06.290 --> 03:25:11.190
but they found there was still something to be thankful for, because the great sycamore,

03:25:11.430 --> 03:25:16.770
the shelter of their beds, was a ruin now, blasted by the lightnings, and they were not

03:25:16.770 --> 03:25:22.530
under it when the catastrophe happened. Everything in camp was drenched, the campfire as well,

03:25:22.770 --> 03:25:27.230
for they were but heedless lads, like their generation, and had made no provision against

03:25:27.230 --> 03:25:32.750
rain. Here was matter for dismay, for they were soaked through and chilled. They were

03:25:32.750 --> 03:25:37.370
eloquent in their distress, but they presently discovered that the fire had eaten so far

03:25:37.370 --> 03:25:42.730
up under the great log it had been built against, where it curved upward and separated itself

03:25:42.730 --> 03:25:48.410
from the ground, that a hand-breadth or so of it had escaped wetting. So they patiently

03:25:48.410 --> 03:25:55.250
wrought until, with shreds and bark gathered from under sides of sheltered logs, they coaxed

03:25:55.250 --> 03:26:00.430
the fire to burn again. Then they piled on great dead boughs till they had a roaring

03:26:00.430 --> 03:26:06.570
furnace and were glad-hearted once more. They dried their boiled ham and had a feast, and

03:26:06.570 --> 03:26:10.870
after that they sat by the fire and expanded and glorified their midnight adventure until

03:26:10.870 --> 03:26:17.110
morning, for there was not a dry spot to sleep on anywhere around. As the sun began to steal

03:26:17.110 --> 03:26:22.250
in upon the boys, drowsiness came over them, and they went out on the sandbar and lay down

03:26:22.250 --> 03:26:27.170
to sleep. They got scorched out by and by and drearily set about getting breakfast.

03:26:27.710 --> 03:26:33.470
After the meal they felt rusty and stiff-jointed and a little homesick once more. Tom saw the

03:26:33.470 --> 03:26:38.450
signs and fell to cheering up the pirates as well as he could. But they cared nothing

03:26:38.450 --> 03:26:43.950
for marbles or circus or swimming or anything. He reminded them of the imposing secret and

03:26:43.950 --> 03:26:48.990
raised a rave cheer. While it lasted he got them interested in a new device. This was

03:26:48.990 --> 03:26:53.970
to knock off being pirates for a while and be Indians for a change. They were attracted

03:26:53.970 --> 03:26:58.850
by this idea, so it was not long before they were stripped and striped from head to heel

03:26:58.850 --> 03:27:04.030
with black mud like so many zebras—all of them chiefs, of course—and then they went

03:27:04.030 --> 03:27:08.770
tearing through the woods to attack an English settlement. By and by they separated into

03:27:08.770 --> 03:27:14.050
three hostile tribes and darted upon each other from ambush with dreadful war-woops

03:27:14.050 --> 03:27:20.550
and killed and scalped each other by thousands. It was a gory day. Consequently it was an

03:27:20.550 --> 03:27:22.090
extremely satisfactory one.

03:27:22.850 --> 03:27:28.550
They assembled in camp towards supper-time, hungry and happy. But now a difficulty arose.

03:27:28.930 --> 03:27:33.210
Hostile Indians could not break the bread of hospitality together without first making

03:27:33.210 --> 03:27:38.530
peace, and this was a simple impossibility without smoking a pipe of peace. There was

03:27:38.530 --> 03:27:42.850
no other process that they ever had heard of. Two of the savages almost wished they

03:27:42.850 --> 03:27:48.750
had remained pirates. However, there was no other way. So, with such show of cheerfulness

03:27:48.750 --> 03:27:52.670
as they could muster, they called for the pipe and took their whiff as it passed in

03:27:52.670 --> 03:27:57.710
due form. And, behold, they were glad they had gone into savagery, for they had gained

03:27:57.710 --> 03:28:02.070
something. They found that they could now smoke a little without having to go and hunt

03:28:02.070 --> 03:28:07.850
for lost knife. They did not get sick enough to be seriously uncomfortable. They were not

03:28:07.850 --> 03:28:14.750
to fool away this high promise for lack of effort. No, they practiced cautiously after

03:28:14.750 --> 03:28:20.070
supper with right fair success, and so they spent a jubilant evening. They were prouder

03:28:20.070 --> 03:28:24.510
and happier in their new acquirement than they would have been in the scalping and skinning

03:28:24.510 --> 03:28:30.130
of the six nations. We will leave them to smoke and chatter and brag, since we have

03:28:30.130 --> 03:28:31.910
no further use for them at present.

03:28:36.490 --> 03:28:37.770
CHAPTER XVII.

03:28:38.090 --> 03:28:40.110
PIRATES AT THEIR OWN FUNERAL

03:28:40.690 --> 03:28:45.890
But there was no hilarity in the little town that same tranquil Saturday afternoon the

03:28:45.890 --> 03:28:51.130
Harpers and Aunt Polly's family were being put into mourning with great grief and many

03:28:51.130 --> 03:28:56.250
tears. An unusual quiet possessed the village, although it was ordinarily quiet enough in

03:28:56.250 --> 03:29:01.650
all conscience. The villagers conducted their concerns with an absent mind and talked little,

03:29:01.650 --> 03:29:07.410
but they sighed often. The Saturday holiday seemed a burden to the children. They had

03:29:07.410 --> 03:29:12.010
no heart in their sports and gradually gave them up. In the afternoon Becky Thatcher found

03:29:12.010 --> 03:29:17.170
herself moping about the deserted schoolhouse yard and feeling very melancholy, but she

03:29:17.170 --> 03:29:20.270
found nothing there to comfort her. She solitiquised,

03:29:21.170 --> 03:29:27.050
"'Oh, if I only had a brass and iron knob again! But I haven't got anything now to remember

03:29:27.050 --> 03:29:29.710
him by!' and she choked back a little sob.

03:29:30.310 --> 03:29:32.350
Presently she stopped and said to herself,

03:29:32.690 --> 03:29:38.830
"'It was right here. Oh, if it was to do over again I wouldn't say that. I wouldn't say

03:29:38.830 --> 03:29:44.930
it for the whole world. But he's gone now. I'll never, never, never see him any more.'

03:29:44.930 --> 03:29:50.090
This thought broke her down and she wandered away, with the tears rolling down her cheeks.

03:29:50.510 --> 03:29:56.730
Then quite a group of boys and girls—playmates of Toms and Joes—came by and stood looking

03:29:56.730 --> 03:30:02.050
over the paling fence and talking in reverent tones of how Tom did so-and-so the last time

03:30:02.050 --> 03:30:07.570
they saw him, and how Joes said this and that small trifle, pregnant with awful prophecy,

03:30:07.910 --> 03:30:13.610
as they could easily see now. And each speaker pointed out the exact spot where the lost

03:30:13.610 --> 03:30:16.350
lad stood at the time, and then added something like,

03:30:16.630 --> 03:30:22.750
"'And I was a-standing just so, just as I am now. And as if you was him, I was as close

03:30:22.750 --> 03:30:27.950
as that.' And he smiled just this way, and then something seemed to go all over me, like,

03:30:28.350 --> 03:30:34.730
awful, you know, and I never thought what it meant. Of course, but I can see now.'

03:30:34.730 --> 03:30:40.270
Then there was a dispute about who saw the dead boys last in life, and many claimed that

03:30:40.270 --> 03:30:45.270
dismal distinction, and offered evidences more or less tampered with by the witness.

03:30:45.610 --> 03:30:50.850
And when it was ultimately decided who did see the departed last, and exchanged the last

03:30:50.850 --> 03:30:56.170
words with them, the lucky parties took upon themselves a sort of sacred importance, and

03:30:56.170 --> 03:31:01.690
were gaped at and envied by all the rest. One poor chap, who had no other grandeur to

03:31:01.690 --> 03:31:05.470
offer, said, with tolerably manifest pride in the remembrance,

03:31:06.050 --> 03:31:12.850
"'Well, Tom Sawyer, he licked me once.' But that bid for glory was a failure. Most of

03:31:12.850 --> 03:31:18.210
the boys could say that, and so that cheapened the distinction too much. The group loitered

03:31:18.210 --> 03:31:22.590
away, still recalling memories of the lost heroes in awed voices.

03:31:23.010 --> 03:31:28.250
When the Sunday-school hour was finished the next morning, the bell began to toll instead

03:31:28.250 --> 03:31:34.210
of ringing in the usual way. It was a very still Sabbath, and the mournful sound seemed

03:31:34.210 --> 03:31:40.070
in keeping with the musing hush that lay upon nature. The villagers began to gather, loitering

03:31:40.070 --> 03:31:45.090
a moment in the vestibule to converse and whispers about the sad event. But there was

03:31:45.090 --> 03:31:50.590
whispering in the house. Only the funereal rustling of dresses, as the women gathered

03:31:50.590 --> 03:31:55.770
to their seats, disturbed the silence there. None could remember when the little church

03:31:55.770 --> 03:32:01.410
had been so full before. There was finally a waiting pause, an expectant dumbness, and

03:32:01.410 --> 03:32:07.170
then Aunt Polly entered, followed by Sid and Mary, and they by the Harper family, all in

03:32:07.170 --> 03:32:12.410
deep black, and the whole congregation, the old ministers well, rose reverently and stood,

03:32:12.870 --> 03:32:17.610
until the mourners were seated in the front pew. There was another communing silence,

03:32:17.750 --> 03:32:22.950
broken at intervals by muffled sobs, and then the minister spread his hands abroad and prayed.

03:32:23.630 --> 03:32:28.490
A moving hymn was sung, and the text followed, I AM THE RESURRECTION AND THE LIFE.

03:32:29.050 --> 03:32:34.370
As the service proceeded, the clergyman drew such pictures of the graces, the winning ways,

03:32:34.750 --> 03:32:39.570
and the rare promise of the lost lads, that every soul there thinking he recognized these

03:32:39.570 --> 03:32:44.830
pictures, felt a pang in remembering that he had persistently blinded himself to them

03:32:44.830 --> 03:32:51.210
always before, and had as persistently seen only faults and flaws in the poor boys. The

03:32:51.210 --> 03:32:56.270
minister related many a touching incident in the lives of the departed, too, which illustrated

03:32:56.270 --> 03:33:01.930
their sweet, generous natures, and the people could easily see now how noble and beautiful

03:33:01.930 --> 03:33:07.710
those episodes were, and remembered with grief that at the time they occurred they had seemed

03:33:07.710 --> 03:33:14.050
rank rascalities, well deserving of the cow-hide. The congregation became more and more moved

03:33:14.050 --> 03:33:19.350
as the pathetic tale went on, till at last the whole company broke down and joined the

03:33:19.350 --> 03:33:24.450
weeping mourners in a chorus of anguished sobs, the preacher himself giving way to his

03:33:24.450 --> 03:33:26.430
feelings and crying in the pulpit.

03:33:27.070 --> 03:33:32.170
There was a rustle in the gallery which nobody noticed. A moment later the church door creaked.

03:33:32.170 --> 03:33:37.890
The minister raised his streaming eyes above his handkerchief and stood transfixed. First

03:33:37.890 --> 03:33:43.450
one, and another pair of eyes followed the minister's, and then almost with one impulse

03:33:43.450 --> 03:33:48.030
the congregation rose and stared while the three dead boys came marching up the aisle,

03:33:48.370 --> 03:33:53.950
Tom in the lead, Joe next, and Huck, a ruin of drooping rags, sneaking sheepishly in the

03:33:53.950 --> 03:34:00.110
rear. They had been hid in the unused gallery, listening to their own funeral sermon. Aunt

03:34:00.110 --> 03:34:05.110
Polly, Mary, and the Harpers threw themselves upon their restored ones, smothered them with

03:34:05.110 --> 03:34:09.870
kisses and poured out thanksgivings, while poor Huck stood abashed and uncomfortable,

03:34:10.430 --> 03:34:15.770
not knowing exactly what to do or where to hide from so many unwelcoming eyes. He wavered

03:34:15.770 --> 03:34:18.590
and started to slink away, but Tom seized him and said,

03:34:19.030 --> 03:34:23.230
"'Aunt Polly, it ain't fair. Somebody's got to be glad to see Huck.'

03:34:23.790 --> 03:34:27.670
"'And so they shall. I'm glad to see him, poor motherless thing.'

03:34:27.670 --> 03:34:33.390
And the loving attentions Aunt Polly lavished upon him were the one thing capable of making

03:34:33.390 --> 03:34:39.010
him more uncomfortable than he was before. Suddenly the minister shouted at the top of

03:34:39.010 --> 03:34:39.430
his voice,

03:34:40.050 --> 03:34:46.750
"'Praise God, from whom all blessings flow! Sing! And put your hearts in it!'

03:34:46.750 --> 03:34:52.990
And they did. Old hundred swelled up with a triumphant burst, and while it shook the

03:34:52.990 --> 03:34:58.870
Tom Sawyer the pirate looked around upon the envying juveniles about him, and confessed

03:34:58.870 --> 03:35:05.030
in his heart that this was the proudest moment of his life. As the souled congregation trooped

03:35:05.030 --> 03:35:09.950
out they said they would almost be willing to be made ridiculous again to hear old hundred

03:35:09.950 --> 03:35:16.270
sung like that once more. Tom got more cuffs and kisses that day, according to Aunt Polly's

03:35:16.270 --> 03:35:21.710
varying moods, than he had earned before in a year, and he hardly knew which expressed

03:35:21.710 --> 03:35:25.350
the most gratefulness to God, and affection for himself.

03:35:42.450 --> 03:35:45.510
XVIII. Tom Reveals His Dream Secret.

03:35:46.970 --> 03:35:50.670
That was Tom's great secret, the scheme to return home with his brother

03:35:50.670 --> 03:35:54.730
pirates and attend their own funerals. They had paddled over to the

03:35:54.730 --> 03:35:58.710
Missouri shore in a log, at dusk on Saturday, landing five or six

03:35:58.710 --> 03:36:01.950
miles below the village. They had slept in the woods at the edge of

03:36:01.950 --> 03:36:06.110
the town till nearly daylight, and had then crept through back lanes

03:36:06.110 --> 03:36:10.150
and alleys and finished their sleep in the gallery of the church among

03:36:10.150 --> 03:36:12.410
a chaos of invalid benches.

03:36:13.090 --> 03:36:17.070
At breakfast Monday morning Aunt Polly and Mary were very loving to

03:36:17.070 --> 03:36:21.010
Tom, and very attentive to his wants. There was an unusual amount of

03:36:21.630 --> 03:36:23.450
In the course of it, Aunt Polly said,

03:36:23.950 --> 03:36:27.810
Well, I don't say it wasn't a fine joke, Tom, to keep everybody

03:36:27.810 --> 03:36:32.230
suffering most a week, so you boys had a good time, but it is a pity

03:36:32.230 --> 03:36:37.170
you could be so hard-hearted as to let me suffer so. If you could have

03:36:37.170 --> 03:36:41.290
come over on a log to go to your funeral, you could have come over and

03:36:41.290 --> 03:36:45.350
give me a hint some way that you weren't dead, but only run off. Yes,

03:36:45.350 --> 03:36:49.110
you could have done that, Tom, said Mary, and I believe you would, if

03:36:49.110 --> 03:36:50.030
had thought of it.

03:36:50.190 --> 03:36:54.450
Would you, Tom? said Aunt Polly, her face lightning wistfully. Say, now,

03:36:54.610 --> 03:36:56.230
would you, if you'd thought of it?

03:36:57.310 --> 03:36:57.790
I—

03:36:57.790 --> 03:37:00.670
Well, I don't know. Toot has spoiled everything.

03:37:01.330 --> 03:37:04.670
Tom, I hoped you loved me that much, said Aunt Polly, with a grieved

03:37:04.670 --> 03:37:08.130
tone that discomfited the boy. It would have been something if you'd

03:37:08.130 --> 03:37:11.190
cared enough to think of it, even if you didn't do it.

03:37:11.710 --> 03:37:16.390
Now, Auntie, that ain't any harm, pleaded Mary. It's only Tom's giddy

03:37:16.390 --> 03:37:19.590
way. He's always in such a rush that he never thinks of anything.

03:37:20.410 --> 03:37:24.370
More's the pity, Sid would have thought, and Sid would have come and

03:37:24.370 --> 03:37:28.670
done it, too. Tom, you'll look back some day, when it's too late, and

03:37:28.670 --> 03:37:32.070
wish you'd cared a little more for me, when it would have cost you so

03:37:32.070 --> 03:37:32.310
little.

03:37:33.210 --> 03:37:38.610
Now, Auntie, you know I do care for you, said Tom. I'd know it better

03:37:38.610 --> 03:37:40.050
if you acted more like it.

03:37:40.490 --> 03:37:44.890
I wish now I'd thought, said Tom, with a repentant tone, but I dreamed

03:37:44.890 --> 03:37:49.690
you anyway. That's something, ate it. It ain't much. A cat does that

03:37:49.690 --> 03:37:54.890
much, but it's better than nothing. What did you dream? Why, Wednesday

03:37:54.890 --> 03:37:57.950
night I dreamt that you was sitting over there by the bed, and Sid was

03:37:57.950 --> 03:38:03.350
sitting by the wood-box, and Mary next to him. Well, so we did. So we

03:38:03.350 --> 03:38:07.770
always do. I'm glad your dreams could take even that much trouble about

03:38:07.770 --> 03:38:13.790
us. And I dreamt that Joe Harper's mother was here. Why, she was here.

03:38:13.790 --> 03:38:19.890
Did you dream any more? Oh, lots, but it's so dim now. Well, try to

03:38:19.890 --> 03:38:24.530
recollect, can't you? Somehow it seems to me that the wind—the wind

03:38:24.530 --> 03:38:30.030
blowed. The—the—try harder, Tom. The wind did blow something. Come."

03:38:30.030 --> 03:38:33.170
Tom pressed his fingers to his forehead an anxious minute, and then

03:38:33.170 --> 03:38:33.370
said,

03:38:34.010 --> 03:38:37.410
"'I've got it now. I've got it now. It blowed the candle.'

03:38:37.410 --> 03:38:40.330
"'Mercy on us. Go on, Tom. Go on.'

03:38:40.330 --> 03:38:44.550
"'And it seems to me that you said, Why, I believe that that door—'

03:38:44.910 --> 03:38:49.910
"'Go on, Tom. Just let me study a moment. Just a moment. Oh, yes. You

03:38:49.910 --> 03:38:54.450
said you believed the door was open. As I'm sitting here, I did. Didn't

03:38:54.450 --> 03:38:58.150
I, Mary? Go on. And then—and then—'

03:38:58.190 --> 03:39:01.710
"'Well, I won't be certain, but it seems like—like as if you made Sid

03:39:01.710 --> 03:39:03.290
go and—and—'

03:39:03.410 --> 03:39:08.730
"'Well? Well, what did I make him do, Tom? What did I make him do? You

03:39:08.730 --> 03:39:15.190
made him—you—oh—you made him shut it. Well, for Lyon's sake, I

03:39:15.190 --> 03:39:18.370
never heard the beat of that in all my days. Don't tell me there ain't

03:39:18.370 --> 03:39:22.110
anything in dreams any more. Serenity Harper shall know of this before

03:39:22.110 --> 03:39:25.910
I'm an hour older. I'd like to see her get around this with her rubbish

03:39:25.910 --> 03:39:31.370
about superstition. Go on, Tom. Oh, it's all getting just as bright as

03:39:31.370 --> 03:39:36.050
day now. Next you said I warn't bad. Only mischievous and harem-scarum,

03:39:36.050 --> 03:39:41.890
and not any more responsible than—than—I think it was a colt or

03:39:41.890 --> 03:39:47.690
something. And so it was. Well, goodness gracious, go on, Tom. And then

03:39:47.690 --> 03:39:52.810
you began to cry. So I did. So I did. Not the first time, neither. And

03:39:52.810 --> 03:39:57.110
then—or then Mrs. Harper, she began to cry, and said Joe was just the

03:39:57.110 --> 03:40:00.470
same, and she wished she hadn't whipped him for taking cream when she'd

03:40:00.470 --> 03:40:06.030
throated out of her own self. Tom, the spirit was upon you. You was a

03:40:06.030 --> 03:40:10.690
office-sion. That's what you was a-doing. Land alive. Go on, Tom. Well,

03:40:10.690 --> 03:40:12.950
then, Sid, he said—he said—

03:40:12.950 --> 03:40:15.730
"'I don't think I said anything,' said Sid."

03:40:15.730 --> 03:40:19.630
"'Yes, you did, Sid,' said Mary. "'Shut your heads and let Tom go. What

03:40:19.630 --> 03:40:21.090
did he say, Tom?'

03:40:21.090 --> 03:40:22.070
"'He said—'

03:40:22.210 --> 03:40:26.410
"'I think he said he hoped I was better off where I was gone to, but if

03:40:26.410 --> 03:40:28.150
I'd been better sometimes—'

03:40:28.410 --> 03:40:33.070
"'There, do you hear that?' It was his very words. And you shut him up

03:40:33.070 --> 03:40:37.670
sharp. I lay, I did. There must have been an angel there. There was an

03:40:37.670 --> 03:40:41.830
angel there, somewheres. And Mrs. Harper told about Joe scaring her with

03:40:41.830 --> 03:40:45.750
a firecracker, and you told about Peter and the painkiller—just as true

03:40:45.750 --> 03:40:49.490
as I live. And then there was a whole lot of talk about dragging the

03:40:49.490 --> 03:40:54.130
river for us, and about having the funeral Sunday. And then you and old

03:40:54.130 --> 03:41:03.050
Miss Harper hugged and cried, and she went. It happened just so. It

03:41:03.050 --> 03:41:07.170
Tom, you couldn't have told it more like if you'd seen it. And then what?

03:41:07.290 --> 03:41:08.610
Go on, Tom.'

03:41:08.610 --> 03:41:12.210
"'Then I thought you prayed for me, and I could see you and hear every

03:41:12.210 --> 03:41:16.810
word you said. And you went to bed, and I was so sorry that I took and

03:41:16.810 --> 03:41:21.010
wrote on a piece of sycamore bark, We ain't dead, we are only off being

03:41:21.010 --> 03:41:25.410
pirates,' and put it on the table by the candle. And then you looked so

03:41:25.410 --> 03:41:28.910
good laying there asleep that I thought I went and leaned over and kissed

03:41:28.910 --> 03:41:30.130
you on the lips.'

03:41:30.130 --> 03:41:35.270
"'Did you, Tom? Did you? I just forgive you everything for that.' And she

03:41:35.270 --> 03:41:38.610
sees the boy in a crushing embrace that made him feel like the guiltiest

03:41:38.610 --> 03:41:44.810
of villains. It was very kind, even though it was only—'A dream,' said

03:41:44.810 --> 03:41:46.450
Soliloquyze, just audibly.

03:41:46.810 --> 03:41:50.470
"'Shut up, Sid. A body does just the same in a dream as he'd do if he

03:41:50.470 --> 03:41:53.970
was awake. Here's a big mylam apple I've been saving for you, Tom, if

03:41:53.970 --> 03:41:58.070
he was ever found again. Now go along to school. I'm thankful to the

03:41:58.070 --> 03:42:02.070
good God and Father of us all I've got you back. That's long-suffering

03:42:02.070 --> 03:42:05.270
and merciful to them that believe on him and keep his word, though

03:42:05.270 --> 03:42:09.150
goodness knows I'm unworthy of it. But if only the worthy ones got his

03:42:09.150 --> 03:42:13.270
blessings, and had his hand to help them over the rough places, there's

03:42:13.270 --> 03:42:17.410
few enough would smile here or ever enter into his rest when the long

03:42:17.410 --> 03:42:22.750
night comes. Go along, Sid, Mary, Tom. Take yourselves off. You've

03:42:22.750 --> 03:42:26.190
hindered me long enough.' The children left for school, and the old

03:42:26.190 --> 03:42:30.070
lady to call on Mrs. Harper and vanquish her realism with Tom's

03:42:30.070 --> 03:42:33.790
marvellous dream. Sid had better judgment than to utter the thought that

03:42:33.790 --> 03:42:36.870
was in his mind as he left the house. It was this—

03:42:36.870 --> 03:42:42.050
"'Pretty thin. As long as a dream is that. Without any mistakes in it.'

03:42:42.050 --> 03:42:46.230
What a hero Tom was become now! He did not go skipping and prancing, but

03:42:46.230 --> 03:42:50.210
moved with a dignified swagger as became a pirate who felt that the

03:42:50.210 --> 03:42:54.450
public eye was on him. And indeed it was. He tried not to seem to see

03:42:54.450 --> 03:42:58.330
the looks or hear the remarks as he passed along, but they were food

03:42:58.330 --> 03:43:02.650
and drink to him. Smaller boys than himself flocked at his heels as

03:43:02.650 --> 03:43:06.890
proud to be seen with him and tolerated by him, as if he had been the

03:43:06.890 --> 03:43:10.490
drummer at the head of a procession, or the elephant leading a menagerie

03:43:10.490 --> 03:43:14.590
into town. Boys of his own size pretended not to know he had been away

03:43:14.590 --> 03:43:18.690
at all, but they were consuming with envy nevertheless. They would have

03:43:18.690 --> 03:43:23.070
given anything to have had that swarthy sun-tanned skin of his, and his

03:43:23.070 --> 03:43:27.430
glittering notoriety, and Tom would not have parted with either for a

03:43:27.430 --> 03:43:32.310
circus. At school the children made so much of him and of Joe, and

03:43:32.310 --> 03:43:36.190
delivered such eloquent admiration from their eyes that the two heroes

03:43:36.190 --> 03:43:40.470
were not long in becoming insufferably stuck up. They began to tell

03:43:40.470 --> 03:43:44.530
their adventures to hungry listeners, but they only began, it was not a

03:43:44.530 --> 03:43:48.170
thing likely to have an end, with imaginations like theirs to furnish

03:43:48.170 --> 03:43:52.490
material. And finally, when they got out their pipes and went serenely

03:43:52.490 --> 03:43:57.330
puffing around, the very summit of glory was reached. Tom decided that

03:43:57.330 --> 03:44:01.810
he could be independent of Becky Thatcher now. Glory was sufficient. He

03:44:01.810 --> 03:44:06.390
would live for glory. Now that he was distinguished, maybe she would be

03:44:06.390 --> 03:44:11.290
wanting to make up. Well, let her. She should see that he could be as

03:44:11.290 --> 03:44:15.310
indifferent as some other people. Presently she arrived. Tom pretended

03:44:15.310 --> 03:44:18.690
not to see her. He moved away and joined a group of boys and girls and

03:44:18.690 --> 03:44:22.430
began to talk. Soon he observed that she was tripping gaily back and

03:44:22.430 --> 03:44:26.270
forth with flushed face and dancing eyes, pretending to be busy chasing

03:44:26.270 --> 03:44:30.410
schoolmates and screaming with laughter when she made a capture. But he

03:44:30.410 --> 03:44:34.550
noticed that she always made her captures in his vicinity, and that she

03:44:34.550 --> 03:44:39.310
seemed to cast a conscious eye in his direction at such times too. It

03:44:39.310 --> 03:44:43.250
gratified all the vicious vanity that was in him, and so, instead of

03:44:43.250 --> 03:44:47.190
winning him, it only set him up the more, and made him the more diligent

03:44:47.190 --> 03:44:51.610
to avoid betraying that he knew she was about. Presently she gave over

03:44:51.610 --> 03:44:55.830
to Tom, sky-larking, and moved irresolutely about, sighing once or

03:44:55.830 --> 03:45:00.410
twice and glancing furtively and wistfully toward Tom. Then she observed

03:45:00.410 --> 03:45:03.970
that now Tom was talking more particularly to Amy Lawrence than to

03:45:03.970 --> 03:45:07.990
any one else. She felt a sharp pang and grew disturbed and uneasy at

03:45:07.990 --> 03:45:12.170
once. She tried to go away, but her feet were treacherous, and carried

03:45:12.170 --> 03:45:16.070
her to the group instead. She said to a girl almost at Tom's elbow with

03:45:16.070 --> 03:45:16.990
sham vivacity,

03:45:16.990 --> 03:45:21.210
Why, Mary Austin, you bad girl, why didn't you come to Sunday school?

03:45:21.690 --> 03:45:26.810
I did come, didn't you see me? Why, no, did you? Where did you sit? I

03:45:26.810 --> 03:45:29.910
was in Miss Peter's class, where I always go. I saw you.

03:45:30.270 --> 03:45:34.470
Did you? Why, it's funny, I didn't see you. I wanted to tell you about

03:45:34.470 --> 03:45:34.890
the picnic.

03:45:35.470 --> 03:45:39.190
Oh, that's jolly, who's going to give it? My ma's going to let me have

03:45:39.190 --> 03:45:44.150
one. Oh, goody, I hope she'll let me come. Well, she will. The picnic's

03:45:44.150 --> 03:45:48.670
for me. She'll let anybody come that I want, and I want you. That's

03:45:48.670 --> 03:45:50.550
ever so nice. When is it going to be?

03:45:50.930 --> 03:45:52.970
By and by. Maybe about vacation.

03:45:53.710 --> 03:45:56.850
Oh, won't it be fun? You going to have all the girls and boys?

03:45:57.450 --> 03:46:01.350
Yes, every one that's friends to me, or wants to be. And she glanced

03:46:01.350 --> 03:46:04.970
ever so furtively at Tom. But he talked right along to Amy Lawrence

03:46:04.970 --> 03:46:08.510
about the terrible storm on the island, and how the lightning tore the

03:46:08.510 --> 03:46:12.610
great sycamore tree all to flinders while he was standing within three

03:46:12.610 --> 03:46:13.150
feet of it.

03:46:13.150 --> 03:46:18.470
Oh, may I come? said Gracie Miller. Yes. And me? said Sally Rogers.

03:46:18.770 --> 03:46:23.370
Yes. And me too? said Susy Harper. And Joe? Yes.

03:46:23.890 --> 03:46:27.490
And so on, with clapping of joyful hands till all the group had begged

03:46:27.490 --> 03:46:32.050
for invitations but Tom and Amy. Then Tom turned coolly away, still

03:46:32.050 --> 03:46:36.850
talking, and took Amy with him. Becky's lips trembled, and the tears

03:46:36.850 --> 03:46:41.530
came to her eyes. She hid these signs with a forced deity and went on

03:46:41.530 --> 03:46:45.030
chattering, but the life had gone out of the picnic now, and out of

03:46:45.030 --> 03:46:48.930
everything else. She got away as soon as she could, and hid herself,

03:46:48.970 --> 03:46:53.690
and had what her sex called a good cry. Then she sat moody with wounded

03:46:53.690 --> 03:46:58.130
pride till the bell rang. She roused up now with a vindictive cast in

03:46:58.130 --> 03:47:02.530
her eye, and gave her plaited tails a shake, and said she knew what

03:47:02.530 --> 03:47:03.090
she'd do.

03:47:03.550 --> 03:47:08.770
At recess Tom continued his flirtation with Amy with jubilant self-satisfaction,

03:47:08.770 --> 03:47:13.130
and he kept drifting about to find Becky and lacerate her with a

03:47:13.130 --> 03:47:16.950
performance. At last he spied her, but there was a sudden falling of

03:47:16.950 --> 03:47:20.790
his mercury. She was sitting cosily on a little bench behind the

03:47:20.790 --> 03:47:24.050
schoolhouse looking at a picture book with Alfred Temple, and so

03:47:24.050 --> 03:47:27.330
absorbed were they, and their heads so close together over the book

03:47:27.330 --> 03:47:30.690
that they did not seem to be conscious of anything in the world besides.

03:47:31.390 --> 03:47:35.530
Jealousy ran red hot through Tom's veins. He began to hate himself for

03:47:35.530 --> 03:47:38.810
throwing away the chance Becky had offered for a reconciliation. He

03:47:38.810 --> 03:47:42.290
called himself a fool, and all the hard names he could think of. He

03:47:42.290 --> 03:47:46.350
wanted to cry with vexation. Amy chatted happily along as they walked,

03:47:46.390 --> 03:47:50.670
for her heart was singing, but Tom's tongue had lost its function. He

03:47:50.670 --> 03:47:54.230
did not hear what Amy was saying, and whenever she paused expectantly

03:47:54.230 --> 03:47:58.230
he could only stammer an awkward ascent, which was as often misplaced

03:47:58.230 --> 03:48:02.450
as otherwise. He kept drifting to the rear of the schoolhouse again and

03:48:02.450 --> 03:48:06.810
to sear his eyeballs with a hateful spectacle there. He could not help

03:48:06.810 --> 03:48:10.610
it, and it maddened him to see, as he thought he saw, that Becky

03:48:10.610 --> 03:48:13.910
Thatcher never once suspected that he was even in the land of the

03:48:13.910 --> 03:48:17.990
living. But she did see, nevertheless, and she knew she was winning

03:48:17.990 --> 03:48:22.210
her fight, too, and was glad to see him suffer as she had suffered.

03:48:23.010 --> 03:48:27.290
Amy's happy prattle became intolerable. Tom hinted at things he had to

03:48:27.290 --> 03:48:31.510
attend to, things that must be done, and time was fleeting. But in vain

03:48:31.510 --> 03:48:36.150
the girl chirped on. Tom thought, Oh, hang her! Ain't I ever going to

03:48:36.150 --> 03:48:40.090
get rid of her? At last he must be attending to those things, and she

03:48:40.090 --> 03:48:44.250
said artlessly that she would be around when school left out, and he

03:48:44.250 --> 03:48:45.910
hastened away, hating her for it.

03:48:46.590 --> 03:48:51.030
Any other boy, Tom thought, grating his teeth. Any boy in the whole

03:48:51.030 --> 03:48:55.690
town but that St. Louis smarty that thinks he dresses so fine and is

03:48:55.690 --> 03:48:59.390
aristocracy. Oh, all right, I licked you the first day you ever saw

03:48:59.390 --> 03:49:02.950
this town, mister, and I'll lick you again. You just wait till I catch

03:49:02.950 --> 03:49:04.810
you out. I'll just take and—

03:49:04.810 --> 03:49:07.950
And he went through the motions of thrashing an imaginary boy, pummeling

03:49:07.950 --> 03:49:11.270
the air and kicking and gouging. Oh, you do, do you? You holler enough,

03:49:11.290 --> 03:49:13.470
do you? Now, then, let that learn you.

03:49:13.710 --> 03:49:17.430
And so the imaginary flogging was finished to his satisfaction. Tom

03:49:17.430 --> 03:49:21.350
fled home at noon. His conscience could not endure any more of Amy's

03:49:21.350 --> 03:49:24.830
grateful happiness, and his jealousy could bear no more of the other

03:49:24.830 --> 03:49:25.310
distress.

03:49:25.310 --> 03:49:29.450
Becky resumed her picture inspections with Alfred, but as the minutes

03:49:29.450 --> 03:49:34.350
dragged along and no Tom came to suffer, her triumph began to cloud, and

03:49:34.350 --> 03:49:39.230
she lost interest. Gravity and absent-mindedness followed, and then

03:49:39.230 --> 03:49:43.490
melancholy. Two or three times she pricked up her ear at a footstep, but

03:49:43.490 --> 03:49:48.670
it was a false hope. No Tom came. At last she grew entirely miserable and

03:49:48.670 --> 03:49:53.030
wished she hadn't carried it so far. When poor Alfred seemed that he was

03:49:53.030 --> 03:49:56.410
losing her—he did not know how—kept exclaiming,

03:49:56.730 --> 03:50:00.790
"'Oh, here's a jolly one! Look at this!' She lost patience at last and

03:50:00.790 --> 03:50:05.030
said, "'Oh, don't bother me! I don't care for them!' and burst into

03:50:05.030 --> 03:50:09.010
tears and got up and walked away. Alfred dropped alongside and was going

03:50:09.010 --> 03:50:12.510
to try to comfort her, but she said, "'Go away and leave me alone, can't

03:50:12.510 --> 03:50:16.810
you? I hate you!' So the boy halted, wondering what he could have done,

03:50:16.970 --> 03:50:20.010
for she had said she would look at pictures all through the nooning,

03:50:20.010 --> 03:50:24.150
and she walked on crying. Then Alfred went musing into the deserted

03:50:24.150 --> 03:50:28.810
schoolhouse. He was humiliated and angry. He easily guessed his way to

03:50:28.810 --> 03:50:32.910
the truth. The girl had simply made a convenience of him, to vent her

03:50:32.910 --> 03:50:37.750
spite upon Tom Sawyer. He was far from hating Tom the Less, when this

03:50:37.750 --> 03:50:40.910
thought occurred to him. He wished there was some way to get that boy

03:50:40.910 --> 03:50:44.530
into trouble without much risk to himself. Tom's spelling-book fell

03:50:44.530 --> 03:50:48.830
under his eye. Here was his opportunity. He gratefully opened to the

03:50:48.830 --> 03:50:52.830
lesson for the afternoon and poured ink upon the page. Becky, glancing

03:50:52.830 --> 03:50:56.330
in at a window behind him at the moment, saw the act and moved on

03:50:56.330 --> 03:51:00.610
without discovering herself. She started homeward now, intending to

03:51:00.610 --> 03:51:04.110
find Tom and tell him. Tom would be thankful and their troubles would

03:51:04.110 --> 03:51:08.150
be healed. Before she was half-way home, however, she had changed her

03:51:08.150 --> 03:51:11.610
mind. The thought of Tom's treatment of her when she was talking about

03:51:11.610 --> 03:51:15.370
her picnic came scorching back and filled her with shame. She resolved

03:51:15.370 --> 03:51:18.950
to let him get whipped on the damaged spelling-book's account and to

03:51:18.950 --> 03:51:20.890
hate him forever into the bargain.

03:51:24.910 --> 03:51:25.990
CHAPTER XIX.

03:51:26.430 --> 03:51:27.410
THE CRUELTY OF

03:51:27.410 --> 03:51:28.660
I DIDN'T THINK.

03:51:30.230 --> 03:51:33.870
Tom arrived at home in a dreary mood, and the first thing his aunt

03:51:33.870 --> 03:51:37.030
said to him showed him that he had brought his sorrows to an

03:51:37.030 --> 03:51:37.990
unpromising market.

03:51:38.450 --> 03:51:40.810
Tom, I have a notion to skin you alive.

03:51:41.530 --> 03:51:42.650
Auntie, what have I done?

03:51:42.650 --> 03:51:47.410
Well, you've done enough. Here I go over to Serenity Harper, like an

03:51:47.410 --> 03:51:50.510
old softie, expecting I'm going to make her believe all that rubbish

03:51:50.510 --> 03:51:54.970
about that dream, when, lo and behold you, she'd found out from Joe

03:51:54.970 --> 03:51:58.710
that you was over here and heard all the talk we had that night. Tom,

03:51:58.770 --> 03:52:02.110
I don't know what is to become of a boy that will act like that. It

03:52:02.110 --> 03:52:05.470
makes me feel so bad to think that you could let me go to Serenity

03:52:05.470 --> 03:52:08.470
Harper and make such a fool of myself and never say a word.

03:52:09.050 --> 03:52:12.630
This was a new aspect of the thing. His smartness of the morning had

03:52:12.630 --> 03:52:16.150
seemed to Tom a good joke before, and very ingenious. It merely

03:52:16.150 --> 03:52:20.090
looked mean and shabby now. He hung his head and could not think of

03:52:20.090 --> 03:52:22.150
anything to say for a moment. Then he said,

03:52:23.010 --> 03:52:27.130
Auntie, I wished I hadn't done it, but I didn't think.

03:52:27.790 --> 03:52:31.650
Oh, child, you never think. You never think of anything but your own

03:52:31.650 --> 03:52:34.930
selfishness. You could think to come all the way over here from

03:52:34.930 --> 03:52:38.610
Jackson's Island in the night to laugh at our troubles, and you could

03:52:38.610 --> 03:52:42.170
think to fool me with a lie about a dream. But you could never think to

03:52:42.170 --> 03:52:43.890
pity us and save us from sorrow.

03:52:44.750 --> 03:52:48.790
Auntie, I know now it was mean, but I didn't mean it to be mean. I

03:52:48.790 --> 03:52:52.230
didn't honest. And besides, I didn't come over here to laugh at you

03:52:52.230 --> 03:52:56.090
that night. What did you come for, then? It was to tell you not to be

03:52:56.090 --> 03:53:01.110
uneasy about us, because we hadn't got drowned. Tom, Tom, I would be

03:53:01.110 --> 03:53:04.390
the thankfulest soul in this world if I could believe you ever had as

03:53:04.390 --> 03:53:08.590
good a thought as that. But you know you never did, and I know it, Tom.

03:53:08.590 --> 03:53:13.690
Indeed, indeed, I did, Auntie. I wish I may never stir if I didn't. Oh,

03:53:13.830 --> 03:53:17.070
Tom, don't lie. Don't do it. It only makes things a hundred times

03:53:17.070 --> 03:53:20.830
worse. It ain't a lie, Auntie. It's the truth. I wanted to keep you from

03:53:20.830 --> 03:53:25.190
grieving. That was all that made me come. I'd give the whole world to

03:53:25.190 --> 03:53:29.810
believe that. It would cover up a power of sins, Tom. I'd most be

03:53:29.810 --> 03:53:34.610
glad you'd run off and acted so bad. But it ain't reasonable, because

03:53:34.610 --> 03:53:39.730
why didn't you tell me, child? Why, you see, when you got to talking

03:53:39.730 --> 03:53:43.450
about the funeral, I just got all full of the idea of our coming and

03:53:43.450 --> 03:53:47.110
hiding in the church, and I couldn't somehow bear to spoil it. So I

03:53:47.110 --> 03:53:49.770
just put the bark back in my pocket and kept mum.

03:53:50.470 --> 03:53:54.870
What bark? The bark I wrote on to tell you we'd gone pirating. I wished

03:53:54.870 --> 03:53:59.150
now you'd waked up. When I kissed you, I do honest. The hard lines in

03:53:59.150 --> 03:54:02.750
his aunt's face relaxed, and a sudden tenderness dawned in her eyes.

03:54:02.750 --> 03:54:09.130
Did you kiss me, Tom? Why, yes, I did. Are you sure you did, Tom? Why,

03:54:09.130 --> 03:54:13.870
yes, I did, Auntie, certain sure. What did you kiss me for, Tom? Because

03:54:13.870 --> 03:54:18.330
I loved you so, and you laid there moaning, and I was so sorry. The

03:54:18.330 --> 03:54:21.630
words sounded like truth. The old lady could not hide a tremor in her

03:54:21.630 --> 03:54:22.490
voice when she said,

03:54:22.970 --> 03:54:27.110
"'Kiss me again, Tom, and be off with you to school now, and don't

03:54:27.110 --> 03:54:31.250
bother me any more.' The moment he was gone she ran to a closet and got

03:54:31.250 --> 03:54:35.250
out the ruin of a jacket which Tom had gone pirating in. Then she

03:54:35.250 --> 03:54:37.470
stopped with it in her hand and said to herself,

03:54:38.090 --> 03:54:43.090
"'No, I don't dare.' Poor boy, I reckon he'd lied about it. But it's a

03:54:43.090 --> 03:54:47.090
blessed, blessed lie. There's such a comfort come from it. I hope the

03:54:47.090 --> 03:54:50.650
Lord I know the Lord will forgive him, because it was such good-heartedness

03:54:50.650 --> 03:54:54.670
in him to tell it. But I don't want to find out it's a lie. I won't look.'

03:54:55.210 --> 03:54:59.230
She put the jacket away and stood by, musing a minute. Twice she put out

03:54:59.230 --> 03:55:03.310
her hand to take the garment again, and twice she refrained. Once more

03:55:03.310 --> 03:55:05.890
she ventured, and this time she fortified herself with a thought,

03:55:06.150 --> 03:55:11.350
"'It's a good lie. It's a good lie. I won't let it grieve me.' So she

03:55:11.350 --> 03:55:15.130
sought the jacket pocket. A moment later she was reading Tom's piece of

03:55:15.130 --> 03:55:16.770
bark through the flowing tears and saying,

03:55:17.390 --> 03:55:21.310
"'I forgive the boy now, if he'd committed a million sins.'

03:55:26.490 --> 03:55:29.650
CHAPTER XX. Tom takes Becky's punishment.

03:55:30.750 --> 03:55:33.770
There was something about Aunt Polly's manner when she kissed Tom that

03:55:33.770 --> 03:55:37.130
swept away his low spirits and made him light-hearted and happy again.

03:55:37.450 --> 03:55:41.110
He started to school and had the luck of coming upon Becky Thatcher at

03:55:41.110 --> 03:55:45.550
the head of Meadow Lane. His mood always determined his manner. Without

03:55:45.550 --> 03:55:47.430
a moment's hesitation he ran to her and said,

03:55:47.430 --> 03:55:52.170
"'I acted mighty mean today, Becky, and I'm so sorry. I won't ever,

03:55:52.170 --> 03:55:55.750
ever do that way again. As long as I ever live, please make up, won't

03:55:55.750 --> 03:55:59.190
you?' The girl stopped and looked at him scornfully in the face.

03:55:59.630 --> 03:56:03.770
"'I'll thank you to keep yourself to yourself, Mr. Thomas Sawyer. I'll

03:56:03.770 --> 03:56:08.430
never speak to you again.' She tossed her head and passed on. Tom was so

03:56:08.430 --> 03:56:10.910
stunned that he had not even presence of mind enough to say,

03:56:11.150 --> 03:56:14.770
"'Who cares, Miss Smarty?' until the right time to say it had gone by.

03:56:14.770 --> 03:56:19.510
So he said nothing. But he was in a fine rage, nevertheless. He moped

03:56:19.510 --> 03:56:22.810
into the schoolyard wishing she were a boy and imagining how he would

03:56:22.810 --> 03:56:26.390
trounce her if she were. He presently encountered her and delivered a

03:56:26.390 --> 03:56:30.250
stinging remark as he passed. She hurled one in return and the angry

03:56:30.250 --> 03:56:34.310
breach was complete. It seemed to Becky, in her hot resentment, that she

03:56:34.310 --> 03:56:37.910
could hardly wait for school to take in. She was so impatient to see Tom

03:56:37.910 --> 03:56:41.530
flogged for the injured spelling-book. If she had had any lingering

03:56:41.530 --> 03:56:45.770
notion of exposing to Alfred Temple, Tom's offensive fling had driven it

03:56:45.770 --> 03:56:50.590
entirely away. Poor girl! She did not know how fast she was nearing

03:56:50.590 --> 03:56:55.030
trouble herself. The master, Mr. Dobbins, had reached middle age with an

03:56:55.030 --> 03:56:59.670
unsatisfied ambition. The darling of his desires was to be a doctor, but

03:56:59.670 --> 03:57:02.730
poverty had decreed that he should be nothing higher than a village

03:57:02.730 --> 03:57:06.850
schoolmaster. Every day he took a mysterious book out of his desk and

03:57:06.850 --> 03:57:10.810
absorbed himself in it at times when no classes were reciting. He kept

03:57:10.810 --> 03:57:14.650
that book under lock and key. There was not an urchin in school, but was

03:57:14.650 --> 03:57:18.770
perishing to have a glimpse of it, but the chance never came. Every boy

03:57:18.770 --> 03:57:22.330
and girl had a theory about the nature of that book, but no two theories

03:57:22.330 --> 03:57:25.410
were alike, and there was no way of getting at the facts in the case.

03:57:25.790 --> 03:57:29.770
Now, as Becky was passing by the desk, which stood near the door, she

03:57:29.770 --> 03:57:33.570
noticed that the key was in the lock. It was a precious moment. She

03:57:33.570 --> 03:57:37.050
glanced around, found herself alone, and the next instant she had the

03:57:37.050 --> 03:57:40.710
book in her hands. The title page, Professor Somebody's Anatomy,

03:57:41.170 --> 03:57:44.370
carried no information to her mind, so she begun to turn the leaves.

03:57:44.830 --> 03:57:48.230
She came at once upon a handsomely engraved and colored frontispiece,

03:57:48.530 --> 03:57:53.010
a human figure, stark naked. At that moment a shadow fell on the page,

03:57:53.450 --> 03:57:56.630
and Tom Sawyer stepped in at the door and caught the glimpse of the

03:57:56.630 --> 03:58:00.750
picture. Becky snatched at the book to close it, and had the hard luck

03:58:00.750 --> 03:58:04.610
to tear the pictured plate half down the middle. She thrust the

03:58:04.610 --> 03:58:07.330
volumes into the desk, turned the key, and burst out crying with shame

03:58:07.330 --> 03:58:08.050
and vexation.

03:58:08.670 --> 03:58:12.250
Tom Sawyer, you are just as mean as you can be to sneak up on a person

03:58:12.250 --> 03:58:15.750
and look at what they're looking at. How could I know you was looking

03:58:15.750 --> 03:58:19.150
at anything? You ought to be ashamed of yourself, Tom Sawyer. You know

03:58:19.150 --> 03:58:22.610
you're going to tell on me, and I—I—what shall I do? What shall I

03:58:22.610 --> 03:58:25.910
do? I'll be whipped, and I never was whipped in school.

03:58:26.370 --> 03:58:28.050
Then she stamped her little foot and said,

03:58:28.330 --> 03:58:32.030
Be so mean if you want to. I know something that's going to happen.

03:58:32.030 --> 03:58:36.490
You just wait, and you'll see. Hateful, hateful, hateful! And she flung

03:58:36.490 --> 03:58:39.110
out of the house with a new explosion of crying.

03:58:39.870 --> 03:58:43.810
Tom stood still, rather flustered by this onslaught. Presently he said

03:58:43.810 --> 03:58:44.310
to himself,

03:58:44.910 --> 03:58:49.090
What a curious kind of a fool a girl is. Never been licked in school.

03:58:49.470 --> 03:58:53.310
Shucks! What's a licking? That's just like a girl. They're so thin

03:58:53.310 --> 03:58:57.010
skinned and chicken-hearted. Well, of course I ain't going to tell old

03:58:57.010 --> 03:58:59.990
Dobbins on this little fool, because there's other ways of getting

03:58:59.990 --> 03:59:04.870
on her that ain't so mean. But what of it? Old Dobbins will ask who it

03:59:04.870 --> 03:59:08.690
was tore his book. Nobody'll answer. Then he'll do just the way he

03:59:08.690 --> 03:59:12.410
always does—ask first one, then tether, and when he comes to the

03:59:12.410 --> 03:59:16.450
right girl he'll know it, without any telling. Girls' faces always tell

03:59:16.450 --> 03:59:20.930
on them. They ain't got any backbone. She'll get licked. Well, it's a

03:59:20.930 --> 03:59:24.010
kind of a tight place for Becky Thatcher, because there ain't any way

03:59:24.010 --> 03:59:27.530
out of it. Tom conned the thing a moment longer, and then added,

03:59:27.530 --> 03:59:31.950
All right, though. She'd like to see me in such a fix. Let her sweat it

03:59:31.950 --> 03:59:36.150
out. Tom joined the mob of skylarking scholars outside. In a few

03:59:36.150 --> 03:59:40.050
moments the master arrived, and school took in. Tom did not feel a

03:59:40.050 --> 03:59:43.170
strong interest in his studies. Every time he stole a glance at the

03:59:43.170 --> 03:59:46.590
girl's side of the room, Becky's face troubled him. Considering all

03:59:46.590 --> 03:59:50.150
things, he did not want to pity her, and yet it was all he could do to

03:59:50.150 --> 03:59:53.970
help it. He could get up no exaltation that was really worthy the name.

03:59:53.970 --> 03:59:57.810
Presently the spelling-book discovery was made, and Tom's mind was

03:59:57.810 --> 04:00:01.590
entirely full of his own matters for a while after that. Becky roused

04:00:01.590 --> 04:00:04.470
up from her lethargy of distress and showed good interest in the

04:00:04.470 --> 04:00:07.890
proceedings. She did not expect that Tom could get out of his trouble

04:00:07.890 --> 04:00:11.610
by denying that he spilt the ink on the book himself, and she was

04:00:11.610 --> 04:00:15.930
right. The denial only seemed to make the thing worse for Tom. Becky

04:00:15.930 --> 04:00:19.170
supposed she would be glad of that, and she tried to believe she was

04:00:19.170 --> 04:00:23.590
glad of it, but she found she was not certain. When the worst came to

04:00:23.590 --> 04:00:27.650
the worst, she had an impulse to get up and tell on Alfred Temple. But

04:00:27.650 --> 04:00:30.550
she made an effort, and forced herself to keep still.

04:00:30.810 --> 04:00:34.430
"'Because,' said she to herself, "'he'll tell about me tearing the

04:00:34.430 --> 04:00:39.410
book, sure.' I wouldn't say a word not to save his life." Tom took his

04:00:39.410 --> 04:00:43.410
whipping and went back to his seat, not at all broken-hearted, for he

04:00:43.410 --> 04:00:46.710
thought it was possible that he had unknowingly upset the ink on the

04:00:46.710 --> 04:00:50.550
spelling-book himself in some skylarking bout. He had denied it for

04:00:50.550 --> 04:00:54.510
Tom's sake, and because it was custom, and had stuck to the denial from

04:00:54.510 --> 04:00:58.890
principle. A whole hour drifted by, the master sat nodding in his

04:00:58.890 --> 04:01:02.830
throne, the air was drowsy with a hum of study. By and by Mr. Dobbins

04:01:02.830 --> 04:01:05.810
straightened himself up, yawned, and then unlocked his desk and reached

04:01:05.810 --> 04:01:09.470
for his book, but seemed undecided whether to take it out or leave it.

04:01:09.770 --> 04:01:13.230
Most of the pupils glanced up languidly, but there was two among them

04:01:13.230 --> 04:01:17.170
that watched his movements with intent eyes. Mr. Dobbins fingered his

04:01:17.170 --> 04:01:21.410
book absently for a while, then took it out and settled himself in his

04:01:21.410 --> 04:01:25.990
chair to read. Tom shot a glance at Becky. He had seen a hunted and

04:01:25.990 --> 04:01:29.230
helpless rabbit look as she did, with a gun levelled at its head.

04:01:29.670 --> 04:01:33.330
Instantly he forgot his quarrel with her. Quick, something must be done,

04:01:33.510 --> 04:01:36.730
done in a flash, too. But the very imminence of the emergency

04:01:36.730 --> 04:01:40.850
paralysed his invention. Good, he had an inspiration. He would run and

04:01:40.850 --> 04:01:44.590
snatch the book, spring through the door, and fly. But his resolution

04:01:44.590 --> 04:01:47.990
shook for one little instant, and the chance was lost. The master

04:01:47.990 --> 04:01:51.910
opened the volume. If Tom only had the wasted opportunity back again,

04:01:52.210 --> 04:01:56.290
too late. There was no help for Becky now, he said. The next moment

04:01:56.290 --> 04:02:01.070
the master faced the school. Every eye sank under his gaze. There was

04:02:01.070 --> 04:02:04.990
that in it which smote even the innocent with fear. There was silence

04:02:04.990 --> 04:02:09.150
while one might count ten. The master was gathering his wrath. Then he

04:02:09.150 --> 04:02:10.150
spoke,—

04:02:10.150 --> 04:02:16.250
"'Who tore this book?' There was not a sound. One could have heard a pin

04:02:16.250 --> 04:02:21.450
drop. The stillness continued. The master searched face after face for

04:02:21.450 --> 04:02:26.430
signs of guilt. "'Benjamin Rogers, did you tear this book?' A denial.

04:02:26.730 --> 04:02:32.390
Another pause. "'Joseph Harper, did you?' Another denial. Tom's

04:02:32.390 --> 04:02:35.750
uneasiness grew more and more intense into the slow torture of these

04:02:35.750 --> 04:02:39.670
proceedings. The master scanned the ranks of boys, considered a while,

04:02:39.850 --> 04:02:45.390
then turned to the girls. "'Amy Lawrence!' A shake of the head. "'Gracy

04:02:45.390 --> 04:02:51.450
Miller.' The same sign. "'Susan Harper, did you do this?' Another

04:02:51.450 --> 04:02:55.210
negative. The next girl was Becky Thatcher. Tom was trembling from head

04:02:55.210 --> 04:02:58.410
to foot, with excitement and a sense of hopelessness of the situation.

04:02:59.150 --> 04:03:02.510
"'Rebecca Thatcher!' Tom glanced at her face. It was white with terror.

04:03:02.510 --> 04:03:07.570
"'Did you tear—no, look me in the face!' Her hands rose in appeal.

04:03:08.070 --> 04:03:12.370
"'Did you tear this book?' A thought shot like lightning through Tom's

04:03:12.370 --> 04:03:16.430
brain. He sprang to his feet and shouted,—'I done it!' The school

04:03:16.430 --> 04:03:21.150
stared in perplexity at this incredible folly. Tom stood a moment to

04:03:21.150 --> 04:03:24.870
gather his dismembered faculties, and when he stepped forward to go to

04:03:24.870 --> 04:03:28.490
his punishment, the surprise, the gratitude, the adoration that shone

04:03:28.490 --> 04:03:32.610
upon him out of poor Becky's eyes, seemed pay enough for a hundred

04:03:32.610 --> 04:03:36.650
floggings. Inspired by the splendour of his own act, he took without an

04:03:36.650 --> 04:03:40.150
outcry the most merciless flaying that even Mr. Dobbins had ever

04:03:40.150 --> 04:03:44.190
administered, and also received with indifference the added cruelty of a

04:03:44.190 --> 04:03:48.490
command to remain two hours after school should be dismissed, for he

04:03:48.490 --> 04:03:52.570
knew who would wait for him outside till his captivity was done, and

04:03:52.570 --> 04:03:57.030
not count the tedious time as loss, either. Tom went to bed that night

04:03:57.030 --> 04:04:00.770
planning vengeance against Alfred Temple, for with shame and

04:04:00.770 --> 04:04:05.170
repentance Becky had told him all, not forgetting her own treachery,

04:04:05.470 --> 04:04:09.110
but even the longing for vengeance had to give way soon to pleasanter

04:04:09.110 --> 04:04:12.930
musings, and he fell asleep at last, with Becky's latest words

04:04:12.930 --> 04:04:18.310
lingering dreamily in his ear. Tom, how could you be so noble?

04:04:33.810 --> 04:04:35.450
CHAPTER XXI.

04:04:35.850 --> 04:04:39.570
ELEQUENCE AND THE MASTER'S GILLED DOME.

04:04:40.210 --> 04:04:45.650
Vacation was approaching. The schoolmaster, always severe, grew severer, and more exacting

04:04:45.650 --> 04:04:51.690
than ever, for he wanted the school to make a good showing on Examination Day. His rod

04:04:51.690 --> 04:04:58.110
and his ferrel were seldom idle now, at least among the smaller pupils. Only the biggest

04:04:58.110 --> 04:05:03.670
boys and young ladies of eighteen and twenty escaped lashing. Mr. Dobbin's lashings were

04:05:03.670 --> 04:05:09.030
very vigorous ones, too, for although he carried under his wig a perfectly bald and shiny head,

04:05:09.090 --> 04:05:14.130
he had only reached middle age, and there was no sign of feebleness in his muscle. As

04:05:14.130 --> 04:05:19.090
the great day approached, all the tyranny that was in him came to the surface. He seemed

04:05:19.090 --> 04:05:24.390
to take a vindictive pleasure in punishing the least shortcomings. The consequence was

04:05:24.390 --> 04:05:28.790
that the smaller boys spent their days in terror and suffering, and their nights in

04:05:28.790 --> 04:05:34.510
plotting revenge. They threw away no opportunity to do the master a mischief, but he kept ahead

04:05:34.510 --> 04:05:39.830
all the time. The retribution that followed every vengeful success was so sweeping and

04:05:39.830 --> 04:05:46.390
that the boys all was retired from the field, badly worsted. At last they conspired together

04:05:46.390 --> 04:05:52.130
and hit upon a plan that promised a dazzling victory. They swore in the sign-painter's

04:05:52.130 --> 04:05:57.410
boy, told him the scheme, and asked his help. He had his own reason for being delighted,

04:05:57.710 --> 04:06:02.530
for the master boarded in his father's family, and had given the boy ample cause to hate

04:06:02.530 --> 04:06:07.450
him. The master's wife would go on a visit to the country in a few days, and there would

04:06:07.450 --> 04:06:12.710
be nothing to interfere with the plan. The master always prepared himself for great occasions

04:06:12.710 --> 04:06:18.290
by getting pretty well-fuddled, and the sign-painter's boy said that when the domine had reached

04:06:18.290 --> 04:06:23.830
the proper condition on examination evening, he would manage the thing, while he napped

04:06:23.830 --> 04:06:28.830
in his chair. Then he would have him awakened at the right time, and hurried away to school.

04:06:29.530 --> 04:06:35.790
In the fullness of time the interesting occasion arrived. At eight in the evening the school-house

04:06:35.790 --> 04:06:40.690
was brilliantly lighted, and adorned with wreaths and festoons of foliage and flowers.

04:06:41.350 --> 04:06:46.090
The master sat throned in his great chair upon a raised platform with his blackboard

04:06:46.090 --> 04:06:52.470
behind him. He was looking tolerably mellow. Three rows of benches on each side, and six

04:06:52.470 --> 04:06:57.190
rows in front of him, were occupied by the dignitaries of the town, and by the parents

04:06:57.190 --> 04:07:03.050
of the pupils. To his left, back of the rows of citizens, was a spacious temporary platform

04:07:03.050 --> 04:07:07.790
upon which were seated the scholars, who were to take part in the exercises of the evening.

04:07:08.390 --> 04:07:13.950
Rows of small boys, washed and dressed to an intolerable state of discomfort, rows of

04:07:13.950 --> 04:07:20.410
gawky big boys, snow-banks of girls and young ladies clad in lawn and muslim and conspicuously

04:07:20.410 --> 04:07:25.990
conscious of their bare arms, their grandmothers' ancient trinkets, their bits of pink and blue

04:07:25.990 --> 04:07:31.510
ribbon, and the flowers in their hair. All the rest of the house was filled with non-participating

04:07:31.510 --> 04:07:37.710
scholars. The exercises began. A very little boy stood up and sheepishly recited,

04:07:38.050 --> 04:07:43.790
"'You'd scarce expect one of my age to speak in public on the stage,' etc., accompanying

04:07:43.790 --> 04:07:48.690
himself with the painfully exact and spasmodic gestures which a machine might have used,

04:07:49.110 --> 04:07:54.410
supposing the machine to be a trifle out of order. But he got through safely, though cruelly

04:07:54.410 --> 04:07:59.770
scared, and got a fine round of applause when he made his manufactured bow and retired.

04:07:59.770 --> 04:08:06.610
A little shame-faced girl lisp'd. Mary had a little lamb, etc., performed a compassion-inspired

04:08:06.610 --> 04:08:12.670
curtsy, got her mead of applause, and sat down flushed and happy. Tom Sawyer stepped

04:08:12.670 --> 04:08:18.010
forward with conceited confidence, and soared into the unquenchable and indestructible

04:08:18.010 --> 04:08:24.030
"'Give me liberty or give me death!' speech, with fine fury and frantic gesticulation,

04:08:24.350 --> 04:08:29.750
and broke down in the middle of it. A ghastly stage-fright seized him, his legs quaked under

04:08:29.750 --> 04:08:35.150
him, and he was like to choke. True, he had the manifest sympathy of the house, but he

04:08:35.150 --> 04:08:40.670
had the house's silence, too, which was even worse than its sympathy. The master frowned,

04:08:40.990 --> 04:08:46.010
and this completed the disaster. Tom struggled a while, and then retired utterly defeated.

04:08:46.450 --> 04:08:49.110
There was a weak attempt at applause, but it died early.

04:08:49.790 --> 04:08:58.250
The boy stood on the burning deck, followed. Also, the Assyrian came down—and other declamatory

04:08:58.250 --> 04:09:04.690
gems. Then there were reading exercises and a spelling-fight. The meagre Latin class recited

04:09:04.690 --> 04:09:10.410
with honour—the prime feature of the evening was in order now—original compositions by

04:09:10.410 --> 04:09:15.350
the young ladies. Each in her turn stepped forward to the edge of the platform, cleared

04:09:15.350 --> 04:09:20.790
her throat, held up her manuscript tied with dainty ribbon, and proceeded to read with

04:09:20.790 --> 04:09:27.710
laboured attention to expression and punctuation. The themes were the same that had been illuminated

04:09:27.710 --> 04:09:33.010
upon similar occasions by their mothers before them, their grandmothers, and doubtless all

04:09:33.010 --> 04:09:39.570
their ancestors in the female line clear back to the crusades. Friendship was one. Memories

04:09:39.570 --> 04:09:48.510
of other days. Religion in history. Dreamland. The advantages of culture. Forms of political

04:09:48.510 --> 04:09:57.910
government compared and contrasted. Melancholy. Filial love. Heart longings, etc., etc. A

04:09:57.910 --> 04:10:03.290
prevalent feature in these compositions was a nursed and petted melancholy. Another was

04:10:03.290 --> 04:10:10.270
a wasteful and opulent gush of fine language. Another was a tendency to lug in by the ears

04:10:10.270 --> 04:10:15.930
particularly prized words and phrases until they were worn entirely out, and a peculiarity

04:10:15.930 --> 04:10:21.270
that conspicuously marked and marred them was the inveterate and intolerable sermon

04:10:21.270 --> 04:10:26.350
that wagged its crippled tail at the end of each and every one of them. No matter what

04:10:26.350 --> 04:10:31.090
the subject might be, a brain-wracking effort was made to squirm it into some aspect or

04:10:31.090 --> 04:10:36.670
other that the moral and religious mind could contemplate with edification. The glaring

04:10:36.670 --> 04:10:41.430
insincerity of these sermons was not sufficient to compass the banishment of the fashion from

04:10:41.430 --> 04:10:46.690
the schools, and it is not sufficient today. It never will be sufficient while the world

04:10:46.690 --> 04:10:51.990
stands perhaps. There is no school in all our land where the young ladies do not feel

04:10:51.990 --> 04:10:57.070
obliged to close their compositions with a sermon, and you will find that the sermon

04:10:57.070 --> 04:11:02.190
of the most frivolous and the least religious girl in the school is always the longest and

04:11:02.190 --> 04:11:08.250
the most relentlessly pious. But enough of this. Homely truth is unpalatable.

04:11:08.250 --> 04:11:14.490
Let us return to the examination. The first composition that was read was one entitled—Is

04:11:15.230 --> 04:11:21.850
this, then, life? Perhaps the reader can endure and extract from it. In the

04:11:21.850 --> 04:11:27.290
common walks of life, with what delightful emotions does the youthful mind look forward to some

04:11:27.290 --> 04:11:33.330
anticipated scene of festivity? Imagination is busy sketching rose-tinted pictures of

04:11:33.330 --> 04:11:40.010
joy. In fancy the voluptuous rotary of fashion sees herself amid the festive throng, the

04:11:40.010 --> 04:11:45.790
observed of all observers. Her graceful form, arrayed in snowy robes, is whirling through

04:11:45.790 --> 04:11:51.210
the mazes of the joyous dance. Her eye is brightest. Her step is lightest in the gay

04:11:51.210 --> 04:11:57.670
assembly. In such delicious fancies time quickly glides by, and the welcome hour arrives for

04:11:57.670 --> 04:12:03.490
her entrance into the Elysian world, of which she has had such bright dreams. How fairy-like

04:12:03.490 --> 04:12:08.930
does everything appear to her enchanted vision? Each new scene is more charming than the last,

04:12:09.350 --> 04:12:15.130
but after a while she finds that beneath this goodly exterior all is vanity. The flattery

04:12:15.130 --> 04:12:21.190
which once charmed her soul now grates harshly upon her ear. The ballroom has lost its charms,

04:12:21.590 --> 04:12:26.630
and with wasted health and embittered heart she turns away with a conviction that earthly

04:12:26.630 --> 04:12:32.430
pleasures cannot satisfy the longings of the soul, and so forth and so on. There was

04:12:32.430 --> 04:12:36.450
a buzz of gratification from time to time during the reading, accompanied by whispered

04:12:36.450 --> 04:12:42.950
ejaculations of how sweet, how eloquent, so true, etc., and after the thing had closed

04:12:42.950 --> 04:12:49.670
with a peculiarly afflicting sermon the applause was enthusiastic. Then arose a slight melancholy

04:12:49.670 --> 04:12:56.590
girl, whose face had the interesting paleness that comes of pills and indigestion, and read

04:12:56.590 --> 04:12:59.390
a poem. Two stanzas of it will do.

04:12:59.890 --> 04:13:02.950
A Missouri Maiden's Farewell to Alabama

04:13:03.790 --> 04:13:10.310
Alabama, good-bye! I love thee well, but yet for a while do I leave thee now. Sad, yes,

04:13:10.470 --> 04:13:16.150
sad thoughts of thee my heart to swell, and burning recollections throng my brow, for

04:13:16.150 --> 04:13:21.590
I have wandered through thy flowery woods, have roamed and read near Talapusa's stream,

04:13:21.930 --> 04:13:28.990
have listened to Talasea's warring floods, and wooed on Cusa's side Aurora's beam. Yet

04:13:28.990 --> 04:13:36.170
shame I not to bear an aweful heart, nor blush to turn behind my tearful eyes, tis from no

04:13:36.170 --> 04:13:43.390
stranger land I now must part, tis to no stranger's left I yield these sighs. Welcome and home

04:13:43.390 --> 04:13:49.410
were mine within this state, whose veils I leave, whose spires fade fast from me, and

04:13:49.410 --> 04:13:56.430
cold must be mine eyes, and heart and tete, when, dear Alabama, they turn cold on thee.

04:13:57.470 --> 04:14:03.230
There were very few there who knew what tete meant, but the poem was very satisfactory

04:14:03.230 --> 04:14:03.790
nevertheless.

04:14:04.550 --> 04:14:09.770
Next appeared a dark-complexion, black-eyed, black-haired young lady, who paused an impressive

04:14:09.770 --> 04:14:15.330
moment, assumed a tragic expression, and began to read in a measured, solemn tone.

04:14:15.990 --> 04:14:17.070
A vision!

04:14:18.210 --> 04:14:24.730
Dark and tempestuous was night. Around the throne on high not a single star quivered,

04:14:24.730 --> 04:14:30.090
but the deep intonations of the heavy thunder constantly vibrated upon the ear, whilst the

04:14:30.090 --> 04:14:39.750
terrific lightning reveled in angry mood through the cloudy chambers of heaven, seeming to

04:14:39.750 --> 04:14:45.450
Even the boisterous winds unanimously came forth from their mystic homes, and blustered

04:14:45.450 --> 04:14:52.050
about as if to enhance by their aid the wildness of the scene. At such a time so dark, so dreary,

04:14:52.370 --> 04:14:56.370
for human sympathy, my very spirit sighed, but instead thereof,

04:14:56.990 --> 04:15:03.130
My dearest friend, my counsellor, my comforter and guide, my joy in grief, my second bliss

04:15:03.130 --> 04:15:05.410
in joy, came to my side.

04:15:05.990 --> 04:15:11.590
She moved like one of those bright beings pictured in the sunny walks of fancies, Eden,

04:15:11.970 --> 04:15:17.790
by the romantic and young, a queen of beauty unadorned save by her own transcendent loveliness.

04:15:18.230 --> 04:15:24.450
So soft was her step, it failed to make even a sound, and but for the magical thrill imparted

04:15:24.450 --> 04:15:31.290
by her genial touch as other unobtrusive beauties, she would have glided away unperceived, unsought.

04:15:31.290 --> 04:15:37.270
A strange sadness rested upon her features, like icy tears upon the robe of December,

04:15:37.490 --> 04:15:42.710
as she pointed to the contending elements without and bad me contemplate the two beings

04:15:42.710 --> 04:15:43.290
presented.

04:15:44.390 --> 04:15:51.710
This nightmare occupied some ten pages of manuscript, and wound up with a sermon so

04:15:51.710 --> 04:15:58.810
destructive of all hope to non-Presbyterians that it took the first prize. This composition

04:15:58.810 --> 04:16:03.590
was considered to be the very finest effort of the evening. The Mayor of the village,

04:16:03.970 --> 04:16:08.890
in delivering the prize to the author of it, made a warm speech in which he said that it

04:16:08.890 --> 04:16:15.050
was by far the most eloquent thing he had ever listened to, and that Daniel Webster

04:16:15.050 --> 04:16:20.730
himself might well be proud of it. It may be remarked in passing that the number of

04:16:20.730 --> 04:16:26.310
compositions in which the word BEAUTIOUS was over-fondled, and human experience referred

04:16:26.310 --> 04:16:34.010
to as LIFE'S PAGES, was up to the usual average. Now the Master, mellow almost to the verge

04:16:34.010 --> 04:16:39.570
of geniality, put his chair aside, turned his back to the audience, and began to draw

04:16:39.570 --> 04:16:45.690
a map of America on the blackboard, to exercise the geography class upon. But he made a sad

04:16:45.690 --> 04:16:50.450
business of it, with his unsteady hand, and a smothered titter rippled over the house.

04:16:50.790 --> 04:16:56.110
He knew what the matter was, and set himself to write it. He sponged out lines and remade

04:16:56.110 --> 04:17:00.730
them, but he only distorted them more than ever, and the tittering was more pronounced.

04:17:01.170 --> 04:17:05.870
He threw his entire attention upon his work now, as if determined not to be put down by

04:17:05.870 --> 04:17:11.370
the mirth. He felt that all eyes were fastened upon him. He imagined he was succeeding, and

04:17:11.370 --> 04:17:16.870
yet the tittering continued. It even manifestly increased, and well it might. There was a

04:17:16.870 --> 04:17:21.950
garret above, pierced with a scuttle over his head, and down through this scuttle came

04:17:22.690 --> 04:17:27.870
suspended around the haunches by a string. She had a rag tied about her head and jaws

04:17:27.870 --> 04:17:33.010
to keep her from ewing. As she slowly descended she curved upward and clawed at the string.

04:17:33.430 --> 04:17:38.970
She swung downward and clawed at the intangible air. The tittering rose higher and higher.

04:17:39.230 --> 04:17:44.710
The cat was within six inches of the absorbed teacher's head, down, down, a little lower,

04:17:44.990 --> 04:17:49.770
and she grabbed his wig with her desperate claws, clung to it, and was snatched up into

04:17:49.770 --> 04:17:55.070
the garret in an instant with her trophy still in her possession. And how the light did blaze

04:17:55.070 --> 04:18:01.470
abroad from the master's bald pate, for the sign-painter's boy had gilded it! That broke

04:18:01.470 --> 04:18:05.810
up the meeting. The boys were avenged. Vacation had come.

04:18:07.170 --> 04:18:12.910
NOTE. The pretended compositions quoted in this chapter are taken without alteration

04:18:12.910 --> 04:18:20.170
from a volume entitled, PROS AND POETRY BY A WESTERN LADY. But they are exactly and precisely

04:18:20.170 --> 04:18:25.890
after the schoolgirl pattern, and hence are much happier than any mere imitations could

04:18:25.890 --> 04:18:26.390
be.

04:18:30.750 --> 04:18:38.530
CHAPTER XXII. Huck Finn quotes scriptures. Tom joined the new order of cadets of temperance,

04:18:38.530 --> 04:18:43.950
being attracted by the showy character of their regalia. He promised to abstain from

04:18:43.950 --> 04:18:49.590
smoking, chewing, and profanity, as long as he remained a member. Now he found out a new

04:18:50.270 --> 04:18:54.530
thing—namely, that to promise not to do a thing is the surest way in the world to

04:18:54.530 --> 04:19:00.310
make a body want to go and do that very thing. Tom soon found himself tormented with a desire

04:19:00.310 --> 04:19:05.330
to drink and swear. The desire grew to be so intense that nothing but the hope of a

04:19:05.330 --> 04:19:09.850
chance to display himself in his red sash kept him from withdrawing from the order.

04:19:10.650 --> 04:19:16.170
Fourth of July was coming, but he soon gave that up—gave it up before he had worn his

04:19:16.170 --> 04:19:21.410
shackles over forty-eight hours, and fixed his hopes upon old Judge Fraser, Justice of

04:19:21.410 --> 04:19:26.110
the Peace, who was apparently on his death-bed and would have a big public funeral, since

04:19:26.110 --> 04:19:31.310
he was so high and official. During three days Tom was deeply concerned about the judge's

04:19:31.310 --> 04:19:37.250
condition and hungry for news of it. Sometimes his hopes ran so high that he would venture

04:19:37.250 --> 04:19:42.550
to get out his regalia and practice before the looking-glass. But the judge had a most

04:19:42.550 --> 04:19:48.770
discouraging way of fluctuating. At last he was pronounced upon the mend, and then

04:19:48.770 --> 04:19:56.050
convalescent. Tom was disgusted, and felt a sense of injury, too. He handed in his resignation

04:19:56.050 --> 04:20:01.050
at once, and that night the judge suffered a relapse and died. Tom resolved that he would

04:20:01.050 --> 04:20:07.010
never trust a man like that again. The funeral was a fine thing—the cadets paraded in a

04:20:07.010 --> 04:20:12.910
style calculated to kill the late member with envy. Tom was a free boy again, however—there

04:20:12.910 --> 04:20:17.710
was something in that. He could drink and swear now, but found to his surprise that

04:20:17.710 --> 04:20:23.150
he did not want to. The simple fact that he could took the desire away and the charm of

04:20:23.150 --> 04:20:28.390
it. Tom presently wondered to find that his coveted vacation was beginning to hang a little

04:20:28.390 --> 04:20:34.210
heavily on his hands. He attempted a diary, but nothing happened during three days, and

04:20:34.210 --> 04:20:35.310
so he abandoned it.

04:20:35.530 --> 04:20:41.030
The first of all the negro minstrel shows came to town, and made a sensation. Tom and

04:20:41.030 --> 04:20:46.150
Joe Harper got up a band of performers and were happy for two days. Even the glorious

04:20:46.150 --> 04:20:51.850
fourth was in some sense a failure, for it rained hard, there was no procession in consequence,

04:20:52.130 --> 04:20:57.390
and the greatest man in the world, as Tom supposed, Mr. Benton, an actual United States

04:20:57.390 --> 04:21:03.150
senator, proved an overwhelming disappointment, for he was not twenty-five feet high, nor

04:21:03.150 --> 04:21:08.230
even anywhere in the neighborhood of it. A circus came, the boys played circus for three

04:21:08.230 --> 04:21:15.250
days afterward in tents made of rag-carpeting—admission, three pins for boys, two for girls, and then

04:21:15.250 --> 04:21:21.490
circusing was abandoned. A phrenologist and a mesmerizer came, and went again, and left

04:21:21.490 --> 04:21:26.050
the village duller and drearier than ever. There were some boys' and girls' parties,

04:21:26.050 --> 04:21:31.790
but they were so few and so delightful that they only made the aching voids between ache

04:21:31.790 --> 04:21:36.970
the harder. Becky Thatcher was gone to her Constantinople home to stay with her parents

04:21:36.970 --> 04:21:42.410
during vacation, so there was no bright side to life anywhere. The dreadful secret of the

04:21:42.410 --> 04:21:49.170
murder was a chronic misery. It was a very cancer for permanency and pain. Then came

04:21:49.170 --> 04:21:55.250
the measles. During two long weeks Tom lay a prisoner, dead to the world and its happenings.

04:21:55.570 --> 04:22:01.390
He was very ill. He was interested in nothing. When he got upon his feet at last and moved

04:22:01.390 --> 04:22:06.670
feebly downtown, a melancholy change had come over everything and every creature. There

04:22:06.670 --> 04:22:11.570
had been a revival, and everybody had got religion—not only the adults, but even the

04:22:11.570 --> 04:22:16.930
boys and girls. Tom went about hoping against hope for the sight of one blessed sinful face,

04:22:17.370 --> 04:22:21.890
but disappointment crossed him everywhere. He found Joe Harper studying a testament,

04:22:21.890 --> 04:22:27.230
and turned sadly away from the depressing spectacle. He sought Ben Rogers, and found

04:22:27.230 --> 04:22:32.670
him visiting the poor with a basket of tracts. He handed up Jim Hollis, who called his attention

04:22:32.670 --> 04:22:37.970
to the precious blessing of his late measles as a warning. Every boy he encountered added

04:22:37.970 --> 04:22:43.170
another ton to his depression, and when, in desperation, he flew for refuge at last to

04:22:43.170 --> 04:22:48.450
the bosom of Huckleberry Finn and was received with a scriptural quotation, his heart broke,

04:22:48.450 --> 04:22:55.290
and he crept home and to bed, realizing that he alone of all the town was lost forever and forever.

04:22:56.050 --> 04:23:00.570
And that night there came on a terrific storm, with driving rain, awful claps of thunder,

04:23:00.650 --> 04:23:05.290
and blinding sheets of lightning. He covered his head with his bedclothes and waited in a horror

04:23:05.290 --> 04:23:10.930
of suspense for his doom, for he had not the shadow of a doubt that all this hubbub was about

04:23:10.930 --> 04:23:16.190
him. He believed he had taxed the forbearance of the powers above to the extremity of endurance,

04:23:16.190 --> 04:23:21.370
and that this was the result. It might have seemed to him a waste of pomp and ammunition

04:23:21.370 --> 04:23:25.650
to kill a bug with a battery of artillery, but there seemed nothing incongruous about

04:23:25.650 --> 04:23:31.790
the getting up such an expensive thunderstorm as this to knock the turf from under an insect

04:23:31.790 --> 04:23:37.650
like himself. By and by the tempest spent itself and died without accomplishing its object.

04:23:37.990 --> 04:23:44.030
The boy's first impulse was to be grateful and reform. His second was to wait, for there might

04:23:44.030 --> 04:23:51.330
be no more storms. The next day the doctors were back. Tom had relapsed. The three weeks he spent

04:23:51.330 --> 04:23:57.330
on his back this time seemed an entire age. When he got abroad at last, he was hardly grateful

04:23:57.330 --> 04:24:03.070
that he had been spared, remembering how lonely was his estate, how companionless and forlorn he

04:24:03.070 --> 04:24:09.030
was. He drifted listlessly down the street and found Jim Hollis acting as judge in a juvenile

04:24:09.030 --> 04:24:15.270
court that was trying a cat for murder, in the presence of her victim, a bird. He found Joe

04:24:15.270 --> 04:24:22.270
Harper and Huck Finn up an alley eating a stolen melon. Poor lads! They, like Tom, had suffered a

04:24:22.270 --> 04:24:25.190
relapse. CHAPTER XXII.

04:24:26.910 --> 04:24:30.490
CHAPTER XXIII. The Salvation of Muff Potter.

04:24:31.450 --> 04:24:36.990
At last the sleepy atmosphere was stirred, and vigorously, the murder trial came on in the court.

04:24:36.990 --> 04:24:42.550
It became the absorbing topic of village talk immediately. Tom could not get away from it.

04:24:42.890 --> 04:24:47.990
Every reference to the murder sent a shudder to his heart, for his troubled conscience and fears

04:24:47.990 --> 04:24:53.770
almost persuaded him that these remarks were put forth in his hearing as feelers. He did not see

04:24:53.770 --> 04:24:58.610
how he could be suspected of knowing anything about the murder, but still he could not be

04:24:58.610 --> 04:25:03.470
comfortable in the midst of this gossip. It kept him in a cold shiver all the time.

04:25:03.470 --> 04:25:09.270
He took Huck to a lonely place to have a talk with him. It would be some relief to unseal his

04:25:09.270 --> 04:25:14.070
tongue for a little while, to divide his burden of distress with another sufferer. Moreover,

04:25:14.210 --> 04:25:17.570
he wanted to assure himself that Huck had remained discreet.

04:25:17.970 --> 04:25:21.870
Huck, have you ever told anybody about—that?

04:25:22.530 --> 04:25:23.330
About what?

04:25:23.970 --> 04:25:24.790
You know what?

04:25:25.430 --> 04:25:27.390
Oh, course I haven't.

04:25:27.710 --> 04:25:28.430
Never a word?

04:25:29.330 --> 04:25:32.530
Never a solitary word, so help me. What makes you ask?

04:25:32.530 --> 04:25:34.590
Well, I was afeard.

04:25:35.090 --> 04:25:40.590
Why, Tom Sawyer, we wouldn't be alive two days if that got found out. You know that.

04:25:40.950 --> 04:25:42.250
Tom felt more comfortable.

04:25:42.890 --> 04:25:43.730
After a pause.

04:25:44.290 --> 04:25:47.850
Huck, they couldn't anybody get you to tell, could they?

04:25:48.770 --> 04:25:53.210
Get me to tell? Why, if I wanted that half-breed devil to drown me,

04:25:53.210 --> 04:25:56.010
they could get me to tell. They ain't no different way.

04:25:56.790 --> 04:26:00.570
Well, that's all right, then. I reckon we're safe as long as we keep Mum.

04:26:00.570 --> 04:26:03.190
But let's swear again, anyway. It's more sure.

04:26:03.770 --> 04:26:04.590
I'm agreed.

04:26:05.050 --> 04:26:07.370
So they swore again, with dread solemnities.

04:26:07.770 --> 04:26:11.030
What is the talk around, Huck? I've heard a power of it.

04:26:11.330 --> 04:26:15.370
Talk? Well, it's just Muff Potter, Muff Potter, Muff Potter all the time.

04:26:15.510 --> 04:26:19.490
It keeps me in a sweat, constant, so as I want to hide somewheres.

04:26:19.750 --> 04:26:23.810
That's just the same way they go on round me. I reckon he's a goner.

04:26:23.950 --> 04:26:25.670
Don't you feel sorry for him sometimes?

04:26:26.350 --> 04:26:29.750
Most always, most always. He ain't no account. But

04:26:29.750 --> 04:26:33.690
then he ain't ever done anything to hurt anybody. Just fishes a little,

04:26:33.910 --> 04:26:37.350
to get money to get drunk on, and loess around considerable.

04:26:37.950 --> 04:26:42.750
But, Lord, we all do that. Least ways most of us. Preachers and such like.

04:26:43.330 --> 04:26:47.630
But he's kind of good. He give me half a fish once, when there weren't

04:26:47.630 --> 04:26:52.190
enough for two. And lots of times he's kind of stood by me when I was

04:26:52.190 --> 04:26:56.570
out of luck. Well, he's mended kites for me, Huck, and knitted hooks

04:26:56.570 --> 04:26:59.390
onto my line. I wish we could get him out of there.

04:26:59.850 --> 04:27:04.630
My, we couldn't get him out, Tom. And besides, to do any good, they'd

04:27:04.630 --> 04:27:05.330
catch him again.

04:27:05.550 --> 04:27:09.730
Yes, so they would. But I hate to hear him abuse him so like the

04:27:09.730 --> 04:27:12.150
Dickens, when he never done that.

04:27:12.870 --> 04:27:16.930
I do too, Tom. Lord, I hear him say he's the bloodiest-looking villain

04:27:16.930 --> 04:27:21.210
in this country, and they wonder he wasn't ever hung before. Yes, they

04:27:21.210 --> 04:27:25.410
talk like that all the time. I've heard him say that if he was to get

04:27:25.410 --> 04:27:28.230
free they'd lynch him. And they do it too.

04:27:28.770 --> 04:27:32.330
The boys had a long talk, but it brought them little comfort. As the

04:27:32.330 --> 04:27:35.010
twilight drew on, they found themselves hanging about the neighborhood

04:27:35.010 --> 04:27:38.970
of the little isolated jail, perhaps with an undefined hope that

04:27:38.970 --> 04:27:42.390
something would happen that might clear away their difficulties. But

04:27:42.390 --> 04:27:46.130
nothing happened. There seemed to be no angels or fairies interested in

04:27:46.130 --> 04:27:47.450
this luckless captive.

04:27:48.130 --> 04:27:51.890
The boys did as they had often done before. Went to the cell grating

04:27:51.890 --> 04:27:55.770
and gave Potter some tobacco and matches. He was on the ground floor,

04:27:55.810 --> 04:27:59.710
and there were no guards. His gratitude for their gifts had always

04:27:59.710 --> 04:28:03.990
smote their conscience before. It cut deeper than ever this time. They

04:28:03.990 --> 04:28:07.090
felt cowardly and treacherous to the last degree when Potter said,

04:28:07.330 --> 04:28:11.370
You've been mighty good to me, boys. Better than anybody else in this

04:28:11.370 --> 04:28:16.250
town. And I don't forget it. I don't. Often I says to myself, says I,

04:28:16.410 --> 04:28:19.870
I used to mend all the boys' kites and things, and show them where the

04:28:19.870 --> 04:28:24.050
good fishing places was, and befriend them when I could. And now

04:28:24.050 --> 04:28:27.830
they've all forgot old Muff when he's in trouble. But Tom don't and

04:28:27.830 --> 04:28:31.910
Huck don't. They don't forget him, says I, and I don't forget them.

04:28:32.370 --> 04:28:36.330
Well, boys, I had done an awful thing. Drunk and crazy at the time.

04:28:36.650 --> 04:28:40.190
That's the only way I count for it. And now I got the swing for it,

04:28:40.190 --> 04:28:44.990
and it's right. Right and best, too, I reckon. I hope so, anyway.

04:28:45.670 --> 04:28:49.290
Well, we won't talk about that. I don't want to make you feel bad.

04:28:49.290 --> 04:28:54.050
You've befriended me. But what I want to say is, don't you ever get

04:28:54.050 --> 04:28:58.730
drunk. Then you won't ever get here. Stand a little further west. So

04:28:58.730 --> 04:29:02.590
that's it. It's a prime comfort to see faces that's friendly when a

04:29:02.590 --> 04:29:06.490
body's in such a muck of trouble. And there don't none come here but

04:29:06.490 --> 04:29:12.950
yorn. Good friendly faces. Good friendly faces. Get up on one other's

04:29:12.950 --> 04:29:17.650
backs, and let me touch them. That's it. Shake hands. Yorn'll come

04:29:17.650 --> 04:29:22.910
through the bars, but mine's too big. Little hands and weak. And they've

04:29:22.910 --> 04:29:26.750
helped Muff Potter a power, and they'd help him more if they could.

04:29:27.490 --> 04:29:30.910
Tom went home miserable, and his dreams that night were full of

04:29:30.910 --> 04:29:34.290
horrors. The next day and the day after he hung about the courtroom,

04:29:34.830 --> 04:29:38.830
drawn by an impossibly resistible impulse to go in but forcing himself

04:29:38.830 --> 04:29:42.850
to stay out. Huck was having the same experience. They studiously

04:29:42.850 --> 04:29:47.350
avoided each other. Each wandered away from time to time, but the same

04:29:47.350 --> 04:29:51.310
dismal fascination always brought them back presently. Tom kept his

04:29:51.310 --> 04:29:55.190
ears open when idlers sauntered out of the courtroom, but invariably

04:29:55.190 --> 04:29:59.170
heard distressing news. The toils were closing more and more

04:29:59.170 --> 04:30:03.590
relentlessly around poor Potter. At the end of the second day the

04:30:03.590 --> 04:30:07.190
village talk was to the effect that Injun Joe's evidence stood firm and

04:30:07.190 --> 04:30:10.710
unshaken, and that there was not the slightest question as to what the

04:30:10.710 --> 04:30:15.030
jury's verdict would be. Tom was out late that night, and came to bed

04:30:15.030 --> 04:30:19.050
through the window. He was in a tremendous state of excitement. It was

04:30:19.050 --> 04:30:22.790
hours before he got to sleep. All the village flocked to the courthouse

04:30:22.790 --> 04:30:27.430
the next morning, for this was to be the great day. Both sexes were about

04:30:27.430 --> 04:30:31.370
equally represented in the packed audience. After a long wait the jury

04:30:31.370 --> 04:30:36.150
filed in and took their places. Shortly afterward, Potter, pale and

04:30:36.150 --> 04:30:40.650
haggard, timid and hopeless, was brought in with chains upon him, and

04:30:40.650 --> 04:30:44.390
seated where all the curious eyes could stare at him. No less

04:30:44.390 --> 04:30:48.650
conspicuous was Injun Joe, stolid as ever. There was another pause,

04:30:48.890 --> 04:30:51.790
and then the judge arrived and the sheriff proclaimed the opening of

04:30:51.790 --> 04:30:55.610
the court. The usual whisperings among the lawyers and gathering

04:30:55.610 --> 04:30:59.610
together of papers followed. These details and accompanying delays

04:30:59.610 --> 04:31:03.630
worked up an atmosphere of preparation that was as impressive as it was

04:31:03.630 --> 04:31:08.190
fascinating. Now a witness was called who testified that he found Muff

04:31:08.190 --> 04:31:11.570
Potter washing in the brook at an early hour of the morning that the

04:31:11.570 --> 04:31:15.870
murder was discovered, and that he immediately sneaked away. After some

04:31:15.870 --> 04:31:18.430
further questioning, counsel for the prosecution said,

04:31:18.850 --> 04:31:22.990
"'Take the witness.' The prisoner raised his eyes for a moment, but

04:31:22.990 --> 04:31:25.310
dropped them again when his own counsel said,

04:31:25.730 --> 04:31:29.710
"'I have no questions to ask him.' The next witness proved the finding

04:31:29.710 --> 04:31:33.310
of the knife near the corpse. Counsel for the prosecution said,

04:31:33.590 --> 04:31:34.930
"'Take the witness.'

04:31:34.930 --> 04:31:38.990
"'I have no questions to ask him,' Potter's lawyer replied. A third

04:31:38.990 --> 04:31:42.250
witness swore he had often seen the knife in Potter's possession.

04:31:43.110 --> 04:31:47.150
"'Take the witness.' Counsel for Potter declined to question him.

04:31:47.630 --> 04:31:51.330
The faces of the audience began to betray annoyance. Did this attorney

04:31:51.330 --> 04:31:55.010
mean to throw away his client's life without an effort? Several

04:31:55.010 --> 04:31:58.570
witnesses deposed concerning Potter's guilty behavior when brought to

04:31:58.570 --> 04:32:01.890
the scene of the murder. They were allowed to leave the stand without

04:32:01.890 --> 04:32:06.190
being cross-questioned. Every detail of the damaging circumstances

04:32:06.190 --> 04:32:09.310
that occurred in the graveyard upon that morning, which all present

04:32:09.310 --> 04:32:13.470
remembered so well, was brought out by credible witnesses, but none of

04:32:13.470 --> 04:32:17.370
them were cross-examined by Potter's lawyer. The perplexity and

04:32:17.370 --> 04:32:21.130
dissatisfaction of the house expressed itself in murmurs and provoked a

04:32:21.130 --> 04:32:24.470
reproof from the bench. Counsel for the prosecution now said,

04:32:24.890 --> 04:32:29.550
"'By the oaths of citizens whose simple word is above suspicion, we

04:32:29.550 --> 04:32:33.610
have fastened this awful crime, beyond all possibility of question,

04:32:33.610 --> 04:32:40.090
upon the unhappy prisoner at the bar. We rest our case here.' A groan

04:32:40.090 --> 04:32:44.050
escaped from poor Potter, and he put his face in his hands and rocked

04:32:44.050 --> 04:32:47.970
his body softly to and fro, while a painful silence reigned in the

04:32:47.970 --> 04:32:53.310
courtroom. Many men were removed, and many women's compassion testified

04:32:53.310 --> 04:32:58.310
itself in tears. Counsel for the defense rose and said, "'Your honor,

04:32:58.630 --> 04:33:02.850
in our remarks at the opening of this trial we foreshadowed our purpose

04:33:02.850 --> 04:33:06.390
to prove that our client did this fearful deed while under the

04:33:06.390 --> 04:33:11.350
influence of a blind and irresponsible delirium produced by drink. We

04:33:11.350 --> 04:33:15.710
have changed our mind. We shall not offer that plea.' Then to the

04:33:15.710 --> 04:33:21.910
clerk, "'Call Thomas Sawyer.' A puzzled amazement awoke in every face

04:33:21.910 --> 04:33:26.730
in the house, not even accepting Potter's. Every eye fastened itself

04:33:26.730 --> 04:33:31.290
with wondering interest upon Tom as he rose and took his place upon the

04:33:31.290 --> 04:33:35.910
stand. The boy looked wild enough, for he was badly scared. The oath

04:33:35.910 --> 04:33:40.970
was administered. Thomas Sawyer, where were you on the seventeenth of

04:33:40.970 --> 04:33:46.370
June, about the hour of midnight?' Tom glanced at Injun Joe's iron face,

04:33:46.630 --> 04:33:50.910
and his tongue failed him. The audience listened breathless, but the

04:33:50.910 --> 04:33:54.930
words refused to come. After a few moments, however, the boy got a little

04:33:54.930 --> 04:33:58.550
of his strength back, and managed to put enough of it into his voice to

04:33:58.550 --> 04:34:00.230
make part of the house hear.

04:34:00.810 --> 04:34:02.230
"'In the graveyard?'

04:34:02.950 --> 04:34:06.610
"'A little bit louder, please. Don't be afraid. You were in the

04:34:06.610 --> 04:34:11.150
graveyard.' A contemptuous smile flitted across Injun Joe's face.

04:34:11.350 --> 04:34:14.940
"'Were you anywhere near Horse William's grave?'

04:34:15.470 --> 04:34:16.550
"'Yes, sir.'

04:34:16.550 --> 04:34:19.540
"'Speak up, just a trifle louder. How near were you?'

04:34:19.970 --> 04:34:21.700
"'Near as I am to you.'

04:34:21.970 --> 04:34:23.700
"'Were you hidden or not?'

04:34:24.070 --> 04:34:25.170
"'I was hid.'

04:34:25.170 --> 04:34:26.350
"'Where?'

04:34:26.350 --> 04:34:29.270
"'Behind the elms that's on the edge of the grave.'

04:34:29.270 --> 04:34:32.050
Injun Joe gave a barely perceptible start.

04:34:32.610 --> 04:34:33.730
"'Anyone with you?'

04:34:34.090 --> 04:34:36.310
"'Yes, sir. I went there with—'

04:34:36.470 --> 04:34:40.370
"'Wait. Wait a moment. Never mind mentioning your companion's name.

04:34:40.490 --> 04:34:44.390
We will produce him at the proper time. Did you carry anything there

04:34:44.390 --> 04:34:47.390
with you?' Tom hesitated and looked confused.

04:34:47.590 --> 04:34:51.410
"'Speak out, my boy. Don't be diffident. The truth is always

04:34:51.410 --> 04:34:53.770
respectable. What did you take there?'

04:34:57.250 --> 04:34:58.170
"'Only—uh—uh—dead cat.'

04:34:58.170 --> 04:35:00.890
There was a ripple of mirth which the court checked.

04:35:01.250 --> 04:35:05.450
"'We will produce the skeleton of that cat. Now, my boy, tell us

04:35:05.450 --> 04:35:08.630
everything that occurred. Tell it in your own way. Don't skip

04:35:08.630 --> 04:35:10.190
anything, and don't be afraid.'

04:35:11.130 --> 04:35:15.430
Tom began hesitatingly at first, but as he warmed to his subject his

04:35:15.430 --> 04:35:19.310
words flowed more and more easily. In a little while every sound

04:35:19.310 --> 04:35:24.410
ceased but his own voice. Every eye fixed itself upon him. With

04:35:24.410 --> 04:35:27.730
parted lips and bated breath the audience hung upon his words,

04:35:28.010 --> 04:35:31.570
taking no note of time, wrapped in the ghastly fascination of the

04:35:31.570 --> 04:35:36.690
tale. The strain upon pent emotion reached its climax when the boys

04:35:36.690 --> 04:35:41.610
said, "'And as the doctor fetched the board around and Muff Potter

04:35:41.610 --> 04:35:44.270
fell, Injun Joe jumped with a knife and—'

04:35:45.030 --> 04:35:48.970
Crash! Quick as lightning the half-breed sprang for a window,

04:35:48.970 --> 04:35:52.090
tore his way through all opposers, and was gone.'

04:36:10.110 --> 04:36:10.730
XXIV.

04:36:11.010 --> 04:36:13.950
Splendid days and fearsome nights.

04:36:14.850 --> 04:36:20.450
Tom was a glittering hero once more, the pet of the old, the envy of the young.

04:36:20.450 --> 04:36:24.830
His name even went into immortal print, for the village paper magnified

04:36:24.830 --> 04:36:28.310
him. There were some that believed he would be president yet, if he

04:36:28.310 --> 04:36:33.650
escaped hanging. As usual, the fickle, unreasoning world took Muff Potter

04:36:33.650 --> 04:36:38.710
to its bosom, and fondled him as lavishly as it had abused him before.

04:36:39.230 --> 04:36:43.070
But that sort of conduct is to the world's credit, therefore it is not

04:36:43.070 --> 04:36:44.450
well to find fault with it.

04:36:45.150 --> 04:36:49.950
Tom's days were days of splendour and exultation to him, but his nights

04:36:49.950 --> 04:36:55.610
were seasons of horror. Injun Joe infested all his dreams, and all was

04:36:55.610 --> 04:36:59.910
with doom in his eye. Hardly any temptation could persuade the boy to

04:36:59.910 --> 04:37:03.750
stir abroad after nightfall. Poor Huck was in the same state of

04:37:03.750 --> 04:37:07.490
wretchedness and terror, for Tom had told the whole story to the lawyer

04:37:07.490 --> 04:37:11.670
the night before the great day of the trial, and Huck was sore afraid

04:37:11.670 --> 04:37:15.990
that his share in the business might leak out yet, notwithstanding,

04:37:15.990 --> 04:37:19.890
Injun Joe's flight had saved him the suffering of testifying in court.

04:37:20.390 --> 04:37:24.330
The poor fellow had got the attorney to promise secrecy, but what of

04:37:24.330 --> 04:37:28.870
that? Since Tom's harassed conscience had managed to drive him to the

04:37:28.870 --> 04:37:32.870
lawyer's house by night and wring a dread tale from lips that had been

04:37:32.870 --> 04:37:37.290
sealed with a dismalist and most formidable of oaths, Huck's confidence

04:37:37.290 --> 04:37:39.890
in the human race was well nigh obliterated.

04:37:40.550 --> 04:37:45.830
Daily Muff Potter's gratitude made Tom glad he had spoken, but nightly

04:37:45.830 --> 04:37:50.310
he wished he had sealed up his tongue. Half the time Tom was afraid

04:37:50.310 --> 04:37:54.330
Injun Joe would never be captured, the other half he was afraid he

04:37:54.330 --> 04:37:58.450
would be. He felt sure he never could draw a safe breath again until

04:37:58.450 --> 04:38:03.490
that man was dead and he had seen the corpse. Rewards had been offered,

04:38:03.810 --> 04:38:08.470
the country had been scoured, but no Injun Joe was found. One of those

04:38:08.470 --> 04:38:12.410
omniscient and awe-inspiring marvels, a detective, came up from St.

04:38:12.490 --> 04:38:17.310
Louis, moused around, shook his head, looked wise, and made that sort

04:38:17.310 --> 04:38:21.630
of astounding success which members of the craft usually achieve. That

04:38:21.630 --> 04:38:27.170
is to say, he found a clue. But you can't hang a clue for murder, and

04:38:27.170 --> 04:38:32.150
so after that detective had got through and gone home, Tom felt just as

04:38:32.150 --> 04:38:33.470
insecure as he was before.

04:38:33.930 --> 04:38:38.870
The slow days drifted on, and each left behind it a slightly lightened

04:38:38.870 --> 04:38:40.610
weight of apprehension.

04:38:44.390 --> 04:38:45.750
CHAPTER XXV.

04:38:46.350 --> 04:38:47.930
Seeking the Buried Treasure.

04:38:48.950 --> 04:38:52.890
There comes a time in every rightly constructed boy's life when he has

04:38:52.890 --> 04:38:57.230
a raging desire to go somewhere and dig for hidden treasure. This

04:38:57.230 --> 04:39:01.230
desire suddenly came upon Tom one day. He sallied out to find Joe

04:39:01.230 --> 04:39:06.290
Harper, but failed of success. Next he sought Ben Rogers. He had gone

04:39:06.290 --> 04:39:11.210
fishing. Presently he stumbled upon Huck Finn, the red-handed. Huck

04:39:11.210 --> 04:39:15.270
would answer. Tom took him to a private place and opened the matter to

04:39:15.270 --> 04:39:20.030
him confidentially. Huck was willing. Huck was always willing to take a

04:39:20.030 --> 04:39:23.130
hand in any enterprise that offered entertainment and required no

04:39:23.130 --> 04:39:27.550
capital, for he had a troublesome superabundance of that sort of time

04:39:27.550 --> 04:39:29.350
which is not money.

04:39:29.870 --> 04:39:31.510
"'Where'll we dig?' said Huck.

04:39:31.890 --> 04:39:33.550
"'Oh, most anywhere.'

04:39:33.550 --> 04:39:35.590
"'Why, is it hid all round?'

04:39:35.590 --> 04:39:39.650
"'No, indeed it ain't. It's hid in mighty particular places, Huck,

04:39:39.890 --> 04:39:44.110
sometimes on islands, sometimes in rotten chests under the end of a

04:39:44.110 --> 04:39:48.350
limb of an old dead tree, just where the shadow falls at midnight, but

04:39:48.350 --> 04:39:51.590
mostly under the floor in haunted houses.'

04:39:51.590 --> 04:39:53.210
"'Who hides it?'

04:39:53.210 --> 04:39:57.130
"'Why, robbers, of course. Who'd you reckon? Sunday-school

04:39:57.650 --> 04:39:58.150
superintendents?'

04:39:58.150 --> 04:40:02.430
"'I don't know. If it was mine, I wouldn't hide it. I'd spend it and

04:40:02.430 --> 04:40:03.630
have a good time.'

04:40:03.630 --> 04:40:08.390
"'So would I. But robbers don't do that way. They always hide it and

04:40:08.390 --> 04:40:12.070
leave it there. Don't they come after it any more?'

04:40:12.070 --> 04:40:15.690
"'No, they think they will, but they generally forget the marks, or

04:40:15.690 --> 04:40:19.730
else they die. Anyway, it lays there a long time and gets rusty, and

04:40:19.730 --> 04:40:23.250
by-and-by somebody finds an old yellow paper that tells how to find

04:40:23.250 --> 04:40:27.310
the marks. A paper that's got to be ciphered over about a week, because

04:40:27.310 --> 04:40:30.250
it's mostly signs and hieroglyphics.'

04:40:30.250 --> 04:40:31.550
"'Hiro-which?'

04:40:31.550 --> 04:40:36.110
"'Hiro-glyphics. Pictures and things, you know, that don't seem to mean

04:40:36.110 --> 04:40:36.810
anything.'

04:40:36.810 --> 04:40:39.250
"'Have you got one of them papers, Tom?'

04:40:39.890 --> 04:40:40.410
"'No.'

04:40:40.410 --> 04:40:42.910
"'Well, then how are you going to find the marks?'

04:40:42.910 --> 04:40:47.010
"'I don't want to find any marks. They always bury it under a haunted

04:40:47.010 --> 04:40:50.470
house or on an island, or under a dead tree that's got one limb

04:40:50.470 --> 04:40:51.210
sticking out.'

04:40:51.210 --> 04:40:55.510
"'Well, we've tried Jackson's Island a little, and we can try it again

04:40:55.510 --> 04:40:59.110
some time. And there's the old haunted house up the still house

04:40:59.110 --> 04:41:04.490
branch. And there's lots of dead-limb trees—dead loads of them.'

04:41:04.490 --> 04:41:06.350
"'Is it under all of them?'

04:41:06.350 --> 04:41:10.810
"'How you talk! No! Then how are you going to know which one to go

04:41:10.810 --> 04:41:11.690
for?'

04:41:11.690 --> 04:41:13.370
"'Go for all of them.'

04:41:13.370 --> 04:41:15.610
"'Why, Tom, it'll take all summer.'

04:41:16.330 --> 04:41:20.070
"'Well, what of that? Suppose you find a brass pot with a hundred

04:41:20.070 --> 04:41:24.130
dollars in it, all rusty and gay, or a rotten chest full of diamonds.

04:41:24.410 --> 04:41:25.530
How's that?'

04:41:25.530 --> 04:41:27.150
Huck's eyes glowed.

04:41:27.730 --> 04:41:31.510
"'That's bully. Plenty bully enough for me. Just you give me the

04:41:31.510 --> 04:41:33.470
hundred dollars, and I don't want no diamonds.'

04:41:33.990 --> 04:41:37.510
"'All right. But I bet you I ain't going to throw off on diamonds.

04:41:37.930 --> 04:41:41.370
Some of them's worth twenty dollars a piece. There ain't any hardly

04:41:41.370 --> 04:41:43.330
but's worth six bits or a dollar.'

04:41:44.210 --> 04:41:44.730
"'No.'

04:41:44.730 --> 04:41:48.890
"'Is that so? Certainly. Anybody'll tell you so. Ain't you ever seen

04:41:48.890 --> 04:41:49.510
one, Huck?'

04:41:49.510 --> 04:41:51.470
"'Not as I remember.'

04:41:51.470 --> 04:41:54.510
"'Oh, kings have slathers of them.'

04:41:54.510 --> 04:41:58.670
"'Well, I don't know no kings, Tom. I reckon you don't. But if you

04:41:58.670 --> 04:42:01.390
was to go to Europe, you'd see a raft of them hopping around.'

04:42:01.390 --> 04:42:03.010
"'Do they hop?'

04:42:03.010 --> 04:42:03.710
"'Hop?'

04:42:03.710 --> 04:42:04.570
"'Your granny.'

04:42:05.290 --> 04:42:05.750
"'No.'

04:42:05.750 --> 04:42:08.310
"'Well, what'd you say they did for?'

04:42:08.310 --> 04:42:12.130
"'Shucks, I only meant you'd see him, not hopping, of course. What do

04:42:12.130 --> 04:42:15.670
they want to hop for? But I mean you'd just see him scattered round,

04:42:15.670 --> 04:42:19.790
you know, in a kind of a general way, like that old hump-backed

04:42:19.790 --> 04:42:20.590
Richard.'

04:42:21.230 --> 04:42:21.670
"'Richard?'

04:42:21.670 --> 04:42:22.910
"'What's his other name?'

04:42:22.910 --> 04:42:25.870
"'He didn't have any other name. Kings don't have any but a given

04:42:25.870 --> 04:42:26.590
name.'

04:42:27.310 --> 04:42:27.750
"'No.'

04:42:27.750 --> 04:42:29.210
"'But they don't.'

04:42:29.210 --> 04:42:32.390
"'Well, if they like it, Tom, all right. But I don't want to be a king

04:42:32.390 --> 04:42:36.650
and have only just a given name, like a nigger. But say, where you

04:42:36.650 --> 04:42:37.930
going to dig first?'

04:42:37.930 --> 04:42:42.450
"'Well, I don't know. Suppose we tackle that old dead limb-tree on the

04:42:42.450 --> 04:42:44.230
hill to the other side of Stillhouse branch.'

04:42:44.230 --> 04:42:45.930
"'I'm agreed.'

04:42:45.930 --> 04:42:50.050
"'So they got a crippled pick and a shovel, and set out on their three-mile

04:42:50.050 --> 04:42:54.350
tramp. They arrived hot and panting, and threw themselves down in the

04:42:54.350 --> 04:42:56.970
shade of a neighbouring elm to rest and have a smoke.'

04:42:57.890 --> 04:42:59.510
"'I like this,' said Tom.

04:43:00.090 --> 04:43:01.570
"'So do I.'

04:43:01.570 --> 04:43:04.730
"'Say, Huck, if we find a treasure here, what are you going to do with

04:43:04.730 --> 04:43:05.470
your share?'

04:43:06.290 --> 04:43:10.330
"'Well, I'll have pie and a glass of soda every day, and I'll go to

04:43:10.330 --> 04:43:13.710
every circus that comes along. I bet I'll have a gay time.'

04:43:13.710 --> 04:43:15.930
"'Well, ain't you going to save any of it?'

04:43:15.930 --> 04:43:18.030
"'Save it? What for?'

04:43:18.030 --> 04:43:21.030
"'Why, so as to have something to live on by and by.'

04:43:21.030 --> 04:43:25.650
"'Oh, that ain't any use. Pap would come back to this year town some day

04:43:25.650 --> 04:43:29.670
and get his claws on it, if I didn't hurry up, and I tell you he'd

04:43:29.670 --> 04:43:33.110
clean it out pretty quick. What you going to do with urine, Tom?'

04:43:33.110 --> 04:43:37.710
"'I'm going to buy a new drum, and a sure enough sword, and a red

04:43:37.710 --> 04:43:40.770
necktie, and a bullpup, and get married.'

04:43:40.770 --> 04:43:42.790
"'Married? That's it.'

04:43:43.490 --> 04:43:44.450
"'Tom, you—'

04:43:44.690 --> 04:43:45.910
"'Why, you ain't in your right mind.'

04:43:46.590 --> 04:43:47.910
"'Wait, you'll see.'

04:43:48.630 --> 04:43:52.150
"'Well, that's the foolishest thing you could do. Look at Pap and my

04:43:52.150 --> 04:43:55.950
mother. Fight! Why, they used to fight all the time. I remember

04:43:55.950 --> 04:43:56.990
mighty well.'

04:43:56.990 --> 04:44:00.250
"'That ain't anything. The girl I'm going to marry won't fight.'

04:44:00.250 --> 04:44:05.310
"'Tom, I reckon they're all alike. They'll all comb a body. Now, you

04:44:05.310 --> 04:44:08.650
better think about this awhile. I tell you, you better. What's the

04:44:08.650 --> 04:44:09.930
name of the gal?'

04:44:09.930 --> 04:44:13.070
"'It ain't a gal at all. It's a girl.'

04:44:13.070 --> 04:44:17.550
"'It's all the same, I reckon. Some says gal, some says girl. Both's

04:44:17.550 --> 04:44:20.290
right, like enough. Anyway, what's her name, Tom?'

04:44:20.290 --> 04:44:22.810
"'I'll tell you some time. Not now.'

04:44:22.810 --> 04:44:26.350
"'All right, that'll do. Only if you get married I'll be more

04:44:26.350 --> 04:44:27.830
lonesomer than ever.'

04:44:27.830 --> 04:44:32.090
"'No, you won't. You'll come and live with me. Now, stir out of this,

04:44:32.090 --> 04:44:33.070
and we'll go to digging.'

04:44:33.610 --> 04:44:37.310
They worked and sweated for half an hour. No result. They toiled

04:44:37.310 --> 04:44:40.490
another half hour. Still no result. Huck said,

04:44:40.670 --> 04:44:43.530
"'Do they always bury it as deep as this?'

04:44:43.530 --> 04:44:47.850
"'Sometimes. Not always. Not generally. I reckon we haven't got the

04:44:47.850 --> 04:44:48.350
right place.'

04:44:48.970 --> 04:44:52.630
So they chose a new spot and began again. The labour dragged a

04:44:52.630 --> 04:44:56.590
little, but still they made progress. They pegged away in silence for

04:44:56.590 --> 04:45:00.710
some time. Finally Huck leaned on his shovel, swabbed the beaded

04:45:00.710 --> 04:45:02.750
drops from his brow with his sleeve, and said,

04:45:02.750 --> 04:45:06.350
"'Where are you going to dig next after we get this one?'

04:45:07.010 --> 04:45:10.350
"'I reckon maybe we'll tackle the old tree that's over yonder on

04:45:10.350 --> 04:45:12.190
Cardiff Hill, back of the widows.'

04:45:12.190 --> 04:45:15.790
"'I reckon that'll be a good one. But won't the widow take it away

04:45:15.790 --> 04:45:17.770
from us, Tom? It's on her land.'

04:45:17.770 --> 04:45:23.190
"'She take it away? Maybe she'd like to try it once. Whoever finds one

04:45:23.190 --> 04:45:26.250
of these hid treasures, it belongs to him. It don't make any

04:45:26.250 --> 04:45:27.570
difference whose land it's on.'

04:45:28.150 --> 04:45:29.390
That was satisfactory.

04:45:29.770 --> 04:45:32.330
"'The work went on,' by and by Huck said.

04:45:32.750 --> 04:45:36.330
"'Blame it. We must be in the wrong place again. What do you think?'

04:45:36.330 --> 04:45:40.990
"'It is mighty curious, Huck. I don't understand it. Sometimes

04:45:40.990 --> 04:45:44.870
witches interfere. I reckon maybe that's what's the trouble now.'

04:45:44.870 --> 04:45:48.310
"'Shucks, witches ain't got no power in the daytime.'

04:45:48.310 --> 04:45:52.510
"'Well, that's so. I didn't think of that. Oh, I know what the matter

04:45:52.510 --> 04:45:56.610
is. What a blamed lot of fools we are. You got to find out where the

04:45:56.610 --> 04:45:59.530
shadow of the limb falls at midnight, and that's where you dig.'

04:45:59.530 --> 04:46:04.070
"'Then con sound it. We fooled away all this work for nothing. Now

04:46:04.070 --> 04:46:07.590
hang it all, we've got to come back in the night. It's an awful long

04:46:07.590 --> 04:46:08.930
way. Can you get out?'

04:46:08.930 --> 04:46:13.310
"'I bet I will. We've got to do it to-night, too, because if somebody

04:46:13.310 --> 04:46:16.830
sees these holes, they'll know in a minute what's here, and they'll go

04:46:16.830 --> 04:46:17.250
for it.'

04:46:17.250 --> 04:46:20.110
"'Well, I'll come around and mow to-night.'

04:46:20.110 --> 04:46:23.130
"'All right. Let's hide the tools in the bushes.'

04:46:23.130 --> 04:46:27.330
The boys were there that night about the appointed time. They sat in

04:46:27.330 --> 04:46:31.610
the shadow waiting. It was a lonely place, and an hour made solemn by

04:46:31.610 --> 04:46:36.770
old traditions. Spirits whispered in the rustling leaves, ghosts lurked

04:46:36.770 --> 04:46:40.890
in the murky nooks, the deep baying of a hound floated up out of the

04:46:40.890 --> 04:46:45.190
distance. An owl answered with his sepulchral note. The boys were

04:46:45.190 --> 04:46:49.430
subdued by these solemnities, and talked little. By-and-by they judged

04:46:49.430 --> 04:46:53.090
that twelve had come, they marked where the shadow fell, and began to

04:46:53.090 --> 04:46:57.590
dig. Their hopes commenced to rise, their interests grew stronger, and

04:46:57.590 --> 04:47:01.870
their industry kept pace with it. The hole deepened, and still deepened.

04:47:02.030 --> 04:47:05.210
But every time their hearts jumped to hear the pick strike upon

04:47:05.210 --> 04:47:09.530
something, they only suffered a new disappointment. It was only a stone

04:47:09.530 --> 04:47:12.050
or a chunk. At last Tom said,

04:47:12.310 --> 04:47:15.750
"'It ain't no use, Huck. We're wrong again.'

04:47:15.750 --> 04:47:20.450
"'Well, but we can't be wrong. We spotted the shatter to a dot.'

04:47:20.450 --> 04:47:23.630
"'I know it. But then there's another thing.'

04:47:24.410 --> 04:47:25.370
"'What's that?'

04:47:25.370 --> 04:47:29.670
"'Why, we only guessed at the time. Like enough it was too late or too

04:47:29.670 --> 04:47:30.530
early.'

04:47:30.530 --> 04:47:31.970
Huck dropped his shovel.

04:47:32.450 --> 04:47:33.510
"'That's it,' he said.

04:47:33.790 --> 04:47:37.870
"'That's the very trouble. We've got to give this one up. We can't ever

04:47:37.870 --> 04:47:41.950
tell the right time. And besides, this kind of thing's too awful. Here

04:47:41.950 --> 04:47:45.170
are this time of night with witches and ghosts a-fluttering around, so

04:47:45.170 --> 04:47:49.550
I feel as if something's behind me all the time, and I'm a-fear to turn

04:47:49.550 --> 04:47:53.150
around, because maybe there's others in front of waiting for a chance.

04:47:53.550 --> 04:47:57.050
I've been creeping all over ever since I got here.'

04:47:57.050 --> 04:48:01.730
"'Well, I've been pretty much so too, Huck. They most always put in a

04:48:01.730 --> 04:48:05.650
dead man when they bury a treasure under a tree to look out for it.'

04:48:05.650 --> 04:48:06.590
"'Lordy!'

04:48:06.590 --> 04:48:08.690
"'Yes, they do. I've always heard that.'

04:48:09.230 --> 04:48:12.710
"'Tom, I don't like to fool around much where there's dead people. A

04:48:12.710 --> 04:48:14.650
body's bound to get into trouble with them, sure.'

04:48:14.650 --> 04:48:19.250
"'I don't like to stir them up, either. Suppose this one here was to

04:48:19.250 --> 04:48:20.970
stick his skull out and say something.'

04:48:20.970 --> 04:48:22.690
"'Don't, Tom, it's awful.'

04:48:22.690 --> 04:48:27.570
"'Well, it just is. Huck, I don't feel comfortable a bit.'

04:48:27.570 --> 04:48:30.990
"'Say, Tom, let's give this place up and try somewhere else.'

04:48:30.990 --> 04:48:32.890
"'All right, I reckon we'd better.'

04:48:32.890 --> 04:48:33.810
"'What'll it be?'

04:48:34.390 --> 04:48:36.290
Tom considered a while, and then said,

04:48:36.610 --> 04:48:38.510
"'The Hanted House, that's it.'

04:48:38.510 --> 04:48:43.330
"'Blame it, I don't like Hanted Houses, Tom. Why, they're a darn sight

04:48:43.330 --> 04:48:46.950
worse than dead people. Dead people might talk, maybe, but they don't

04:48:46.950 --> 04:48:50.910
come sliding round in a shroud when you ain't noticing, and peep over

04:48:50.910 --> 04:48:53.830
your shoulder all of a sudden and grit their teeth the way a ghost

04:48:53.830 --> 04:48:58.230
does. I couldn't stand such a thing as that, Tom. Nobody could.'

04:48:58.230 --> 04:49:03.210
"'Yes, but, Huck, ghosts don't travel around only at night. They won't

04:49:03.210 --> 04:49:05.910
hinder us from digging there in the daytime.'

04:49:06.450 --> 04:49:10.270
"'Well, that's so. But you know mighty well people don't go about

04:49:10.270 --> 04:49:12.390
that Hanted House in the day, nor the night.'

04:49:13.250 --> 04:49:16.450
"'Well, that's mostly because they don't like to go where a man's been

04:49:16.450 --> 04:49:20.050
murdered, anyway. But nothing's ever been seen around that house,

04:49:20.190 --> 04:49:24.270
except in the night. Just some blue lights slipping by the windows. No

04:49:24.270 --> 04:49:25.310
regular ghosts.'

04:49:25.970 --> 04:49:29.750
"'Well, where you see one of them blue lights flickering around, Tom,

04:49:29.770 --> 04:49:33.090
you can bet there's a ghost mighty close behind it. It stands to

04:49:33.090 --> 04:49:37.270
reason. Because you know that they don't anybody but ghosts use them.'

04:49:37.270 --> 04:49:41.110
"'Yes, that's so. But anyway, they don't come round in the daytime. So

04:49:41.110 --> 04:49:42.410
what's the use of our being afeard?'

04:49:43.150 --> 04:49:47.010
"'Well, all right. We'll tackle the Hanted House, if you say so. But I

04:49:47.010 --> 04:49:48.310
reckon it's taken chances.'

04:49:48.850 --> 04:49:52.410
They had started down the hill by this time. There, in the middle of

04:49:52.410 --> 04:49:55.830
the moonlit valley below them, stood the Hanted House, utterly

04:49:55.830 --> 04:50:00.770
isolated, its fences gone long ago, rank weeds smothering the very

04:50:00.770 --> 04:50:05.550
doorsteps, the chimney crumpled to ruin, the window sashes vacant, a

04:50:05.550 --> 04:50:09.610
corner of the roof caved in, the boys gazed awhile, half expecting to

04:50:09.610 --> 04:50:14.750
see a blue light flit past a window. Then, talking in a low tone, as

04:50:14.750 --> 04:50:18.630
befitted the time and the circumstances, they struck far off to the

04:50:18.630 --> 04:50:23.090
right, to give the Hanted House a wide berth, and took their way

04:50:23.090 --> 04:50:27.270
homeward through the woods that adorned the rearward side of Cardiff

04:50:27.270 --> 04:50:30.190
Hill.

04:50:46.830 --> 04:50:47.450
XXVI.

04:50:47.790 --> 04:50:50.630
Real robbers seize the box of gold.

04:50:51.430 --> 04:50:56.430
About noon the next day the boys arrived at the dead tree. They had come for their tools.

04:50:56.430 --> 04:51:02.630
Tom was impatient to go to the haunted house. Huck was measurably so, also, but suddenly said,

04:51:03.170 --> 04:51:08.270
"'Looky here, Tom, do you know what day it is?' Tom mentally ran over the days of the week,

04:51:08.330 --> 04:51:11.150
and then quickly lifted his eyes with a startled look in them.

04:51:11.470 --> 04:51:14.150
"'My! I never once thought of it, Huck!'

04:51:14.650 --> 04:51:19.010
Well, I didn't either, but all at once it popped on to me that it was Friday.

04:51:19.610 --> 04:51:24.570
Blame me! A body can't be too careful, Huck. We might have got into an awful scrape

04:51:24.570 --> 04:51:30.970
tackling such a thing on a Friday. Might. Better say we would. There's some lucky days,

04:51:31.110 --> 04:51:36.890
maybe, but Friday ain't. Any fool knows that. I don't reckon you was the first that found it out,

04:51:37.190 --> 04:51:42.950
Huck. Well, I never said it was, did I? And Friday ain't all, neither. I had a rotten bad

04:51:42.950 --> 04:51:50.670
dream last night, dreamt about rats. No! Sure sign of trouble. Did they fight? No. Well,

04:51:50.670 --> 04:51:54.690
that's good, Huck. When they don't fight, it's only a sign that there's trouble around,

04:51:54.690 --> 04:51:59.910
you know. All we got to do is to look mighty sharp and keep out of it. We'll drop this thing

04:51:59.910 --> 04:52:05.390
for today and play. Do you know Robin Hood, Huck? No. Who's Robin Hood?'

04:52:06.310 --> 04:52:10.070
"'Why, he was one of the greatest men that was ever in England, and the best.

04:52:10.270 --> 04:52:17.810
He was a robber.' Cracky, I wished I was. Who did he rob? Only sheriffs and bishops and rich

04:52:17.810 --> 04:52:22.830
people and kings and such like. But he never bothered the poor. He loved them. He always

04:52:22.830 --> 04:52:28.630
divided up with them perfectly square. Well, he must have been a brick. I bet you he was,

04:52:28.850 --> 04:52:34.470
Huck. Oh, he was the noblest man that ever was. There ain't any such men now, I can tell you.

04:52:34.750 --> 04:52:40.210
He could lick any man in England with one hand tied behind him, and he could take his u-bow and

04:52:40.210 --> 04:52:48.250
plug a ten-cent piece every time a mile and a half. What's a u-bow? I don't know. It's some

04:52:48.250 --> 04:52:54.010
kind of a bow, of course, and if he hit that dime only on the edge, he would sit down and cry and

04:52:54.010 --> 04:52:58.820
curse. But we'll play Robin Hood, and it's knobby fun. I'll learn you.'

04:52:59.590 --> 04:53:04.750
"'I'm agreed.' So they played Robin Hood all afternoon, now and then casting a yearning eye

04:53:04.750 --> 04:53:09.530
down upon the haunted house and passing a remark about the morrow's prospects and possibilities

04:53:10.110 --> 04:53:15.750
as the sun began to sink into the west, they took their way homeward to thwart the long shadows of

04:53:15.750 --> 04:53:21.510
the trees, and soon were buried from sight in the forests of Cardiff Hill. On Saturday, shortly

04:53:21.510 --> 04:53:27.570
afternoon, the boys were at the dead tree again. They had a smoke and a chat in the shade, and then

04:53:27.570 --> 04:53:32.410
dug a little in their last hole, not with great hope, but merely because Tom said there were

04:53:32.410 --> 04:53:37.090
so many cases where people had given up a treasure after getting down within six inches of it,

04:53:37.090 --> 04:53:42.370
and then somebody else had come along and turned it up with a single thrust of a shovel. The thing

04:53:42.370 --> 04:53:47.310
failed this time, however, so the boys shouldered their tools and went away feeling that they had

04:53:47.310 --> 04:53:52.090
not trifled with fortune, but had fulfilled all the requirements that belonged to the business

04:53:52.090 --> 04:53:57.510
of treasure-hunting. When they reached the haunted house there was something so weird and grisly

04:53:57.510 --> 04:54:02.850
about the dead silence that reigned there under the baking sun, and something so depressing about

04:54:02.850 --> 04:54:08.510
the loneliness and desolation of the place that they were afraid, for a moment, to venture in.

04:54:08.970 --> 04:54:14.070
Then they crept to the door and took a trembling peep. They saw a weed-grown,

04:54:14.330 --> 04:54:20.430
floorless room, unplastered, an ancient fireplace, vacant windows, a ruinous staircase,

04:54:20.810 --> 04:54:26.450
and here, there, and everywhere hung ragged and abandoned cobwebs. They presently entered,

04:54:26.690 --> 04:54:32.490
softly, with quickened pulses, talking in whispers, ears alert to catch the slightest sound,

04:54:32.490 --> 04:54:38.250
and muscles tense and ready for instant retreat. In a little while familiarity modified their

04:54:38.250 --> 04:54:43.210
fears, and they gave the place a critical and interested examination, rather admiring their

04:54:43.210 --> 04:54:49.270
own boldness and wondering at it, too. Next, they wanted to look upstairs. This was something like

04:54:49.270 --> 04:54:54.190
cutting off the retreat. But they got to daring each other, and of course there could be but

04:54:54.190 --> 04:55:00.610
one result. They threw their tools into a corner and made the ascent. Up there were the same signs

04:55:00.610 --> 04:55:05.710
of decay. In one corner they found a closet that promised mystery, but the promise was a fraud—there

04:55:05.710 --> 04:55:11.150
was nothing in it. Their courage was up now, and well in hand. They were about to go down and begin

04:55:11.150 --> 04:55:11.750
work when—

04:55:11.750 --> 04:55:12.810
"'Shh!' said Tom.

04:55:13.430 --> 04:55:19.150
"'What is it?' whispered Huck, blanching with fright. "'Shh! There! Hear it? Yes! Oh my! Let's

04:55:19.150 --> 04:55:23.550
run! Keep still! Don't you budge! They're coming right toward the door!'

04:55:24.190 --> 04:55:29.030
The boys stretched themselves upon the floor with their eyes to knotholes in the planking,

04:55:29.030 --> 04:55:31.070
and lay waiting in a misery of fear.

04:55:31.550 --> 04:55:36.870
"'They've stopped! No! Coming! Here they are! Don't whisper another word, Huck! My goodness,

04:55:36.910 --> 04:55:38.370
I wish I was out of this!'

04:55:38.370 --> 04:55:41.230
Two men entered. Each boy said to himself,

04:55:41.250 --> 04:55:45.970
"'There's the old deaf and dumb Spaniard that's been about town once or twice lately.

04:55:46.330 --> 04:55:47.950
Never saw Totherman before.'

04:55:47.950 --> 04:55:53.490
Tother was a ragged, unkempt creature, with nothing very pleasant in his face. The Spaniard

04:55:53.490 --> 04:55:59.790
wrapped in a sarape. He had bushy white whiskers, long white hair flowed from under his sombrero,

04:56:00.090 --> 04:56:05.350
and he wore green goggles. When they came in, Tother was talking in a low voice. They

04:56:05.350 --> 04:56:10.210
sat down on the ground, facing the door, with their backs to the wall, and the speaker continued

04:56:10.210 --> 04:56:15.190
his remarks. His manner became less guarded and his words more distinct as he proceeded.

04:56:15.530 --> 04:56:20.130
"'No,' said he, "'I've thought it all over, and I don't like it. It's dangerous.'

04:56:21.430 --> 04:56:26.010
"'Dangerous!' grunted the deaf and dumb Spaniard, to the vast surprise of the boys.

04:56:27.270 --> 04:56:32.990
"'Milksop!' This voice made the boys gasp and quake. It was Injun Joe's. There was silence

04:56:32.990 --> 04:56:38.250
for some time. Then Joe said, "'What's any more dangerous than that job up yonder?

04:56:38.510 --> 04:56:39.850
But nothing's come of it.'

04:56:40.470 --> 04:56:44.090
"'That's different. Away up the river so, and not another house about.

04:56:44.550 --> 04:56:48.050
Don't ever be known that we tried, anyway, long as we didn't succeed.'

04:56:48.670 --> 04:56:53.030
"'Well, what's more dangerous than coming here in the daytime? Anybody would

04:56:53.030 --> 04:56:54.690
suspicion us that saw us.'

04:56:55.110 --> 04:57:00.130
"'I know that. But there weren't any other places handy after that fool of a job. I

04:57:00.130 --> 04:57:04.410
want to quit this shanty. I wanted to yesterday, only it weren't any use

04:57:04.410 --> 04:57:08.070
trying to stir out of here with those infernal boys playing over there on

04:57:08.070 --> 04:57:09.710
the hill right in full view.'

04:57:09.710 --> 04:57:14.090
Those infernal boys quaked again under the inspiration of this remark,

04:57:14.090 --> 04:57:17.630
and thought how lucky it was that they had remembered it was Friday and

04:57:17.630 --> 04:57:21.550
concluded to wait a day. They wished in their hearts they had waited a

04:57:21.550 --> 04:57:26.330
year. The two men got out some food and made a luncheon. After a long and

04:57:26.330 --> 04:57:28.130
thoughtful silence, Injun Joe said,

04:57:28.770 --> 04:57:33.390
"'Look here, lad. You go back up the river where you belong. Wait there

04:57:33.390 --> 04:57:37.130
till you hear from me. I'll take the chances on dropping into this town

04:57:37.130 --> 04:57:42.050
just once more for a look. We'll do that dangerous job after I've spied

04:57:42.050 --> 04:57:47.090
around a little and think things look well for it. Then for Texas. We'll

04:57:47.090 --> 04:57:47.690
leg it together.'

04:57:48.350 --> 04:57:52.790
This was satisfactory. Both men presently fell to yawning, and Injun Joe

04:57:52.790 --> 04:57:53.130
said,

04:57:53.730 --> 04:57:58.510
"'I'm dead for sleep. It's your turn to watch.' He curled down into the

04:57:58.510 --> 04:58:03.010
weeds, and soon began to snore. His comrade stirred him once or twice, and

04:58:03.010 --> 04:58:07.970
he became quiet. Presently the watcher began to nod. His head drooped

04:58:07.970 --> 04:58:11.390
lower and lower, and both men began to snore now.

04:58:11.390 --> 04:58:15.510
The boys drew a long, grateful breath. Tom whispered,

04:58:15.730 --> 04:58:17.970
"'Now's our chance. Come.'

04:58:17.970 --> 04:58:18.570
Huck said,

04:58:18.950 --> 04:58:21.590
"'I can't. I'd die if they whisked awake.'

04:58:22.050 --> 04:58:27.970
Tom urged. Huck held back. At last Tom rose slowly and softly and

04:58:27.970 --> 04:58:32.070
started alone. But the first step he made rung such a hideous creek from

04:58:32.070 --> 04:58:35.930
the crazy floor that he sank down almost dead with fright. He never made

04:58:35.930 --> 04:58:40.250
a second attempt. The boys lay there counting the dragging moments till

04:58:40.250 --> 04:58:44.510
it seemed to them that time must be done, and eternity growing gray.

04:58:44.870 --> 04:58:48.030
And then they were grateful to note that at last the sun was setting.

04:58:48.750 --> 04:58:54.670
Now one snore ceased. Injun Joe sat up, stared around, smiled grimly upon

04:58:54.670 --> 04:58:58.870
his comrade, whose head was drooping upon his knees, stirred him up with

04:58:58.870 --> 04:58:59.590
his foot, and said,

04:58:59.850 --> 04:59:04.370
"'Here! You're a watchman, ain't you? All right, though. Nothing's

04:59:04.370 --> 04:59:05.130
happened.'

04:59:05.130 --> 04:59:10.650
My! Have I been asleep? Oh, partly, partly. Nearly time for us to be

04:59:10.650 --> 04:59:14.770
moving, pard. What'll we do with what little swag we've got left? I

04:59:14.770 --> 04:59:18.790
don't know. Leave it here as we've always done, I reckon. No use to

04:59:18.790 --> 04:59:22.390
take it away till we start south. Six hundred and fifty and silver's

04:59:22.390 --> 04:59:25.970
something to carry. Well, all right, it won't matter to come here once

04:59:25.970 --> 04:59:30.670
more. No, but I'd say come in the night as we used to do. It's better.

04:59:31.290 --> 04:59:35.050
Yes, but look here. It may be a good while before I get the right chance

04:59:35.050 --> 04:59:39.290
at that job. Accidents might happen. Taintin's such a very good place.

04:59:39.690 --> 04:59:42.590
We'll just regularly bury it, and bury it deep.'

04:59:43.310 --> 04:59:47.150
"'Good idea,' said the comrade, who walked across the room, knelt down,

04:59:47.290 --> 04:59:50.630
raised one of the rearward hearth-stones, and took out a bag that

04:59:50.630 --> 04:59:54.350
jingled pleasantly. He subtracted from it twenty or thirty dollars for

04:59:54.350 --> 04:59:58.390
himself, and as much for Injun Joe, and passed the bag to the latter,

04:59:58.670 --> 05:00:01.710
who was on his knees in the corner now, digging with his bowie-knife.

05:00:01.710 --> 05:00:06.590
The boys forgot all their fears, all their miseries in an instant. With

05:00:06.590 --> 05:00:11.290
gloating eyes they watched every movement. Luck! The splendor of it was

05:00:11.290 --> 05:00:15.710
beyond all imagination. Six hundred dollars was money enough to make

05:00:15.710 --> 05:00:19.790
half a dozen boys rich. Here was treasure hunting under the happiest

05:00:19.790 --> 05:00:24.230
auspices. There would not be any bothersome uncertainty as to where to

05:00:24.230 --> 05:00:28.490
dig. They nudged each other every moment, eloquent nudges, and easily

05:00:28.490 --> 05:00:33.410
understood, for they simply meant, "'Oh, but ain't you glad now we're

05:00:33.410 --> 05:00:36.090
here!' Joe's knife struck upon something.

05:00:36.570 --> 05:00:37.670
"'Hullo,' he said.

05:00:38.050 --> 05:00:39.330
"'What is it?' said his comrade.

05:00:39.790 --> 05:00:45.370
"'Half rotten plank. No, it's a box, I believe. Here, bear a hand, and

05:00:45.370 --> 05:00:49.070
we'll see what it's here for. Never mind, I've broke a hole.' He

05:00:49.070 --> 05:00:51.270
reached his hand in, and drew it out.

05:00:51.630 --> 05:00:53.040
"'Man, it's money!'

05:00:53.670 --> 05:00:58.250
The two men examined the handful of coins. They were gold. The boys

05:00:58.250 --> 05:01:02.910
above were as excited as themselves, and as delighted. Joe's comrade

05:01:02.910 --> 05:01:06.610
said, "'We'll make quick work of this. There's an old rusty pick over

05:01:06.610 --> 05:01:09.590
amongst the weeds in the corner, the other side of the fireplace. I saw

05:01:09.590 --> 05:01:13.830
it a minute ago.' He ran and brought the boys' pick and shovel. Injun

05:01:13.830 --> 05:01:17.930
Joe took the pick, looked it over critically, shook his head, muttered

05:01:17.930 --> 05:01:21.490
something to himself, and then began to use it. The box was soon

05:01:21.490 --> 05:01:26.510
unearthed. It was not very large. It was iron-bound, and had been very

05:01:26.510 --> 05:01:30.550
strong before the slow years had injured it. The men contemplated the

05:01:30.550 --> 05:01:32.350
treasure a while, in blissful silence.

05:01:33.010 --> 05:01:36.790
"'Pard, there's thousands of dollars here,' said Injun Joe.

05:01:37.170 --> 05:01:40.870
"'Twas always said that Murrell's gang used to be around here one

05:01:40.870 --> 05:01:42.210
summer,' the stranger observed.

05:01:42.530 --> 05:01:46.090
"'I know it,' said Injun Joe. And this looks like it, I should say.

05:01:46.490 --> 05:01:48.890
"'Now you won't need to do that job.'

05:01:49.450 --> 05:01:51.370
The half-breed frowned, said he.

05:01:51.650 --> 05:01:56.130
"'You don't know me. Least you don't know all about that thing. Taint

05:01:56.130 --> 05:02:00.490
robbery altogether. It's revenge.' And a wicked light flamed in his

05:02:00.490 --> 05:02:05.150
eyes. I'll need your help in it. When it's finished, then Texas. Go

05:02:05.150 --> 05:02:08.470
home to your nance and your kids, and stand by till you hear from me.'

05:02:09.090 --> 05:02:12.630
"'Well, if you say so. What'll we do with this? Bury it again?'

05:02:13.590 --> 05:02:15.610
"'Yes,' ravishing delight overhead.

05:02:15.950 --> 05:02:21.230
"'No, by the great Sackham, no!' profound distress overhead. I'd nearly

05:02:21.230 --> 05:02:25.930
forgot. That pick had fresh earth on it.' The boys were sick with terror

05:02:25.930 --> 05:02:30.610
in a moment. What business has a pick and a shovel here? What business

05:02:30.610 --> 05:02:34.650
with fresh earth on them? Who brought them here? And where are they

05:02:34.650 --> 05:02:39.470
gone? Have you heard anybody? Seen anybody? What, bury it again and

05:02:39.470 --> 05:02:43.550
leave them to come and see the ground disturbed? Not exactly. Not

05:02:43.550 --> 05:02:46.090
exactly. We'll take it to my den.'

05:02:46.730 --> 05:02:50.870
"'Why, of course. Might have thought of that before. You mean number

05:02:51.590 --> 05:02:56.250
No. Number two, under the cross. The other place is bad. Too common.'

05:02:56.970 --> 05:02:59.130
"'All right. It's nearly dark enough to start.'

05:02:59.530 --> 05:03:02.990
Injun Joe got up and went about from window to window, cautiously

05:03:02.990 --> 05:03:04.650
peeping out. Presently he said,

05:03:04.910 --> 05:03:08.730
"'Who could have brought those tools here? Do you reckon they can be

05:03:09.350 --> 05:03:09.870
upstairs?'

05:03:09.870 --> 05:03:13.930
The boys' breath forsook them. Injun Joe put his hand on his knife,

05:03:14.330 --> 05:03:18.770
halted a moment, undecided, and then turned toward the stairway. The

05:03:18.770 --> 05:03:22.450
boys thought of the closet, but their strength was gone. The steps

05:03:22.450 --> 05:03:26.490
came creaking up the stairs. The intolerable distress of the situation

05:03:26.490 --> 05:03:29.930
woke the stricken resolution of the lads. They were about to spring for

05:03:29.930 --> 05:03:33.310
the closet, when there was a crash of rotten timbers and Joe landed on

05:03:33.310 --> 05:03:37.170
the ground amid debris of the ruined stairway. He gathered himself up,

05:03:37.250 --> 05:03:38.610
cursing, and his comrades said,

05:03:38.930 --> 05:03:42.390
"'Now what's the use of all that? If it's anybody and they're up there,

05:03:42.610 --> 05:03:46.310
let them stay there. Who cares? If they want to jump down now and get

05:03:46.310 --> 05:03:50.270
into trouble, who objects? It will be dark in fifteen minutes. And

05:03:50.270 --> 05:03:54.150
then let them follow us if they want to. I'm willing. In my opinion,

05:03:54.290 --> 05:03:57.490
whoever hoved those things in here caught a sight of us and took us for

05:03:57.490 --> 05:04:00.210
ghosts or devils or something. I'll bet they're running yet.'

05:04:00.810 --> 05:04:04.330
Joe grumbled a while. Then he agreed with his friend that what

05:04:04.330 --> 05:04:07.910
daylight was left ought to be economized in getting things ready for

05:04:07.910 --> 05:04:11.210
leaving. Shortly afterward they slipped out of the house in the

05:04:11.210 --> 05:04:14.590
deepening twilight and moved towards the river with their precious

05:04:14.590 --> 05:04:20.210
gold box. Tom and Huck rose up, weak but vastly relieved, and stared

05:04:20.210 --> 05:04:23.910
after them through the chinks between the logs of the house. Follow?

05:04:24.330 --> 05:04:28.330
Not they. They were content to reach ground again without broken necks

05:04:28.330 --> 05:04:32.690
and take the townward track over the hill. They did not talk much. They

05:04:32.690 --> 05:04:36.630
were too much absorbed in hating themselves, hating the ill luck that

05:04:36.630 --> 05:04:40.770
made them take the spade and the pick there. But for that Injun Joe

05:04:40.770 --> 05:04:44.070
never would have suspected. He would have hidden the silver with the

05:04:44.070 --> 05:04:48.190
gold to wait there till his revenge was satisfied, and then he would

05:04:48.190 --> 05:04:52.150
have had the misfortune to find that money turn up missing. Bitter,

05:04:52.290 --> 05:04:56.330
bitter luck that the tools were ever brought there. They resolved to

05:04:56.330 --> 05:05:00.150
keep a look out for that Spaniard, when he should come to town spying

05:05:00.150 --> 05:05:04.910
out for chances to do his revengeful job, and follow him to Number Two,

05:05:04.950 --> 05:05:08.490
wherever that might be. Then a ghastly thought occurred to Tom.

05:05:09.290 --> 05:05:14.870
Revenge? What if he means us, Huck? Oh, don't, said Huck, nearly

05:05:14.870 --> 05:05:18.950
fainting. They talked it all over, and as they entered town they agreed

05:05:18.950 --> 05:05:23.010
to believe that he might possibly mean somebody else, at least that he

05:05:23.010 --> 05:05:28.670
might at least mean nobody but Tom, since only Tom had testified. Very,

05:05:28.670 --> 05:05:33.490
very small comfort it was to Tom to be alone in danger. Company would be

05:05:33.490 --> 05:05:35.050
palpable improvement, he thought.

05:05:52.770 --> 05:05:55.510
XXVII. Trembling on the Trail.

05:05:56.910 --> 05:06:02.370
The adventure of the day mightily tormented Tom's dreams that night. Four times he had

05:06:02.370 --> 05:06:07.470
his hands on that rich treasure, and four times it wasted to nothingness in his fingers,

05:06:07.890 --> 05:06:13.010
as sleep forsook him, and wakefulness brought back the hard reality of his misfortune.

05:06:13.370 --> 05:06:18.170
As he lay in the early morning recalling the incidents of his great adventure, he noticed

05:06:18.170 --> 05:06:23.230
that they seemed curiously subdued and far away, somewhat as if they had happened in

05:06:23.230 --> 05:06:28.850
another world, or in a time long gone by. Then it occurred to him that the great adventure

05:06:28.850 --> 05:06:35.070
must be a dream. There was one very strong argument in favour of this idea, namely, that

05:06:35.070 --> 05:06:41.170
the quantity of coin he had seen was too vast to be real. He had never seen as much as fifty

05:06:41.170 --> 05:06:46.130
dollars in one mass before, and he was like all boys of his age and stationed in life,

05:06:46.490 --> 05:06:51.850
in that he imagined that all references to hundreds and thousands were mere fanciful

05:06:51.850 --> 05:06:58.170
forms of speech, and that no such sums really existed in the world. He never had supposed

05:06:58.170 --> 05:07:03.790
for a moment that so large a sum as a hundred dollars was to be found in actual money in

05:07:03.790 --> 05:07:09.410
any one's possession. If his notions of hidden treasure had been analysed, they would have

05:07:09.410 --> 05:07:15.270
been found to consist of a handful of real dimes and a bushel of vague, splendid, ungraspable

05:07:15.270 --> 05:07:15.770
dollars.

05:07:16.370 --> 05:07:21.270
But the incidents of his adventure grew sensibly sharper and clearer under the attrition of

05:07:21.270 --> 05:07:25.730
thinking them over, and so he presently found himself leaning to the impression that the

05:07:25.730 --> 05:07:32.250
might not have been a dream, after all. This uncertainty must be swept away. He would snatch

05:07:32.250 --> 05:07:34.230
a hurried breakfast and go and find Huck.

05:07:34.710 --> 05:07:39.290
Huck was sitting on the gunnel of a flatboat, listlessly dangling his feet in the water

05:07:39.290 --> 05:07:44.730
and looking very melancholy. Tom concluded to let Huck lead up to the subject. If he

05:07:44.730 --> 05:07:49.070
did not do it, then the adventure would be proved to have been only a dream.

05:07:49.710 --> 05:07:50.350
Hello, Huck.

05:07:50.730 --> 05:07:51.630
Hello, yourself.

05:07:52.030 --> 05:07:53.090
Silence for a minute.

05:07:53.630 --> 05:07:59.090
Tom, if we'd left the blamed tools at the dead tree, we'd have got the money. Oh, ain't

05:07:59.090 --> 05:07:59.650
it awful!

05:08:00.450 --> 05:08:05.830
Taint a dream, then! Taint a dream! Somehow I most wish it was. Dogged if I don't, Huck.

05:08:06.350 --> 05:08:07.290
What ain't a dream?

05:08:07.650 --> 05:08:13.990
Oh, that thing yesterday! I'd been half-thinking it was. Dream! If them stairs hadn't broke

05:08:13.990 --> 05:08:18.690
down, you'd have seen how much dream it was. I've had dreams enough all night, with that

05:08:18.690 --> 05:08:22.430
patch-eyed Spanish devil going for me all through him. Rot him!

05:08:23.250 --> 05:08:29.870
No, not rot him! Find him! Track the money! Tom, we'll never find him. A feller don't

05:08:29.870 --> 05:08:35.010
have only one chance for such a pile, and that one's lost. I'd feel mighty shaky if

05:08:35.010 --> 05:08:36.350
I was to see him, anyway.

05:08:37.010 --> 05:08:42.170
Well, so'd I. But I'd like to see him anyway. Track him out. To his number two.

05:08:42.790 --> 05:08:48.090
Number two, yes, that's it. I've been thinking about that. But I can't make nothing out

05:08:48.090 --> 05:08:49.930
of it. What do you reckon it is?

05:08:50.230 --> 05:08:52.110
I don't know. It's too deep.

05:08:52.710 --> 05:08:55.170
Say, Huck, maybe it's the number of a house.

05:08:55.890 --> 05:09:01.350
Goodie! No, Tom, that ain't it. If it is, it ain't in this one-horse town. There ain't

05:09:01.350 --> 05:09:02.330
no numbers here.

05:09:02.810 --> 05:09:08.550
Well, that's so. Let me think a minute. Here, it's the number of a room, in a tavern, you

05:09:08.550 --> 05:09:08.850
know.

05:09:09.350 --> 05:09:15.010
Oh, that's the trick. There ain't only two taverns. We can find out quick. You stay here,

05:09:15.010 --> 05:09:15.830
Huck, till I come.

05:09:16.750 --> 05:09:22.190
Tom was off at once. He did not care to have Huck's company in public places. He was gone

05:09:22.190 --> 05:09:27.650
half an hour. He found that in the best tavern, number two had long been occupied by a young

05:09:27.650 --> 05:09:33.770
lawyer and was still so occupied. In the less ostentatious house, number two was a mystery.

05:09:34.250 --> 05:09:38.470
The tavern keeper's young son said it was kept locked all the time, and he never saw

05:09:38.470 --> 05:09:43.570
anybody go into it or come out of it except at night. He did not know any particular reason

05:09:43.570 --> 05:09:49.190
for this state of things, had had some little curiosity, but it was rather feeble, had made

05:09:49.190 --> 05:09:54.330
the most of the mystery by entertaining himself with the idea that the room was haunted, had

05:09:54.330 --> 05:09:57.190
noticed that there was a light in there the night before.

05:09:57.690 --> 05:10:02.390
That's what I've found out, Huck. I reckon that's the very number two we're after.

05:10:02.970 --> 05:10:06.170
I reckon it is, Tom. Now, what you going to do?

05:10:06.690 --> 05:10:07.370
Let me think.

05:10:07.990 --> 05:10:09.870
Tom thought a long time. Then he said,

05:10:09.870 --> 05:10:15.090
I'll tell you. The back door of that number two is the door that comes out into the little

05:10:15.090 --> 05:10:20.510
close alley between the tavern and the old rattle-trap of a brick store. Now, you get

05:10:20.510 --> 05:10:25.490
hold of all the door-keys you can find, and I'll nip all of Anty's, and the first dark

05:10:25.490 --> 05:10:29.930
night we'll go there and try him. And mind you, keep a look out for Injun Joe, because

05:10:29.930 --> 05:10:33.810
he said he was going to drop into town and spy around once more for a chance to get his

05:10:33.810 --> 05:10:38.550
revenge. If you see him, you just follow him, and if he don't go to that number two, that

05:10:38.550 --> 05:10:39.350
ain't the place.

05:10:40.170 --> 05:10:42.690
Lordy, I don't want to follow him by myself.

05:10:43.230 --> 05:10:49.430
Why, it'll be a night, sure. He might never see you. And if he did, maybe he'd never think

05:10:49.430 --> 05:10:49.830
anything.

05:10:50.530 --> 05:10:53.310
Well, if it's pretty dark, I reckon I'll track him.

05:10:53.490 --> 05:10:55.470
I don't know. I don't know.

05:10:55.850 --> 05:10:56.590
I'll try.

05:10:57.310 --> 05:11:02.610
You bet I'll follow him, if it's dark, Huck. Why, he might have found out that you couldn't

05:11:02.610 --> 05:11:05.410
get his revenge and be going right after that money.

05:11:05.970 --> 05:11:09.670
It's so, Tom, it's so. I'll follow him. I will, by jingos.

05:11:10.110 --> 05:11:14.330
Now you're talking! Don't you ever weaken Huck, and I won't.

05:11:17.930 --> 05:11:18.970
CHAPTER XXVIII.

05:11:19.630 --> 05:11:21.590
In the lair of Injun Joe.

05:11:22.750 --> 05:11:26.990
That night Tom and Huck were ready for their adventure. They hung about the neighborhood

05:11:26.990 --> 05:11:31.970
of the tavern until after nine, one watching the alley at a distance, and the other the

05:11:31.970 --> 05:11:37.590
door. Nobody entered the alley or left it. Nobody resembling the Spaniard entered or

05:11:37.590 --> 05:11:43.790
left the tavern door. The night promised to be a fair one, so Tom went home with the understanding

05:11:43.790 --> 05:11:49.690
that if a considerable degree of darkness came on, Huck was to come and mow, whereupon

05:11:49.690 --> 05:11:55.170
he would slip out and try the keys. But the night remained clear, and Huck closed his

05:11:55.170 --> 05:11:58.990
watch and retired to bed in an empty sugar hog's head about twelve.

05:11:59.850 --> 05:12:05.550
Tuesday the boys had the same ill luck. Also Wednesday. But Thursday night promised better.

05:12:06.010 --> 05:12:11.610
Tom slipped out in good season with his aunt's old tin lantern and a large towel to blindfold

05:12:11.610 --> 05:12:17.430
it with. He hid the lantern in Huck's sugar hog's head, and the watch began. An hour before

05:12:17.430 --> 05:12:22.090
midnight the tavern closed up, and its lights, the only ones thereabouts, were put out.

05:12:22.530 --> 05:12:27.930
No Spaniard had been seen. Nobody entered or left the alley. Everything was auspicious.

05:12:27.930 --> 05:12:33.230
The blackness of darkness reigned. The perfect stillness was interrupted only by occasional

05:12:33.230 --> 05:12:38.790
mutterings of distant thunder. Tom got his lantern, lit it in the hog's head, wrapped

05:12:38.790 --> 05:12:44.150
it closely in the towel, and the two adventurers crept in the gloom toward the tavern. Huck

05:12:44.150 --> 05:12:49.010
stood sentry, and Tom felt his way into the alley. Then there was a season of waiting

05:12:49.010 --> 05:12:53.510
anxiety that weighed upon Huck's spirits like a mountain. He began to wish he could

05:12:53.510 --> 05:12:57.930
a flash from the lantern. It would frighten him, but it would at least tell him that Tom

05:12:57.930 --> 05:13:03.470
was alive yet. It seemed hours since Tom had disappeared. Surely he must have fainted.

05:13:03.570 --> 05:13:08.930
Maybe he was dead. Maybe his heart had burst under terror and excitement. In his uneasiness

05:13:08.930 --> 05:13:14.090
Huck found himself drawing closer and closer to the alley, fearing all sorts of dreadful

05:13:14.090 --> 05:13:18.330
things and momentarily expecting some catastrophe to happen that would take away his breath.

05:13:18.810 --> 05:13:24.430
There was not much to take away, for he seemed only able to inhale it by thimble-fuls, and

05:13:24.430 --> 05:13:28.930
his heart would soon wear itself out the way it was beating. Suddenly there was a flash

05:13:28.930 --> 05:13:30.770
of light and Tom came tearing by him.

05:13:30.970 --> 05:13:32.990
"'Run!' said he. "'Run for your life!'

05:13:32.990 --> 05:13:38.190
He needn't have repeated it. Once was enough. Huck was making thirty or forty miles an hour

05:13:38.190 --> 05:13:42.150
before the repetition was uttered. The boys never stopped till they reached the shed of

05:13:42.150 --> 05:13:46.050
a deserted slaughter-house at the lower end of the village. Just as they got within its

05:13:46.050 --> 05:13:50.690
shelter the storm burst and the rain poured down. As soon as Tom got his breath he said,

05:13:51.030 --> 05:13:56.730
"'Huck, it was awful! I tried two of the keys, just as soft as I could, but they seemed to

05:13:56.730 --> 05:14:01.890
make such a power of a racket that I couldn't hardly get my breath, I was so scared. They

05:14:01.890 --> 05:14:06.570
wouldn't turn in the lock either. Well, without noticing what I was doing, I took hold of

05:14:06.570 --> 05:14:12.050
the knob and open comes the door. It warn't locked. I hopped in and shook off the towel

05:14:12.050 --> 05:14:14.510
and—'Great Caesar's Ghost!'

05:14:14.510 --> 05:14:16.410
"'What? What you see, Tom?'

05:14:16.410 --> 05:14:19.650
"'Huck, I most stepped on to Injun Joe's hand.'

05:14:20.270 --> 05:14:20.770
"'No.'

05:14:20.770 --> 05:14:25.590
"'Yes. He was laying there, sound asleep on the floor, with his old patch on his eye and

05:14:25.590 --> 05:14:29.730
his arms spread out. Lordy, what did you do? Did he wake up?'

05:14:29.730 --> 05:14:34.070
"'No, never budged. Drunk, I reckon. I just grabbed that towel and started.'

05:14:34.790 --> 05:14:36.840
"'I'd never thought of the towel, I bet.'

05:14:37.270 --> 05:14:40.720
"'Well, I would. My aunt would make me mighty sick if I lost it.'

05:14:41.310 --> 05:14:43.590
"'Say, Tom, did you see that box?'

05:14:43.590 --> 05:14:48.630
"'Huck, I didn't wait to look around. I didn't see the box, I didn't see the cross. I didn't

05:14:48.630 --> 05:14:53.410
see anything but a bottle and a tin cup on the floor by Injun Joe. Yes, and I saw two

05:14:53.410 --> 05:14:55.710
barrels and lots more bottles in the room.'

05:14:55.710 --> 05:14:59.270
"'Don't you see, now? What's the matter with that haunted room?'

05:15:00.150 --> 05:15:00.630
"'How?'

05:15:00.630 --> 05:15:05.690
"'Why, it's haunted with whiskey. Maybe all the Temperance Taverns have got a haunted

05:15:05.690 --> 05:15:07.230
room, hey, Huck?'

05:15:07.230 --> 05:15:12.090
"'Well, I reckon maybe that's so. Who'd a thought such a thing. But say, Tom, now's

05:15:12.090 --> 05:15:14.970
a mighty good time to get that box if Injun Joe's drunk.'

05:15:14.970 --> 05:15:18.050
"'It is that. You try it.' Huck shuddered.

05:15:18.750 --> 05:15:21.230
"'Well, no, I reckon not.'

05:15:21.230 --> 05:15:26.130
"'And I reckon not, Huck. Only one bottle alongside of Injun Joe ain't enough. If there'd

05:15:26.130 --> 05:15:30.370
been three, he'd be drunk enough and I'd do it.' There was a long pause for reflection,

05:15:30.430 --> 05:15:31.230
and then Tom said,

05:15:31.890 --> 05:15:36.810
"'Looky here, Huck, let's not try that thing any more till we know Injun Joe's not in there.

05:15:36.810 --> 05:15:42.750
It's too scary. Now, if we watch every night, we'll be dead sure to see him go out, some

05:15:42.750 --> 05:15:45.670
time or other, and then we'll snatch that box quicker in lightning.'

05:15:46.390 --> 05:15:51.270
"'Well, I'm agreed. I'll watch the whole night long, and I'll do it every night, too, if

05:15:51.270 --> 05:15:52.590
you'll do the other part of the job.'

05:15:53.590 --> 05:15:58.490
"'All right, I will. All you got to do is to trot up Hooper Street a block and mow,

05:15:58.770 --> 05:16:02.990
and if I'm asleep, you throw some gravel at the window and that'll fetch me.'

05:16:02.990 --> 05:16:04.790
"'Agreed. And good as wheat.'

05:16:05.570 --> 05:16:09.610
"'Now, Huck, the storm's over and I'll go home. It'll begin to be daylight in a couple

05:16:09.610 --> 05:16:12.570
hours. You go back and watch that long, will you?'

05:16:12.570 --> 05:16:17.870
"'I said I would, Tom, and I will. I'll hant that tavern every night for a year. I'll sleep

05:16:17.870 --> 05:16:20.130
all day and I'll stand watch all night.'

05:16:20.130 --> 05:16:23.390
"'That's all right. Now, where are you going to sleep?'

05:16:23.390 --> 05:16:29.590
In Ben Rogers' hayloft. He lets me, and so does his pap's nigger man, Uncle Jake. I tote

05:16:29.590 --> 05:16:34.030
water for Uncle Jake whenever he wants me to, and any time I ask him he gives me a little

05:16:34.030 --> 05:16:39.450
something to eat if he can spare it. That's a mighty good nigger, Tom. He likes me, because

05:16:39.450 --> 05:16:45.610
I don't ever act as if I was above him. Sometimes I sit right down and eat with him. But you

05:16:45.610 --> 05:16:49.950
needn't tell that. A body's got to do things when he's awful hungry he wouldn't want to

05:16:49.950 --> 05:16:54.830
do as a steady thing. Well, if I don't want you in the daytime, I'll let you sleep. I

05:16:54.830 --> 05:16:59.190
won't come bothering round. Any time you see something's up in the night, just skip right

05:16:59.190 --> 05:17:00.030
around and mow.'

05:17:16.250 --> 05:17:19.290
XXIX. Huck Saves the Widow.

05:17:20.350 --> 05:17:26.200
The first thing Tom heard on Friday morning was a glad piece of news. Judge Thatcher's

05:17:26.200 --> 05:17:31.940
family had come back to town the night before. Both Inge and Joe and the treasurer sank

05:17:31.940 --> 05:17:36.800
into secondary importance for a moment, and Becky took the chief place in the boy's interest.

05:17:37.160 --> 05:17:43.400
He saw her, and they had an exhausting good time playing High Spy and Gully Keeper with

05:17:43.400 --> 05:17:48.860
a crowd of their schoolmates. The day was completed and crowned in a peculiarly satisfactory

05:17:48.860 --> 05:17:54.240
way. Becky teased her mother to appoint the next day for the long-promised and long-delayed

05:17:54.240 --> 05:18:00.860
picnic, and she consented. The child's delight was boundless, and Tom's not more moderate.

05:18:01.420 --> 05:18:06.220
The invitations were sent out before sunset, and straightway the young folks of the village

05:18:06.220 --> 05:18:12.120
were thrown into a fever of preparation and pleasurable anticipation. Tom's excitement

05:18:12.120 --> 05:18:17.680
enabled him to keep awake until a pretty late hour, and he had good hopes of hearing Huck's

05:18:17.680 --> 05:18:24.740
and of having his treasure to astonish Becky and the picnickers with next day. But he was

05:18:24.740 --> 05:18:31.500
disappointed. No signal came that night. Morning came, eventually, and by ten or eleven o'clock

05:18:31.500 --> 05:18:36.480
a giddy and rollicking company were gathered at Judge Thatcher's, and everything was ready

05:18:36.480 --> 05:18:41.800
for a start. It was not the custom for elderly people to mar picnics with their presence.

05:18:42.120 --> 05:18:46.560
The children were considered safe enough under the wings of a few young ladies of eighteen,

05:18:46.560 --> 05:18:52.020
and a few young gentlemen of twenty-three or thereabouts. The old steam ferry-boat

05:18:52.020 --> 05:18:57.280
was chartered for the occasion. Presently the gay throng filed up the main street laden

05:18:57.280 --> 05:19:03.040
with provision baskets. Sid was sick, and had to miss the fun. Mary remained at home

05:19:03.040 --> 05:19:06.780
to entertain him. The last thing Mrs. Thatcher said to Becky was,

05:19:07.200 --> 05:19:11.760
"'You'll not get back till late. Perhaps you'd better stay all night with some of the girls

05:19:11.760 --> 05:19:14.320
that live near the ferry landing, child.'

05:19:14.320 --> 05:19:16.860
"'Then I'll stay with Susy Harper, Mama.'

05:19:16.860 --> 05:19:21.020
"'Very well. And mind and behave yourself, and don't be any trouble.'

05:19:21.880 --> 05:19:24.640
Presently, as they tripped along, Tom said to Becky,

05:19:25.600 --> 05:19:30.440
"'Say, I'll tell you what we'll do. Instead of going to Joe Harper's, we'll climb right

05:19:30.440 --> 05:19:36.020
up the hill and stop at the Widow Douglas's. She'll have ice cream—she has it most every

05:19:36.560 --> 05:19:40.340
day—dead loads of it—and she'll be awful glad to have us.'

05:19:40.340 --> 05:19:42.640
"'Oh, that will be fun!'

05:19:42.640 --> 05:19:44.400
Then Becky reflected a moment and said,

05:19:44.640 --> 05:19:46.340
"'But what will Mama say?'

05:19:46.340 --> 05:19:47.880
"'All she'll ever know.'

05:19:47.880 --> 05:19:51.500
The girl turned the idea over in her mind, and said reluctantly,

05:19:52.060 --> 05:19:54.340
"'I reckon it's wrong, but—'

05:19:54.420 --> 05:19:59.160
"'But, shucks, your mother won't know, and so what's the harm? All she wants is that

05:19:59.160 --> 05:20:04.300
you'll be safe. And I bet you she'd have said, Go there, if she'd a thought about it. I know

05:20:04.300 --> 05:20:05.360
she would.'

05:20:05.360 --> 05:20:10.860
The Widow Douglas's splendid hospitality was a tempting bait. It and Tom's persuasions

05:20:10.860 --> 05:20:15.300
presently carried the day, so it was decided to say nothing to anybody about the night's

05:20:15.300 --> 05:20:19.980
program. Presently it occurred to Tom that maybe Huck might come in this very night and

05:20:19.980 --> 05:20:24.880
give the signal. The thought took a deal of the spirit out of his anticipation. Still,

05:20:24.880 --> 05:20:29.580
he could not bear to give up the fun at Widow Douglas's. And why should he give it up, he

05:20:29.580 --> 05:20:34.000
reasoned? The signal did not come the night before, so why should it be any more likely

05:20:34.000 --> 05:20:40.120
to come to-night? The sure fun of the evening outweighed the uncertain treasure, and, boylike,

05:20:40.240 --> 05:20:44.840
he determined to yield to the stronger inclination and not allow himself to think of the box

05:20:44.840 --> 05:20:46.420
of money another time that day.

05:20:47.300 --> 05:20:51.640
Three miles below town the ferry-boat stopped at the mouth of the woody hollow and tied

05:20:51.640 --> 05:20:57.280
up. The crowd swarmed ashore, and soon the forest distances and craggy heights echoed

05:20:57.280 --> 05:21:02.240
far and near with shoutings and laughter. All the different ways of getting hot and tired

05:21:02.240 --> 05:21:08.240
with, and by and by the rovers straggled back to camp, fortified with responsible appetites,

05:21:08.520 --> 05:21:13.540
and then the destruction of the good things began. After the feast there was a refreshing

05:21:13.540 --> 05:21:18.380
season of rest and chat in the shade of spreading oaks. By and by somebody shouted,

05:21:18.820 --> 05:21:20.460
"'Who's ready for the cave?'

05:21:21.340 --> 05:21:26.380
"'Everybody was.' Bundles of candles were procured, and straight away there was a general

05:21:26.380 --> 05:21:31.360
scamper up the hill. The mouth of the cave was up the hillside, an opening shaped like

05:21:31.360 --> 05:21:37.500
the letter A. Its massive oaken door stood unbarred. Within was a small chamber, chilly

05:21:37.500 --> 05:21:42.760
as an ice-house, and walled by nature with solid limestone that was dewy with a cold

05:21:42.760 --> 05:21:48.700
sweat. It was romantic and mysterious to stand here in the deep gloom and look out upon the

05:21:48.700 --> 05:21:54.360
green valley shining in the sun. But the impressiveness of the situation quickly wore off, and the

05:21:54.360 --> 05:21:59.300
romping began again. The moment a candle was lighted there was a general rush upon the

05:21:59.300 --> 05:22:03.980
owner of it. A struggle and a gallant defence followed, but the candle was soon knocked

05:22:03.980 --> 05:22:09.280
down or blown out, and then there was a glad clamour of laughter and a new chase. But all

05:22:09.280 --> 05:22:14.080
things have an end. By and by the procession went filing down the steep descent of the

05:22:14.080 --> 05:22:19.700
main avenue, the flickering rank of lights dimly revealing the lofty walls of rock almost

05:22:19.700 --> 05:22:25.060
to their point of junction sixty feet overhead. This main avenue was not more than eight or

05:22:25.060 --> 05:22:30.880
ten feet wide. Every few steps other lofty and still narrower crevices branched from

05:22:30.880 --> 05:22:36.820
it on either hand, for MacDougall's cave was but a vast labyrinth of crooked aisles that

05:22:36.820 --> 05:22:42.280
ran into each other and out again and led nowhere. It was said that one might wander

05:22:42.280 --> 05:22:47.460
days and nights together through its intricate tangle of rifts and chasms, and never find

05:22:47.460 --> 05:22:52.060
the end of the cave, and that he might go down and down and still down into the earth,

05:22:52.060 --> 05:22:58.660
and it was just the same—labyrinth, underneath labyrinth, and no end to any of them. No man

05:22:58.660 --> 05:23:04.420
knew the cave. That was an impossible thing. Most of the young men knew a portion of it,

05:23:04.460 --> 05:23:09.900
and it was not customary to venture much beyond this known portion. Tom Sawyer knew as much

05:23:09.900 --> 05:23:15.040
of the cave as any one. The procession moved along the main avenue some three quarters

05:23:15.040 --> 05:23:20.700
of a mile, then groups and couples began to slip aside into branch avenues, fly along

05:23:20.700 --> 05:23:24.840
the dismal corridors, and take each other by surprise at points where the corridors

05:23:24.840 --> 05:23:29.680
joined again. Parties were able to elude each other for the space of half an hour without

05:23:29.680 --> 05:23:35.980
going beyond the known ground. By and by one group after another came straggling back to

05:23:35.980 --> 05:23:41.260
the mouth of the cave, panting, hilarious, smeared from head to foot with tallow-drippings,

05:23:41.760 --> 05:23:46.900
daubed with clay, and entirely delighted with the success of the day. Then they were astonished

05:23:46.900 --> 05:23:52.680
that they had been taking no note of time, and that night was about at hand. The clanging

05:23:52.680 --> 05:23:57.840
bell had been calling for half an hour. However, this sort of close to the day's adventures

05:23:57.840 --> 05:24:03.560
was romantic and therefore satisfactory. When the ferry-boat with her wild freight pushed

05:24:03.560 --> 05:24:08.700
into the stream, nobody cared sixpence for the wasted time but the captain of the craft.

05:24:09.760 --> 05:24:14.620
Huck was already upon his watch when the ferry-boat's lights went glinting past the wharf. He heard

05:24:14.620 --> 05:24:19.780
no noise on board, for the young people were as subdued and still as people usually are

05:24:19.780 --> 05:24:25.080
who were nearly tired to death. He wondered what boat it was, and why she did not stop

05:24:25.080 --> 05:24:29.460
at the wharf, and then he dropped her out of his mind and put his attention upon his

05:24:29.460 --> 05:24:35.060
business. The night was growing cloudy and dark. Ten o'clock came, and the noise of the

05:24:35.060 --> 05:24:41.000
vehicle ceased. Scattered lights began to wink out. All straggling foot-passengers disappeared.

05:24:41.310 --> 05:24:46.600
The village betook itself to its slumbers and left the small watcher alone with the

05:24:46.600 --> 05:24:51.780
silence and the ghosts. Eleven o'clock came, and the tavern lights were put out. Darkness

05:24:51.780 --> 05:24:58.660
everywhere now. Huck waited what seemed a weary long time, but nothing happened. His

05:24:58.660 --> 05:25:05.640
faith was weakening. Was there any use? Was there really any use? Why not give it up and

05:25:05.640 --> 05:25:06.220
turn in?

05:25:06.760 --> 05:25:12.560
A noise fell upon his ear. He was all attention in an instant. The alley-door closed softly.

05:25:13.000 --> 05:25:18.120
He sprang to the corner of the brick-store. The next moment two men brushed by him, and

05:25:18.120 --> 05:25:23.020
one seemed to have something under his arm. It must be that box. So they were going to

05:25:23.020 --> 05:25:28.380
remove the treasurer. Why call Tom now? It would be absurd. The men would get away with

05:25:28.380 --> 05:25:33.080
the box and never be found again. No, he would stick to their wake and follow them. He would

05:25:33.080 --> 05:25:38.540
trust to the darkness for security from discovery. So communing with himself, Huck stepped out

05:25:38.540 --> 05:25:43.600
and glided along behind the men, cat-like, with bare feet, allowing them to keep just

05:25:43.600 --> 05:25:48.520
far enough ahead not to be invisible. They moved up the river-street three blocks, then

05:25:48.520 --> 05:25:53.200
turned to the left up a cross-street. They went straight ahead, then, until they came

05:25:53.200 --> 05:25:58.640
to the path that led up Cardiff Hill. This they took. They passed by the old Welshman's

05:25:58.640 --> 05:26:04.880
house, half-way up the hill, without hesitating, and still climbed upward. Good thought, Huck!

05:26:05.100 --> 05:26:10.020
They will bury it in the old quarry. But they never stopped at the quarry. They passed on

05:26:10.020 --> 05:26:15.780
up the summit. They plunged into the narrow path between the tall Sumac bushes and were

05:26:15.780 --> 05:26:17.120
at once hidden in the gloom.

05:26:17.640 --> 05:26:22.300
Huck closed up and shortened his distance now, for they would never be able to see him.

05:26:22.500 --> 05:26:27.660
He trotted along a while, then slackened his pace, fearing he was gaining too fast, moved

05:26:27.660 --> 05:26:34.000
on apiece, then stopped altogether, listened. No sound. None, save that he seemed to hear

05:26:34.000 --> 05:26:38.600
the beating of his own heart. The hooting of an owl came from over the hill. Ominous

05:26:38.600 --> 05:26:45.320
sound! But no footsteps. Heavens! Was everything lost? He was about to spring with winged feet

05:26:45.320 --> 05:26:47.900
when a man cleared his throat not four feet from him.

05:26:48.560 --> 05:26:53.460
Huck's heart shot into his throat, but he swallowed it again, and then he stood there,

05:26:53.460 --> 05:26:59.160
shaking as if a dozen agues had taken charge of him at once, and so weak that he thought

05:26:59.160 --> 05:27:05.180
he must surely fall to the ground. He knew where he was. He knew he was within five steps

05:27:05.180 --> 05:27:10.860
of the stile leading into Widow Douglas's grounds. Very well, he thought, let them bury

05:27:10.860 --> 05:27:13.000
it there. It won't be hard to find.

05:27:13.680 --> 05:27:17.840
Now there was a voice, a very low voice, Injun Joe's.

05:27:18.400 --> 05:27:23.320
Damn her! Maybe she's got company. There's lights, late as it is.

05:27:23.900 --> 05:27:29.160
I can't see any. This was that stranger's voice, the stranger of the haunted house.

05:27:29.580 --> 05:27:35.880
A deadly chill went to Huck's heart. This, then, was the revenge job. His thought was

05:27:35.880 --> 05:27:40.600
to fly. Then he remembered that the Widow Douglas had been kind to him more than once,

05:27:40.800 --> 05:27:45.980
and maybe these men were going to murder her. He wished he dared venture to warn her, but

05:27:45.980 --> 05:27:50.940
he knew he didn't dare. They might come and catch him. He thought all this and more in

05:27:50.940 --> 05:27:54.980
the moment that the lapse between the stranger's remark and Injun Joe's next, which was,

05:27:55.200 --> 05:28:00.860
"'Because the bush is in your way. Now this way. Now you see, don't you?'

05:28:00.860 --> 05:28:05.360
"'Yes. Well, there is company there, I reckon. Better give it up.'

05:28:05.360 --> 05:28:10.780
"'Give it up? And I just leaving this country forever? Give it up, and maybe never have

05:28:10.780 --> 05:28:15.380
another chance? I tell you again, as I've told you before, I don't care for her swag.

05:28:15.380 --> 05:28:21.240
You may have it. But her husband was rough on me. Many times he was rough on me. And

05:28:21.240 --> 05:28:25.720
mainly he was the justice of the peace that jugged me for a vagrant. And that ain't all.

05:28:25.960 --> 05:28:31.060
It ain't a millionth part of it. He had me horse-whipped. Horse-whipped in front of the

05:28:31.060 --> 05:28:36.300
jail, like a nigger, with all the town looking on. Horse-whipped, do you understand? He took

05:28:36.300 --> 05:28:39.580
advantage of me and died, but I'll take it out of her.'

05:28:40.240 --> 05:28:46.280
"'Oh, don't kill her. Don't do that. Kill? Who said anything about killing? I would kill

05:28:46.280 --> 05:28:50.480
him if he were here, but not her. When you want to get revenge on a woman, you don't

05:28:50.480 --> 05:28:56.320
kill her. Bosh, you go for her looks. You slit her nostrils. You knot your ears, like

05:28:56.320 --> 05:28:58.720
a sow. By God, that's—'

05:28:59.300 --> 05:29:03.760
"'Keep your opinion to yourself. It will be safest for you. I'll tie her to the bed.

05:29:04.160 --> 05:29:09.560
If she bleeds to death, is that my fault? I'll not cry if she does. My friend, you'll

05:29:09.560 --> 05:29:13.980
get help in this thing, for my sake. That's why you're here. I mightn't be able to loan.

05:29:14.440 --> 05:29:18.820
If you flinch, I'll kill you. Do you understand that? And if I have to kill you, I'll kill

05:29:18.820 --> 05:29:24.320
her. And then I reckon nobody'll ever know much about who done this business. Well, if

05:29:24.320 --> 05:29:30.260
it's got to be done, let's get at it. The quicker the better. I'm all in a shiver. Do

05:29:30.260 --> 05:29:36.080
it now? And company there? Look here, I'll get suspicious of you. First thing you know—no,

05:29:36.080 --> 05:29:39.140
we'll wait till the lights are out. There's no hurry."

05:29:39.140 --> 05:29:44.000
Huck felt that a silence was going to ensue—a thing still more awful than any amount of

05:29:44.000 --> 05:29:49.360
murderous talk. So he held his breath and stepped gingerly back, planted his foot carefully

05:29:49.360 --> 05:29:55.500
and firmly, after balancing, one-legged, in a precarious way, and almost toppling over,

05:29:55.720 --> 05:30:01.100
first on one side and then on the other. He took another step back, with the same elaboration

05:30:01.100 --> 05:30:09.620
and the same risks, then another and another, and—a twig snapped under his foot. His breath

05:30:09.620 --> 05:30:15.940
stopped when he listened. There was no sound. The stillness was perfect. His gratitude was

05:30:15.940 --> 05:30:20.880
measureless. Now he turned in his tracks, between the walls of sumac bushes, turned

05:30:20.880 --> 05:30:25.260
himself as carefully as if he were a ship, and then stepped quickly but cautiously along.

05:30:25.620 --> 05:30:30.620
When he emerged at the quarry he felt secure, and so he picked up his nimble heels and flew,

05:30:30.620 --> 05:30:37.280
down, down he sped till he reached the Welshman's. He banged at the door, and presently the

05:30:37.280 --> 05:30:41.180
heads of the old man and his two stalwart sons were thrust from the windows.

05:30:41.540 --> 05:30:44.160
"'What's the row there? Who's banging? What do you want?'

05:30:44.160 --> 05:30:46.500
"'Let me in, quick! I'll tell everything.'

05:30:46.500 --> 05:30:48.040
"'Why, who are you?'

05:30:48.040 --> 05:30:50.740
"'Huckleberry Finn! Quick, let me in!'

05:30:50.740 --> 05:30:55.540
"'Huckleberry Finn, indeed. It ain't a name to open many doors, I judge. But let him in,

05:30:55.740 --> 05:30:57.260
lads, and let's see what's the trouble.'

05:30:57.260 --> 05:31:01.660
"'Please don't ever tell I told you,' were Huck's first words when he got in.

05:31:01.900 --> 05:31:06.800
"'Please don't. I'd be killed, sure. But the widow's been good friends to me sometimes,

05:31:06.800 --> 05:31:11.180
and I want to tell. I will tell, if you'll promise you won't ever say it was me.'

05:31:11.180 --> 05:31:16.180
"'By George, he has got something to tell, or he wouldn't act so,' exclaimed the old

05:31:16.180 --> 05:31:16.500
man.

05:31:16.800 --> 05:31:19.880
"'Out with it, and nobody here'll ever tell, lad.'

05:31:19.880 --> 05:31:24.240
Three minutes later the old man and his sons, well armed, were up the hill and just entering

05:31:24.240 --> 05:31:29.240
the Sumac path on tiptoe, their weapons in their hands. Huck accompanied them no farther.

05:31:29.600 --> 05:31:34.300
He hid behind a great boulder and fell to listening. There was a lagging, anxious silence,

05:31:34.520 --> 05:31:39.760
and then all of a sudden there was an explosion of firearms and a cry. Huck waited for no

05:31:39.760 --> 05:31:44.380
particulars. He sprang away and sped down the hill as fast as his legs could carry him.'

05:32:04.660 --> 05:32:10.100
As the earliest suspicion of dawn appeared on Sunday morning, Huck came groping up the

05:32:10.100 --> 05:32:15.220
hill and rapped gently at the old Welshman's door. The inmates were asleep, but it was

05:32:15.220 --> 05:32:20.700
set on a hair-trigger, on account of the exciting episode of the night. A call came from a

05:32:20.700 --> 05:32:21.040
window.

05:32:21.420 --> 05:32:25.440
"'Who's there?' Huck's scared voice answered in a low tone.

05:32:25.640 --> 05:32:28.500
"'Please let me in. It's only Huck Finn.'

05:32:28.500 --> 05:32:33.920
"'It's a name that can open this door night or day, lad, and welcome.' These were strange

05:32:33.920 --> 05:32:39.520
words to the vagabond boy's ears, and the pleasantest he had ever heard. He could not

05:32:39.520 --> 05:32:45.200
recollect that the closing word had ever been applied in his case before. The door was

05:32:45.200 --> 05:32:50.120
quickly unlocked, and he entered. Huck was given a seat, and the old man and his brace

05:32:50.120 --> 05:32:52.380
of tall suns speedily dressed themselves.

05:32:52.800 --> 05:32:57.320
"'Now, my boy, I hope you're good and hungry, because breakfast will be ready as soon as

05:32:57.320 --> 05:33:02.660
the sun's up, and we'll have a piping hot one, too. Make yourself easy about that. I and

05:33:02.660 --> 05:33:05.660
the boys hoped you'd turn up and stop here last night.'

05:33:05.660 --> 05:33:11.380
"'I was awful scared,' said Huck, and I run. I took out when the pistols went off, and

05:33:11.900 --> 05:33:17.480
for three miles. I've come now because I wanted to know about it, you know, and I come before

05:33:17.480 --> 05:33:22.320
daylight because I didn't want to run across them devils even if they was dead.'

05:33:22.320 --> 05:33:26.960
"'Well, poor chap, you do look as if you'd had a hard night of it. But there's a bed

05:33:26.960 --> 05:33:29.260
here for you, when you've had your breakfast.'

05:33:29.260 --> 05:33:34.460
"'No, they ain't dead, lad. We were sorry enough for that. You see, we knew rightward

05:33:34.460 --> 05:33:39.880
to put our hands on them, by your description, so we crept along on tiptoe till we got within

05:33:39.880 --> 05:33:45.680
fifteen feet of them, dark as the cellar that Sumac Path was. And just then I found I was

05:33:45.680 --> 05:33:50.940
going to sneeze. It was the meanest kind of luck. I tried to keep it back, but no use.

05:33:51.260 --> 05:33:56.500
It was bound to come, and it did come. I was in the lead with my pistol raised, and when

05:33:56.500 --> 05:34:01.200
the sneeze started, those scoundrels were rustling to get out of the path. I sung out

05:34:01.200 --> 05:34:06.580
FIRE, boys, and blazed away at the place where the rustling was. So did the boys. But they

05:34:06.580 --> 05:34:11.260
were off in a jiffy, those villains, and we after them down through the woods. I judge

05:34:11.260 --> 05:34:15.660
we never touched them. They fired a shot apiece as they started, but their bullets whizzed

05:34:15.660 --> 05:34:20.360
by and didn't do us any harm. As soon as we lost the sound of their feet, we quit chasing,

05:34:20.800 --> 05:34:25.560
and went down and stirred up the constables. They got a posse together, and went off to

05:34:25.560 --> 05:34:29.960
guard the river bank. And as soon as it is light, the sheriff and a gang are going to

05:34:29.960 --> 05:34:35.260
beat up the woods. My boys will be with them presently. I wish we had some sort of description

05:34:35.260 --> 05:34:39.660
of those rascals. It would help a good deal. But you couldn't see what they were like

05:34:39.660 --> 05:34:41.660
in the dark, lad, I suppose.

05:34:42.240 --> 05:34:44.920
Oh, yes, I saw them down town and followed them.

05:34:45.480 --> 05:34:48.400
Splendid! Describe them! Describe them, my boy!

05:34:49.200 --> 05:34:54.060
One is the old deaf and dumb Spaniard that's been round here once or twice, and tothers

05:34:54.060 --> 05:34:55.560
a mean-looking ragged—

05:34:55.560 --> 05:35:00.240
That's enough, lad, we know the men. Happened on them in the woods, back of the widows one

05:35:00.240 --> 05:35:01.760
day, and they slunk away.

05:35:02.240 --> 05:35:05.760
Off with you, boys, and tell the sheriff, get your breakfast tomorrow morning."

05:35:05.760 --> 05:35:10.280
The Welshman's sons departed at once. As they were leaving the room, Huck sprang up and

05:35:10.280 --> 05:35:10.600
exclaimed,

05:35:10.780 --> 05:35:14.980
Oh, please don't tell anybody it was me that blowed on them! Oh, please!

05:35:15.480 --> 05:35:19.1000
All right, if you say it, Huck, but you ought to have the credit of what you did. Oh, no,

05:35:20.060 --> 05:35:21.380
no, please don't tell!

05:35:21.780 --> 05:35:24.380
When the young men were gone, the old Welshman said,

05:35:24.760 --> 05:35:28.180
They won't tell, and I won't. But why don't you want it known?

05:35:28.780 --> 05:35:33.480
Huck would not explain. Further than to say that he already knew too much about one of

05:35:33.480 --> 05:35:37.980
those men, and would not have the man know that he knew anything against him for the

05:35:37.980 --> 05:35:40.1000
whole world. He would be killed for knowing it, sure.

05:35:41.720 --> 05:35:44.520
The old man promised secrecy once more, and said,

05:35:44.840 --> 05:35:48.840
How did you come to follow these fellows, lad? Were they looking suspicious?

05:35:49.400 --> 05:35:54.140
Huck was silent, while he framed a duly cautious reply, and then he said,

05:35:54.700 --> 05:36:00.260
Well, you see, I'm a kind of a hard lot, at least everybody says so, and I don't see nothing

05:36:00.260 --> 05:36:05.840
again it, and sometimes I can't sleep much on accounts of thinking about it, and sort

05:36:05.840 --> 05:36:10.280
of trying to strike out a new way of doing. That was the way it was last night, I couldn't

05:36:10.280 --> 05:36:14.740
sleep, and so I come along up street about midnight at turning it all over, and when

05:36:14.740 --> 05:36:19.760
I got to that old shackly brick store by the Temperance Tavern, I backed up again the wall

05:36:19.760 --> 05:36:24.500
to have another think. Well, just then along comes these two chaps, slipping along close

05:36:24.500 --> 05:36:29.420
by me, with something under their arm, and I reckoned they'd stole it. One was a-smoking,

05:36:29.820 --> 05:36:34.180
and t'other one wanted a light, so they stopped right before me, and the cigars lit up their

05:36:34.180 --> 05:36:38.860
faces, and I see that the big one was the deaf and dumb Spaniard, by his white whiskers

05:36:38.860 --> 05:36:44.160
and the patch on his eye, and t'other one was a rusty ragged-looking devil. Could you

05:36:44.160 --> 05:36:46.140
see the rags by the light of the cigars?

05:36:46.840 --> 05:36:49.160
This staggered Huck for a moment. Then he said,

05:36:49.420 --> 05:36:52.600
"'Well, I don't know, but somehow it seems as if I did.'

05:36:52.600 --> 05:36:54.720
"'Then they went on, and you?'

05:36:54.720 --> 05:36:58.100
"'Follow them, yes. That was it. I wanted to see what was up.'

05:36:58.100 --> 05:37:02.940
"'They sneaked along, so I dogged them to the Witter's style, and stood in the dark,

05:37:03.080 --> 05:37:07.1000
and heard the ragged one beg for the Witter, and the Spaniard swear he'd spile her looks,

05:37:08.180 --> 05:37:09.780
just as I told you, in your two--"

05:37:09.780 --> 05:37:13.320
"'What? The deaf and dumb man said all that?'

05:37:13.320 --> 05:37:18.060
Huck had made another terrible mistake. He was trying his best to keep the old man from

05:37:18.060 --> 05:37:22.840
getting the faintest hint of who the Spaniard might be, and yet his tongue seemed determined

05:37:22.840 --> 05:37:27.540
to get him into trouble in spite of all he could do. He made several efforts to creep

05:37:27.540 --> 05:37:32.340
out of his scrape, but the old man's eye was upon him, and he made blunder after blunder.

05:37:33.060 --> 05:37:34.320
Presently the Welshman said,

05:37:34.760 --> 05:37:39.960
"'My boy, don't be afraid of me. I wouldn't hurt a hair of your head for all the world.

05:37:39.960 --> 05:37:46.680
No, I'd protect you. I'll—I'd protect you. This Spaniard is not deaf and dumb. You've

05:37:46.680 --> 05:37:51.760
let that slip without intending it. You can't cover that up now. You know something about

05:37:51.760 --> 05:37:57.320
that Spaniard that you want to keep dark. Now trust me. Tell me what it is, and trust

05:37:57.320 --> 05:38:00.120
me. I won't betray you.'

05:38:00.120 --> 05:38:04.700
Huck looked into the old man's honest eyes a moment, then bent over and whispered in

05:38:04.700 --> 05:38:05.340
his ear,

05:38:06.020 --> 05:38:10.160
"'Taint the Spaniard. It's Injun Joe!"

05:38:10.160 --> 05:38:13.760
The Welshman almost jumped out of his chair. In a moment he said,

05:38:14.060 --> 05:38:19.160
"'It's all plain enough now. When you talked about notching ears and the slitting noses,

05:38:19.360 --> 05:38:23.640
I judged that was your own embellishment, because white men don't take that sort of

05:38:23.640 --> 05:38:27.460
revenge. But an Injun, that's a different matter altogether.'

05:38:27.460 --> 05:38:35.320
During breakfast the talk went on, and in the course of it the old man said that the

05:38:35.320 --> 05:38:40.700
bed was to get a lantern, and examine the style and its vicinity for marks of blood.

05:38:41.080 --> 05:38:44.020
They found none, but captured a bulky bundle of—

05:38:44.020 --> 05:38:45.200
"'Of what?'

05:38:45.200 --> 05:38:49.580
If the words had been lightning they could not have leapt with a more stunning suddenness

05:38:49.580 --> 05:38:55.100
from Huck's blanched lips. His eyes were staring wide now, and his breath suspended, waiting

05:38:55.100 --> 05:39:02.760
for the answer. The Welshman started, stared in return, three seconds, five seconds, ten.'

05:39:02.760 --> 05:39:03.580
Then replied,

05:39:03.860 --> 05:39:08.200
"'Of burglar's tools. Why, what's the matter with you?'

05:39:08.200 --> 05:39:13.720
Huck sank back, panting gently, but deeply, unutterably grateful. The Welshman eyed him

05:39:13.720 --> 05:39:15.820
gravely, curiously, and presently said,

05:39:16.200 --> 05:39:22.180
"'Yes, burglar's tools. That appears to relieve you a good deal. But what did give you that

05:39:22.180 --> 05:39:25.440
turn? What were you expecting we'd found?'

05:39:25.440 --> 05:39:30.580
Huck was in a close place. The inquiring eye was upon him. He would have given anything

05:39:30.580 --> 05:39:36.360
for material for a plausible answer. Nothing suggested itself. The inquiring eye was boring

05:39:36.360 --> 05:39:42.840
deeper and deeper. A senseless reply offered. There was no time to weigh it. So at a venture

05:39:42.840 --> 05:39:44.320
he uttered it, feebly.

05:39:45.460 --> 05:39:47.620
"'Sunday school books, maybe?'

05:39:47.620 --> 05:39:52.800
Poor Huck was too distressed to smile. But the old man laughed loud and joyously, shook

05:39:52.800 --> 05:39:57.420
up the details of his anatomy from head to foot, and ended by saying that such a laugh

05:39:57.420 --> 05:40:01.960
was money in a man's pocket, because it cut down the doctor's bills like everything. Then

05:40:01.960 --> 05:40:02.360
he added,

05:40:02.680 --> 05:40:07.740
"'Poor old chap! You're white and jaded. You ain't well a bit. No wonder you're a little

05:40:07.740 --> 05:40:12.640
flighty and off your balance. But you'll come out of it. Rest and sleep. We'll catch you

05:40:12.640 --> 05:40:14.300
up all right, I hope.'

05:40:14.300 --> 05:40:19.580
Huck was irritated to think he had been such a goose, and betrayed such a suspicious excitement,

05:40:19.880 --> 05:40:24.380
for he had dropped the idea that the parcel brought from the tavern was the treasure as

05:40:24.380 --> 05:40:28.800
soon as he had heard the talk at the Witter's style. He had only thought it was not the

05:40:28.800 --> 05:40:33.560
treasure, however. He had not known that it wasn't, and so the suggestion of a captured

05:40:33.560 --> 05:40:39.260
bundle was too much for his self-possession. But on the whole he felt glad the little episode

05:40:39.260 --> 05:40:45.980
had happened, for now he knew beyond all question that that bundle was not THE bundle, and so

05:40:45.980 --> 05:40:51.300
his mind was at rest and exceedingly comfortable. In fact, everything seemed to be drifting

05:40:51.300 --> 05:40:57.380
just in the right direction now. The treasurer must be still in number two. The men would

05:40:57.380 --> 05:41:02.580
be captured and jailed that day, and he and Tom could seize the gold that night without

05:41:02.580 --> 05:41:04.860
any trouble or any fear of interruption.

05:41:05.560 --> 05:41:09.980
Just as breakfast was completed there was a knock at the door. Huck jumped for a hiding

05:41:09.980 --> 05:41:15.400
place, for he had no mind to be connected even remotely with the late event. The Welshman

05:41:15.400 --> 05:41:20.560
admitted several ladies and gentlemen, among them the widow Douglas, and noticed that groups

05:41:20.560 --> 05:41:25.280
of citizens were climbing up the hill to stare at the style, so the news had spread.

05:41:25.860 --> 05:41:30.140
The Welshman had to tell the story of the night to the visitors. The widow's gratitude

05:41:30.140 --> 05:41:32.520
for her preservation was outspoken.

05:41:33.360 --> 05:41:38.020
"'Don't say a word about it, madam. There's another that you're more beholden to than

05:41:38.020 --> 05:41:42.920
you are to me and my boys, maybe, but he don't allow me to tell his name. We wouldn't have

05:41:42.920 --> 05:41:48.980
been there but for him.' Of course, this excited a curiosity so vast that it almost belittled

05:41:48.980 --> 05:41:53.140
the main matter, but the Welshman allowed it to eat into the vitals of his visitors,

05:41:53.500 --> 05:41:58.400
and through them be transmitted to the whole town, for he refused to part with his secret.

05:41:58.840 --> 05:42:01.140
When all else had been learned, the widow said,

05:42:01.460 --> 05:42:06.420
"'I went to sleep reading in bed, and slept straight through all that noise. Why didn't

05:42:06.420 --> 05:42:07.800
you come and wake me?'

05:42:07.800 --> 05:42:12.740
"'We judged it weren't worth while. Those fellows weren't likely to come again. They

05:42:12.740 --> 05:42:17.140
had many tools left to work with. And what was the use of waking you up and scaring you

05:42:17.140 --> 05:42:22.360
to death? My three negro men stood guard at your house all the rest of the night. They've

05:42:22.360 --> 05:42:23.820
just come back.'

05:42:23.820 --> 05:42:28.500
More visitors came, and the story had to be told and retold for a couple of hours more.

05:42:28.820 --> 05:42:34.020
There was no Sabbath school during day-school vacation, but everybody was early at church.

05:42:34.440 --> 05:42:39.640
The stirring event was well canvassed. News came that not a sign of the two villains had

05:42:39.640 --> 05:42:44.940
been yet discovered. When the sermon was finished, Judge Thatcher's wife dropped alongside of

05:42:44.940 --> 05:42:48.560
Mrs. Harper as she moved down the aisle with a crowd, and said,

05:42:48.620 --> 05:42:54.160
"'Is my Becky going to sleep all day? I just expected she would be tired to death.'

05:42:54.160 --> 05:42:55.1000
"'Your Becky?'

05:42:55.1000 --> 05:43:00.220
"'Yes,' with a startled look. "'Didn't she stay with you last night?'

05:43:00.220 --> 05:43:07.140
"'Why, no!' Mrs. Thatcher turned pale and sank into a pew, just as Aunt Polly, talking

05:43:07.140 --> 05:43:10.260
briskly with a friend, passed by. Aunt Polly said,

05:43:10.640 --> 05:43:14.920
"'Good morning, Mrs. Thatcher. Good morning, Mrs. Harper. I've got a boy that's

05:43:14.920 --> 05:43:20.140
turned up missing. I reckon my Tom stayed at your house last night—one of you. And

05:43:20.140 --> 05:43:24.060
now he's afraid to come to church. I've got to settle with him.'

05:43:24.060 --> 05:43:27.260
Mrs. Thatcher shook her head feebly and turned paler than ever.

05:43:27.380 --> 05:43:32.100
"'He didn't stay with us,' said Mrs. Harper, beginning to look uneasy. A marked anxiety

05:43:32.100 --> 05:43:33.420
came into Aunt Polly's face.

05:43:33.900 --> 05:43:37.040
"'Joe Harper, have you seen my Tom this morning?'

05:43:37.040 --> 05:43:38.400
"'No, ma'am.'

05:43:38.400 --> 05:43:43.820
"'When did you see him last?' Joe tried to remember, but was not sure he could say. The

05:43:43.820 --> 05:43:49.360
people had stopped moving out of church, whispers passed along, and aboding uneasiness took

05:43:49.360 --> 05:43:54.440
possession of every countenance. Children were anxiously questioned, and young teachers.

05:43:54.940 --> 05:43:58.960
They all said they had not noticed whether Tom and Becky were on board the ferry-boat

05:43:58.960 --> 05:44:03.680
on the homeward trip. It was dark. No one thought of inquiring if anyone was missing.

05:44:04.320 --> 05:44:09.560
One young man finally blurted out his fear that they were still in the cave. Mrs. Thatcher

05:44:09.560 --> 05:44:13.500
wound away. Aunt Polly fell to crying and wringing her hands.

05:44:14.380 --> 05:44:18.580
The alarm swept from lip to lip, from group to group, from street to street, and within

05:44:18.580 --> 05:44:23.720
five minutes the bells were wildly clanging and the whole town was up. The Cardiff Hill

05:44:23.720 --> 05:44:28.840
episode sank into instant insignificance, the burglars were forgotten, horses were saddled,

05:44:29.140 --> 05:44:33.520
skiffs were manned, the ferry-boat ordered out, and before the horror was half an hour

05:44:33.520 --> 05:44:38.940
old, two hundred men were pouring down High Road and River toward the cave. All the long

05:44:38.940 --> 05:44:44.280
afternoon the village seemed empty and dead. Many women visited Aunt Polly and Mrs. Thatcher

05:44:44.280 --> 05:44:48.920
and tried to comfort them. They cried with them, too, and that was still better than

05:44:48.920 --> 05:44:54.820
words. All the tedious night the town waited for news, but when the morning dawned at last

05:44:54.820 --> 05:44:58.560
all the word that came was, Send more candles, and send food!

05:44:59.260 --> 05:45:04.540
Mrs. Thatcher was almost crazed, and Aunt Polly also. Judge Thatcher sent messages of

05:45:04.540 --> 05:45:09.1000
hope and encouragement from the cave, but they conveyed no real cheer. The old Welshman

05:45:09.1000 --> 05:45:14.500
came home toward daylight, spattered with candle-grease, smeared with clay, and almost

05:45:14.500 --> 05:45:19.760
worn out. He found Huck still in the bed, that had been provided for him, and delirious

05:45:19.760 --> 05:45:25.160
with fever. The physicians were all at the cave, so the widow Douglas came and took charge

05:45:25.160 --> 05:45:29.960
of the patient. She said she would do her best by him, because, whether he was good,

05:45:30.320 --> 05:45:34.820
or bad, or indifferent, he was the Lord's, and nothing that was the Lord's was a thing

05:45:34.820 --> 05:45:39.820
to be neglected. The Welshman said Huck had good spots in him, and the widow said,

05:45:40.060 --> 05:45:45.240
"'You can depend on it. That's the Lord's mark. He don't leave it off. He never does.

05:45:45.760 --> 05:45:49.560
Puts it somewhere on every creature that comes from his hands.'"

05:45:49.560 --> 05:45:54.380
Early in the forenoon parties of jaded men began to straggle into the village, but the

05:45:54.380 --> 05:45:59.420
strongest of the citizens continued searching. All the news that could be gained was that

05:45:59.420 --> 05:46:04.560
the remotenesses of the cavern were being ransacked, that had never been visited before,

05:46:04.640 --> 05:46:09.760
that every corner and crevice was going to be thoroughly searched, that, wherever one

05:46:09.760 --> 05:46:14.580
wandered through the maze of passages, lights were to be seen flitting hither and thither

05:46:14.580 --> 05:46:19.800
in the distance, and shoutings and pistol-shots sent their hollow reverberations to the ear

05:46:19.800 --> 05:46:25.320
down the somber aisles. In one place, far from the section usually traversed by tourists,

05:46:25.320 --> 05:46:31.840
the names Becky and Tom had been found traced upon the rocky wall with candle-smoke and

05:46:31.840 --> 05:46:36.900
near at hand a grease-soiled bit of ribbon. Mrs. Thatcher recognized the ribbon and cried

05:46:36.900 --> 05:46:42.320
over it. She said it was the last relic she would ever have of her child, and that no

05:46:42.320 --> 05:46:47.680
other memorial of her could ever be so precious, because this one parted latest from the living

05:46:47.680 --> 05:46:53.920
body before the awful death came. Some said that now and then in the cave a faraway speck

05:46:53.920 --> 05:46:58.720
of light would glimmer, and then a glorious shout would burst forth, and a score of men

05:46:58.720 --> 05:47:03.240
go trooping down the echoing aisle, and then a sickening disappointment always followed.

05:47:03.580 --> 05:47:08.680
The children were not there. It was only a searcher's light. Three dreadful days and

05:47:08.680 --> 05:47:13.860
nights dragged their tedious hours along, and the village sank into a hopeless stupor.

05:47:14.400 --> 05:47:20.180
No one had heart for anything. The accidental discovery just made that the proprietor of

05:47:20.180 --> 05:47:26.780
kept liquor on his premises, scarcely fluttered the public pulse, tremendous as the fact was.

05:47:27.220 --> 05:47:32.540
In a lucid interval Huck feebly led up to the subject of taverns, and finally asked,

05:47:32.920 --> 05:47:37.300
dimly dreading the worst, if anything had been discovered at the Temperance Tavern since

05:47:37.300 --> 05:47:38.200
he had been ill.

05:47:38.560 --> 05:47:42.460
"'Yes,' said the widow. Huck started up in bed wild-eyed.

05:47:42.740 --> 05:47:44.700
"'What? What was it?'

05:47:44.700 --> 05:47:47.720
"'Liquor. And the place has been shut up.'

05:47:47.720 --> 05:47:53.860
"'Lie down, child. What a turn you did give me. Only tell me just one thing, only just

05:47:53.860 --> 05:47:57.460
one, please. Was it Tom Sawyer that found it?'

05:47:57.460 --> 05:47:59.140
The widow burst into tears.

05:47:59.700 --> 05:48:05.760
"'Hush, hush, child, hush. I've told you before, you must not talk. You are very, very

05:48:05.760 --> 05:48:06.400
sick.'

05:48:06.400 --> 05:48:11.020
Then nothing but liquor had been found. There would have been a great pow-wow if it had

05:48:11.020 --> 05:48:16.640
been the gold. So the treasure was gone for ever—gone for ever. But what could she be

05:48:16.640 --> 05:48:22.160
crying about? Curious that she should cry? These thoughts worked their dim way through

05:48:22.160 --> 05:48:25.240
Huck's mind, and under the weariness they gave him—'

05:48:25.500 --> 05:48:26.200
He fell asleep.

05:48:26.680 --> 05:48:27.900
The widow said to herself,

05:48:27.920 --> 05:48:34.680
"'There! He's asleep, poor wreck. Tom Sawyer find it. Pity but somebody could find Tom

05:48:34.680 --> 05:48:40.100
Sawyer. Ah, there ain't many left now. It's got hope enough, or strength enough, either,

05:48:40.420 --> 05:48:41.440
to go on searching.'

05:49:00.940 --> 05:49:05.720
Now, to return to Tom and Becky's share in the picnic, they tripped

05:49:05.720 --> 05:49:09.320
along the murky isles with the rest of the company, visiting the

05:49:09.320 --> 05:49:13.420
familiar wonders of the cave, wonders dubbed with rather over-descriptive

05:49:13.420 --> 05:49:18.660
names, such as the Drawing Room, the Cathedral, Aladdin's Palace, and

05:49:18.660 --> 05:49:23.580
so on. Presently the hide-and-seek frolicking began, and Tom and Becky

05:49:23.580 --> 05:49:27.620
engaged in it with zeal, until the exertion began to grow a trifle

05:49:27.620 --> 05:49:31.740
wearisome. Then they wandered down a sinuous avenue, holding their

05:49:31.740 --> 05:49:37.160
candles aloft, and reading the tangled web-work of names, dates, post-office

05:49:37.160 --> 05:49:42.440
addresses, and mottos, with which the rocky walls had been frescoed in

05:49:42.440 --> 05:49:46.680
a candle-smoke. Still drifting along and talking, they scarcely noticed

05:49:46.680 --> 05:49:50.540
that they were now in a part of the cave whose walls were not frescoed.

05:49:50.660 --> 05:49:55.360
They smoked their own names under an overhanging shelf, and moved on.

05:49:55.860 --> 05:49:59.220
Presently they came to a place where a little stream of water, trickling

05:49:59.220 --> 05:50:03.780
over a ledge, and carrying a limestone sediment with it, had, in the

05:50:03.780 --> 05:50:08.820
slow-dragging ages, formed a laced and ruffled Niagara in gleaming and

05:50:08.820 --> 05:50:14.000
imperishable stone. Tom squeezed his small body behind it in order to

05:50:14.000 --> 05:50:18.160
illuminate it for Becky's gratification. He found that it curtained a

05:50:18.160 --> 05:50:23.020
sort of steep natural stairway which was enclosed between narrow walls,

05:50:23.300 --> 05:50:28.340
and at once the ambition to be a discoverer seized him. Becky responded

05:50:28.340 --> 05:50:32.600
to his call, and they made a smoke-mark for future guidance, and started

05:50:32.600 --> 05:50:37.440
upon their quest. They wound this way and that far down into the secret

05:50:37.440 --> 05:50:41.800
depths of the cave, made another mark, and branched off in search of

05:50:41.800 --> 05:50:45.920
novelties to tell the upper world about. In one place they found a

05:50:45.920 --> 05:50:50.340
spacious cavern from whose ceiling depended a multitude of shining

05:50:50.340 --> 05:50:54.520
stalactites of the length and circumference of a man's leg. They walked

05:50:54.520 --> 05:50:58.640
all about it, wondering and admiring, and presently left it by one of

05:50:58.640 --> 05:51:02.920
the numerous passages that opened into it. This shortly brought them to

05:51:02.920 --> 05:51:07.100
a bewitching spring whose basin was encrusted with a frostwork of

05:51:07.100 --> 05:51:11.120
glittering crystals. It was in the midst of a cavern whose walls were

05:51:11.120 --> 05:51:14.960
supported by many fantastic pillars which had been formed by the

05:51:14.960 --> 05:51:19.280
joining of great stalactites and stalagmites together, the result of

05:51:19.280 --> 05:51:23.900
the ceaseless water-drip of centuries. Under the roof, vast knots of

05:51:23.900 --> 05:51:28.200
bats had packed themselves together, thousands in a bunch, the lights

05:51:28.200 --> 05:51:31.500
disturbed the creatures, and they came flocking down by hundreds

05:51:31.500 --> 05:51:35.800
squeaking and darting furiously at the candles. Tom knew their ways, and

05:51:35.800 --> 05:51:39.140
he knew the danger of this sort of conduct. He seized Becky's hand and

05:51:39.140 --> 05:51:42.880
hurried her into the first corridor that offered, and none too soon,

05:51:43.180 --> 05:51:47.440
for a bat struck Becky's light out with its wing while she was passing

05:51:47.440 --> 05:51:51.480
out of the cavern. The bats chased the children a good distance, but

05:51:51.480 --> 05:51:55.280
the fugitives plunged into every new passage that offered, and at last

05:51:55.280 --> 05:51:59.580
got rid of the perilous things. Tom found a subterranean lake shortly,

05:51:59.660 --> 05:52:03.400
which stretched its dim length away until its shape was lost in the

05:52:03.400 --> 05:52:07.420
shadows. He wanted to explore its borders, but concluded that it would

05:52:07.420 --> 05:52:12.280
be best to sit down and rest awhile first. Now, for the first time, the

05:52:12.280 --> 05:52:15.900
deep stillness of the place laid a clammy hand upon the spirits of the

05:52:15.900 --> 05:52:17.560
children. Becky said,

05:52:18.180 --> 05:52:23.120
"'Why, I didn't notice, but it seems ever so long since I heard of any

05:52:23.120 --> 05:52:23.960
of the others.'

05:52:24.540 --> 05:52:28.880
"'Come to think, Becky, we are a way down below them, and I don't know

05:52:28.880 --> 05:52:33.380
how far away north or south or east or whichever it is. We couldn't

05:52:33.380 --> 05:52:36.120
hear them here.' Becky grew apprehensive.

05:52:36.240 --> 05:52:40.240
"'I wonder how long we've been down here, Tom. We'd better start back.'

05:52:40.240 --> 05:52:44.100
"'Yes, I reckon we'd better. Perhaps we'd better. Can you find the way,

05:52:44.100 --> 05:52:46.640
Tom? It's all a mixed-up crookedness to me.'

05:52:47.320 --> 05:52:51.780
"'I reckon I could find it, but then the bats. If they put both of our

05:52:51.780 --> 05:52:56.680
candles out, it will be an awful fix. Let's try some other way, so as

05:52:56.680 --> 05:52:57.920
not to go through there.'

05:52:57.920 --> 05:53:02.660
"'Well, but I hope we won't get lost. It would be so awful.' And the

05:53:02.660 --> 05:53:06.000
girls shuddered at the thought of the dreadful possibilities. They

05:53:06.000 --> 05:53:09.940
started through a corridor and traversed it in silence a long way,

05:53:10.340 --> 05:53:13.840
glancing at each new opening to see if there was anything familiar about

05:53:13.840 --> 05:53:18.140
the look of it. But they were all strange. Every time Tom made an

05:53:18.140 --> 05:53:22.160
examination, Becky would watch his face for an encouraging sign, and he

05:53:22.160 --> 05:53:23.100
would say cheerily,

05:53:23.600 --> 05:53:27.200
"'Oh, it's all right. This ain't the one. But we'll come to it right

05:53:27.200 --> 05:53:28.000
away.'

05:53:28.000 --> 05:53:32.620
But he felt less and less hopeful with each failure, and presently began

05:53:32.620 --> 05:53:37.220
to turn off into diverging avenues at sheer random, in desperate hope of

05:53:37.220 --> 05:53:41.560
finding the one that was wanted. He still said it was all right, but

05:53:41.560 --> 05:53:45.500
there was such a leaden dread at his heart that the words had lost their

05:53:45.500 --> 05:53:47.600
ring and sounded just as if he had said,

05:53:47.900 --> 05:53:52.680
"'All is lost.' Becky clung to his side in an anguish of fear, and tried

05:53:52.680 --> 05:53:57.080
hard to keep back the tears. But they would come. At last she said,

05:53:57.080 --> 05:54:01.860
"'Oh, Tom, never mind the bats. Let's go back that way. We seem to get

05:54:01.860 --> 05:54:04.800
worse and worse off all the time.' Tom stopped.

05:54:05.460 --> 05:54:10.660
"'Listen,' said he. Profound silence. Silence so deep that even their

05:54:10.660 --> 05:54:15.520
breathings were conspicuous in the hush. Tom shouted. The call went

05:54:15.520 --> 05:54:18.800
echoing down the empty aisles and died out in the distance in a faint

05:54:18.800 --> 05:54:21.300
sound that resembled a ripple of mocking laughter.

05:54:21.900 --> 05:54:25.660
"'Oh, don't do it again, Tom. It is too horrid,' said Becky.

05:54:26.180 --> 05:54:30.380
"'It is horrid, but I better, Becky. They might hear us, you know.' And

05:54:30.380 --> 05:54:34.860
he shouted again. The might was even a chillier horror than the ghostly

05:54:34.860 --> 05:54:40.360
laughter. It so confessed a perishing hope. The children stood still and

05:54:40.360 --> 05:54:44.760
listened. But there was no result. Tom turned upon the back track at

05:54:44.760 --> 05:54:49.360
once and hurried his steps. It was but a little while before a certain

05:54:49.360 --> 05:54:53.660
indecision in his manner revealed another fearful fact to Becky. He

05:54:53.660 --> 05:54:55.340
could not find his way back.

05:54:55.880 --> 05:55:01.060
"'Oh, Tom, you didn't make any marks. Becky, I was such a fool, such a

05:55:01.060 --> 05:55:05.200
fool. I never thought we might want to come back. No, I can't find the

05:55:05.200 --> 05:55:10.560
way. It's all mixed up. Tom! Tom, we're lost! We're lost! We never can

05:55:10.560 --> 05:55:15.040
get out of this awful place. Why did we ever leave the others?' She

05:55:15.040 --> 05:55:18.320
sank to the ground and burst into such a frenzy of crying that Tom was

05:55:18.320 --> 05:55:22.980
appalled with the idea that she might die, or lose her reason. He sat

05:55:22.980 --> 05:55:26.820
down by her and put his arms around her. She buried her face in his

05:55:26.820 --> 05:55:30.860
bosom. She clung to him. She poured out her terrors, her unavailing

05:55:30.860 --> 05:55:35.520
regrets, and the far echoes turned them all to jeering laughter. Tom

05:55:35.520 --> 05:55:39.500
begged her to pluck up hope again, and she said she could not. He fell

05:55:39.500 --> 05:55:42.940
to blaming and abusing himself for getting her into this miserable

05:55:42.940 --> 05:55:47.040
situation, and this had a better effect. She said she would try to hope

05:55:47.040 --> 05:55:51.000
again. She would get up and follow wherever he might lead, if only he

05:55:51.000 --> 05:55:54.700
would not talk like that any more, for he was no more to blame than she,

05:55:54.820 --> 05:55:59.700
she said. So they moved on again aimlessly, simply at random. All they

05:55:59.700 --> 05:56:04.200
could do was to move, keep moving. For a little while, hope made a show

05:56:04.200 --> 05:56:08.320
of reviving, not with any reason to back it, but only because it is its

05:56:08.320 --> 05:56:13.000
nature to revive, when the spring has not been taken out of it by age

05:56:13.000 --> 05:56:14.660
and familiarity with failure.

05:56:15.420 --> 05:56:20.720
By and by Tom took Becky's candle and blew it out. This economy meant

05:56:20.720 --> 05:56:25.880
so much. Words were not needed. Becky understood, and her hope died

05:56:25.880 --> 05:56:30.380
again. She knew that Tom had a whole candle and three or four pieces in

05:56:30.380 --> 05:56:35.380
his pockets, yet he must economize. By and by fatigue began to assert

05:56:35.380 --> 05:56:39.340
its claims. The children tried to pay no attention, for it was dreadful

05:56:39.340 --> 05:56:43.940
to think of sitting down when time was grown to be so precious. Moving

05:56:43.940 --> 05:56:48.000
in some direction, in any direction, was at least progress, and might

05:56:48.000 --> 05:56:52.360
bear fruit, but to sit down was to invite death and shorten its pursuit.

05:56:53.100 --> 05:56:57.540
At last Becky's frail limbs refused to carry her farther. She sat down.

05:56:58.140 --> 05:57:02.000
Tom rested with her, and they talked of home, and the friends there,

05:57:02.220 --> 05:57:07.220
and the comfortable beds, and, above all, the light. Becky cried, and

05:57:07.220 --> 05:57:10.480
Tom tried to think of some way of comforting her, but all his

05:57:10.480 --> 05:57:13.620
encouragement were grown threadbare with use, and sounded like

05:57:13.620 --> 05:57:14.380
sarcasms.

05:57:14.960 --> 05:57:19.760
Fatigue bore so heavily upon Becky that she drowsed off to sleep. Tom

05:57:19.760 --> 05:57:23.880
was grateful. He sat looking into her drawn face and saw it grow

05:57:23.880 --> 05:57:28.040
smooth and natural under the influence of pleasant dreams, and by and

05:57:28.040 --> 05:57:32.500
by a smile dawned and rested there. The peaceful face reflected somewhat

05:57:32.500 --> 05:57:36.880
of peace and healing into his own spirit, and his thoughts wandered

05:57:36.880 --> 05:57:39.700
way to bygone times and dreamy memories.

05:57:40.300 --> 05:57:43.920
While he was deep in his musings, Becky woke up with a breezy little

05:57:43.920 --> 05:57:47.860
laugh, but it was stricken dead upon her lips, and a groan followed it.

05:57:48.200 --> 05:57:54.060
Oh, how could I sleep! I wish I never, never had waked! No, no, I don't,

05:57:54.060 --> 05:57:58.980
Tom. Don't look so. I won't say it again. I'm glad you've slept, Becky.

05:57:59.000 --> 05:58:03.340
You'll feel rested now, and we'll find the way out. We can try, Tom,

05:58:03.340 --> 05:58:07.420
But I've seen such a beautiful country in my dream. I reckon we are

05:58:07.420 --> 05:58:08.140
going there.

05:58:08.720 --> 05:58:12.800
Maybe not. Maybe not. Cheer up, Becky, and let's go on trying.

05:58:13.240 --> 05:58:18.340
They rose up and wandered along, hand in hand, and hopeless. They tried

05:58:18.340 --> 05:58:22.000
to estimate how long they had been in the cave, but all they knew was

05:58:22.000 --> 05:58:26.040
that it seemed days and weeks, and yet it was plain that this could not

05:58:26.040 --> 05:58:30.760
be, for their candles were not gone yet. A long time after this, they

05:58:30.760 --> 05:58:34.700
could not tell how long. Tom said they must go softly and listen to

05:58:34.700 --> 05:58:38.960
dripping water. They must find a spring. They found one presently, and

05:58:38.960 --> 05:58:43.140
Tom said it was time to rest again. Both were cruelly tired, yet Becky

05:58:43.140 --> 05:58:46.820
said she thought she could go on a little farther. She was surprised to

05:58:46.820 --> 05:58:51.680
hear Tom dissent. She could not understand it. They sat down, and Tom

05:58:51.680 --> 05:58:56.140
fastened his candle to the wall in front of them with some clay. Thought

05:58:56.140 --> 05:59:00.120
was soon busy, nothing was said for some time. Then Becky broke the

05:59:00.120 --> 05:59:00.440
silence.

05:59:00.960 --> 05:59:06.580
"'Tom, I'm so hungry!' Tom took something out of his pocket. Do you

05:59:06.580 --> 05:59:07.800
remember this?' said he.

05:59:08.240 --> 05:59:09.560
Becky almost smiled.

05:59:09.740 --> 05:59:12.060
"'It's our wedding cake, Tom!'

05:59:12.060 --> 05:59:17.340
"'Yes, I wish it was as big as a barrel, for it's all we've got.'

05:59:17.340 --> 05:59:21.260
"'I saved it from the picnic for us to dream on, Tom, the way grown-up

05:59:21.260 --> 05:59:24.360
people do with wedding cake, but it'll be our--"

05:59:24.360 --> 05:59:26.640
She dropped the sentence, where it was.

05:59:26.640 --> 05:59:30.840
Tom divided the cake, and Becky ate with good appetite, while Tom

05:59:30.840 --> 05:59:35.060
nibbled at his moiety. There was abundance of cold water to finish the

05:59:35.060 --> 05:59:39.600
feast with. By-and-by, Becky suggested that they move on again. Tom was

05:59:39.600 --> 05:59:40.980
silent a moment, then he said,

05:59:41.660 --> 05:59:45.020
"'Becky, can you bear it if I tell you something?'

05:59:45.020 --> 05:59:47.960
Becky's face paled, but she thought she could.

05:59:48.340 --> 05:59:52.000
"'Well, then, Becky, we must stay here, where there's water to drink.

05:59:52.280 --> 05:59:55.300
That little piece is our last candle.'

05:59:55.300 --> 05:59:59.900
Becky gave loose to tears and wailings. Tom did what he could to

05:59:59.900 --> 06:00:03.720
comfort her, but with little effect. At length, Becky said,

06:00:05.060 --> 06:00:05.540
"'Tom!'

06:00:05.540 --> 06:00:08.740
"'Well, Becky, they'll miss us and hunt for us.'

06:00:08.740 --> 06:00:12.360
"'Yes, they will. Certainly they will. Maybe they're hunting for us

06:00:12.360 --> 06:00:13.360
now, Tom.'

06:00:13.360 --> 06:00:16.300
"'Why, I reckon, maybe they are. I hope they are.'

06:00:16.300 --> 06:00:18.080
"'When would they miss us, Tom?'

06:00:18.080 --> 06:00:20.660
"'When they get back to the boat, I reckon.'

06:00:20.660 --> 06:00:24.420
"'Tom, it might be dark, then. Would they notice we hadn't come?'

06:00:24.420 --> 06:00:28.160
"'I don't know. But anyway, your mother would miss you as soon as they

06:00:28.160 --> 06:00:29.180
got home.'

06:00:29.180 --> 06:00:32.620
A frightened look in Becky's face brought Tom to his senses, and he

06:00:32.620 --> 06:00:36.600
saw that he had made a blunder. Becky was not to have gone home that

06:00:36.600 --> 06:00:41.080
night. The children became silent and thoughtful. In a moment a new

06:00:41.080 --> 06:00:44.700
burst of grief from Becky showed Tom that the thing in his mind had

06:00:44.700 --> 06:00:49.040
struck hers also, that the Sabbath morning might be half spent before

06:00:49.040 --> 06:00:53.080
Mrs. Thatcher discovered that Becky was not at Mrs. Harper's. The

06:00:53.080 --> 06:00:56.800
children fastened their eyes upon their bit of candle, and watched it

06:00:56.800 --> 06:01:01.420
melt slowly and pitilessly away, saw the half-inch of wick stand alone

06:01:01.420 --> 06:01:06.640
at last, saw the feeble flame rise and fall, climbed the thin column of

06:01:06.640 --> 06:01:11.900
smoke, linger at its top a moment, and then the horror of utter darkness

06:01:11.900 --> 06:01:12.600
reigned.

06:01:13.320 --> 06:01:16.960
How long afterward it was that Becky came to a slow consciousness that

06:01:16.960 --> 06:01:21.280
she was crying in Tom's arms, neither could tell. All that they knew

06:01:21.280 --> 06:01:26.060
was that, after what seemed a mighty stretch of time, both awoke out

06:01:26.060 --> 06:01:30.740
of a dead stupor of sleep and resumed their miseries once more. Tom

06:01:30.740 --> 06:01:35.100
said it might be Sunday now, maybe Monday. He tried to get Becky to

06:01:35.100 --> 06:01:40.780
talk, but her sorrows were too oppressive. All her hopes were gone. Tom

06:01:40.780 --> 06:01:44.440
said that they must have been missed long ago, and no doubt the search

06:01:44.440 --> 06:01:48.900
was going on. He would shout, and maybe someone would come. He tried

06:01:48.900 --> 06:01:53.220
it, but in the darkness the distant echoes sounded so hideously that

06:01:53.220 --> 06:01:54.460
he tried it no more.

06:01:55.080 --> 06:02:00.380
The hours wasted away, and hunger came to torment the captives again. A

06:02:00.380 --> 06:02:04.960
portion of Tom's half of the cake was left. They divided and ate it. But

06:02:04.960 --> 06:02:09.160
they seemed hungrier than before. The poor morsel of food only whetted

06:02:09.160 --> 06:02:09.640
desire.

06:02:10.400 --> 06:02:11.480
By-and-by Tom said,

06:02:11.680 --> 06:02:13.880
"'Shh! Did you hear that?'

06:02:13.880 --> 06:02:18.140
Both held their breath and listened. There was a sound like the faintest

06:02:18.140 --> 06:02:23.320
far-off shout. Instantly Tom answered it, and leading Becky by the hand,

06:02:23.440 --> 06:02:26.980
started groping down the corridor in its direction. Presently he listened

06:02:26.980 --> 06:02:30.420
again. Again the sound was heard, and apparently a little nearer.

06:02:30.600 --> 06:02:31.980
"'It's them,' said Tom.

06:02:31.980 --> 06:02:36.700
"'They're coming. Come along, Becky. We're all right now.' The joy of the

06:02:36.700 --> 06:02:39.960
prisoners was almost overwhelming. Their speed was slow, however,

06:02:39.980 --> 06:02:43.960
because pitfalls were somewhat common, and had to be guarded against.

06:02:44.310 --> 06:02:48.840
They shortly came to one, and had to stop. It might be three feet deep.

06:02:49.080 --> 06:02:53.360
It might be a hundred. There was no passing it at any rate. Tom got down

06:02:53.360 --> 06:02:58.080
on his breast, and reached as far down as he could. No bottom. They must

06:02:58.080 --> 06:03:02.320
stay there and wait until the searchers came. They listened. Evidently

06:03:02.320 --> 06:03:06.380
the distant shoutings were growing more distant. A moment or two more,

06:03:06.440 --> 06:03:11.200
and they had gone altogether. The heart-sinking misery of it. Tom whooped

06:03:11.200 --> 06:03:16.000
until he was hoarse, but it was of no use. He talked hopefully to Becky,

06:03:16.420 --> 06:03:21.140
but an age of anxious waiting passed, and no sounds came again. The

06:03:21.140 --> 06:03:25.500
children groped their way back to the spring. The weary time dragged on.

06:03:25.820 --> 06:03:30.240
They slept again, and awoke famished and woe-stricken. Tom believed it

06:03:30.240 --> 06:03:35.320
must be Tuesday by this time. Now an idea struck him. There were some

06:03:35.320 --> 06:03:39.560
side passages near at hand. It would be better to explore some of these

06:03:39.560 --> 06:03:43.860
than bear the weight of the heavy time in idleness. He took a kite-line

06:03:43.860 --> 06:03:48.820
from his pocket, tied it to a projection, and he and Becky started, Tom

06:03:48.820 --> 06:03:53.780
in the lead, unwinding the line as he groped along. At the end of twenty

06:03:53.780 --> 06:03:58.540
paces the corridor ended in a jumping-off place. Tom got down on his

06:03:58.540 --> 06:04:02.440
knees and felt below, and then as far around the corner as he could

06:04:02.440 --> 06:04:06.520
reach with his hands conveniently. He made an effort to stretch yet a

06:04:06.520 --> 06:04:10.400
little farther to the right, and at that moment, not twenty yards away,

06:04:10.740 --> 06:04:15.240
a human hand holding a candle appeared from behind a rock. Tom lifted

06:04:15.240 --> 06:04:19.220
up a glorious shout, and instantly that hand was followed by the body

06:04:19.220 --> 06:04:25.900
it belonged to. Injun Joe's! Tom was paralyzed. He could not move. He

06:04:25.900 --> 06:04:29.260
was vastly gratified the next moment to see the Spaniard take to his

06:04:29.260 --> 06:04:33.800
heels and get himself out of sight. Tom wondered that Joe had not

06:04:33.800 --> 06:04:36.860
recognized his voice and come over and killed him for testifying in

06:04:36.860 --> 06:04:41.080
court. But the echoes must have disguised the voice. Without doubt

06:04:41.080 --> 06:04:44.960
that was it, he reasoned. Tom's fright weakened every muscle in his

06:04:44.960 --> 06:04:48.480
body. He said to himself that if he had strength enough to get back to

06:04:48.480 --> 06:04:51.660
the spring he would stay there, and nothing should tempt him to run the

06:04:51.660 --> 06:04:55.440
risk of meeting Injun Joe again. He was careful to keep from Becky what

06:04:55.440 --> 06:04:59.400
it was he had seen. He told her he had only shouted for luck.

06:05:00.020 --> 06:05:04.460
But hunger and wretchedness rise superior to fears in the long run.

06:05:04.920 --> 06:05:08.480
Another tedious wait of the spring and another long sleep brought

06:05:08.480 --> 06:05:13.400
changes. The children awoke, tortured with a raging hunger. Tom

06:05:13.400 --> 06:05:16.880
believed that it must be Wednesday or Thursday, or even Friday or

06:05:16.880 --> 06:05:21.520
Saturday now, and that the search had been given over. He proposed to

06:05:21.520 --> 06:05:26.100
explore another passage. He felt willing to risk Injun Joe and all

06:05:26.100 --> 06:05:30.800
other terrors. But Becky was very weak. She had sunk into a dreary

06:05:30.800 --> 06:05:35.640
apathy and would not be roused. She said she would wait, now, where she

06:05:35.640 --> 06:05:41.160
was, and die. It would not be long. She told Tom to go with his kite

06:05:41.160 --> 06:05:45.140
line and explore if he chose, but she implored him to come back every

06:05:45.140 --> 06:05:48.880
little while and speak to her, and she made him promise that when the

06:05:48.880 --> 06:05:52.980
awful time came he would stay by her and hold her hand until all was

06:05:52.980 --> 06:05:57.740
over. Tom kissed her with a choking sensation in his throat, and made

06:05:57.740 --> 06:06:01.380
a show of being confident of finding the searchers or an escape from

06:06:01.380 --> 06:06:05.220
the cave. Then he took the kite line in his hand and went groping down

06:06:05.220 --> 06:06:09.540
one of the passages on his hands and knees, distressed with hunger and

06:06:09.540 --> 06:06:11.780
sick with bodings of coming doom.

06:06:16.660 --> 06:06:17.740
CHAPTER XXXII.

06:06:18.260 --> 06:06:19.880
Turn out! They're found!

06:06:20.840 --> 06:06:24.920
Tuesday afternoon came and waned to the twilight. The village of St.

06:06:25.080 --> 06:06:29.720
Petersburg still mourned. The lost children had not been found. Public

06:06:29.720 --> 06:06:33.660
prayers had been offered up for them, and many and many a private prayer

06:06:33.660 --> 06:06:37.800
that had the petitioner's whole heart in it, but still no good news came

06:06:37.800 --> 06:06:41.560
from the cave. The majority of the searchers had given up the quest and

06:06:41.560 --> 06:06:47.720
gone back to their daily vocations, saying that it was plain the

06:06:47.720 --> 06:06:51.940
ill, and a great part of the time delirious. People said it was

06:06:51.940 --> 06:06:56.000
heartbreaking to hear her call her child, and raise her head and listen

06:06:56.000 --> 06:06:59.840
a whole minute at a time, then lay it wearily down again with a moan.

06:07:00.580 --> 06:07:04.880
Aunt Polly had drooped into a settled melancholy, and her gray hair had

06:07:04.880 --> 06:07:09.300
grown almost white. The village went to its rest on Tuesday night, sad

06:07:09.300 --> 06:07:13.980
and forlorn. Away in the middle of the night a wild peal burst from the

06:07:13.980 --> 06:07:17.480
village bells, and in a moment the streets were swarming with frantic

06:07:17.480 --> 06:07:18.800
half-clad people, who shouted,

06:07:19.120 --> 06:07:22.380
"'Turn out! Turn out! They're found! They're found!'

06:07:22.380 --> 06:07:26.600
Tin pans and horns were added to the din. The population massed itself

06:07:26.600 --> 06:07:30.400
and moved toward the river, met the children coming in an open carriage

06:07:30.400 --> 06:07:34.540
drawn by shouting citizens, thronged around it, joined its homeward

06:07:34.540 --> 06:07:38.360
march, and swept magnificently up the main street roaring, "'Huzzah!'

06:07:38.360 --> 06:07:39.700
after huzzah!'

06:07:39.700 --> 06:07:46.920
The village was illuminated. Nobody went to bed again. It was the

06:07:46.920 --> 06:07:51.320
a procession of villagers filed through Judge Thatcher's house, seized

06:07:51.320 --> 06:07:55.420
the saved ones, and kissed them, squeezed Mrs. Thatcher's hand, tried

06:07:55.420 --> 06:07:59.420
to speak but couldn't, and drifted out raining tears all over the place.

06:07:59.920 --> 06:08:04.280
Aunt Polly's happiness was complete, and Mrs. Thatcher's nearly so. It

06:08:04.280 --> 06:08:07.660
would be complete, however, as soon as the messenger dispatched with the

06:08:07.660 --> 06:08:12.140
great news to the cave should get the word to her husband. Tom lay upon

06:08:12.140 --> 06:08:16.220
a sofa with an eager auditory about him, and told the history of the

06:08:16.220 --> 06:08:20.040
wonderful adventure, putting in many striking additions to adorn it with

06:08:20.040 --> 06:08:24.720
all, and closed with a description of how he left Becky and went on an

06:08:24.720 --> 06:08:29.140
exploring expedition, how he followed two avenues as far as his kite

06:08:29.140 --> 06:08:32.640
line would reach, how he followed a third to the fullest stretch of the

06:08:32.640 --> 06:08:37.100
kite line, and was about to turn back when he glimpsed a far-off speck

06:08:37.100 --> 06:08:41.560
that looked like daylight, dropped the line and groped toward it, pushed

06:08:41.560 --> 06:08:44.760
his head and shoulders through a small hole, and saw the broad

06:08:44.760 --> 06:08:49.460
Mississippi rolling by. And if it had only happened to be night, he

06:08:49.460 --> 06:08:52.820
would not have seen that speck of daylight, and would not have explored

06:08:52.820 --> 06:08:57.480
that passage any more. He told how he went back for Becky, and broke the

06:08:57.480 --> 06:09:01.160
good news, and she told him not to fret her with such stuff, for she

06:09:01.160 --> 06:09:05.480
was tired, and knew she was going to die, and wanted to. He described

06:09:05.480 --> 06:09:09.440
how he labored with her and convinced her, and how she almost died for

06:09:09.440 --> 06:09:13.380
joy when she had groped to where she actually saw the blue speck of

06:09:13.380 --> 06:09:17.860
daylight, how he pushed his way out at the hole and then helped her out,

06:09:18.200 --> 06:09:22.200
how they sat there and cried for gladness, how some men came along in a

06:09:22.200 --> 06:09:26.040
skiff, and Tom hailed them and told them their situation and their

06:09:26.040 --> 06:09:29.720
famished condition, how the men didn't believe the wild tale at first,

06:09:29.800 --> 06:09:33.820
because, said they, you are five miles down the river, below the valley

06:09:33.820 --> 06:09:37.940
the cave is in, then took them aboard, rode to a house, gave them

06:09:37.940 --> 06:09:42.160
supper, made them rest till two or three hours after dark, and then

06:09:42.160 --> 06:09:42.920
brought them home.

06:09:43.480 --> 06:09:47.320
Before day dawn, Judge Thatcher and the handful of searchers with him

06:09:47.320 --> 06:09:51.400
were tracked out in the cave by the twine clues they had strung behind

06:09:51.400 --> 06:09:55.880
them and informed of the great news. Three days and nights of toil and

06:09:55.880 --> 06:09:59.580
hunger in the cave were not to be shaken off at once, as Tom and Becky

06:09:59.580 --> 06:10:03.320
soon discovered. They were bedridden all of Wednesday and Thursday,

06:10:03.720 --> 06:10:07.480
and seemed to grow more and more tired and worn all the time. Tom got

06:10:07.480 --> 06:10:11.880
about a little on Thursday, was downtown Friday, and nearly as whole as

06:10:11.880 --> 06:10:15.980
ever Saturday, but Becky did not leave her room until Sunday, and then

06:10:15.980 --> 06:10:18.780
she looked as if she had passed through a wasting illness.

06:10:19.500 --> 06:10:23.460
Tom learned of Huck's sickness and went to see him on Friday, but could

06:10:23.460 --> 06:10:27.300
not be admitted to the bedroom. Neither could he on Saturday or Sunday.

06:10:27.660 --> 06:10:31.160
He was admitted daily after that, but was warned to keep still about

06:10:31.160 --> 06:10:35.080
his adventure and introduced no exciting topic. The widow Douglas

06:10:35.080 --> 06:10:39.600
stayed by to see that he obeyed. At home Tom learned of the Cardiff

06:10:39.600 --> 06:10:43.960
kill-event, also that the ragged man's body had eventually been found

06:10:43.960 --> 06:10:47.600
in the river near the ferry landing. He had been drowned while trying

06:10:47.600 --> 06:10:48.900
to escape, perhaps.

06:10:49.440 --> 06:10:53.540
About a fortnight after Tom's rescue from the cave, he started off to

06:10:53.540 --> 06:10:57.160
visit Huck, who had grown plenty strong enough now to hear exciting

06:10:57.160 --> 06:11:01.440
talk, and Tom had some that would interest him, he thought. Judge

06:11:01.440 --> 06:11:09.360
Thatcher's house was on Tom's way, and he stopped to see Becky. The

06:11:09.360 --> 06:11:13.440
ironically, if he wouldn't like to go to the cave again. Tom said he

06:11:13.440 --> 06:11:15.600
thought he wouldn't mind it. The judge said,

06:11:15.740 --> 06:11:20.100
"'Well, there are others just like you, Tom. I've not the least doubt.

06:11:20.500 --> 06:11:24.400
But we have taken care of that. Nobody will get lost in that cave

06:11:24.400 --> 06:11:25.120
any more.'

06:11:25.920 --> 06:11:26.440
"'Why?'

06:11:26.440 --> 06:11:30.620
"'Because I had its big door sheathed with boiler-iron two weeks ago,

06:11:30.760 --> 06:11:33.640
and triple-locked, and I've got the keys.'

06:11:34.020 --> 06:11:35.520
Tom turned as white as a sheet.

06:11:36.080 --> 06:11:40.840
"'What's the matter, boy? Here, run somebody. Fetch a glass of water.'

06:11:40.840 --> 06:11:43.280
The water was brought and thrown into Tom's face.

06:11:43.940 --> 06:11:47.720
"'Ah, now you're all right. What was the matter with you, Tom?'

06:11:47.720 --> 06:11:52.060
"'Oh, Judge! Injun Joe's in the cave!'

06:12:09.400 --> 06:12:12.380
XXXIII. The Fate of Injun Joe.

06:12:13.620 --> 06:12:18.400
Within a few minutes the news had spread, and a dozen skiff-loads of men were on their

06:12:18.400 --> 06:12:22.980
way to MacDougall's cave, and the ferry-boat, well filled with passengers, soon followed.

06:12:22.980 --> 06:12:28.280
Tom Sawyer was in a skiff that bore Judge Thatcher. When the cave-door was unlocked,

06:12:28.800 --> 06:12:35.160
a sorrowful sight presented itself in the dim twilight of the place. Injun Joe lay stretched

06:12:35.160 --> 06:12:40.980
upon the ground, dead, with his face close to the crack of the door, as if his longing

06:12:40.980 --> 06:12:46.840
eyes had been fixed to the latest moment upon the light and the cheer of the free world

06:12:46.840 --> 06:12:52.680
outside. Tom was touched, for he knew by his own experience how this wretch had suffered.

06:12:53.320 --> 06:12:57.840
His pity was moved, but nevertheless he felt an abounding sense of relief and security

06:12:57.840 --> 06:13:03.680
now which revealed to him, in a degree which he had not fully appreciated before, how vast

06:13:03.680 --> 06:13:08.480
a weight of dread had been lying upon him since the day he lifted his voice against

06:13:08.480 --> 06:13:10.180
this bloody-minded outcast.

06:13:10.900 --> 06:13:17.300
Injun Joe's bowie-knife lay close by, its blade broken in two. The great foundation

06:13:17.300 --> 06:13:22.900
beam of the door had been chipped and hacked through with tedious labor. Useless labor,

06:13:23.140 --> 06:13:28.520
too, it was, for the native rock formed a sill outside it, and upon that stubborn material

06:13:28.520 --> 06:13:34.440
the knife had wrought no effect. The only damage done was to the knife itself. But if

06:13:34.440 --> 06:13:38.980
there had been no stony obstruction there, the labor would have been useless still, for

06:13:38.980 --> 06:13:43.780
if the beam had been wholly cut away, Injun Joe could not have squeezed his body under

06:13:43.780 --> 06:13:49.780
the door, and he knew it. So he had only hacked that place in order to be doing something,

06:13:50.080 --> 06:13:56.140
in order to pass the weary time, in order to employ his tortured faculties. Ordinarily

06:13:56.140 --> 06:14:00.600
one could find half a dozen bits of candles stuck around in the crevices of this vestibule,

06:14:00.800 --> 06:14:05.840
left there by tourists, but there were none now. The prisoner had searched them out and

06:14:05.840 --> 06:14:11.620
eaten them. He had also contrived to catch a few bats, and these also he had eaten, leaving

06:14:11.620 --> 06:14:17.620
only their claws. The poor unfortunate had starved to death. In one place near at hand

06:14:17.620 --> 06:14:23.360
a stalagmite had been slowly growing up from the ground for ages, builded by the water-drip

06:14:23.360 --> 06:14:28.1000
from a stalactite overhead. The captive had broken off the stalagmite, and upon the stump

06:14:28.1000 --> 06:14:34.1000
had placed a stone, wherein he had scooped a shallow hollow to catch the precious drop

06:14:34.1000 --> 06:14:40.340
that fell once in every three minutes, with the dreary regularity of a clock-tick, a dessert

06:14:40.340 --> 06:14:46.180
spoonful once in four and twenty hours. That drop was falling when the pyramids were new,

06:14:46.320 --> 06:14:52.100
when Troy fell, when the foundations of Rome were laid, when Christ was crucified, when

06:14:52.100 --> 06:14:57.160
the conqueror created the British Empire, when Columbus sailed, when the massacre at

06:14:57.160 --> 06:15:02.760
Lexington was news. It is falling now. It will still be falling when all these things

06:15:02.760 --> 06:15:07.1000
shall have sunk down the afternoon of history and the twilight of tradition, and been swallowed

06:15:07.1000 --> 06:15:14.140
up in the thick night of oblivion. Has everything a purpose and a mission? Did this drop fall

06:15:14.140 --> 06:15:18.880
patiently during five thousand years to be ready for this flitting human insect's need?

06:15:19.340 --> 06:15:25.340
And has it another important object to accomplish ten thousand years to come? No matter. It

06:15:25.340 --> 06:15:29.840
is many and many a year since the hapless half-breed scooped out the stone to catch

06:15:29.840 --> 06:15:36.220
the priceless drops. But to this day the tourist stares longest at that pathetic stone and

06:15:36.220 --> 06:15:41.400
that slow-dropping water when he comes to see the wonders of MacDougall's cave. Injun

06:15:41.400 --> 06:15:46.880
Joe's cup stands first in the list of the cavern's marvels. Even Aladdin's palace cannot

06:15:46.880 --> 06:15:47.560
rival it.

06:15:48.540 --> 06:15:53.460
Injun Joe was buried near the mouth of the cave, and people flocked there in boats and

06:15:53.460 --> 06:15:58.780
wagons from the towns and from all the farms and hamlets for seven miles around. They brought

06:15:58.780 --> 06:16:03.520
their children and all sorts of provisions, and confessed that they had had almost as

06:16:03.520 --> 06:16:08.620
satisfactory a time at the funeral as they could have had at the hanging. This funeral

06:16:08.620 --> 06:16:13.800
stopped the further growth of one thing—the petition to the governor for Injun Joe's pardon.

06:16:14.160 --> 06:16:19.440
The petition had been largely signed, many tearful and eloquent meetings had been held,

06:16:19.720 --> 06:16:24.380
and a committee of sappy women had been appointed to go in deep mourning and wail around the

06:16:24.780 --> 06:16:30.520
and implore him to be a merciful ass and trample his duty underfoot. Injun Joe was believed

06:16:30.520 --> 06:16:35.380
to have killed five citizens of the village, but what of that? If he had been Satan himself

06:16:35.380 --> 06:16:38.900
there would have been plenty of weaklings ready to scribble their names to a pardon

06:16:38.900 --> 06:16:43.960
petition and drip a tear on it from their permanently impaired and leaky waterworks.

06:16:44.680 --> 06:16:49.140
The morning after the funeral Tom took Huck to a private place to have an important talk.

06:16:49.740 --> 06:16:53.640
Huck had learned all about Tom's adventure from the Welshmen and the widow, Douglas,

06:16:53.640 --> 06:16:58.780
by this time, but Tom said he reckoned there was one thing they had not told him. That

06:16:58.780 --> 06:17:00.900
thing was what he wanted to talk about now.

06:17:01.280 --> 06:17:03.200
Huck's face saddened. He said,

06:17:03.800 --> 06:17:09.060
"'I know what it is. You got into Number Two and never found anything but whiskey. Nobody

06:17:09.060 --> 06:17:14.060
told me it was you, but I just noted must have been you, as soon as I heard about that

06:17:14.060 --> 06:17:18.220
whiskey business. And I knowed you hadn't got the money, because you'd have got it me

06:17:18.220 --> 06:17:23.540
some way or other and told me even if you was mum to everybody else. Tom, something's

06:17:23.540 --> 06:17:26.100
always told me we'd never get hold of that swag.'

06:17:26.820 --> 06:17:31.460
"'Why, Huck, I never told on that tavern keeper. You know his tavern was all right

06:17:31.460 --> 06:17:36.380
the Saturday I went to the picnic. Don't you remember you was to watch there that night?'

06:17:36.380 --> 06:17:41.480
"'Oh, yes. Why, it seems about a year ago. It was that very night that I followed Injun

06:17:41.480 --> 06:17:42.480
Joe to the widders.'

06:17:42.480 --> 06:17:44.200
"'You followed him?'

06:17:44.200 --> 06:17:49.220
"'Yes, but you keep mum. I reckon Injun Joe's left friends behind him, and I don't

06:17:49.220 --> 06:17:54.180
them soaring on me and doing me mean tricks. If it hadn't been for me he'd be down in

06:17:54.180 --> 06:17:59.360
Texas now, all right.' Then Huck told his entire adventure in confidence to Tom, who

06:17:59.360 --> 06:18:01.400
had only heard of the Welshman's part of it before.

06:18:02.380 --> 06:18:06.840
"'Well,' said Huck, presently, coming back to the main question, "'whoever nipped

06:18:06.840 --> 06:18:10.680
the whiskey in Number Two nipped the money, too, I reckon. Anyway, it's a goner for us,

06:18:10.680 --> 06:18:11.260
Tom.'

06:18:11.760 --> 06:18:14.680
"'Huck, that money wasn't ever in Number Two.'

06:18:14.680 --> 06:18:18.080
"'What?' Huck searched his comrade's face keenly.

06:18:18.080 --> 06:18:22.260
"'Tom, have you got on the track of that money again?'

06:18:22.260 --> 06:18:25.300
"'Huck, it's in the cave!' Huck's eyes blazed.

06:18:25.780 --> 06:18:28.800
"'Say it again, Tom. The money's in the cave.'

06:18:29.560 --> 06:18:32.580
"'Tom, honest Injun now, is it fun or earnest?'

06:18:32.580 --> 06:18:36.920
"'Ernest, Huck. Just as earnest as ever I was in my life. Will you go in there with

06:18:36.920 --> 06:18:38.180
me and help me get it out?'

06:18:38.180 --> 06:18:43.360
"'I bet I will. I will if it's where we can blaze our way to it and not get lost. Huck,

06:18:43.360 --> 06:18:46.640
we can do that without the least little bit of trouble in the world.'

06:18:46.640 --> 06:18:49.700
"'Good as wheat. What makes you think the money's—'

06:18:49.940 --> 06:18:54.460
"'Huck, you just wait till we get in there. If we don't find it, I'll agree to give you

06:18:54.460 --> 06:18:57.620
my drum and everything I've got in the world. I will, by jings.'

06:18:57.620 --> 06:19:00.100
"'All right, it's a whiz. When do you say?'

06:19:00.100 --> 06:19:02.1000
"'Right now, if you say it. Are you strong enough?'

06:19:02.1000 --> 06:19:08.020
"'Is it far in the cave? I've been on my pins a little three, four days now, but I can't

06:19:08.020 --> 06:19:11.180
walk more than a mile, Tom. Least I don't think I could.'

06:19:11.180 --> 06:19:15.680
"'It's about five mile into there, the way anybody but me would go, Huck. But there's

06:19:15.680 --> 06:19:20.400
a mighty short cut that they don't anybody but me know about. Huck, I'll take you right

06:19:20.400 --> 06:19:24.700
to it in a skiff. I'll float the skiff down there, and I'll pull it back again all by

06:19:24.700 --> 06:19:30.640
myself. You needn't ever turn your hand over. Let's start right off, Tom. All right. We

06:19:30.640 --> 06:19:35.060
want some bread and meat and our pipes and a little bag or two and two or three kite

06:19:35.060 --> 06:19:39.980
strings and some of these newfangled things they call Lucifer matches. I tell you, many's

06:19:39.980 --> 06:19:44.380
the time I wished I had some when I was in there before. A trifle afternoon the boys

06:19:44.380 --> 06:19:49.240
borrowed a small skiff from a citizen who was absent, and got under way at once. When

06:19:49.240 --> 06:19:51.800
they were several miles below Cave Hollow, Tom said,

06:19:52.300 --> 06:19:57.720
"'Now, you see this bluff here looks all alike all the way down from the Cave Hollow? No

06:19:57.720 --> 06:20:03.500
houses, no woodyards, bushes all alike. But do you see that white place up there, where

06:20:03.500 --> 06:20:09.180
there's been a landslide? Well, that's one of my marks. We'll get ashore now.' They

06:20:09.180 --> 06:20:09.560
landed.

06:20:09.940 --> 06:20:16.140
"'Now, Huck, where we're a-standin', you could touch that hole I got out of with a fishing-pole.

06:20:16.400 --> 06:20:17.860
See if you can find it.'

06:20:17.860 --> 06:20:23.200
Huck searched all the place about and found nothing. Tom proudly marched into a thick

06:20:23.200 --> 06:20:24.920
clump of sumac bushes and said,

06:20:25.220 --> 06:20:30.220
"'Here you are. Look at it, Huck. It's the snuggest hole in this country. You just keep

06:20:30.220 --> 06:20:35.100
mum about it. All along I've been wanted to be a robber, but I knew I'd got to have a

06:20:35.100 --> 06:20:40.560
this, and where to run across it was the bother. We've got it now, and we'll keep it quiet.

06:20:40.760 --> 06:20:45.500
Only we'll let Joe Harper and Ben Rogers in, because, of course, there's got to be a gang,

06:20:45.560 --> 06:20:49.640
or else there wouldn't be any style about it. Tom Sawyer's gang. It sounds splendid,

06:20:49.700 --> 06:20:50.740
don't it, Huck?'

06:20:50.740 --> 06:20:54.100
"'Well, it just does, Tom. And who'll we rob?'

06:20:54.100 --> 06:20:59.040
"'Oh, most anybody. Weigh lay people, that's mostly the way. And kill them?'

06:20:59.040 --> 06:21:03.300
"'No, not always. Hive them in the cave till they raise a ransom.'

06:21:03.300 --> 06:21:04.1000
"'What's a ransom?'

06:21:04.1000 --> 06:21:09.800
"'Money. You make them raise all they can, often their friends, and after you've kept

06:21:09.800 --> 06:21:14.700
them a year, if it ain't raised, then you kill them. That's the general way, only you

06:21:14.700 --> 06:21:19.760
don't kill the women. You shut up the women, but you don't kill them. They're always beautiful

06:21:19.760 --> 06:21:24.800
and rich and awfully scared. You take their watches and things, but you always take your

06:21:24.800 --> 06:21:29.220
hat off and talk plight. They ain't anybody as plight as robbers. You'll see that in any

06:21:29.220 --> 06:21:34.100
book. Well, the women get to loving you, and after they've been in the cave a week or two

06:21:34.100 --> 06:21:39.260
weeks they stop crying, and after that you couldn't get them to leave. If you drove them

06:21:39.260 --> 06:21:42.580
out they'd turn right round and come back. It's so in all the books.'

06:21:42.580 --> 06:21:47.560
"'Why, it's really bully, Tom. I believe it's betterin' to be a pirate.'

06:21:47.560 --> 06:21:52.800
"'Yes, it's better in some ways, because it's close to home and circuses and all that.'

06:21:52.800 --> 06:21:57.280
By this time everything was ready and the boys entered the hole, Tom in the lead. They

06:21:57.280 --> 06:22:01.580
toiled their way to the farther end of the tunnel, then made their spliced kite-strings

06:22:01.580 --> 06:22:07.120
fast and moved on. A few steps brought them to the spring, and Tom felt a shudder quiver

06:22:07.120 --> 06:22:12.220
all through him. He showed Huck the fragment of Candlewick perched on a lump of clay against

06:22:12.220 --> 06:22:17.340
the wall, and described how he and Becky had watched the flames struggle and expire. The

06:22:17.340 --> 06:22:21.800
boys began to quiet down to whispers now, for the stillness and gloom of the place oppressed

06:22:21.800 --> 06:22:26.980
their spirits. They went on, and presently entered, and followed Tom's other corridors

06:22:26.980 --> 06:22:31.600
until they reached the jumping-off place. The candles revealed the fact that it was

06:22:31.600 --> 06:22:37.040
not really a precipice, but only a steep clay hill twenty or thirty feet high. Tom whispered,

06:22:37.300 --> 06:22:42.080
"'Now I'll show you something, Huck.' He held his candle aloft, and said, "'Look as

06:22:42.080 --> 06:22:47.240
far round the corner as you can. Do you see that? There, on the big rock over yonder,

06:22:47.380 --> 06:22:54.740
down with the candle-smoke. Tom, it's a cross. Now, where's your number two?'

06:22:54.740 --> 06:23:00.460
"'Under the cross, hey. Right yonder's where I saw Injun Joe poke up his candle, Huck.'

06:23:00.460 --> 06:23:04.600
Huck stared at the mystic sign awhile, and then said with a shaky voice,

06:23:05.260 --> 06:23:08.120
"'Tom, let's get out of here.'

06:23:08.120 --> 06:23:10.520
"'What! And leave the treasure?'

06:23:10.520 --> 06:23:15.260
"'Yes, leave it. Injun Joe's ghost is round about there, certain.'

06:23:15.260 --> 06:23:20.160
"'No, it ain't, Huck, no it ain't. It would haunt the place where he died, way out at

06:23:20.160 --> 06:23:22.700
the mouth of the cave, five miles from here.'

06:23:22.700 --> 06:23:27.920
"'No, Tom, it wouldn't. It would hang around the money. I know the ways of ghosts, and

06:23:27.920 --> 06:23:29.100
so do you.'

06:23:29.100 --> 06:23:34.580
Tom began to fear that Huck was right. Misgivings gathered in his mind, but presently an idea

06:23:34.580 --> 06:23:35.260
occurred to him.

06:23:35.480 --> 06:23:40.120
"'Look here, Tuck, what fools we're making of ourselves. Injun Joe's ghost ain't a-going

06:23:40.120 --> 06:23:44.800
to come round where there's a cross.' The point was well taken. It had its effect.

06:23:45.440 --> 06:23:51.040
"'Tom, I didn't think of that. But that's so. It's luck for us that cross is. I reckon

06:23:51.040 --> 06:23:54.060
we'll climb down there and have a hunt for that box.'

06:23:54.060 --> 06:23:58.980
Tom went first, cutting rude steps in the clay hill as he descended. Huck followed.

06:23:59.540 --> 06:24:05.020
Four avenues opened out of the small cavern which the great rock stood in. The boys examined

06:24:05.020 --> 06:24:09.460
three of them with no result. They found a small recess in the one nearest the base of

06:24:09.460 --> 06:24:15.480
rock, with a pallet of blankets spread down in it. Also an old suspender, some bacon rind,

06:24:15.860 --> 06:24:22.140
and the well-nog bones of two or three fowls. But there was no money box. The lads searched

06:24:22.140 --> 06:24:25.040
and researched this place, but in vain. Tom said,

06:24:25.400 --> 06:24:30.940
"'He said under the cross. Well, this comes nearest to being under the cross. It can't

06:24:30.940 --> 06:24:36.300
be under the rock itself, because that's set solid on the ground.' They searched everywhere

06:24:36.300 --> 06:24:42.080
once more, and then sat down discouraged. Huck could suggest nothing. By-and-by Tom

06:24:42.080 --> 06:24:42.380
said,

06:24:42.700 --> 06:24:47.020
"'Looky here, Huck, there's footprints and some candle-grease on the clay about one side

06:24:47.020 --> 06:24:51.500
of this rock, but not on the other sides. Now what's that for?'

06:24:51.500 --> 06:24:55.880
"'I bet you the money is under the rock. I'm going to dig in the clay.'

06:24:55.880 --> 06:25:01.360
"'That ain't no bad notion, Tom,' said Huck with animation. Tom's real barlow was out

06:25:01.360 --> 06:25:04.660
at once, and he had not dug four inches before he struck wood.

06:25:04.660 --> 06:25:06.540
"'Hey, Huck, you hear that?'

06:25:06.540 --> 06:25:11.780
Huck began to dig and scratch now. Some boards were soon uncovered and removed. They had

06:25:11.780 --> 06:25:16.760
concealed a natural chasm which led under the rock. Tom got into this and held his candle

06:25:16.760 --> 06:25:21.260
as far under the rock as he could, but said he could not see to the end of the rift. He

06:25:21.260 --> 06:25:26.620
proposed to explore. He stooped and passed under. The narrow way descended gradually.

06:25:27.080 --> 06:25:31.460
He followed its winding course, first to the right and then to the left. Huck at his heels.

06:25:32.020 --> 06:25:34.560
Tom turned a short curve by and by and exclaimed,

06:25:35.300 --> 06:25:37.620
"'My goodness, Huck, looky here!'

06:25:38.180 --> 06:25:43.360
It was the treasure box, sure enough, occupying a snug little cavern, along with an empty

06:25:43.360 --> 06:25:48.860
powder keg, a couple of guns and leather cases, two or three pairs of old moccasins, a leather

06:25:48.860 --> 06:25:52.280
belt, and some other rubbish, well soaked with the water-drip.

06:25:52.600 --> 06:25:57.220
"'Got it at last,' said Huck, ploughing among the tarnished coins with his hands.

06:25:57.660 --> 06:25:59.980
"'My, but we're rich, Tom!'

06:26:00.600 --> 06:26:05.960
"'Huck, I always reckoned we'd get it. It's just too good to believe. But we have got

06:26:05.960 --> 06:26:11.440
it, sure. Say, let's not fool around here. Let's snake it out. Let me see if we can lift

06:26:11.440 --> 06:26:12.440
the box.'

06:26:12.440 --> 06:26:17.400
It weighed about fifty pounds. Tom could lift it after an awkward fashion, but could not

06:26:17.400 --> 06:26:18.340
carry it conveniently.

06:26:18.960 --> 06:26:23.480
"'I thought so,' he said. They carried it like it was heavy, that day at the haunted

06:26:23.480 --> 06:26:28.580
house. I noticed that. I reckon I was right to think of fetching the little bags along."

06:26:28.580 --> 06:26:32.340
The money was soon in the bags, and the boys took it up to the cross-rock.

06:26:32.860 --> 06:26:35.420
"'Now, let's fetch the guns and things,' said Huck.

06:26:35.580 --> 06:26:39.880
"'No, Huck. Leave them there. They're just the tricks to have when you go to robbing.

06:26:40.140 --> 06:26:44.440
We'll keep them there all the time, and we'll hold our orgies there, too. It's an awful

06:26:44.440 --> 06:26:45.700
snug place for orgies.'

06:26:46.640 --> 06:26:47.600
"'What's orgies?'

06:26:47.600 --> 06:26:52.400
"'I don't know. But robbers always have orgies, and of course we've got to have them, too.'

06:26:52.400 --> 06:26:56.960
"'Come along, Huck. We've been here a long time. It's getting late, I reckon. I'm hungry,

06:26:56.960 --> 06:26:59.860
too. We'll eat and smoke when we get to the skiff.'

06:26:59.860 --> 06:27:05.360
They presently emerged into the clump of Sumac bushes, looked warily about, found the coast

06:27:05.360 --> 06:27:10.160
clear, and were soon lunching and smoking in the skiff. As the sun dipped toward the

06:27:10.160 --> 06:27:15.060
horizon they pushed out and got under way. Tom skimmed up the shore through the long

06:27:15.060 --> 06:27:18.980
twilight chatting cheerily with Huck, and landed shortly after dark.

06:27:19.280 --> 06:27:23.460
"'Now, Huck,' said Tom, "'we'll hide the money in the loft of the Witter's woodshed,

06:27:23.460 --> 06:27:27.280
and I'll come up in the morning, and we'll count it and divide it, and then we'll hunt

06:27:27.280 --> 06:27:31.680
up a place out in the woods for it, where it will be safe. Just you lay quiet here and

06:27:31.680 --> 06:27:36.700
watch the stuff till I run up and hook Benny Taylor's little wagon. I won't be gone a minute.'

06:27:36.700 --> 06:27:41.520
He disappeared, and presently returned with the wagon, put the two small sacks into it,

06:27:41.720 --> 06:27:47.300
threw some old rags on top of them, and started off dragging his cargo behind him. When the

06:27:47.300 --> 06:27:51.540
boys reached the Welshman's house they stopped to rest. Just as they were about to move on

06:27:51.540 --> 06:27:52.920
the Welshman stepped out and said,

06:27:53.240 --> 06:27:54.240
"'Hullo, who's that?'

06:27:54.740 --> 06:27:56.280
"'Huck and Tom Sawyer.'

06:27:56.280 --> 06:28:01.100
"'Good. Come along with me, boys. You are keeping everybody waiting. Here, hurry up,

06:28:01.200 --> 06:28:03.200
trot ahead, I'll haul the wagon for you.'

06:28:03.200 --> 06:28:07.140
"'Why, it's not as light as it might be. Got bricks in it? Or old metal?'

06:28:07.660 --> 06:28:08.900
"'Old metal,' said Tom.

06:28:09.280 --> 06:28:14.060
"'I judge so. The boys in this town will take more trouble and fool away more time

06:28:14.060 --> 06:28:19.160
hunting up six bits worth of old iron to sell to the foundry than they would to make twice

06:28:19.160 --> 06:28:23.860
the money at regular work. But that's human nature. Hurry along, hurry along.'

06:28:23.860 --> 06:28:25.840
The boys wanted to know what the hurry was about.

06:28:25.960 --> 06:28:29.480
"'Never mind. You'll see when we get to the widow Douglas's.'

06:28:29.480 --> 06:28:34.140
Huck said with some apprehension, for he was long used to being falsely accused.

06:28:34.500 --> 06:28:37.960
"'Mr. Jones, we haven't been doing nothing.'

06:28:37.960 --> 06:28:39.120
The Welshman laughed.

06:28:39.560 --> 06:28:44.040
"'Well, I don't know, Huck, my boy. I don't know about that. Ain't you and the widow

06:28:44.040 --> 06:28:44.820
good friends?'

06:28:44.820 --> 06:28:48.960
"'Yes. Well, she's been good friends to me, anyways.'

06:28:48.960 --> 06:28:52.040
"'All right, then. What do you want to be frayed for?'

06:28:52.040 --> 06:28:56.280
This question was not entirely answered in Huck's slow mind before he found himself pushed,

06:28:56.400 --> 06:29:01.420
along with Tom, into Mrs. Douglas's drawing-room. Mr. Jones left the wagon near the door and

06:29:01.420 --> 06:29:06.520
followed. The place was grandly lighted, and everybody that was of any consequence in the

06:29:06.520 --> 06:29:12.280
village was there. The Thatchers were there, the Harpers, the Rogerses, Aunt Polly, Sid,

06:29:12.460 --> 06:29:17.460
Mary, the Minister, the Editor, and a great many more, and all dressed in their best.

06:29:17.460 --> 06:29:22.580
The widow received the boys as heartily as any one could well receive two such-looking

06:29:22.580 --> 06:29:28.280
beings. They were covered with clay and candle-grease. Aunt Polly blushed crimson with humiliation

06:29:28.280 --> 06:29:33.120
and frowned and shook her head at Tom. Nobody suffered half as much as the two boys did,

06:29:33.220 --> 06:29:34.840
however. Mr. Jones said,

06:29:35.060 --> 06:29:39.740
"'Tom wasn't at home yet, so I gave him up. But I stumbled on him and Huck right at my

06:29:39.740 --> 06:29:42.860
door, and so I just brought them along in a hurry.'

06:29:42.860 --> 06:29:44.740
"'And you did just right,' said the widow.

06:29:44.740 --> 06:29:48.620
"'Come with me, boys.' She took them to a bed-chamber, and said,

06:29:49.160 --> 06:29:54.080
"'Now, wash and dress yourselves. Here are two new suits of clothes—shirts, socks,

06:29:54.360 --> 06:29:56.800
everything complete. They're Huck's.'

06:29:56.800 --> 06:30:01.840
"'No, no thanks, Huck. Mr. Jones bought one and I the other. But they'll fit both of you.

06:30:02.120 --> 06:30:07.400
Get into them. We'll wait. Come down when you are slicked up enough.' Then she left."

06:30:11.300 --> 06:30:12.600
CHAPTER 34

06:30:13.340 --> 06:30:14.740
FLOODS OF GOLD

06:30:15.240 --> 06:30:16.120
Huck said,

06:30:17.040 --> 06:30:21.780
"'Tom, we can slope if we can find a rope. The window ain't high from the ground.'

06:30:22.700 --> 06:30:24.360
"'Shucks, what do you want to slope for?'

06:30:25.260 --> 06:30:29.840
"'Well, I ain't used to that kind of crowd. I can't stand it. I ain't going down there, Tom.'

06:30:30.540 --> 06:30:35.320
"'Oh, bother it ain't anything. I don't mind it a bit. I'll take care of you,' said appeared.

06:30:36.300 --> 06:30:40.260
"'Tom,' said he, "'Auntie has been waiting for you all the afternoon.

06:30:40.260 --> 06:30:44.400
Mary got your Sunday clothes ready, and everybody's been fretting about you.

06:30:44.800 --> 06:30:49.100
Say, ain't this grease and clay on your clothes? Now, Mr. City,

06:30:49.380 --> 06:30:52.970
you just tend to your own business. What's all this blow-out about, anyway?'

06:30:53.760 --> 06:30:58.400
"'It's one of the widow's parties that she's always having. This time it's for the Welshman

06:30:58.400 --> 06:31:02.240
and his sons, on account of that scrape they helped her out of the other night.

06:31:02.460 --> 06:31:05.880
And say, I can tell you something, if you want to know.'

06:31:05.880 --> 06:31:10.940
"'Well, what? Why, old Mr. Jones is going to try to spring something on the people here

06:31:10.940 --> 06:31:14.660
to-night, but I overheard him tell Auntie to-day about it, as a secret,

06:31:14.960 --> 06:31:19.500
but I reckon it's not much of a secret now. Everybody knows, the widow too,

06:31:19.700 --> 06:31:24.040
for all she tries to let on she don't, Mr. Jones was bound Huck should be here,

06:31:24.360 --> 06:31:27.060
couldn't get along with his grand secret without Huck, you know.'

06:31:27.580 --> 06:31:28.960
"'Secret about what, Sid?'

06:31:29.400 --> 06:31:33.580
"'About Huck tracking the robbers to the widow's. I reckon Mr. Jones was

06:31:33.580 --> 06:31:37.680
going to make a grand time over his surprise, but I bet you it will drop

06:31:37.680 --> 06:31:42.040
pretty flat.' Sid chuckled in a very contented and satisfied way.

06:31:42.580 --> 06:31:44.580
"'Sid, was it you that told?'

06:31:45.200 --> 06:31:49.920
"'Oh, never mind who it was. Somebody told, that's enough. Sid, there's only

06:31:49.920 --> 06:31:53.760
one person in this town mean enough to do that, and that's you. If you'd

06:31:53.760 --> 06:31:56.960
been in Huck's place, you'd have sneaked down the hill and never told

06:31:56.960 --> 06:32:01.860
anybody on the robbers. You can't do any but mean things, and you can't

06:32:01.860 --> 06:32:06.460
see anybody praise for doing good ones. There, no thanks, as the widow

06:32:06.460 --> 06:32:10.040
says, and Tom cuffed Sid's ears and helped him to the door with several

06:32:10.040 --> 06:32:14.180
kicks. Now go and tell Auntie if you dare, and tomorrow you'll catch it.'

06:32:14.680 --> 06:32:17.760
Some minutes later the widow's guests were at the supper table, and a

06:32:17.760 --> 06:32:21.020
dozen children were propped up at little side tables in the same room

06:32:21.020 --> 06:32:25.060
after the fashion of that country and that day. At the proper time Mr.

06:32:25.240 --> 06:32:28.420
Jones made his little speech, in which he thanked the widow for the

06:32:28.420 --> 06:32:32.280
honor she was doing himself and his sons, but said that there was

06:32:32.280 --> 06:32:36.700
another person whose modesty and so forth and so on. He sprung his

06:32:36.700 --> 06:32:39.440
secret about Huck's share in the adventure in the finest dramatic

06:32:39.440 --> 06:32:42.980
manner he was master of, but the surprise at occasion was largely

06:32:42.980 --> 06:32:46.940
counterfeit and not as clamorous and effusive as it might have been

06:32:46.940 --> 06:32:51.420
under happier circumstances. However, the widow made a pretty fair show

06:32:51.420 --> 06:32:54.960
of astonishment and heaped so many compliments and so much gratitude

06:32:54.960 --> 06:32:58.960
upon Huck that he almost forgot the nearly intolerable discomfort of

06:32:58.960 --> 06:33:03.320
his new clothes in the entirely intolerable discomfort of being set up

06:33:03.320 --> 06:33:07.900
as a target for everybody's gaze and everybody's laudations. The widow

06:33:07.900 --> 06:33:10.960
said she meant to give Huck a home under her roof and have him

06:33:10.960 --> 06:33:14.700
educated, and that when she could spare the money she would start him in

06:33:14.700 --> 06:33:18.680
business in a modest way. Tom's chance was come. He said,

06:33:19.320 --> 06:33:24.120
"'Huck don't need it. Huck's rich.' Nothing but a heavy strain upon the

06:33:24.120 --> 06:33:27.460
good manners of the company kept back the due and proper complementary

06:33:27.460 --> 06:33:31.580
laugh at this pleasant joke, but the silence was a little awkward. Tom

06:33:31.580 --> 06:33:36.080
broke it. "'Huck's got money. Maybe you don't believe it, but he's got

06:33:36.080 --> 06:33:40.280
lots of it. Oh, you needn't smile. I reckon I can show you. You just

06:33:40.280 --> 06:33:44.160
wait a minute.' Tom ran out of doors. The company looked at each other

06:33:44.160 --> 06:33:47.620
with a perplexed interest and inquiringly at Huck, who was tongue-tied.

06:33:47.620 --> 06:33:53.1000
"'Sid! What ails Tom?' said Aunt Polly. "'He—well, there ain't ever any

06:33:53.1000 --> 06:33:58.580
making of that boy out. I never—' Tom entered, struggling with the

06:33:58.580 --> 06:34:02.680
weight of his sacks, and Aunt Polly did not finish her sentence. Tom

06:34:02.680 --> 06:34:06.880
poured the mass of yellow coins upon the table and said, "'There! What

06:34:06.880 --> 06:34:11.020
did I tell you? Half of it's Huck's and half of it's mine!' The

06:34:11.020 --> 06:34:15.680
spectacle took the general breath away. All gazed, nobody spoke for a

06:34:15.680 --> 06:34:20.300
moment. Then there was a unanimous call for an explanation. Tom said he

06:34:20.300 --> 06:34:24.480
could furnish it, and he did. The tale was long, but brimful of interest.

06:34:24.880 --> 06:34:28.440
There was scarcely an interruption from any one to break the charm of

06:34:28.440 --> 06:34:33.560
its flow. When he had finished, Mr. Jones said, "'I thought I had fixed

06:34:33.560 --> 06:34:37.120
up a little surprise for this occasion, but it don't amount to anything

06:34:37.120 --> 06:34:42.300
now. This one makes it sing mighty small, I'm willing to allow.' The

06:34:42.300 --> 06:34:47.820
money was counted. The sum amounted to a little over $12,000. It was

06:34:47.820 --> 06:34:51.300
more than any one present had ever seen at one time before, though

06:34:51.300 --> 06:34:55.220
several persons were there who were worth considerably more than that in

06:34:56.260 --> 06:34:56.860
property."

06:34:56.860 --> 06:35:01.500
CHAPTER XXXV.

06:35:02.180 --> 06:35:04.160
RESPECTABLE HUCK JOINS THE GANG.

06:35:05.520 --> 06:35:09.460
The reader may rest satisfied that Tom's and Huck's windfall made a

06:35:09.460 --> 06:35:13.480
mighty stir in the poor little village of St. Petersburg. So vast a sum,

06:35:13.540 --> 06:35:17.980
all in actual cash, seemed next to incredible. It was talked about,

06:35:18.200 --> 06:35:21.760
gloated over, glorified, until the reason of many of the citizens

06:35:21.760 --> 06:35:26.200
tottered under the strain of the unhealthy excitement. Every haunted

06:35:26.200 --> 06:35:30.120
house in St. Petersburg and the neighbouring villages was dissected

06:35:30.120 --> 06:35:33.1000
plank by plank, and its foundations dug up and ransacked for hidden

06:35:33.1000 --> 06:35:39.100
treasure. And not by boys, but men, pretty grave, unromantic men, too,

06:35:39.100 --> 06:35:42.860
some of them. Wherever Tom and Huck appeared they were courted,

06:35:43.040 --> 06:35:46.720
admired, stared at. The boys were not able to remember that their

06:35:46.720 --> 06:35:50.320
remarks had possessed weight before, but now their sayings were

06:35:50.320 --> 06:35:54.320
treasured and repeated. Everything they did seemed somehow to be

06:35:54.320 --> 06:35:58.540
regarded as remarkable. They had evidently lost the power of doing and

06:35:58.540 --> 06:36:02.960
saying commonplace things. Moreover, their past history was raked up

06:36:02.960 --> 06:36:06.940
and discovered to bear marks of conspicuous originality. The village

06:36:06.940 --> 06:36:11.800
published biographical sketches of the boys. The widow Douglas put

06:36:11.800 --> 06:36:15.360
Huck's money out at six per cent, and Judge Thatcher did the same with

06:36:15.360 --> 06:36:19.940
Tom's at Aunt Polly's request. Each lad had an income now that was

06:36:19.940 --> 06:36:24.880
simply prodigious—a dollar for every weekday in the year and half of

06:36:24.880 --> 06:36:29.120
the Sundays. It was just what the minister got—no, it was what he was

06:36:29.120 --> 06:36:32.620
promised. He generally couldn't collect it. A dollar and a quarter a

06:36:32.620 --> 06:36:37.300
week would board, lodge, and school a boy in those old simple days, and

06:36:37.300 --> 06:36:39.500
clothe him and wash him, too, for that matter.

06:36:40.400 --> 06:36:44.420
Judge Thatcher had conceived a great opinion of Tom. He said that no

06:36:44.420 --> 06:36:47.900
commonplace boy would ever have got his daughter out of the cave. When

06:36:47.900 --> 06:36:51.800
Becky told her father, in strict confidence, how Tom had taken her

06:36:51.800 --> 06:36:55.880
whipping at school, the judge was visibly moved. And when she pleaded

06:36:55.880 --> 06:36:59.110
grace for the mighty lie which Tom had told in order to shift that

06:36:59.110 --> 06:37:03.470
from her shoulders to his own, the judge said with a fine outburst that

06:37:03.470 --> 06:37:08.770
it was a noble, a generous, a magnanimous lie—a lie that was worthy

06:37:08.770 --> 06:37:12.870
to hold up its head and march down through history, breast to breast,

06:37:12.930 --> 06:37:17.910
with George Washington's lauded truth about the hatchet. Becky thought

06:37:17.910 --> 06:37:22.290
her father had never looked so tall and so superb as when he walked the

06:37:22.290 --> 06:37:26.050
floor and stamped his foot and said that. She went straight off and told

06:37:26.050 --> 06:37:30.370
Tom about it. Judge Thatcher hoped to see Tom a great lawyer or a great

06:37:30.370 --> 06:37:34.010
soldier some day. He said he meant to look to it that Tom should be

06:37:34.010 --> 06:37:37.670
admitted to the National Military Academy and afterward trained in the

06:37:37.670 --> 06:37:40.930
best law school in the country, in order that he might be ready for

06:37:40.930 --> 06:37:45.770
either career or both. Huck Finn's wealth and the fact that he was now

06:37:45.770 --> 06:37:49.830
under the widow Douglas's protection introduced him into society—no,

06:37:50.290 --> 06:37:55.110
dragged him into it, hurled him into it, and his sufferings were almost

06:37:55.110 --> 06:37:58.950
more than he could bear. The widow's servants kept him clean and neat,

06:37:59.190 --> 06:38:02.790
combed and brushed, and they bedded him nightly in unsympathetic

06:38:02.790 --> 06:38:07.270
sheets that had not one little spot or stain which he could press to his

06:38:07.270 --> 06:38:11.290
heart and know for a friend. He had to eat with knife and fork, and had

06:38:11.290 --> 06:38:16.170
to use napkin, cup, and plate. He had to learn his book. He had to go to

06:38:16.170 --> 06:38:20.190
church. He had to talk so properly that speech was becoming sippid in his

06:38:20.190 --> 06:38:24.710
mouth. Withersoever he turned, the bars and shackles of civilization

06:38:24.710 --> 06:38:29.450
shut him in, and bound him hand and foot. He bravely bore his miseries

06:38:29.450 --> 06:38:34.050
three weeks, and then one day turned up missing. For forty-eight hours

06:38:34.050 --> 06:38:37.890
the widow hunted for him everywhere in great distress. The public were

06:38:37.890 --> 06:38:41.630
profoundly concerned. They searched high and low, they dragged the river

06:38:41.630 --> 06:38:45.510
for his body. Early the third morning Tom Sawyer wisely went poking

06:38:45.510 --> 06:38:49.370
among some old empty hogsheads down behind the abandoned slaughterhouse,

06:38:49.650 --> 06:38:53.890
and in one of them he found the refugee. Huck had slept there. He had

06:38:53.890 --> 06:38:57.950
just breakfast upon some stolen odds and ends of food, and was lying off

06:38:57.950 --> 06:39:02.870
now in comfort with his pipe. He was unkempt, uncombed, and clad in the

06:39:02.870 --> 06:39:06.730
same old ruin of rags that had made him picturesque in the days when he

06:39:06.730 --> 06:39:10.990
was free and happy. Tom routed him out, told him the trouble he had been

06:39:10.990 --> 06:39:15.510
causing, and urged him to go home. Huck's face lost its tranquil content,

06:39:15.830 --> 06:39:18.130
and took a melancholy cast. He said,

06:39:18.790 --> 06:39:23.450
Don't talk about it, Tom. I've tried it, and it don't work. It don't

06:39:23.450 --> 06:39:28.410
work, Tom. It ain't for me. I ain't used to it. The widow's good to me

06:39:28.410 --> 06:39:33.210
and friendly, but I can't stand them ways. She makes me get up just at

06:39:33.210 --> 06:39:37.330
the same time every morning. She makes me wash, they comb me all to

06:39:37.330 --> 06:39:41.210
thunder. She won't let me sleep in the woodshed. I got to wear them

06:39:41.210 --> 06:39:45.470
blamed clothes that just smothers me, Tom. They don't seem to let any

06:39:45.470 --> 06:39:49.390
air get through them somehow, and they're so rotten nice that I can't

06:39:49.390 --> 06:39:54.050
sit down, nor lay down, nor roll around anywheres. I ain't slid on a

06:39:54.050 --> 06:39:58.670
cellar door for—well, it appears to be years. I got to go to church

06:39:58.670 --> 06:40:03.090
and sweat and sweat. I hate them ornery sermons. I can't catch a fly in

06:40:03.090 --> 06:40:07.530
there. I can't chaw. I got to wear shoes all Sunday. The widow eats by

06:40:07.530 --> 06:40:12.250
a bell. She goes to bed by a bell. She gets up by a bell. Everything's

06:40:12.250 --> 06:40:16.430
awful regular. A body can't stand it. Well, everybody does that, Huck.

06:40:16.830 --> 06:40:22.370
Tom, it don't make no difference. I ain't everybody, and I can't stand

06:40:22.370 --> 06:40:26.950
it. It's awful to be tied up so, and grub comes too easy. I don't take

06:40:26.950 --> 06:40:31.150
no interest in vittles that way. I got to ask to go a fishing. I got to

06:40:31.150 --> 06:40:35.530
ask to go in a swimming. Durned if I ain't got to ask to do everything.

06:40:36.150 --> 06:40:40.650
Well, I'd got to talk so nice it wasn't no comfort. I'd got to go up in

06:40:40.650 --> 06:40:44.450
the attic and rip out a while every day to get a taste in my mouth, or

06:40:44.450 --> 06:40:48.610
I'd have died, Tom. The widow wouldn't let me smoke. She wouldn't let

06:40:48.610 --> 06:40:52.830
me yell. She wouldn't let me gape, nor stretch, nor scratch before

06:40:52.830 --> 06:40:58.990
folks. Then, with a spasm of special irritation and injury, and dead

06:40:58.990 --> 06:41:04.050
fetch it, she prayed all the time. I never see such a woman. I had to

06:41:04.050 --> 06:41:07.930
shove, Tom. I just had to. And besides, that school's going to open, and

06:41:07.930 --> 06:41:11.910
I'd have got to go to it. Well, I wouldn't stand that, Tom. Looky here,

06:41:11.910 --> 06:41:15.490
Tom. Being rich ain't what it's cracked up to be. It's just worry and

06:41:15.490 --> 06:41:19.130
worry, and sweat and sweat, and a-wishing you was dead all the time.

06:41:19.350 --> 06:41:24.970
Now, these clothes suits me, and this barrel suits me, and I ain't ever

06:41:24.970 --> 06:41:28.850
going to shake them any more. Tom, I wouldn't ever got into all this

06:41:28.850 --> 06:41:32.330
trouble if it hadn't been for that money. Now, you just take my share of

06:41:32.330 --> 06:41:36.030
it along with urine, and give me a ten cent or sometimes—not many

06:41:36.030 --> 06:41:40.110
times—because I don't give a darn for a thing without its tolerable

06:41:40.110 --> 06:41:43.750
hard-to-get, and you go and beg off for me with a witter.

06:41:44.550 --> 06:41:48.870
Oh, Huck, you know I can't do that. It ain't fair. And besides, if

06:41:48.870 --> 06:41:51.690
you'll try this thing just a while longer you'll come to like it.

06:41:52.290 --> 06:41:57.730
Like it? Yes, the way I'd like a hot stove, if I was to set on it long

06:41:57.730 --> 06:42:02.030
enough. No, Tom, I won't be rich, and I won't live in them cussed

06:42:02.030 --> 06:42:06.950
mothery houses. I like the woods and the river and hogsheads, and I'll

06:42:06.950 --> 06:42:11.290
stick to them, too. Blame it all, just as we've got guns and a cave and

06:42:11.290 --> 06:42:15.110
all just fixed to rob. Hear this darn foolishness has got to come up

06:42:15.110 --> 06:42:18.170
and spile it all. Tom saw his opportunity.

06:42:18.910 --> 06:42:22.190
Looky here, Huck, being rich ain't going to keep me back from turning

06:42:22.190 --> 06:42:22.630
robber.

06:42:22.930 --> 06:42:23.450
No.

06:42:23.710 --> 06:42:27.850
Oh, good licks. Are you in real deadwood earnest, Tom?

06:42:28.250 --> 06:42:30.650
Just as dead earnest as I'm a-sittin' here.

06:42:30.650 --> 06:42:35.290
But, Huck, we can't let you into the gang if you ain't respectable,

06:42:35.450 --> 06:42:35.870
you know.

06:42:36.450 --> 06:42:38.010
Huck's joy was quenched.

06:42:38.410 --> 06:42:42.130
Can't let me in, Tom? Didn't you let me go for a pirate?

06:42:42.730 --> 06:42:46.830
Yes, but that's different. A robber is more high-toned than what a

06:42:46.830 --> 06:42:50.850
pirate is, as a general thing. In most countries they are awful high

06:42:50.850 --> 06:42:52.810
up in the nobility, dukes and such.

06:42:53.530 --> 06:43:00.410
Now, Tom, ain't you always been friendly to me? You wouldn't have

06:43:00.410 --> 06:43:00.870
Tom?

06:43:01.670 --> 06:43:06.230
Huck, I wouldn't want to, and I don't want to, but what would people

06:43:06.230 --> 06:43:08.090
say? Why, they'd say,

06:43:08.850 --> 06:43:11.730
Tom Sawyer's gang, pretty low characters in it.

06:43:12.030 --> 06:43:15.590
They'd mean you, Huck. You wouldn't like that, and I wouldn't.

06:43:15.970 --> 06:43:19.370
Huck was silent for some time, engaged in a mental struggle, and

06:43:19.370 --> 06:43:20.070
finally he said,

06:43:20.670 --> 06:43:24.730
Well, I'll go back to the Whitter for a month and tackle it, and see

06:43:24.730 --> 06:43:28.110
if I can come to stand it, if you'll let me belong to the gang, Tom.

06:43:28.110 --> 06:43:32.310
All right, Huck, it's a whiz. Come along, old chap, and I'll ask the

06:43:32.310 --> 06:43:36.150
Whitter to let up on you a little, Huck. Will you, Tom, now, will you?

06:43:36.530 --> 06:43:40.390
That's good. If she'll let up on some of the roughest things, I'll

06:43:40.390 --> 06:43:44.070
smoke private and cuss private and crowd through or bust. When you're

06:43:44.070 --> 06:43:45.990
going to start the gang and turn robbers?

06:43:46.490 --> 06:43:50.270
Oh, right off. We'll get the boys together and have the initiation

06:43:50.270 --> 06:43:50.970
tonight, maybe.

06:43:51.550 --> 06:43:52.310
Have the which?

06:43:52.990 --> 06:43:54.410
Have the initiation.

06:43:54.930 --> 06:43:55.670
What's that?

06:43:55.670 --> 06:43:59.670
It's to swear to stand by one another and never tell the gang secrets,

06:44:00.010 --> 06:44:04.250
even if you're chopped all to flinders, and kill anybody and all his

06:44:04.250 --> 06:44:05.850
family that hurts one of the gang.

06:44:06.490 --> 06:44:09.450
That's gay, that's mighty gay, Tom, I tell you.

06:44:09.810 --> 06:44:13.750
Well, I bet it is, and all that swearing's got to be done at midnight

06:44:13.750 --> 06:44:17.810
in the lonesomest, awfulest place you can find. A haunted house is the

06:44:17.810 --> 06:44:19.650
best, and they're all ripped up now.

06:44:20.230 --> 06:44:22.450
Well, midnight's good, anyway, Tom.

06:44:22.450 --> 06:44:27.170
Yes, so it is, and you've got to swear on a coffin and sign it with

06:44:27.170 --> 06:44:32.830
blood. Now, that's something like. Why, it's a million times bullier

06:44:32.830 --> 06:44:37.110
than pirating. I'll stick to the witter till I rot, Tom, and if I get

06:44:37.110 --> 06:44:40.950
to be regular ripper of a robber and everybody talking about it, I

06:44:40.950 --> 06:44:43.850
reckon she'll be proud she snaked me in out of the wet.

06:44:46.030 --> 06:44:46.590
Conclusion

06:44:47.450 --> 06:44:52.230
So endeth this chronicle. It being strictly a history of a boy,

06:44:52.230 --> 06:44:56.850
it must stop here. The story could not go much further without

06:44:56.850 --> 06:45:01.450
becoming the history of a man. When one writes a novel about grown

06:45:01.450 --> 06:45:07.130
people, he knows exactly where to stop, that is, with a marriage. But

06:45:07.130 --> 06:45:12.490
when he writes of juveniles, he must stop where he best can. Most of

06:45:12.490 --> 06:45:16.470
the characters that perform in this book still live, and are prosperous

06:45:16.470 --> 06:45:21.370
and happy. Someday, it may seem worthwhile to take up the story of

06:45:21.370 --> 06:45:25.410
younger ones again and see what sort of men and women they turned out

06:45:25.410 --> 06:45:30.230
to be. Therefore, it will be wisest not to reveal any of that part of

06:45:30.230 --> 06:45:31.470
their lives at present.

06:45:32.230 --> 06:45:32.990
The End

06:45:33.610 --> 06:45:38.010
This is the end of The Adventures of Tom Sawyer by Mark Twain.
